2mo i, 1:PREFACE
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:As things now stand, the course of instruction in American history in
2mo i, 1:our public schools embraces three distinct treatments of the subject.
2mo i, 1:Three separate books are used. First, there is the primary book, which
2mo i, 1:is usually a very condensed narrative with emphasis on biographies and
2mo i, 1:anecdotes. Second, there is the advanced text for the seventh or eighth
2mo i, 1:grade, generally speaking, an expansion of the elementary book by the
2mo i, 1:addition of forty or fifty thousand words. Finally, there is the high
2mo i, 1:school manual. This, too, ordinarily follows the beaten path, giving
2mo i, 1:fuller accounts of the same events and characters. To put it bluntly, we
2mo i, 1:do not assume that our children obtain permanent possessions from their
2mo i, 1:study of history in the lower grades. If mathematicians followed the
2mo i, 1:same method, high school texts on algebra and geometry would include the
2mo i, 1:multiplication table and fractions.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:There is, of course, a ready answer to the criticism advanced above. It
2mo i, 1:is that teachers have learned from bitter experience how little history
2mo i, 1:their pupils retain as they pass along the regular route. No teacher of
2mo i, 1:history will deny this. Still it is a standing challenge to existing
2mo i, 1:methods of historical instruction. If the study of history cannot be
2mo i, 1:made truly progressive like the study of mathematics, science, and
2mo i, 1:languages, then the historians assume a grave responsibility in adding
2mo i, 1:their subject to the already overloaded curriculum. If the successive
2mo i, 1:historical texts are only enlarged editions of the first text--more
2mo i, 1:facts, more dates, more words--then history deserves most of the sharp
2mo i, 1:criticism which it is receiving from teachers of science, civics, and
2mo i, 1:economics.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:In this condition of affairs we find our justification for offering a
2mo i, 1:new high school text in American history. Our first contribution is one
2mo i, 1:of omission. The time-honored stories of exploration and the
2mo i, 1:biographies of heroes are left out. We frankly hold that, if pupils know
2mo i, 1:little or nothing about Columbus, Cortes, Magellan, or Captain John
2mo i, 1:Smith by the time they reach the high school, it is useless to tell the
2mo i, 1:same stories for perhaps the fourth time. It is worse than useless. It
2mo i, 1:is an offense against the teachers of those subjects that are
2mo i, 1:demonstrated to be progressive in character.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:In the next place we have omitted all descriptions of battles. Our
2mo i, 1:reasons for this are simple. The strategy of a campaign or of a single
2mo i, 1:battle is a highly technical, and usually a highly controversial, matter
2mo i, 1:about which experts differ widely. In the field of military and naval
2mo i, 1:operations most writers and teachers of history are mere novices. To
2mo i, 1:dispose of Gettysburg or the Wilderness in ten lines or ten pages is
2mo i, 1:equally absurd to the serious student of military affairs. Any one who
2mo i, 1:compares the ordinary textbook account of a single Civil War campaign
2mo i, 1:with the account given by Ropes, for instance, will ask for no further
2mo i, 1:comment. No youth called upon to serve our country in arms would think
2mo i, 1:of turning to a high school manual for information about the art of
2mo i, 1:warfare. The dramatic scene or episode, so useful in arousing the
2mo i, 1:interest of the immature pupil, seems out of place in a book that
2mo i, 1:deliberately appeals to boys and girls on the very threshold of life's
2mo i, 1:serious responsibilities.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:It is not upon negative features, however, that we rest our case. It is
2mo i, 1:rather upon constructive features.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:_First._ We have written a topical, not a narrative, history. We have
2mo i, 1:tried to set forth the important aspects, problems, and movements of
2mo i, 1:each period, bringing in the narrative rather by way of illustration.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:_Second._ We have emphasized those historical topics which help to
2mo i, 1:explain how our nation has come to be what it is to-day.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:_Third._ We have dwelt fully upon the social and economic aspects of our
2mo i, 1:history, especially in relation to the politics of each period.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:_Fourth._ We have treated the causes and results of wars, the problems
2mo i, 1:of financing and sustaining armed forces, rather than military strategy.
2mo i, 1:These are the subjects which belong to a history for civilians. These
2mo i, 1:are matters which civilians can understand--matters which they must
2mo i, 1:understand, if they are to play well their part in war and peace.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:_Fifth._ By omitting the period of exploration, we have been able to
2mo i, 1:enlarge the treatment of our own time. We have given special attention
2mo i, 1:to the history of those current questions which must form the subject
2mo i, 1:matter of sound instruction in citizenship.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:_Sixth._ We have borne in mind that America, with all her unique
2mo i, 1:characteristics, is a part of a general civilization. Accordingly we
2mo i, 1:have given diplomacy, foreign affairs, world relations, and the
2mo i, 1:reciprocal influences of nations their appropriate place.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:_Seventh._ We have deliberately aimed at standards of maturity. The
2mo i, 1:study of a mere narrative calls mainly for the use of the memory. We
2mo i, 1:have aimed to stimulate habits of analysis, comparison, association,
2mo i, 1:reflection, and generalization--habits calculated to enlarge as well as
2mo i, 1:inform the mind. We have been at great pains to make our text clear,
2mo i, 1:simple, and direct; but we have earnestly sought to stretch the
2mo i, 1:intellects of our readers--to put them upon their mettle. Most of them
2mo i, 1:will receive the last of their formal instruction in the high school.
2mo i, 1:The world will soon expect maturity from them. Their achievements will
2mo i, 1:depend upon the possession of other powers than memory alone. The
2mo i, 1:effectiveness of their citizenship in our republic will be measured by
2mo i, 1:the excellence of their judgment as well as the fullness of their
2mo i, 1:information.
