2mo i, 1:     "THE NATIONS OF THE WEST" (popularly called "The
2mo i, 1:     Pioneers"), designed by A. Stirling Calder and modeled by
2mo i, 1:     Mr. Calder, F.G.R. Roth, and Leo Lentelli, topped the Arch
2mo i, 1:     of the Setting Sun at the Panama-Pacific Exposition held at
2mo i, 1:     San Francisco in 1915. Facing the Court of the Universe
2mo i, 1:     moves a group of men and women typical of those who have
2mo i, 1:     made our civilization. From left to right appear the
2mo i, 1:     French-Canadian, the Alaskan, the Latin-American, the
2mo i, 1:     German, the Italian, the Anglo-American, and the American
2mo i, 1:     Indian, squaw and warrior. In the place of honor in the
2mo i, 1:     center of the group, standing between the oxen on the tongue
2mo i, 1:     of the prairie schooner, is a figure, beautiful and almost
2mo i, 1:     girlish, but strong, dignified, and womanly, the Mother of
2mo i, 1:     To-morrow. Above the group rides the Spirit of Enterprise,
2mo i, 1:     flanked right and left by the Hopes of the Future in the
2mo i, 1:     person of two boys. The group as a whole is beautifully
2mo i, 1:     symbolic of the westward march of American civilization.
