2mo i, 1:THE GREAT MIGRATION TO AMERICA
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The tide of migration that set in toward the shores of North America
2mo i, 1:during the early years of the seventeenth century was but one phase in
2mo i, 1:the restless and eternal movement of mankind upon the surface of the
2mo i, 1:earth. The ancient Greeks flung out their colonies in every direction,
2mo i, 1:westward as far as Gaul, across the Mediterranean, and eastward into
2mo i, 1:Asia Minor, perhaps to the very confines of India. The Romans, supported
2mo i, 1:by their armies and their government, spread their dominion beyond the
2mo i, 1:narrow lands of Italy until it stretched from the heather of Scotland to
2mo i, 1:the sands of Arabia. The Teutonic tribes, from their home beyond the
2mo i, 1:Danube and the Rhine, poured into the empire of the Caesars and made the
2mo i, 1:beginnings of modern Europe. Of this great sweep of races and empires
2mo i, 1:the settlement of America was merely a part. And it was, moreover, only
2mo i, 1:one aspect of the expansion which finally carried the peoples, the
2mo i, 1:institutions, and the trade of Europe to the very ends of the earth.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:In one vital point, it must be noted, American colonization differed
2mo i, 1:from that of the ancients. The Greeks usually carried with them
2mo i, 1:affection for the government they left behind and sacred fire from the
2mo i, 1:altar of the parent city; but thousands of the immigrants who came to
2mo i, 1:America disliked the state and disowned the church of the mother
2mo i, 1:country. They established compacts of government for themselves and set
2mo i, 1:up altars of their own. They sought not only new soil to till but also
2mo i, 1:political and religious liberty for themselves and their children.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:THE AGENCIES OF AMERICAN COLONIZATION
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:It was no light matter for the English to cross three thousand miles of
2mo i, 1:water and found homes in the American wilderness at the opening of the
2mo i, 1:seventeenth century. Ships, tools, and supplies called for huge outlays
2mo i, 1:of money. Stores had to be furnished in quantities sufficient to sustain
2mo i, 1:the life of the settlers until they could gather harvests of their own.
2mo i, 1:Artisans and laborers of skill and industry had to be induced to risk
2mo i, 1:the hazards of the new world. Soldiers were required for defense and
2mo i, 1:mariners for the exploration of inland waters. Leaders of good judgment,
2mo i, 1:adept in managing men, had to be discovered. Altogether such an
2mo i, 1:enterprise demanded capital larger than the ordinary merchant or
2mo i, 1:gentleman could amass and involved risks more imminent than he dared to
2mo i, 1:assume. Though in later days, after initial tests had been made, wealthy
2mo i, 1:proprietors were able to establish colonies on their own account, it was
2mo i, 1:the corporation that furnished the capital and leadership in the
2mo i, 1:beginning.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Trading Company.=--English pioneers in exploration found an
2mo i, 1:instrument for colonization in companies of merchant adventurers, which
2mo i, 1:had long been employed in carrying on commerce with foreign countries.
2mo i, 1:Such a corporation was composed of many persons of different ranks of
2mo i, 1:society--noblemen, merchants, and gentlemen--who banded together for a
2mo i, 1:particular undertaking, each contributing a sum of money and sharing in
2mo i, 1:the profits of the venture. It was organized under royal authority; it
2mo i, 1:received its charter, its grant of land, and its trading privileges from
2mo i, 1:the king and carried on its operations under his supervision and
2mo i, 1:control. The charter named all the persons originally included in the
2mo i, 1:corporation and gave them certain powers in the management of its
2mo i, 1:affairs, including the right to admit new members. The company was in
2mo i, 1:fact a little government set up by the king. When the members of the
2mo i, 1:corporation remained in England, as in the case of the Virginia Company,
2mo i, 1:they operated through agents sent to the colony. When they came over the
2mo i, 1:seas themselves and settled in America, as in the case of Massachusetts,
2mo i, 1:they became the direct government of the country they possessed. The
2mo i, 1:stockholders in that instance became the voters and the governor, the
2mo i, 1:chief magistrate.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:[Illustration: JOHN WINTHROP, GOVERNOR OF THE MASSACHUSETTS BAY
2mo i, 1:COMPANY]
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Four of the thirteen colonies in America owed their origins to the
2mo i, 1:trading corporation. It was the London Company, created by King James I,
2mo i, 1:in 1606, that laid during the following year the foundations of Virginia
2mo i, 1:at Jamestown. It was under the auspices of their West India Company,
2mo i, 1:chartered in 1621, that the Dutch planted the settlements of the New
2mo i, 1:Netherland in the valley of the Hudson. The founders of Massachusetts
2mo i, 1:were Puritan leaders and men of affairs whom King Charles I incorporated
2mo i, 1:in 1629 under the title: "The governor and company of the Massachusetts
2mo i, 1:Bay in New England." In this case the law did but incorporate a group
2mo i, 1:drawn together by religious ties. "We must be knit together as one man,"
2mo i, 1:wrote John Winthrop, the first Puritan governor in America. Far to the
2mo i, 1:south, on the banks of the Delaware River, a Swedish commercial company
2mo i, 1:in 1638 made the beginnings of a settlement, christened New Sweden; it
2mo i, 1:was destined to pass under the rule of the Dutch, and finally under the
2mo i, 1:rule of William Penn as the proprietary colony of Delaware.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:In a certain sense, Georgia may be included among the "company
2mo i, 1:colonies." It was, however, originally conceived by the moving spirit,
2mo i, 1:James Oglethorpe, as an asylum for poor men, especially those imprisoned
2mo i, 1:for debt. To realize this humane purpose, he secured from King George
2mo i, 1:II, in 1732, a royal charter uniting several gentlemen, including
2mo i, 1:himself, into "one body politic and corporate," known as the "Trustees
2mo i, 1:for establishing the colony of Georgia in America." In the structure of
2mo i, 1:their organization and their methods of government, the trustees did not
2mo i, 1:differ materially from the regular companies created for trade and
2mo i, 1:colonization. Though their purposes were benevolent, their transactions
2mo i, 1:had to be under the forms of law and according to the rules of business.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Religious Congregation.=--A second agency which figured largely in
2mo i, 1:the settlement of America was the religious brotherhood, or
2mo i, 1:congregation, of men and women brought together in the bonds of a common
2mo i, 1:religious faith. By one of the strange fortunes of history, this
2mo i, 1:institution, founded in the early days of Christianity, proved to be a
2mo i, 1:potent force in the origin and growth of self-government in a land far
2mo i, 1:away from Galilee. "And the multitude of them that believed were of one
2mo i, 1:heart and of one soul," we are told in the Acts describing the Church at
2mo i, 1:Jerusalem. "We are knit together as a body in a most sacred covenant of
2mo i, 1:the Lord ... by virtue of which we hold ourselves strictly tied to all
2mo i, 1:care of each other's good and of the whole," wrote John Robinson, a
2mo i, 1:leader among the Pilgrims who founded their tiny colony of Plymouth in
2mo i, 1:1620. The Mayflower Compact, so famous in American history, was but a
2mo i, 1:written and signed agreement, incorporating the spirit of obedience to
2mo i, 1:the common good, which served as a guide to self-government until
2mo i, 1:Plymouth was annexed to Massachusetts in 1691.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:[Illustration: THE ORIGINAL GRANTS]
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Three other colonies, all of which retained their identity until the eve
2mo i, 1:of the American Revolution, likewise sprang directly from the
2mo i, 1:congregations of the faithful: Rhode Island, Connecticut, and New
2mo i, 1:Hampshire, mainly offshoots from Massachusetts. They were founded by
2mo i, 1:small bodies of men and women, "united in solemn covenants with the
2mo i, 1:Lord," who planted their settlements in the wilderness. Not until many a
2mo i, 1:year after Roger Williams and Anne Hutchinson conducted their followers
2mo i, 1:to the Narragansett country was Rhode Island granted a charter of
2mo i, 1:incorporation (1663) by the crown. Not until long after the congregation
2mo i, 1:of Thomas Hooker from Newtown blazed the way into the Connecticut River
2mo i, 1:Valley did the king of England give Connecticut a charter of its own
2mo i, 1:(1662) and a place among the colonies. Half a century elapsed before the
2mo i, 1:towns laid out beyond the Merrimac River by emigrants from Massachusetts
2mo i, 1:were formed into the royal province of New Hampshire in 1679.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Even when Connecticut was chartered, the parchment and sealing wax of
2mo i, 1:the royal lawyers did but confirm rights and habits of self-government
2mo i, 1:and obedience to law previously established by the congregations. The
2mo i, 1:towns of Hartford, Windsor, and Wethersfield had long lived happily
2mo i, 1:under their "Fundamental Orders" drawn up by themselves in 1639; so had
2mo i, 1:the settlers dwelt peacefully at New Haven under their "Fundamental
2mo i, 1:Articles" drafted in the same year. The pioneers on the Connecticut
2mo i, 1:shore had no difficulty in agreeing that "the Scriptures do hold forth a
2mo i, 1:perfect rule for the direction and government of all men."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Proprietor.=--A third and very important colonial agency was the
2mo i, 1:proprietor, or proprietary. As the name, associated with the word
2mo i, 1:"property," implies, the proprietor was a person to whom the king
2mo i, 1:granted property in lands in North America to have, hold, use, and enjoy
2mo i, 1:for his own benefit and profit, with the right to hand the estate down
2mo i, 1:to his heirs in perpetual succession. The proprietor was a rich and
2mo i, 1:powerful person, prepared to furnish or secure the capital, collect the
2mo i, 1:ships, supply the stores, and assemble the settlers necessary to found
2mo i, 1:and sustain a plantation beyond the seas. Sometimes the proprietor
2mo i, 1:worked alone. Sometimes two or more were associated like partners in the
2mo i, 1:common undertaking.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Five colonies, Maryland, Pennsylvania, New Jersey, and the Carolinas,
2mo i, 1:owe their formal origins, though not always their first settlements, nor
2mo i, 1:in most cases their prosperity, to the proprietary system. Maryland,
2mo i, 1:established in 1634 under a Catholic nobleman, Lord Baltimore, and
2mo i, 1:blessed with religious toleration by the act of 1649, flourished under
2mo i, 1:the mild rule of proprietors until it became a state in the American
2mo i, 1:union. New Jersey, beginning its career under two proprietors, Berkeley
2mo i, 1:and Carteret, in 1664, passed under the direct government of the crown
2mo i, 1:in 1702. Pennsylvania was, in a very large measure, the product of the
2mo i, 1:generous spirit and tireless labors of its first proprietor, the leader
2mo i, 1:of the Friends, William Penn, to whom it was granted in 1681 and in
2mo i, 1:whose family it remained until 1776. The two Carolinas were first
2mo i, 1:organized as one colony in 1663 under the government and patronage of
2mo i, 1:eight proprietors, including Lord Clarendon; but after more than half a
2mo i, 1:century both became royal provinces governed by the king.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:[Illustration: WILLIAM PENN, PROPRIETOR OF PENNSYLVANIA]
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:THE COLONIAL PEOPLES
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The English.=--In leadership and origin the thirteen colonies, except
2mo i, 1:New York and Delaware, were English. During the early days of all, save
2mo i, 1:these two, the main, if not the sole, current of immigration was from
2mo i, 1:England. The colonists came from every walk of life. They were men,
2mo i, 1:women, and children of "all sorts and conditions." The major portion
2mo i, 1:were yeomen, or small land owners, farm laborers, and artisans. With
2mo i, 1:them were merchants and gentlemen who brought their stocks of goods or
2mo i, 1:their fortunes to the New World. Scholars came from Oxford and
2mo i, 1:Cambridge to preach the gospel or to teach. Now and then the son of an
2mo i, 1:English nobleman left his baronial hall behind and cast his lot with
2mo i, 1:America. The people represented every religious faith--members of the
2mo i, 1:Established Church of England; Puritans who had labored to reform that
2mo i, 1:church; Separatists, Baptists, and Friends, who had left it altogether;
2mo i, 1:and Catholics, who clung to the religion of their fathers.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:New England was almost purely English. During the years between 1629 and
2mo i, 1:1640, the period of arbitrary Stuart government, about twenty thousand
2mo i, 1:Puritans emigrated to America, settling in the colonies of the far
2mo i, 1:North. Although minor additions were made from time to time, the greater
2mo i, 1:portion of the New England people sprang from this original stock.
2mo i, 1:Virginia, too, for a long time drew nearly all her immigrants from
2mo i, 1:England alone. Not until the eve of the Revolution did other
2mo i, 1:nationalities, mainly the Scotch-Irish and Germans, rival the English in
2mo i, 1:numbers.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The populations of later English colonies--the Carolinas, New York,
2mo i, 1:Pennsylvania, and Georgia--while receiving a steady stream of
2mo i, 1:immigration from England, were constantly augmented by wanderers from
2mo i, 1:the older settlements. New York was invaded by Puritans from New England
2mo i, 1:in such numbers as to cause the Anglican clergymen there to lament that
2mo i, 1:"free thinking spreads almost as fast as the Church." North Carolina was
2mo i, 1:first settled toward the northern border by immigrants from Virginia.
2mo i, 1:Some of the North Carolinians, particularly the Quakers, came all the
2mo i, 1:way from New England, tarrying in Virginia only long enough to learn how
2mo i, 1:little they were wanted in that Anglican colony.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Scotch-Irish.=--Next to the English in numbers and influence were
2mo i, 1:the Scotch-Irish, Presbyterians in belief, English in tongue. Both
2mo i, 1:religious and economic reasons sent them across the sea. Their Scotch
2mo i, 1:ancestors, in the days of Cromwell, had settled in the north of Ireland
2mo i, 1:whence the native Irish had been driven by the conqueror's sword. There
2mo i, 1:the Scotch nourished for many years enjoying in peace their own form of
2mo i, 1:religion and growing prosperous in the manufacture of fine linen and
2mo i, 1:woolen cloth. Then the blow fell. Toward the end of the seventeenth
2mo i, 1:century their religious worship was put under the ban and the export of
2mo i, 1:their cloth was forbidden by the English Parliament. Within two decades
2mo i, 1:twenty thousand Scotch-Irish left Ulster alone, for America; and all
2mo i, 1:during the eighteenth century the migration continued to be heavy.
2mo i, 1:Although no exact record was kept, it is reckoned that the Scotch-Irish
2mo i, 1:and the Scotch who came directly from Scotland, composed one-sixth of
2mo i, 1:the entire American population on the eve of the Revolution.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:[Illustration: SETTLEMENTS OF GERMAN AND SCOTCH-IRISH
2mo i, 1:IMMIGRANTS]
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:These newcomers in America made their homes chiefly in New Jersey,
2mo i, 1:Pennsylvania, Maryland, Virginia, and the Carolinas. Coming late upon
2mo i, 1:the scene, they found much of the land immediately upon the seaboard
2mo i, 1:already taken up. For this reason most of them became frontier people
2mo i, 1:settling the interior and upland regions. There they cleared the land,
2mo i, 1:laid out their small farms, and worked as "sturdy yeomen on the soil,"
2mo i, 1:hardy, industrious, and independent in spirit, sharing neither the
2mo i, 1:luxuries of the rich planters nor the easy life of the leisurely
2mo i, 1:merchants. To their agriculture they added woolen and linen
2mo i, 1:manufactures, which, flourishing in the supple fingers of their tireless
2mo i, 1:women, made heavy inroads upon the trade of the English merchants in
2mo i, 1:the colonies. Of their labors a poet has sung:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:        "O, willing hands to toil;
2mo i, 1:    Strong natures tuned to the harvest-song and bound to the kindly soil;
2mo i, 1:    Bold pioneers for the wilderness, defenders in the field."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Germans.=--Third among the colonists in order of numerical
2mo i, 1:importance were the Germans. From the very beginning, they appeared in
2mo i, 1:colonial records. A number of the artisans and carpenters in the first
2mo i, 1:Jamestown colony were of German descent. Peter Minuit, the famous
2mo i, 1:governor of New Motherland, was a German from Wesel on the Rhine, and
2mo i, 1:Jacob Leisler, leader of a popular uprising against the provincial
2mo i, 1:administration of New York, was a German from Frankfort-on-Main. The
2mo i, 1:wholesale migration of Germans began with the founding of Pennsylvania.
2mo i, 1:Penn was diligent in searching for thrifty farmers to cultivate his
2mo i, 1:lands and he made a special effort to attract peasants from the Rhine
2mo i, 1:country. A great association, known as the Frankfort Company, bought
2mo i, 1:more than twenty thousand acres from him and in 1684 established a
2mo i, 1:center at Germantown for the distribution of German immigrants. In old
2mo i, 1:New York, Rhinebeck-on-the-Hudson became a similar center for
2mo i, 1:distribution. All the way from Maine to Georgia inducements were offered
2mo i, 1:to the German farmers and in nearly every colony were to be found, in
2mo i, 1:time, German settlements. In fact the migration became so large that
2mo i, 1:German princes were frightened at the loss of so many subjects and
2mo i, 1:England was alarmed by the influx of foreigners into her overseas
2mo i, 1:dominions. Yet nothing could stop the movement. By the end of the
2mo i, 1:colonial period, the number of Germans had risen to more than two
2mo i, 1:hundred thousand.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The majority of them were Protestants from the Rhine region, and South
2mo i, 1:Germany. Wars, religious controversies, oppression, and poverty drove
2mo i, 1:them forth to America. Though most of them were farmers, there were also
2mo i, 1:among them skilled artisans who contributed to the rapid growth of
2mo i, 1:industries in Pennsylvania. Their iron, glass, paper, and woolen mills,
2mo i, 1:dotted here and there among the thickly settled regions, added to the
2mo i, 1:wealth and independence of the province.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:[Illustration: _From an old print_
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:A GLIMPSE OF OLD GERMANTOWN]
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Unlike the Scotch-Irish, the Germans did not speak the language of the
2mo i, 1:original colonists or mingle freely with them. They kept to themselves,
2mo i, 1:built their own schools, founded their own newspapers, and published
2mo i, 1:their own books. Their clannish habits often irritated their neighbors
2mo i, 1:and led to occasional agitations against "foreigners." However, no
2mo i, 1:serious collisions seem to have occurred; and in the days of the
2mo i, 1:Revolution, German soldiers from Pennsylvania fought in the patriot
2mo i, 1:armies side by side with soldiers from the English and Scotch-Irish
2mo i, 1:sections.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Other Nationalities.=--Though the English, the Scotch-Irish, and the
2mo i, 1:Germans made up the bulk of the colonial population, there were other
2mo i, 1:racial strains as well, varying in numerical importance but contributing
2mo i, 1:their share to colonial life.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:From France came the Huguenots fleeing from the decree of the king which
2mo i, 1:inflicted terrible penalties upon Protestants.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:From "Old Ireland" came thousands of native Irish, Celtic in race and
2mo i, 1:Catholic in religion. Like their Scotch-Irish neighbors to the north,
2mo i, 1:they revered neither the government nor the church of England imposed
2mo i, 1:upon them by the sword. How many came we do not know, but shipping
2mo i, 1:records of the colonial period show that boatload after boatload left
2mo i, 1:the southern and eastern shores of Ireland for the New World.
2mo i, 1:Undoubtedly thousands of their passengers were Irish of the native
2mo i, 1:stock. This surmise is well sustained by the constant appearance of
2mo i, 1:Celtic names in the records of various colonies.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:[Illustration:_From an old print_
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:OLD DUTCH FORT AND ENGLISH CHURCH NEAR ALBANY]
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The Jews, then as ever engaged in their age-long battle for religious
2mo i, 1:and economic toleration, found in the American colonies, not complete
2mo i, 1:liberty, but certainly more freedom than they enjoyed in England,
2mo i, 1:France, Spain, or Portugal. The English law did not actually recognize
2mo i, 1:their right to live in any of the dominions, but owing to the easy-going
2mo i, 1:habits of the Americans they were allowed to filter into the seaboard
2mo i, 1:towns. The treatment they received there varied. On one occasion the
2mo i, 1:mayor and council of New York forbade them to sell by retail and on
2mo i, 1:another prohibited the exercise of their religious worship. Newport,
2mo i, 1:Philadelphia, and Charleston were more hospitable, and there large
2mo i, 1:Jewish colonies, consisting principally of merchants and their families,
2mo i, 1:flourished in spite of nominal prohibitions of the law.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Though the small Swedish colony in Delaware was quickly submerged
2mo i, 1:beneath the tide of English migration, the Dutch in New York continued
2mo i, 1:to hold their own for more than a hundred years after the English
2mo i, 1:conquest in 1664. At the end of the colonial period over one-half of the
2mo i, 1:170,000 inhabitants of the province were descendants of the original
2mo i, 1:Dutch--still distinct enough to give a decided cast to the life and
2mo i, 1:manners of New York. Many of them clung as tenaciously to their mother
2mo i, 1:tongue as they did to their capacious farmhouses or their Dutch ovens;
2mo i, 1:but they were slowly losing their identity as the English pressed in
2mo i, 1:beside them to farm and trade.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The melting pot had begun its historic mission.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:THE PROCESS OF COLONIZATION
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Considered from one side, colonization, whatever the motives of the
2mo i, 1:emigrants, was an economic matter. It involved the use of capital to pay
2mo i, 1:for their passage, to sustain them on the voyage, and to start them on
2mo i, 1:the way of production. Under this stern economic necessity, Puritans,
2mo i, 1:Scotch-Irish, Germans, and all were alike laid.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Immigrants Who Paid Their Own Way.=--Many of the immigrants to America
2mo i, 1:in colonial days were capitalists themselves, in a small or a large way,
2mo i, 1:and paid their own passage. What proportion of the colonists were able
2mo i, 1:to finance their voyage across the sea is a matter of pure conjecture.
2mo i, 1:Undoubtedly a very considerable number could do so, for we can trace the
2mo i, 1:family fortunes of many early settlers. Henry Cabot Lodge is authority
2mo i, 1:for the statement that "the settlers of New England were drawn from the
2mo i, 1:country gentlemen, small farmers, and yeomanry of the mother
2mo i, 1:country.... Many of the emigrants were men of wealth, as the old lists
2mo i, 1:show, and all of them, with few exceptions, were men of property and
2mo i, 1:good standing. They did not belong to the classes from which emigration
2mo i, 1:is usually supplied, for they all had a stake in the country they left
2mo i, 1:behind." Though it would be interesting to know how accurate this
2mo i, 1:statement is or how applicable to the other colonies, no study has as
2mo i, 1:yet been made to gratify that interest. For the present it is an
2mo i, 1:unsolved problem just how many of the colonists were able to bear the
2mo i, 1:cost of their own transfer to the New World.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Indentured Servants.=--That at least tens of thousands of immigrants
2mo i, 1:were unable to pay for their passage is established beyond the shadow of
2mo i, 1:a doubt by the shipping records that have come down to us. The great
2mo i, 1:barrier in the way of the poor who wanted to go to America was the cost
2mo i, 1:of the sea voyage. To overcome this difficulty a plan was worked out
2mo i, 1:whereby shipowners and other persons of means furnished the passage
2mo i, 1:money to immigrants in return for their promise, or bond, to work for a
2mo i, 1:term of years to repay the sum advanced. This system was called
2mo i, 1:indentured servitude.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:It is probable that the number of bond servants exceeded the original
2mo i, 1:twenty thousand Puritans, the yeomen, the Virginia gentlemen, and the
2mo i, 1:Huguenots combined. All the way down the coast from Massachusetts to
2mo i, 1:Georgia were to be found in the fields, kitchens, and workshops, men,
2mo i, 1:women, and children serving out terms of bondage generally ranging from
2mo i, 1:five to seven years. In the proprietary colonies the proportion of bond
2mo i, 1:servants was very high. The Baltimores, Penns, Carterets, and other
2mo i, 1:promoters anxiously sought for workers of every nationality to till
2mo i, 1:their fields, for land without labor was worth no more than land in the
2mo i, 1:moon. Hence the gates of the proprietary colonies were flung wide open.
2mo i, 1:Every inducement was offered to immigrants in the form of cheap land,
2mo i, 1:and special efforts were made to increase the population by importing
2mo i, 1:servants. In Pennsylvania, it was not uncommon to find a master with
2mo i, 1:fifty bond servants on his estate. It has been estimated that two-thirds
2mo i, 1:of all the immigrants into Pennsylvania between the opening of the
2mo i, 1:eighteenth century and the outbreak of the Revolution were in bondage.
2mo i, 1:In the other Middle colonies the number was doubtless not so large; but
2mo i, 1:it formed a considerable part of the population.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The story of this traffic in white servants is one of the most striking
2mo i, 1:things in the history of labor. Bondmen differed from the serfs of the
2mo i, 1:feudal age in that they were not bound to the soil but to the master.
2mo i, 1:They likewise differed from the negro slaves in that their servitude had
2mo i, 1:a time limit. Still they were subject to many special disabilities. It
2mo i, 1:was, for instance, a common practice to impose on them penalties far
2mo i, 1:heavier than were imposed upon freemen for the same offense. A free
2mo i, 1:citizen of Pennsylvania who indulged in horse racing and gambling was
2mo i, 1:let off with a fine; a white servant guilty of the same unlawful conduct
2mo i, 1:was whipped at the post and fined as well.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The ordinary life of the white servant was also severely restricted. A
2mo i, 1:bondman could not marry without his master's consent; nor engage in
2mo i, 1:trade; nor refuse work assigned to him. For an attempt to escape or
2mo i, 1:indeed for any infraction of the law, the term of service was extended.
2mo i, 1:The condition of white bondmen in Virginia, according to Lodge, "was
2mo i, 1:little better than that of slaves. Loose indentures and harsh laws put
2mo i, 1:them at the mercy of their masters." It would not be unfair to add that
2mo i, 1:such was their lot in all other colonies. Their fate depended upon the
2mo i, 1:temper of their masters.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Cruel as was the system in many ways, it gave thousands of people in the
2mo i, 1:Old World a chance to reach the New--an opportunity to wrestle with fate
2mo i, 1:for freedom and a home of their own. When their weary years of servitude
2mo i, 1:were over, if they survived, they might obtain land of their own or
2mo i, 1:settle as free mechanics in the towns. For many a bondman the gamble
2mo i, 1:proved to be a losing venture because he found himself unable to rise
2mo i, 1:out of the state of poverty and dependence into which his servitude
2mo i, 1:carried him. For thousands, on the contrary, bondage proved to be a real
2mo i, 1:avenue to freedom and prosperity. Some of the best citizens of America
2mo i, 1:have the blood of indentured servants in their veins.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Transported--Involuntary Servitude.=--In their anxiety to secure
2mo i, 1:settlers, the companies and proprietors having colonies in America
2mo i, 1:either resorted to or connived at the practice of kidnapping men, women,
2mo i, 1:and children from the streets of English cities. In 1680 it was
2mo i, 1:officially estimated that "ten thousand persons were spirited away" to
2mo i, 1:America. Many of the victims of the practice were young children, for
2mo i, 1:the traffic in them was highly profitable. Orphans and dependents were
2mo i, 1:sometimes disposed of in America by relatives unwilling to support them.
2mo i, 1:In a single year, 1627, about fifteen hundred children were shipped to
2mo i, 1:Virginia.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:In this gruesome business there lurked many tragedies, and very few
2mo i, 1:romances. Parents were separated from their children and husbands from
2mo i, 1:their wives. Hundreds of skilled artisans--carpenters, smiths, and
2mo i, 1:weavers--utterly disappeared as if swallowed up by death. A few thus
2mo i, 1:dragged off to the New World to be sold into servitude for a term of
2mo i, 1:five or seven years later became prosperous and returned home with
2mo i, 1:fortunes. In one case a young man who was forcibly carried over the sea
2mo i, 1:lived to make his way back to England and establish his claim to a
2mo i, 1:peerage.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Akin to the kidnapped, at least in economic position, were convicts
2mo i, 1:deported to the colonies for life in lieu of fines and imprisonment. The
2mo i, 1:Americans protested vigorously but ineffectually against this practice.
2mo i, 1:Indeed, they exaggerated its evils, for many of the "criminals" were
2mo i, 1:only mild offenders against unduly harsh and cruel laws. A peasant
2mo i, 1:caught shooting a rabbit on a lord's estate or a luckless servant girl
2mo i, 1:who purloined a pocket handkerchief was branded as a criminal along with
2mo i, 1:sturdy thieves and incorrigible rascals. Other transported offenders
2mo i, 1:were "political criminals"; that is, persons who criticized or opposed
2mo i, 1:the government. This class included now Irish who revolted against
2mo i, 1:British rule in Ireland; now Cavaliers who championed the king against
2mo i, 1:the Puritan revolutionists; Puritans, in turn, dispatched after the
2mo i, 1:monarchy was restored; and Scotch and English subjects in general who
2mo i, 1:joined in political uprisings against the king.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The African Slaves.=--Rivaling in numbers, in the course of time, the
2mo i, 1:indentured servants and whites carried to America against their will
2mo i, 1:were the African negroes brought to America and sold into slavery. When
2mo i, 1:this form of bondage was first introduced into Virginia in 1619, it was
2mo i, 1:looked upon as a temporary necessity to be discarded with the increase
2mo i, 1:of the white population. Moreover it does not appear that those planters
2mo i, 1:who first bought negroes at the auction block intended to establish a
2mo i, 1:system of permanent bondage. Only by a slow process did chattel slavery
2mo i, 1:take firm root and become recognized as the leading source of the labor
2mo i, 1:supply. In 1650, thirty years after the introduction of slavery, there
2mo i, 1:were only three hundred Africans in Virginia.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The great increase in later years was due in no small measure to the
2mo i, 1:inordinate zeal for profits that seized slave traders both in Old and in
2mo i, 1:New England. Finding it relatively easy to secure negroes in Africa,
2mo i, 1:they crowded the Southern ports with their vessels. The English Royal
2mo i, 1:African Company sent to America annually between 1713 and 1743 from five
2mo i, 1:to ten thousand slaves. The ship owners of New England were not far
2mo i, 1:behind their English brethren in pushing this extraordinary traffic.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:As the proportion of the negroes to the free white population steadily
2mo i, 1:rose, and as whole sections were overrun with slaves and slave traders,
2mo i, 1:the Southern colonies grew alarmed. In 1710, Virginia sought to curtail
2mo i, 1:the importation by placing a duty of $5 on each slave. This effort was
2mo i, 1:futile, for the royal governor promptly vetoed it. From time to time
2mo i, 1:similar bills were passed, only to meet with royal disapproval. South
2mo i, 1:Carolina, in 1760, absolutely prohibited importation; but the measure
2mo i, 1:was killed by the British crown. As late as 1772, Virginia, not daunted
2mo i, 1:by a century of rebuffs, sent to George III a petition in this vein:
2mo i, 1:"The importation of slaves into the colonies from the coast of Africa
2mo i, 1:hath long been considered as a trade of great inhumanity and under its
2mo i, 1:present encouragement, we have too much reason to fear, will endanger
2mo i, 1:the very existence of Your Majesty's American dominions.... Deeply
2mo i, 1:impressed with these sentiments, we most humbly beseech Your Majesty to
2mo i, 1:remove all those restraints on Your Majesty's governors of this colony
2mo i, 1:which inhibit their assenting to such laws as might check so very
2mo i, 1:pernicious a commerce."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:All such protests were without avail. The negro population grew by leaps
2mo i, 1:and bounds, until on the eve of the Revolution it amounted to more than
2mo i, 1:half a million. In five states--Maryland, Virginia, the two Carolinas,
2mo i, 1:and Georgia--the slaves nearly equalled or actually exceeded the whites
2mo i, 1:in number. In South Carolina they formed almost two-thirds of the
2mo i, 1:population. Even in the Middle colonies of Delaware and Pennsylvania
2mo i, 1:about one-fifth of the inhabitants were from Africa. To the North, the
2mo i, 1:proportion of slaves steadily diminished although chattel servitude was
2mo i, 1:on the same legal footing as in the South. In New York approximately one
2mo i, 1:in six and in New England one in fifty were negroes, including a few
2mo i, 1:freedmen.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The climate, the soil, the commerce, and the industry of the North were
2mo i, 1:all unfavorable to the growth of a servile population. Still, slavery,
2mo i, 1:though sectional, was a part of the national system of economy. Northern
2mo i, 1:ships carried slaves to the Southern colonies and the produce of the
2mo i, 1:plantations to Europe. "If the Northern states will consult their
2mo i, 1:interest, they will not oppose the increase in slaves which will
2mo i, 1:increase the commodities of which they will become the carriers," said
2mo i, 1:John Rutledge, of South Carolina, in the convention which framed the
2mo i, 1:Constitution of the United States. "What enriches a part enriches the
2mo i, 1:whole and the states are the best judges of their particular interest,"
2mo i, 1:responded Oliver Ellsworth, the distinguished spokesman of Connecticut.
