2mo i, 1:CHAPTER II
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:COLONIAL AGRICULTURE, INDUSTRY, AND COMMERCE
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:THE LAND AND THE WESTWARD MOVEMENT
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Significance of Land Tenure.=--The way in which land may be
2mo i, 1:acquired, held, divided among heirs, and bought and sold exercises a
2mo i, 1:deep influence on the life and culture of a people. The feudal and
2mo i, 1:aristocratic societies of Europe were founded on a system of landlordism
2mo i, 1:which was characterized by two distinct features. In the first place,
2mo i, 1:the land was nearly all held in great estates, each owned by a single
2mo i, 1:proprietor. In the second place, every estate was kept intact under the
2mo i, 1:law of primogeniture, which at the death of a lord transferred all his
2mo i, 1:landed property to his eldest son. This prevented the subdivision of
2mo i, 1:estates and the growth of a large body of small farmers or freeholders
2mo i, 1:owning their own land. It made a form of tenantry or servitude
2mo i, 1:inevitable for the mass of those who labored on the land. It also
2mo i, 1:enabled the landlords to maintain themselves in power as a governing
2mo i, 1:class and kept the tenants and laborers subject to their economic and
2mo i, 1:political control. If land tenure was so significant in Europe, it was
2mo i, 1:equally important in the development of America, where practically all
2mo i, 1:the first immigrants were forced by circumstances to derive their
2mo i, 1:livelihood from the soil.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Experiments in Common Tillage.=--In the New World, with its broad
2mo i, 1:extent of land awaiting the white man's plow, it was impossible to
2mo i, 1:introduce in its entirety and over the whole area the system of lords
2mo i, 1:and tenants that existed across the sea. So it happened that almost
2mo i, 1:every kind of experiment in land tenure, from communism to feudalism,
2mo i, 1:was tried. In the early days of the Jamestown colony, the land, though
2mo i, 1:owned by the London Company, was tilled in common by the settlers. No
2mo i, 1:man had a separate plot of his own. The motto of the community was:
2mo i, 1:"Labor and share alike." All were supposed to work in the fields and
2mo i, 1:receive an equal share of the produce. At Plymouth, the Pilgrims
2mo i, 1:attempted a similar experiment, laying out the fields in common and
2mo i, 1:distributing the joint produce of their labor with rough equality among
2mo i, 1:the workers.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:In both colonies the communistic experiments were failures. Angry at the
2mo i, 1:lazy men in Jamestown who idled their time away and yet expected regular
2mo i, 1:meals, Captain John Smith issued a manifesto: "Everyone that gathereth
2mo i, 1:not every day as much as I do, the next day shall be set beyond the
2mo i, 1:river and forever banished from the fort and live there or starve." Even
2mo i, 1:this terrible threat did not bring a change in production. Not until
2mo i, 1:each man was given a plot of his own to till, not until each gathered
2mo i, 1:the fruits of his own labor, did the colony prosper. In Plymouth, where
2mo i, 1:the communal experiment lasted for five years, the results were similar
2mo i, 1:to those in Virginia, and the system was given up for one of separate
2mo i, 1:fields in which every person could "set corn for his own particular."
2mo i, 1:Some other New England towns, refusing to profit by the experience of
2mo i, 1:their Plymouth neighbor, also made excursions into common ownership and
2mo i, 1:labor, only to abandon the idea and go in for individual ownership of
2mo i, 1:the land. "By degrees it was seen that even the Lord's people could not
2mo i, 1:carry the complicated communist legislation into perfect and wholesome
2mo i, 1:practice."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Feudal Elements in the Colonies--Quit Rents, Manors, and
2mo i, 1:Plantations.=--At the other end of the scale were the feudal elements of
2mo i, 1:land tenure found in the proprietary colonies, in the seaboard regions
2mo i, 1:of the South, and to some extent in New York. The proprietor was in fact
2mo i, 1:a powerful feudal lord, owning land granted to him by royal charter. He
2mo i, 1:could retain any part of it for his personal use or dispose of it all in
2mo i, 1:large or small lots. While he generally kept for himself an estate of
2mo i, 1:baronial proportions, it was impossible for him to manage directly any
2mo i, 1:considerable part of the land in his dominion. Consequently he either
2mo i, 1:sold it in parcels for lump sums or granted it to individuals on
2mo i, 1:condition that they make to him an annual payment in money, known as
2mo i, 1:"quit rent." In Maryland, the proprietor sometimes collected as high as
2mo i, 1:$9000 (equal to about $500,000 to-day) in a single year from this
2mo i, 1:source. In Pennsylvania, the quit rents brought a handsome annual
2mo i, 1:tribute into the exchequer of the Penn family. In the royal provinces,
2mo i, 1:the king of England claimed all revenues collected in this form from the
2mo i, 1:land, a sum amounting to $19,000 at the time of the Revolution. The quit
2mo i, 1:rent,--"really a feudal payment from freeholders,"--was thus a material
2mo i, 1:source of income for the crown as well as for the proprietors. Wherever
2mo i, 1:it was laid, however, it proved to be a burden, a source of constant
2mo i, 1:irritation; and it became a formidable item in the long list of
2mo i, 1:grievances which led to the American Revolution.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Something still more like the feudal system of the Old World appeared in
2mo i, 1:the numerous manors or the huge landed estates granted by the crown, the
2mo i, 1:companies, or the proprietors. In the colony of Maryland alone there
2mo i, 1:were sixty manors of three thousand acres each, owned by wealthy men and
2mo i, 1:tilled by tenants holding small plots under certain restrictions of
2mo i, 1:tenure. In New York also there were many manors of wide extent, most of
2mo i, 1:which originated in the days of the Dutch West India Company, when
2mo i, 1:extensive concessions were made to patroons to induce them to bring over
2mo i, 1:settlers. The Van Rensselaer, the Van Cortlandt, and the Livingston
2mo i, 1:manors were so large and populous that each was entitled to send a
2mo i, 1:representative to the provincial legislature. The tenants on the New
2mo i, 1:York manors were in somewhat the same position as serfs on old European
2mo i, 1:estates. They were bound to pay the owner a rent in money and kind; they
2mo i, 1:ground their grain at his mill; and they were subject to his judicial
2mo i, 1:power because he held court and meted out justice, in some instances
2mo i, 1:extending to capital punishment.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The manors of New York or Maryland were, however, of slight consequence
2mo i, 1:as compared with the vast plantations of the Southern seaboard--huge
2mo i, 1:estates, far wider in expanse than many a European barony and tilled by
2mo i, 1:slaves more servile than any feudal tenants. It must not be forgotten
2mo i, 1:that this system of land tenure became the dominant feature of a large
2mo i, 1:section and gave a decided bent to the economic and political life of
2mo i, 1:America.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:[Illustration: SOUTHERN PLANTATION MANSION]
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Small Freehold.=--In the upland regions of the South, however, and
2mo i, 1:throughout most of the North, the drift was against all forms of
2mo i, 1:servitude and tenantry and in the direction of the freehold; that is,
2mo i, 1:the small farm owned outright and tilled by the possessor and his
2mo i, 1:family. This was favored by natural circumstances and the spirit of the
2mo i, 1:immigrants. For one thing, the abundance of land and the scarcity of
2mo i, 1:labor made it impossible for the companies, the proprietors, or the
2mo i, 1:crown to develop over the whole continent a network of vast estates. In
2mo i, 1:many sections, particularly in New England, the climate, the stony soil,
2mo i, 1:the hills, and the narrow valleys conspired to keep the farms within a
2mo i, 1:moderate compass. For another thing, the English, Scotch-Irish, and
2mo i, 1:German peasants, even if they had been tenants in the Old World, did not
2mo i, 1:propose to accept permanent dependency of any kind in the New. If they
2mo i, 1:could not get freeholds, they would not settle at all; thus they forced
2mo i, 1:proprietors and companies to bid for their enterprise by selling land in
2mo i, 1:small lots. So it happened that the freehold of modest proportions
2mo i, 1:became the cherished unit of American farmers. The people who tilled the
2mo i, 1:farms were drawn from every quarter of western Europe; but the freehold
2mo i, 1:system gave a uniform cast to their economic and social life in America.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:[Illustration: _From an old print_
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:A NEW ENGLAND FARMHOUSE]
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Social Effects of Land Tenure.=--Land tenure and the process of western
2mo i, 1:settlement thus developed two distinct types of people engaged in the
2mo i, 1:same pursuit--agriculture. They had a common tie in that they both
2mo i, 1:cultivated the soil and possessed the local interest and independence
2mo i, 1:which arise from that occupation. Their methods and their culture,
2mo i, 1:however, differed widely.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The Southern planter, on his broad acres tilled by slaves, resembled the
2mo i, 1:English landlord on his estates more than he did the colonial farmer who
2mo i, 1:labored with his own hands in the fields and forests. He sold his rice
2mo i, 1:and tobacco in large amounts directly to English factors, who took his
2mo i, 1:entire crop in exchange for goods and cash. His fine clothes,
2mo i, 1:silverware, china, and cutlery he bought in English markets. Loving the
2mo i, 1:ripe old culture of the mother country, he often sent his sons to Oxford
2mo i, 1:or Cambridge for their education. In short, he depended very largely for
2mo i, 1:his prosperity and his enjoyment of life upon close relations with the
2mo i, 1:Old World. He did not even need market towns in which to buy native
2mo i, 1:goods, for they were made on his own plantation by his own artisans who
2mo i, 1:were usually gifted slaves.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The economic condition of the small farmer was totally different. His
2mo i, 1:crops were not big enough to warrant direct connection with English
2mo i, 1:factors or the personal maintenance of a corps of artisans. He needed
2mo i, 1:local markets, and they sprang up to meet the need. Smiths, hatters,
2mo i, 1:weavers, wagon-makers, and potters at neighboring towns supplied him
2mo i, 1:with the rough products of their native skill. The finer goods, bought
2mo i, 1:by the rich planter in England, the small farmer ordinarily could not
2mo i, 1:buy. His wants were restricted to staples like tea and sugar, and
2mo i, 1:between him and the European market stood the merchant. His community
2mo i, 1:was therefore more self-sufficient than the seaboard line of great
2mo i, 1:plantations. It was more isolated, more provincial, more independent,
2mo i, 1:more American. The planter faced the Old East. The farmer faced the New
2mo i, 1:West.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Westward Movement.=--Yeoman and planter nevertheless were alike in
2mo i, 1:one respect. Their land hunger was never appeased. Each had the eye of
2mo i, 1:an expert for new and fertile soil; and so, north and south, as soon as
2mo i, 1:a foothold was secured on the Atlantic coast, the current of migration
2mo i, 1:set in westward, creeping through forests, across rivers, and over
2mo i, 1:mountains. Many of the later immigrants, in their search for cheap
2mo i, 1:lands, were compelled to go to the border; but in a large part the path
2mo i, 1:breakers to the West were native Americans of the second and third
2mo i, 1:generations. Explorers, fired by curiosity and the lure of the
2mo i, 1:mysterious unknown, and hunters, fur traders, and squatters, following
2mo i, 1:their own sweet wills, blazed the trail, opening paths and sending back
2mo i, 1:stories of the new regions they traversed. Then came the regular
2mo i, 1:settlers with lawful titles to the lands they had purchased, sometimes
2mo i, 1:singly and sometimes in companies.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:In Massachusetts, the westward movement is recorded in the founding of
2mo i, 1:Springfield in 1636 and Great Barrington in 1725. By the opening of the
2mo i, 1:eighteenth century the pioneers of Connecticut had pushed north and west
2mo i, 1:until their outpost towns adjoined the Hudson Valley settlements. In New
2mo i, 1:York, the inland movement was directed by the Hudson River to Albany,
2mo i, 1:and from that old Dutch center it radiated in every direction,
2mo i, 1:particularly westward through the Mohawk Valley. New Jersey was early
2mo i, 1:filled to its borders, the beginnings of the present city of New
2mo i, 1:Brunswick being made in 1681 and those of Trenton in 1685. In
2mo i, 1:Pennsylvania, as in New York, the waterways determined the main lines of
2mo i, 1:advance. Pioneers, pushing up through the valley of the Schuylkill,
2mo i, 1:spread over the fertile lands of Berks and Lancaster counties, laying
2mo i, 1:out Reading in 1748. Another current of migration was directed by the
2mo i, 1:Susquehanna, and, in 1726, the first farmhouse was built on the bank
2mo i, 1:where Harrisburg was later founded. Along the southern tier of counties
2mo i, 1:a thin line of settlements stretched westward to Pittsburgh, reaching
2mo i, 1:the upper waters of the Ohio while the colony was still under the Penn
2mo i, 1:family.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:In the South the westward march was equally swift. The seaboard was
2mo i, 1:quickly occupied by large planters and their slaves engaged in the
2mo i, 1:cultivation of tobacco and rice. The Piedmont Plateau, lying back from
2mo i, 1:the coast all the way from Maryland to Georgia, was fed by two streams
2mo i, 1:of migration, one westward from the sea and the other southward from the
2mo i, 1:other colonies--Germans from Pennsylvania and Scotch-Irish furnishing
2mo i, 1:the main supply. "By 1770, tide-water Virginia was full to overflowing
2mo i, 1:and the 'back country' of the Blue Ridge and the Shenandoah was fully
2mo i, 1:occupied. Even the mountain valleys ... were claimed by sturdy pioneers.
2mo i, 1:Before the Declaration of Independence, the oncoming tide of
2mo i, 1:home-seekers had reached the crest of the Alleghanies."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:[Illustration: DISTRIBUTION OF POPULATION, 1790]
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Beyond the mountains pioneers had already ventured, harbingers of an
2mo i, 1:invasion that was about to break in upon Kentucky and Tennessee. As
2mo i, 1:early as 1769 that mighty Nimrod, Daniel Boone, curious to hunt
2mo i, 1:buffaloes, of which he had heard weird reports, passed through the
2mo i, 1:Cumberland Gap and brought back news of a wonderful country awaiting the
2mo i, 1:plow. A hint was sufficient. Singly, in pairs, and in groups, settlers
2mo i, 1:followed the trail he had blazed. A great land corporation, the
2mo i, 1:Transylvania Company, emulating the merchant adventurers of earlier
2mo i, 1:times, secured a huge grant of territory and sought profits in quit
2mo i, 1:rents from lands sold to farmers. By the outbreak of the Revolution
2mo i, 1:there were several hundred people in the Kentucky region. Like the older
2mo i, 1:colonists, they did not relish quit rents, and their opposition wrecked
2mo i, 1:the Transylvania Company. They even carried their protests into the
2mo i, 1:Continental Congress in 1776, for by that time they were our "embryo
2mo i, 1:fourteenth colony."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:INDUSTRIAL AND COMMERCIAL DEVELOPMENT
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Though the labor of the colonists was mainly spent in farming, there was
2mo i, 1:a steady growth in industrial and commercial pursuits. Most of the
2mo i, 1:staple industries of to-day, not omitting iron and textiles, have their
2mo i, 1:beginnings in colonial times. Manufacturing and trade soon gave rise to
2mo i, 1:towns which enjoyed an importance all out of proportion to their
2mo i, 1:numbers. The great centers of commerce and finance on the seaboard
2mo i, 1:originated in the days when the king of England was "lord of these
2mo i, 1:dominions."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:[Illustration: DOMESTIC INDUSTRY: DIPPING TALLOW CANDLES]
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Textile Manufacture as a Domestic Industry.=--Colonial women, in
2mo i, 1:addition to sharing every hardship of pioneering, often the heavy labor
2mo i, 1:of the open field, developed in the course of time a national industry
2mo i, 1:which was almost exclusively their own. Wool and flax were raised in
2mo i, 1:abundance in the North and South. "Every farm house," says Coman, the
2mo i, 1:economic historian, "was a workshop where the women spun and wove the
2mo i, 1:serges, kerseys, and linsey-woolseys which served for the common wear."
2mo i, 1:By the close of the seventeenth century, New England manufactured cloth
2mo i, 1:in sufficient quantities to export it to the Southern colonies and to
2mo i, 1:the West Indies. As the industry developed, mills were erected for the
2mo i, 1:more difficult process of dyeing, weaving, and fulling, but carding and
2mo i, 1:spinning continued to be done in the home. The Dutch of New Netherland,
2mo i, 1:the Swedes of Delaware, and the Scotch-Irish of the interior "were not
2mo i, 1:one whit behind their Yankee neighbors."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The importance of this enterprise to British economic life can hardly be
2mo i, 1:overestimated. For many a century the English had employed their fine
2mo i, 1:woolen cloth as the chief staple in a lucrative foreign trade, and the
2mo i, 1:government had come to look upon it as an object of special interest and
2mo i, 1:protection. When the colonies were established, both merchants and
2mo i, 1:statesmen naturally expected to maintain a monopoly of increasing value;
2mo i, 1:but before long the Americans, instead of buying cloth, especially of
2mo i, 1:the coarser varieties, were making it to sell. In the place of
2mo i, 1:customers, here were rivals. In the place of helpless reliance upon
2mo i, 1:English markets, here was the germ of economic independence.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:If British merchants had not discovered it in the ordinary course of
2mo i, 1:trade, observant officers in the provinces would have conveyed the news
2mo i, 1:to them. Even in the early years of the eighteenth century the royal
2mo i, 1:governor of New York wrote of the industrious Americans to his home
2mo i, 1:government: "The consequence will be that if they can clothe themselves
2mo i, 1:once, not only comfortably, but handsomely too, without the help of
2mo i, 1:England, they who already are not very fond of submitting to government
2mo i, 1:will soon think of putting in execution designs they have long harboured
2mo i, 1:in their breasts. This will not seem strange when you consider what sort
2mo i, 1:of people this country is inhabited by."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Iron Industry.=--Almost equally widespread was the art of iron
2mo i, 1:working--one of the earliest and most picturesque of colonial
2mo i, 1:industries. Lynn, Massachusetts, had a forge and skilled artisans within
2mo i, 1:fifteen years after the founding of Boston. The smelting of iron began
2mo i, 1:at New London and New Haven about 1658; in Litchfield county,
2mo i, 1:Connecticut, a few years later; at Great Barrington, Massachusetts, in
2mo i, 1:1731; and near by at Lenox some thirty years after that. New Jersey had
2mo i, 1:iron works at Shrewsbury within ten years after the founding of the
2mo i, 1:colony in 1665. Iron forges appeared in the valleys of the Delaware and
2mo i, 1:the Susquehanna early in the following century, and iron masters then
2mo i, 1:laid the foundations of fortunes in a region destined to become one of
2mo i, 1:the great iron centers of the world. Virginia began iron working in the
2mo i, 1:year that saw the introduction of slavery. Although the industry soon
2mo i, 1:lapsed, it was renewed and flourished in the eighteenth century.
2mo i, 1:Governor Spotswood was called the "Tubal Cain" of the Old Dominion
2mo i, 1:because he placed the industry on a firm foundation. Indeed it seems
2mo i, 1:that every colony, except Georgia, had its iron foundry. Nails, wire,
2mo i, 1:metallic ware, chains, anchors, bar and pig iron were made in large
2mo i, 1:quantities; and Great Britain, by an act in 1750, encouraged the
2mo i, 1:colonists to export rough iron to the British Islands.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Shipbuilding.=--Of all the specialized industries in the colonies,
2mo i, 1:shipbuilding was the most important. The abundance of fir for masts, oak
2mo i, 1:for timbers and boards, pitch for tar and turpentine, and hemp for rope
2mo i, 1:made the way of the shipbuilder easy. Early in the seventeenth century a
2mo i, 1:ship was built at New Amsterdam, and by the middle of that century
2mo i, 1:shipyards were scattered along the New England coast at Newburyport,
2mo i, 1:Salem, New Bedford, Newport, Providence, New London, and New Haven.
2mo i, 1:Yards at Albany and Poughkeepsie in New York built ships for the trade
2mo i, 1:of that colony with England and the Indies. Wilmington and Philadelphia
2mo i, 1:soon entered the race and outdistanced New York, though unable to equal
2mo i, 1:the pace set by New England. While Maryland, Virginia, and South
2mo i, 1:Carolina also built ships, Southern interest was mainly confined to the
2mo i, 1:lucrative business of producing ship materials: fir, cedar, hemp, and
2mo i, 1:tar.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Fishing.=--The greatest single economic resource of New England outside
2mo i, 1:of agriculture was the fisheries. This industry, started by hardy
2mo i, 1:sailors from Europe, long before the landing of the Pilgrims, flourished
2mo i, 1:under the indomitable seamanship of the Puritans, who labored with the
2mo i, 1:net and the harpoon in almost every quarter of the Atlantic. "Look,"
2mo i, 1:exclaimed Edmund Burke, in the House of Commons, "at the manner in
2mo i, 1:which the people of New England have of late carried on the whale
2mo i, 1:fishery. Whilst we follow them among the tumbling mountains of ice and
2mo i, 1:behold them penetrating into the deepest frozen recesses of Hudson's Bay
2mo i, 1:and Davis's Straits, while we are looking for them beneath the arctic
2mo i, 1:circle, we hear that they have pierced into the opposite region of polar
2mo i, 1:cold, that they are at the antipodes and engaged under the frozen
2mo i, 1:serpent of the south.... Nor is the equinoctial heat more discouraging
2mo i, 1:to them than the accumulated winter of both poles. We know that, whilst
2mo i, 1:some of them draw the line and strike the harpoon on the coast of
2mo i, 1:Africa, others run the longitude and pursue their gigantic game along
2mo i, 1:the coast of Brazil. No sea but what is vexed by their fisheries. No
2mo i, 1:climate that is not witness to their toils. Neither the perseverance of
2mo i, 1:Holland nor the activity of France nor the dexterous and firm sagacity
2mo i, 1:of English enterprise ever carried this most perilous mode of hard
2mo i, 1:industry to the extent to which it has been pushed by this recent
2mo i, 1:people."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The influence of the business was widespread. A large and lucrative
2mo i, 1:European trade was built upon it. The better quality of the fish caught
2mo i, 1:for food was sold in the markets of Spain, Portugal, and Italy, or
2mo i, 1:exchanged for salt, lemons, and raisins for the American market. The
2mo i, 1:lower grades of fish were carried to the West Indies for slave
2mo i, 1:consumption, and in part traded for sugar and molasses, which furnished
2mo i, 1:the raw materials for the thriving rum industry of New England. These
2mo i, 1:activities, in turn, stimulated shipbuilding, steadily enlarging the
2mo i, 1:demand for fishing and merchant craft of every kind and thus keeping the
2mo i, 1:shipwrights, calkers, rope makers, and other artisans of the seaport
2mo i, 1:towns rushed with work. They also increased trade with the mother
2mo i, 1:country for, out of the cash collected in the fish markets of Europe and
2mo i, 1:the West Indies, the colonists paid for English manufactures. So an
2mo i, 1:ever-widening circle of American enterprise centered around this single
2mo i, 1:industry, the nursery of seamanship and the maritime spirit.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Oceanic Commerce and American Merchants.=--All through the eighteenth
2mo i, 1:century, the commerce of the American colonies spread in every direction
2mo i, 1:until it rivaled in the number of people employed, the capital engaged,
2mo i, 1:and the profits gleaned, the commerce of European nations. A modern
2mo i, 1:historian has said: "The enterprising merchants of New England developed
2mo i, 1:a network of trade routes that covered well-nigh half the world." This
2mo i, 1:commerce, destined to be of such significance in the conflict with the
2mo i, 1:mother country, presented, broadly speaking, two aspects.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:On the one side, it involved the export of raw materials and
2mo i, 1:agricultural produce. The Southern colonies produced for shipping,
2mo i, 1:tobacco, rice, tar, pitch, and pine; the Middle colonies, grain, flour,
2mo i, 1:furs, lumber, and salt pork; New England, fish, flour, rum, furs, shoes,
2mo i, 1:and small articles of manufacture. The variety of products was in fact
2mo i, 1:astounding. A sarcastic writer, while sneering at the idea of an
2mo i, 1:American union, once remarked of colonial trade: "What sort of dish will
2mo i, 1:you make? New England will throw in fish and onions. The middle states,
2mo i, 1:flax-seed and flour. Maryland and Virginia will add tobacco. North
2mo i, 1:Carolina, pitch, tar, and turpentine. South Carolina, rice and indigo,
2mo i, 1:and Georgia will sprinkle the whole composition with sawdust. Such an
2mo i, 1:absurd jumble will you make if you attempt to form a union among such
2mo i, 1:discordant materials as the thirteen British provinces."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:On the other side, American commerce involved the import trade,
2mo i, 1:consisting principally of English and continental manufactures, tea, and
2mo i, 1:"India goods." Sugar and molasses, brought from the West Indies,
2mo i, 1:supplied the flourishing distilleries of Massachusetts, Rhode Island,
2mo i, 1:and Connecticut. The carriage of slaves from Africa to the Southern
2mo i, 1:colonies engaged hundreds of New England's sailors and thousands of
2mo i, 1:pounds of her capital.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The disposition of imported goods in the colonies, though in part
2mo i, 1:controlled by English factors located in America, employed also a large
2mo i, 1:and important body of American merchants like the Willings and Morrises
2mo i, 1:of Philadelphia; the Amorys, Hancocks, and Faneuils of Boston; and the
2mo i, 1:Livingstons and Lows of New York. In their zeal and enterprise, they
2mo i, 1:were worthy rivals of their English competitors, so celebrated for
2mo i, 1:world-wide commercial operations. Though fully aware of the advantages
2mo i, 1:they enjoyed in British markets and under the protection of the British
2mo i, 1:navy, the American merchants were high-spirited and mettlesome, ready to
2mo i, 1:contend with royal officers in order to shield American interests
2mo i, 1:against outside interference.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:[Illustration: THE DUTCH WEST INDIA WAREHOUSE IN NEW AMSTERDAM
2mo i, 1:(NEW YORK CITY)]
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Measured against the immense business of modern times, colonial commerce
2mo i, 1:seems perhaps trivial. That, however, is not the test of its
2mo i, 1:significance. It must be considered in relation to the growth of English
2mo i, 1:colonial trade in its entirety--a relation which can be shown by a few
2mo i, 1:startling figures. The whole export trade of England, including that to
2mo i, 1:the colonies, was, in 1704, $6,509,000. On the eve of the American
2mo i, 1:Revolution, namely, in 1772, English exports to the American colonies
2mo i, 1:alone amounted to $6,024,000; in other words, almost as much as the
2mo i, 1:whole foreign business of England two generations before. At the first
2mo i, 1:date, colonial trade was but one-twelfth of the English export business;
2mo i, 1:at the second date, it was considerably more than one-third. In 1704,
2mo i, 1:Pennsylvania bought in English markets goods to the value of $11,459; in
2mo i, 1:1772 the purchases of the same colony amounted to $507,909. In short,
2mo i, 1:Pennsylvania imports increased fifty times within sixty-eight years,
2mo i, 1:amounting in 1772 to almost the entire export trade of England to the
2mo i, 1:colonies at the opening of the century. The American colonies were
2mo i, 1:indeed a great source of wealth to English merchants.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Intercolonial Commerce.=--Although the bad roads of colonial times made
2mo i, 1:overland transportation difficult and costly, the many rivers and
2mo i, 1:harbors along the coast favored a lively water-borne trade among the
2mo i, 1:colonies. The Connecticut, Hudson, Delaware, and Susquehanna rivers in
2mo i, 1:the North and the many smaller rivers in the South made it possible for
2mo i, 1:goods to be brought from, and carried to, the interior regions in little
2mo i, 1:sailing vessels with comparative ease. Sloops laden with manufactures,
2mo i, 1:domestic and foreign, collected at some city like Providence, New York,
2mo i, 1:or Philadelphia, skirted the coasts, visited small ports, and sailed up
2mo i, 1:the navigable rivers to trade with local merchants who had for exchange
2mo i, 1:the raw materials which they had gathered in from neighboring farms.
2mo i, 1:Larger ships carried the grain, live stock, cloth, and hardware of New
2mo i, 1:England to the Southern colonies, where they were traded for tobacco,
2mo i, 1:leather, tar, and ship timber. From the harbors along the Connecticut
2mo i, 1:shores there were frequent sailings down through Long Island Sound to
2mo i, 1:Maryland, Virginia, and the distant Carolinas.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Growth of Towns.=--In connection with this thriving trade and industry
2mo i, 1:there grew up along the coast a number of prosperous commercial centers
2mo i, 1:which were soon reckoned among the first commercial towns of the whole
2mo i, 1:British empire, comparing favorably in numbers and wealth with such
2mo i, 1:ports as Liverpool and Bristol. The statistical records of that time are
2mo i, 1:mainly guesses; but we know that Philadelphia stood first in size among
2mo i, 1:these towns. Serving as the port of entry for Pennsylvania, Delaware,
2mo i, 1:and western Jersey, it had drawn within its borders, just before the
2mo i, 1:Revolution, about 25,000 inhabitants. Boston was second in rank, with
2mo i, 1:somewhat more than 20,000 people. New York, the "commercial capital of
2mo i, 1:Connecticut and old East Jersey," was slightly smaller than Boston, but
2mo i, 1:growing at a steady rate. The fourth town in size was Charleston, South
2mo i, 1:Carolina, with about 10,000 inhabitants. Newport in Rhode Island, a
2mo i, 1:center of rum manufacture and shipping, stood fifth, with a population
2mo i, 1:of about 7000. Baltimore and Norfolk were counted as "considerable
2mo i, 1:towns." In the interior, Hartford in Connecticut, Lancaster and York in
2mo i, 1:Pennsylvania, and Albany in New York, with growing populations and
2mo i, 1:increasing trade, gave prophecy of an urban America away from the
2mo i, 1:seaboard. The other towns were straggling villages. Williamsburg,
2mo i, 1:Virginia, for example, had about two hundred houses, in which dwelt a
2mo i, 1:dozen families of the gentry and a few score of tradesmen. Inland county
2mo i, 1:seats often consisted of nothing more than a log courthouse, a prison,
2mo i, 1:and one wretched inn to house judges, lawyers, and litigants during the
2mo i, 1:sessions of the court.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The leading towns exercised an influence on colonial opinion all out of
2mo i, 1:proportion to their population. They were the centers of wealth, for one
2mo i, 1:thing; of the press and political activity, for another. Merchants and
2mo i, 1:artisans could readily take concerted action on public questions arising
2mo i, 1:from their commercial operations. The towns were also centers for news,
2mo i, 1:gossip, religious controversy, and political discussion. In the market
2mo i, 1:places the farmers from the countryside learned of British policies and
2mo i, 1:laws, and so, mingling with the townsmen, were drawn into the main
2mo i, 1:currents of opinion which set in toward colonial nationalism and
2mo i, 1:independence.
