2mo i, 1:Chapter III
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:SOCIAL AND POLITICAL PROGRESS
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Colonial life, crowded as it was with hard and unremitting toil, left
2mo i, 1:scant leisure for the cultivation of the arts and sciences. There was
2mo i, 1:little money in private purses or public treasuries to be dedicated to
2mo i, 1:schools, libraries, and museums. Few there were with time to read long
2mo i, 1:and widely, and fewer still who could devote their lives to things that
2mo i, 1:delight the eye and the mind. And yet, poor and meager as the
2mo i, 1:intellectual life of the colonists may seem by way of comparison, heroic
2mo i, 1:efforts were made in every community to lift the people above the plane
2mo i, 1:of mere existence. After the first clearings were opened in the forests
2mo i, 1:those efforts were redoubled, and with lengthening years told upon the
2mo i, 1:thought and spirit of the land. The appearance, during the struggle with
2mo i, 1:England, of an extraordinary group of leaders familiar with history,
2mo i, 1:political philosophy, and the arts of war, government, and diplomacy
2mo i, 1:itself bore eloquent testimony to the high quality of the American
2mo i, 1:intellect. No one, not even the most critical, can run through the
2mo i, 1:writings of distinguished Americans scattered from Massachusetts to
2mo i, 1:Georgia--the Adamses, Ellsworth, the Morrises, the Livingstons,
2mo i, 1:Hamilton, Franklin, Washington, Madison, Marshall, Henry, the Randolphs,
2mo i, 1:and the Pinckneys--without coming to the conclusion that there was
2mo i, 1:something in American colonial life which fostered minds of depth and
2mo i, 1:power. Women surmounted even greater difficulties than the men in the
2mo i, 1:process of self-education, and their keen interest in public issues is
2mo i, 1:evident in many a record like the _Letters_ of Mrs. John Adams to her
2mo i, 1:husband during the Revolution; the writings of Mrs. Mercy Otis Warren,
2mo i, 1:the sister of James Otis, who measured her pen with the British
2mo i, 1:propagandists; and the patriot newspapers founded and managed by women.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:THE LEADERSHIP OF THE CHURCHES
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:In the intellectual life of America, the churches assumed a role of high
2mo i, 1:importance. There were abundant reasons for this. In many of the
2mo i, 1:colonies--Maryland, Pennsylvania, and New England--the religious impulse
2mo i, 1:had been one of the impelling motives in stimulating immigration. In all
2mo i, 1:the colonies, the clergy, at least in the beginning, formed the only
2mo i, 1:class with any leisure to devote to matters of the spirit. They preached
2mo i, 1:on Sundays and taught school on week days. They led in the discussion of
2mo i, 1:local problems and in the formation of political opinion, so much of
2mo i, 1:which was concerned with the relation between church and state. They
2mo i, 1:wrote books and pamphlets. They filled most of the chairs in the
2mo i, 1:colleges; under clerical guidance, intellectual and spiritual, the
2mo i, 1:Americans received their formal education. In several of the provinces
2mo i, 1:the Anglican Church was established by law. In New England the Puritans
2mo i, 1:were supreme, notwithstanding the efforts of the crown to overbear their
2mo i, 1:authority. In the Middle colonies, particularly, the multiplication of
2mo i, 1:sects made the dominance of any single denomination impossible; and in
2mo i, 1:all of them there was a growing diversity of faith, which promised in
2mo i, 1:time a separation of church and state and freedom of opinion.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Church of England.=--Virginia was the stronghold of the English
2mo i, 1:system of church and state. The Anglican faith and worship were
2mo i, 1:prescribed by law, sustained by taxes imposed on all, and favored by the
2mo i, 1:governor, the provincial councilors, and the richest planters. "The
2mo i, 1:Established Church," says Lodge, "was one of the appendages of the
2mo i, 1:Virginia aristocracy. They controlled the vestries and the ministers,
2mo i, 1:and the parish church stood not infrequently on the estate of the
2mo i, 1:planter who built and managed it." As in England, Catholics and
2mo i, 1:Protestant Dissenters were at first laid under heavy disabilities. Only
2mo i, 1:slowly and on sufferance were they admitted to the province; but when
2mo i, 1:once they were even covertly tolerated, they pressed steadily in, until,
2mo i, 1:by the Revolution, they outnumbered the adherents of the established
2mo i, 1:order.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The Church was also sanctioned by law and supported by taxes in the
2mo i, 1:Carolinas after 1704, and in Georgia after that colony passed directly
2mo i, 1:under the crown in 1754--this in spite of the fact that the majority of
2mo i, 1:the inhabitants were Dissenters. Against the protests of the Catholics
2mo i, 1:it was likewise established in Maryland. In New York, too,
2mo i, 1:notwithstanding the resistance of the Dutch, the Established Church was
2mo i, 1:fostered by the provincial officials, and the Anglicans, embracing about
2mo i, 1:one-fifteenth of the population, exerted an influence all out of
2mo i, 1:proportion to their numbers.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Many factors helped to enhance the power of the English Church in the
2mo i, 1:colonies. It was supported by the British government and the official
2mo i, 1:class sent out to the provinces. Its bishops and archbishops in England
2mo i, 1:were appointed by the king, and its faith and service were set forth by
2mo i, 1:acts of Parliament. Having its seat of power in the English monarchy, it
2mo i, 1:could hold its clergy and missionaries loyal to the crown and so
2mo i, 1:counteract to some extent the independent spirit that was growing up in
2mo i, 1:America. The Church, always a strong bulwark of the state, therefore had
2mo i, 1:a political role to play here as in England. Able bishops and far-seeing
2mo i, 1:leaders firmly grasped this fact about the middle of the eighteenth
2mo i, 1:century and redoubled their efforts to augment the influence of the
2mo i, 1:Church in provincial affairs. Unhappily for their plans they failed to
2mo i, 1:calculate in advance the effect of their methods upon dissenting
2mo i, 1:Protestants, who still cherished memories of bitter religious conflicts
2mo i, 1:in the mother country.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Puritanism in New England.=--If the established faith made for imperial
2mo i, 1:unity, the same could not be said of Puritanism. The Plymouth Pilgrims
2mo i, 1:had cast off all allegiance to the Anglican Church and established a
2mo i, 1:separate and independent congregation before they came to America. The
2mo i, 1:Puritans, essaying at first the task of reformers within the Church,
2mo i, 1:soon after their arrival in Massachusetts, likewise flung off their yoke
2mo i, 1:of union with the Anglicans. In each town a separate congregation was
2mo i, 1:organized, the male members choosing the pastor, the teachers, and the
2mo i, 1:other officers. They also composed the voters in the town meeting, where
2mo i, 1:secular matters were determined. The union of church and government was
2mo i, 1:thus complete, and uniformity of faith and life prescribed by law and
2mo i, 1:enforced by civil authorities; but this worked for local autonomy
2mo i, 1:instead of imperial unity.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The clergy became a powerful class, dominant through their learning and
2mo i, 1:their fearful denunciations of the faithless. They wrote the books for
2mo i, 1:the people to read--the famous Cotton Mather having three hundred and
2mo i, 1:eighty-three books and pamphlets to his credit. In cooperation with the
2mo i, 1:civil officers they enforced a strict observance of the Puritan
2mo i, 1:Sabbath--a day of rest that began at six o'clock on Saturday evening and
2mo i, 1:lasted until sunset on Sunday. All work, all trading, all amusement, and
2mo i, 1:all worldly conversation were absolutely prohibited during those hours.
2mo i, 1:A thoughtless maid servant who for some earthly reason smiled in church
2mo i, 1:was in danger of being banished as a vagabond. Robert Pike, a devout
2mo i, 1:Puritan, thinking the sun had gone to rest, ventured forth on horseback
2mo i, 1:one Sunday evening and was luckless enough to have a ray of light strike
2mo i, 1:him through a rift in the clouds. The next day he was brought into court
2mo i, 1:and fined for "his ungodly conduct." With persons accused of witchcraft
2mo i, 1:the Puritans were still more ruthless. When a mania of persecution swept
2mo i, 1:over Massachusetts in 1692, eighteen people were hanged, one was pressed
2mo i, 1:to death, many suffered imprisonment, and two died in jail.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Just about this time, however, there came a break in the uniformity of
2mo i, 1:Puritan rule. The crown and church in England had long looked upon it
2mo i, 1:with disfavor, and in 1684 King Charles II annulled the old charter of
2mo i, 1:the Massachusetts Bay Company. A new document issued seven years later
2mo i, 1:wrested from the Puritans of the colony the right to elect their own
2mo i, 1:governor and reserved the power of appointment to the king. It also
2mo i, 1:abolished the rule limiting the suffrage to church members, substituting
2mo i, 1:for it a simple property qualification. Thus a royal governor and an
2mo i, 1:official family, certain to be Episcopalian in faith and monarchist in
2mo i, 1:sympathies, were forced upon Massachusetts; and members of all religious
2mo i, 1:denominations, if they had the required amount of property, were
2mo i, 1:permitted to take part in elections. By this act in the name of the
2mo i, 1:crown, the Puritan monopoly was broken down in Massachusetts, and that
2mo i, 1:province was brought into line with Connecticut, Rhode Island, and New
2mo i, 1:Hampshire, where property, not religious faith, was the test for the
2mo i, 1:suffrage.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Growth of Religious Toleration.=--Though neither the Anglicans of
2mo i, 1:Virginia nor the Puritans of Massachusetts believed in toleration for
2mo i, 1:other denominations, that principle was strictly applied in Rhode
2mo i, 1:Island. There, under the leadership of Roger Williams, liberty in
2mo i, 1:matters of conscience was established in the beginning. Maryland, by
2mo i, 1:granting in 1649 freedom to those who professed to believe in Jesus
2mo i, 1:Christ, opened its gates to all Christians; and Pennsylvania, true to
2mo i, 1:the tenets of the Friends, gave freedom of conscience to those "who
2mo i, 1:confess and acknowledge the one Almighty and Eternal God to be the
2mo i, 1:creator, upholder, and ruler of the World." By one circumstance or
2mo i, 1:another, the Middle colonies were thus early characterized by diversity
2mo i, 1:rather than uniformity of opinion. Dutch Protestants, Huguenots,
2mo i, 1:Quakers, Baptists, Presbyterians, New Lights, Moravians, Lutherans,
2mo i, 1:Catholics, and other denominations became too strongly intrenched and
2mo i, 1:too widely scattered to permit any one of them to rule, if it had
2mo i, 1:desired to do so. There were communities and indeed whole sections where
2mo i, 1:one or another church prevailed, but in no colony was a legislature
2mo i, 1:steadily controlled by a single group. Toleration encouraged diversity,
2mo i, 1:and diversity, in turn, worked for greater toleration.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The government and faith of the dissenting denominations conspired with
2mo i, 1:economic and political tendencies to draw America away from the English
2mo i, 1:state. Presbyterians, Quakers, Baptists, and Puritans had no hierarchy
2mo i, 1:of bishops and archbishops to bind them to the seat of power in London.
2mo i, 1:Neither did they look to that metropolis for guidance in interpreting
2mo i, 1:articles of faith. Local self-government in matters ecclesiastical
2mo i, 1:helped to train them for local self-government in matters political. The
2mo i, 1:spirit of independence which led Dissenters to revolt in the Old World,
2mo i, 1:nourished as it was amid favorable circumstances in the New World, made
2mo i, 1:them all the more zealous in the defense of every right against
2mo i, 1:authority imposed from without.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:SCHOOLS AND COLLEGES
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Religion and Local Schools.=--One of the first cares of each Protestant
2mo i, 1:denomination was the education of the children in the faith. In this
2mo i, 1:work the Bible became the center of interest. The English version was
2mo i, 1:indeed the one book of the people. Farmers, shopkeepers, and artisans,
2mo i, 1:whose life had once been bounded by the daily routine of labor, found in
2mo i, 1:the Scriptures not only an inspiration to religious conduct, but also a
2mo i, 1:book of romance, travel, and history. "Legend and annal," says John
2mo i, 1:Richard Green, "war-song and psalm, state-roll and biography, the mighty
2mo i, 1:voices of prophets, the parables of Evangelists, stories of mission
2mo i, 1:journeys, of perils by sea and among the heathen, philosophic arguments,
2mo i, 1:apocalyptic visions, all were flung broadcast over minds unoccupied for
2mo i, 1:the most part by any rival learning.... As a mere literary monument, the
2mo i, 1:English version of the Bible remains the noblest example of the English
2mo i, 1:tongue." It was the King James version just from the press that the
2mo i, 1:Pilgrims brought across the sea with them.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:For the authority of the Established Church was substituted the
2mo i, 1:authority of the Scriptures. The Puritans devised a catechism based upon
2mo i, 1:their interpretation of the Bible, and, very soon after their arrival in
2mo i, 1:America, they ordered all parents and masters of servants to be diligent
2mo i, 1:in seeing that their children and wards were taught to read religious
2mo i, 1:works and give answers to the religious questions. Massachusetts was
2mo i, 1:scarcely twenty years old before education of this character was
2mo i, 1:declared to be compulsory, and provision was made for public schools
2mo i, 1:where those not taught at home could receive instruction in reading and
2mo i, 1:writing.
2mo i, 1:
