2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Outside of New England the idea of compulsory education was not regarded
2mo i, 1:with the same favor; but the whole land was nevertheless dotted with
2mo i, 1:little schools kept by "dames, itinerant teachers, or local parsons."
2mo i, 1:Whether we turn to the life of Franklin in the North or Washington in
2mo i, 1:the South, we read of tiny schoolhouses, where boys, and sometimes
2mo i, 1:girls, were taught to read and write. Where there were no schools,
2mo i, 1:fathers and mothers of the better kind gave their children the rudiments
2mo i, 1:of learning. Though illiteracy was widespread, there is evidence to show
2mo i, 1:that the diffusion of knowledge among the masses was making steady
2mo i, 1:progress all through the eighteenth century.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Religion and Higher Learning.=--Religious motives entered into the
2mo i, 1:establishment of colleges as well as local schools. Harvard, founded in
2mo i, 1:1636, and Yale, opened in 1718, were intended primarily to train
2mo i, 1:"learned and godly ministers" for the Puritan churches of New England.
2mo i, 1:To the far North, Dartmouth, chartered in 1769, was designed first as a
2mo i, 1:mission to the Indians and then as a college for the sons of New England
2mo i, 1:farmers preparing to preach, teach, or practice law. The College of New
2mo i, 1:Jersey, organized in 1746 and removed to Princeton eleven years later,
2mo i, 1:was sustained by the Presbyterians. Two colleges looked to the
2mo i, 1:Established Church as their source of inspiration and support: William
2mo i, 1:and Mary, founded in Virginia in 1693, and King's College, now Columbia
2mo i, 1:University, chartered by King George II in 1754, on an appeal from the
2mo i, 1:New York Anglicans, alarmed at the growth of religious dissent and the
2mo i, 1:"republican tendencies" of the age. Two colleges revealed a drift away
2mo i, 1:from sectarianism. Brown, established in Rhode Island in 1764, and the
2mo i, 1:Philadelphia Academy, forerunner of the University of Pennsylvania,
2mo i, 1:organized by Benjamin Franklin, reflected the spirit of toleration by
2mo i, 1:giving representation on the board of trustees to several religious
2mo i, 1:sects. It was Franklin's idea that his college should prepare young men
2mo i, 1:to serve in public office as leaders of the people and ornaments to
2mo i, 1:their country.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Self-education in America.=--Important as were these institutions of
2mo i, 1:learning, higher education was by no means confined within their walls.
2mo i, 1:Many well-to-do families sent their sons to Oxford or Cambridge in
2mo i, 1:England. Private tutoring in the home was common. In still more families
2mo i, 1:there were intelligent children who grew up in the great colonial school
2mo i, 1:of adversity and who trained themselves until, in every contest of mind
2mo i, 1:and wit, they could vie with the sons of Harvard or William and Mary or
2mo i, 1:any other college. Such, for example, was Benjamin Franklin, whose
2mo i, 1:charming autobiography, in addition to being an American classic, is a
2mo i, 1:fine record of self-education. His formal training in the classroom was
2mo i, 1:limited to a few years at a local school in Boston; but his
2mo i, 1:self-education continued throughout his life. He early manifested a zeal
2mo i, 1:for reading, and devoured, he tells us, his father's dry library on
2mo i, 1:theology, Bunyan's works, Defoe's writings, Plutarch's _Lives_, Locke's
2mo i, 1:_On the Human Understanding_, and innumerable volumes dealing with
2mo i, 1:secular subjects. His literary style, perhaps the best of his time,
2mo i, 1:Franklin acquired by the diligent and repeated analysis of the
2mo i, 1:_Spectator_. In a life crowded with labors, he found time to read widely
2mo i, 1:in natural science and to win single-handed recognition at the hands of
2mo i, 1:European savants for his discoveries in electricity. By his own efforts
2mo i, 1:he "attained an acquaintance" with Latin, Italian, French, and Spanish,
2mo i, 1:thus unconsciously preparing himself for the day when he was to speak
2mo i, 1:for all America at the court of the king of France.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Lesser lights than Franklin, educated by the same process, were found
2mo i, 1:all over colonial America. From this fruitful source of native ability,
2mo i, 1:self-educated, the American cause drew great strength in the trials of
2mo i, 1:the Revolution.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:THE COLONIAL PRESS
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Rise of the Newspaper.=--The evolution of American democracy into a
2mo i, 1:government by public opinion, enlightened by the open discussion of
2mo i, 1:political questions, was in no small measure aided by a free press. That
2mo i, 1:too, like education, was a matter of slow growth. A printing press was
2mo i, 1:brought to Massachusetts in 1639, but it was put in charge of an
2mo i, 1:official censor and limited to the publication of religious works. Forty
2mo i, 1:years elapsed before the first newspaper appeared, bearing the curious
2mo i, 1:title, _Public Occurrences Both Foreign and Domestic_, and it had not
2mo i, 1:been running very long before the government of Massachusetts suppressed
2mo i, 1:it for discussing a political question.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Publishing, indeed, seemed to be a precarious business; but in 1704
2mo i, 1:there came a second venture in journalism, _The Boston News-Letter_,
2mo i, 1:which proved to be a more lasting enterprise because it refrained from
2mo i, 1:criticizing the authorities. Still the public interest languished. When
2mo i, 1:Franklin's brother, James, began to issue his _New England Courant_
2mo i, 1:about 1720, his friends sought to dissuade him, saying that one
2mo i, 1:newspaper was enough for America. Nevertheless he continued it; and his
2mo i, 1:confidence in the future was rewarded. In nearly every colony a gazette
2mo i, 1:or chronicle appeared within the next thirty years or more. Benjamin
2mo i, 1:Franklin was able to record in 1771 that America had twenty-five
2mo i, 1:newspapers. Boston led with five. Philadelphia had three: two in English
2mo i, 1:and one in German.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Censorship and Restraints on the Press.=--The idea of printing,
2mo i, 1:unlicensed by the government and uncontrolled by the church, was,
2mo i, 1:however, slow in taking form. The founders of the American colonies had
2mo i, 1:never known what it was to have the free and open publication of books,
2mo i, 1:pamphlets, broadsides, and newspapers. When the art of printing was
2mo i, 1:first discovered, the control of publishing was vested in clerical
2mo i, 1:authorities. After the establishment of the State Church in England in
2mo i, 1:the reign of Elizabeth, censorship of the press became a part of royal
2mo i, 1:prerogative. Printing was restricted to Oxford, Cambridge, and London;
2mo i, 1:and no one could publish anything without previous approval of the
2mo i, 1:official censor. When the Puritans were in power, the popular party,
2mo i, 1:with a zeal which rivaled that of the crown, sought, in turn, to silence
2mo i, 1:royalist and clerical writers by a vigorous censorship. After the
2mo i, 1:restoration of the monarchy, control of the press was once more placed
2mo i, 1:in royal hands, where it remained until 1695, when Parliament, by
2mo i, 1:failing to renew the licensing act, did away entirely with the official
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:censorship. By that time political parties were so powerful and so
2mo i, 1:active and printing presses were so numerous that official review of all
2mo i, 1:published matter became a sheer impossibility.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:In America, likewise, some troublesome questions arose in connection
2mo i, 1:with freedom of the press. The Puritans of Massachusetts were no less
2mo i, 1:anxious than King Charles or the Archbishop of London to shut out from
2mo i, 1:the prying eyes of the people all literature "not mete for them to
2mo i, 1:read"; and so they established a system of official licensing for
2mo i, 1:presses, which lasted until 1755. In the other colonies where there was
2mo i, 1:more diversity of opinion and publishers could set up in business with
2mo i, 1:impunity, they were nevertheless constantly liable to arrest for
2mo i, 1:printing anything displeasing to the colonial governments. In 1721 the
2mo i, 1:editor of the _Mercury_ in Philadelphia was called before the
2mo i, 1:proprietary council and ordered to apologize for a political article,
2mo i, 1:and for a later offense of a similar character he was thrown into jail.
2mo i, 1:A still more famous case was that of Peter Zenger, a New York publisher,
2mo i, 1:who was arrested in 1735 for criticising the administration. Lawyers who
2mo i, 1:ventured to defend the unlucky editor were deprived of their licenses to
2mo i, 1:practice, and it became necessary to bring an attorney all the way from
2mo i, 1:Philadelphia. By this time the tension of feeling was high, and the
2mo i, 1:approbation of the public was forthcoming when the lawyer for the
2mo i, 1:defense exclaimed to the jury that the very cause of liberty itself, not
2mo i, 1:that of the poor printer, was on trial! The verdict for Zenger, when it
2mo i, 1:finally came, was the signal for an outburst of popular rejoicing.
2mo i, 1:Already the people of King George's province knew how precious a thing
2mo i, 1:is the freedom of the press.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Thanks to the schools, few and scattered as they were, and to the
2mo i, 1:vigilance of parents, a very large portion, perhaps nearly one-half, of
2mo i, 1:the colonists could read. Through the newspapers, pamphlets, and
2mo i, 1:almanacs that streamed from the types, the people could follow the
2mo i, 1:course of public events and grasp the significance of political
2mo i, 1:arguments. An American opinion was in the process of making--an
2mo i, 1:independent opinion nourished by the press and enriched by discussions
2mo i, 1:around the fireside and at the taverns. When the day of resistance to
2mo i, 1:British rule came, government by opinion was at hand. For every person
2mo i, 1:who could hear the voice of Patrick Henry and Samuel Adams, there were a
2mo i, 1:thousand who could see their appeals on the printed page. Men who had
2mo i, 1:spelled out their letters while poring over Franklin's _Poor Richard's
2mo i, 1:Almanac_ lived to read Thomas Paine's thrilling call to arms.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:THE EVOLUTION IN POLITICAL INSTITUTIONS
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Two very distinct lines of development appeared in colonial politics.
2mo i, 1:The one, exalting royal rights and aristocratic privileges, was the
2mo i, 1:drift toward provincial government through royal officers appointed in
2mo i, 1:England. The other, leading toward democracy and self-government, was
2mo i, 1:the growth in the power of the popular legislative assembly. Each
2mo i, 1:movement gave impetus to the other, with increasing force during the
2mo i, 1:passing years, until at last the final collision between the two ideals
2mo i, 1:of government came in the war of independence.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Royal Provinces.=--Of the thirteen English colonies eight were
2mo i, 1:royal provinces in 1776, with governors appointed by the king. Virginia
2mo i, 1:passed under the direct rule of the crown in 1624, when the charter of
2mo i, 1:the London Company was annulled. The Massachusetts Bay corporation lost
2mo i, 1:its charter in 1684, and the new instrument granted seven years later
2mo i, 1:stripped the colonists of the right to choose their chief executive. In
2mo i, 1:the early decades of the eighteenth century both the Carolinas were
2mo i, 1:given the provincial instead of the proprietary form. New Hampshire,
2mo i, 1:severed from Massachusetts in 1679, and Georgia, surrendered by the
2mo i, 1:trustees in 1752, went into the hands of the crown. New York,
2mo i, 1:transferred to the Duke of York on its capture from the Dutch in 1664,
2mo i, 1:became a province when he took the title of James II in 1685. New
2mo i, 1:Jersey, after remaining for nearly forty years under proprietors, was
2mo i, 1:brought directly under the king in 1702. Maryland, Pennsylvania, and
2mo i, 1:Delaware, although they retained their proprietary character until the
2mo i, 1:Revolution, were in some respects like the royal colonies, for their
2mo i, 1:governors were as independent of popular choice as were the appointees
2mo i, 1:of King George. Only two colonies, Rhode Island and Connecticut,
2mo i, 1:retained full self-government on the eve of the Revolution. They alone
2mo i, 1:had governors and legislatures entirely of their own choosing.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The chief officer of the royal province was the governor, who enjoyed
2mo i, 1:high and important powers which he naturally sought to augment at every
2mo i, 1:turn. He enforced the laws and, usually with the consent of a council,
2mo i, 1:appointed the civil and military officers. He granted pardons and
2mo i, 1:reprieves; he was head of the highest court; he was commander-in-chief
2mo i, 1:of the militia; he levied troops for defense and enforced martial law in
2mo i, 1:time of invasion, war, and rebellion. In all the provinces, except
2mo i, 1:Massachusetts, he named the councilors who composed the upper house of
2mo i, 1:the legislature and was likely to choose those who favored his claims.
2mo i, 1:He summoned, adjourned, and dissolved the popular assembly, or the lower
2mo i, 1:house; he laid before it the projects of law desired by the crown; and
2mo i, 1:he vetoed measures which he thought objectionable. Here were in America
2mo i, 1:all the elements of royal prerogative against which Hampden had
2mo i, 1:protested and Cromwell had battled in England.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:[Illustration: THE ROYAL GOVERNOR'S PALACE AT NEW BERNE]
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The colonial governors were generally surrounded by a body of
2mo i, 1:office-seekers and hunters for land grants. Some of them were noblemen
2mo i, 1:of broken estates who had come to America to improve their fortunes. The
2mo i, 1:pretensions of this circle grated on colonial nerves, and privileges
2mo i, 1:granted to them, often at the expense of colonists, did much to deepen
2mo i, 1:popular antipathy to the British government. Favors extended to
2mo i, 1:adherents of the Established Church displeased Dissenters. The
2mo i, 1:reappearance of this formidable union of church and state, from which
2mo i, 1:they had fled, stirred anew the ancient wrath against that combination.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Colonial Assembly.=--Coincident with the drift toward
2mo i, 1:administration through royal governors was the second and opposite
2mo i, 1:tendency, namely, a steady growth in the practice of self-government.
2mo i, 1:The voters of England had long been accustomed to share in taxation and
2mo i, 1:law-making through representatives in Parliament, and the idea was early
2mo i, 1:introduced in America. Virginia was only twelve years old (1619) when
2mo i, 1:its first representative assembly appeared. As the towns of
2mo i, 1:Massachusetts multiplied and it became impossible for all the members of
2mo i, 1:the corporation to meet at one place, the representative idea was
2mo i, 1:adopted, in 1633. The river towns of Connecticut formed a representative
2mo i, 1:system under their "Fundamental Orders" of 1639, and the entire colony
2mo i, 1:was given a royal charter in 1662. Generosity, as well as practical
2mo i, 1:considerations, induced such proprietors as Lord Baltimore and William
2mo i, 1:Penn to invite their colonists to share in the government as soon as any
2mo i, 1:considerable settlements were made. Thus by one process or another every
2mo i, 1:one of the colonies secured a popular assembly.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:It is true that in the provision for popular elections, the suffrage was
2mo i, 1:finally restricted to property owners or taxpayers, with a leaning
2mo i, 1:toward the freehold qualification. In Virginia, the rural voter had to
2mo i, 1:be a freeholder owning at least fifty acres of land, if there was no
2mo i, 1:house on it, or twenty-five acres with a house twenty-five feet square.
2mo i, 1:In Massachusetts, the voter for member of the assembly under the charter
2mo i, 1:of 1691 had to be a freeholder of an estate worth forty shillings a year
2mo i, 1:at least or of other property to the value of forty pounds sterling. In
2mo i, 1:Pennsylvania, the suffrage was granted to freeholders owning fifty acres
2mo i, 1:or more of land well seated, twelve acres cleared, and to other persons
2mo i, 1:worth at least fifty pounds in lawful money.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Restrictions like these undoubtedly excluded from the suffrage a very
2mo i, 1:considerable number of men, particularly the mechanics and artisans of
2mo i, 1:the towns, who were by no means content with their position.
2mo i, 1:Nevertheless, it was relatively easy for any man to acquire a small
2mo i, 1:freehold, so cheap and abundant was land; and in fact a large proportion
2mo i, 1:of the colonists were land owners. Thus the assemblies, in spite of the
2mo i, 1:limited suffrage, acquired a democratic tone.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The popular character of the assemblies increased as they became engaged
2mo i, 1:in battles with the royal and proprietary governors. When called upon by
2mo i, 1:the executive to make provision for the support of the administration,
2mo i, 1:the legislature took advantage of the opportunity to make terms in the
2mo i, 1:interest of the taxpayers. It made annual, not permanent, grants of
2mo i, 1:money to pay official salaries and then insisted upon electing a
2mo i, 1:treasurer to dole it out. Thus the colonists learned some of the
2mo i, 1:mysteries of public finance, as well as the management of rapacious
2mo i, 1:officials. The legislature also used its power over money grants to
2mo i, 1:force the governor to sign bills which he would otherwise have vetoed.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Contests between Legislatures and Governors.=--As may be imagined, many
2mo i, 1:and bitter were the contests between the royal and proprietary governors
2mo i, 1:and the colonial assemblies. Franklin relates an amusing story of how
2mo i, 1:the Pennsylvania assembly held in one hand a bill for the executive to
2mo i, 1:sign and, in the other hand, the money to pay his salary. Then, with sly
2mo i, 1:humor, Franklin adds: "Do not, my courteous reader, take pet at our
2mo i, 1:proprietary constitution for these our bargain and sale proceedings in
2mo i, 1:legislation. It is a happy country where justice and what was your own
2mo i, 1:before can be had for ready money. It is another addition to the value
2mo i, 1:of money and of course another spur to industry. Every land is not so
2mo i, 1:blessed."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:It must not be thought, however, that every governor got off as easily
2mo i, 1:as Franklin's tale implies. On the contrary, the legislatures, like
2mo i, 1:Caesar, fed upon meat that made them great and steadily encroached upon
2mo i, 1:executive prerogatives as they tried out and found their strength. If
2mo i, 1:we may believe contemporary laments, the power of the crown in America
2mo i, 1:was diminishing when it was struck down altogether. In New York, the
2mo i, 1:friends of the governor complained in 1747 that "the inhabitants of
2mo i, 1:plantations are generally educated in republican principles; upon
2mo i, 1:republican principles all is conducted. Little more than a shadow of
2mo i, 1:royal authority remains in the Northern colonies." "Here," echoed the
2mo i, 1:governor of South Carolina, the following year, "levelling principles
2mo i, 1:prevail; the frame of the civil government is unhinged; a governor, if
2mo i, 1:he would be idolized, must betray his trust; the people have got their
2mo i, 1:whole administration in their hands; the election of the members of the
2mo i, 1:assembly is by ballot; not civil posts only, but all ecclesiastical
2mo i, 1:preferments, are in the disposal or election of the people."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Though baffled by the "levelling principles" of the colonial assemblies,
2mo i, 1:the governors did not give up the case as hopeless. Instead they evolved
2mo i, 1:a system of policy and action which they thought could bring the
2mo i, 1:obstinate provincials to terms. That system, traceable in their letters
2mo i, 1:to the government in London, consisted of three parts: (1) the royal
2mo i, 1:officers in the colonies were to be made independent of the legislatures
2mo i, 1:by taxes imposed by acts of Parliament; (2) a British standing army was
2mo i, 1:to be maintained in America; (3) the remaining colonial charters were to
2mo i, 1:be revoked and government by direct royal authority was to be enlarged.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Such a system seemed plausible enough to King George III and to many
2mo i, 1:ministers of the crown in London. With governors, courts, and an army
2mo i, 1:independent of the colonists, they imagined it would be easy to carry
2mo i, 1:out both royal orders and acts of Parliament. This reasoning seemed both
2mo i, 1:practical and logical. Nor was it founded on theory, for it came fresh
2mo i, 1:from the governors themselves. It was wanting in one respect only. It
2mo i, 1:failed to take account of the fact that the American people were growing
2mo i, 1:strong in the practice of self-government and could dispense with the
2mo i, 1:tutelage of the British ministry, no matter how excellent it might be or
2mo i, 1:how benevolent its intentions.
