2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:CHAPTER IV
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:THE DEVELOPMENT OF COLONIAL NATIONALISM
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:It is one of the well-known facts of history that a people loosely
2mo i, 1:united by domestic ties of a political and economic nature, even a
2mo i, 1:people torn by domestic strife, may be welded into a solid and compact
2mo i, 1:body by an attack from a foreign power. The imperative call to common
2mo i, 1:defense, the habit of sharing common burdens, the fusing force of common
2mo i, 1:service--these things, induced by the necessity of resisting outside
2mo i, 1:interference, act as an amalgam drawing together all elements, except,
2mo i, 1:perhaps, the most discordant. The presence of the enemy allays the most
2mo i, 1:virulent of quarrels, temporarily at least. "Politics," runs an old
2mo i, 1:saying, "stops at the water's edge."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:This ancient political principle, so well understood in diplomatic
2mo i, 1:circles, applied nearly as well to the original thirteen American
2mo i, 1:colonies as to the countries of Europe. The necessity for common
2mo i, 1:defense, if not equally great, was certainly always pressing. Though it
2mo i, 1:has long been the practice to speak of the early settlements as founded
2mo i, 1:in "a wilderness," this was not actually the case. From the earliest
2mo i, 1:days of Jamestown on through the years, the American people were
2mo i, 1:confronted by dangers from without. All about their tiny settlements
2mo i, 1:were Indians, growing more and more hostile as the frontier advanced and
2mo i, 1:as sharp conflicts over land aroused angry passions. To the south and
2mo i, 1:west was the power of Spain, humiliated, it is true, by the disaster to
2mo i, 1:the Armada, but still presenting an imposing front to the British
2mo i, 1:empire. To the north and west were the French, ambitious, energetic,
2mo i, 1:imperial in temper, and prepared to contest on land and water the
2mo i, 1:advance of British dominion in America.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:RELATIONS WITH THE INDIANS AND THE FRENCH
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Indian Affairs.=--It is difficult to make general statements about the
2mo i, 1:relations of the colonists to the Indians. The problem was presented in
2mo i, 1:different shape in different sections of America. It was not handled
2mo i, 1:according to any coherent or uniform plan by the British government,
2mo i, 1:which alone could speak for all the provinces at the same time. Neither
2mo i, 1:did the proprietors and the governors who succeeded one another, in an
2mo i, 1:irregular train, have the consistent policy or the matured experience
2mo i, 1:necessary for dealing wisely with Indian matters. As the difficulties
2mo i, 1:arose mainly on the frontiers, where the restless and pushing pioneers
2mo i, 1:were making their way with gun and ax, nearly everything that happened
2mo i, 1:was the result of chance rather than of calculation. A personal quarrel
2mo i, 1:between traders and an Indian, a jug of whisky, a keg of gunpowder, the
2mo i, 1:exchange of guns for furs, personal treachery, or a flash of bad temper
2mo i, 1:often set in motion destructive forces of the most terrible character.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:On one side of the ledger may be set innumerable generous records--of
2mo i, 1:Squanto and Samoset teaching the Pilgrims the ways of the wilds; of
2mo i, 1:Roger Williams buying his lands from the friendly natives; or of William
2mo i, 1:Penn treating with them on his arrival in America. On the other side of
2mo i, 1:the ledger must be recorded many a cruel and bloody conflict as the
2mo i, 1:frontier rolled westward with deadly precision. The Pequots on the
2mo i, 1:Connecticut border, sensing their doom, fell upon the tiny settlements
2mo i, 1:with awful fury in 1637 only to meet with equally terrible punishment. A
2mo i, 1:generation later, King Philip, son of Massasoit, the friend of the
2mo i, 1:Pilgrims, called his tribesmen to a war of extermination which brought
2mo i, 1:the strength of all New England to the field and ended in his own
2mo i, 1:destruction. In New York, the relations with the Indians, especially
2mo i, 1:with the Algonquins and the Mohawks, were marked by periodic and
2mo i, 1:desperate wars. Virginia and her Southern neighbors suffered as did New
2mo i, 1:England. In 1622 Opecacano, a brother of Powhatan, the friend of the
2mo i, 1:Jamestown settlers, launched a general massacre; and in 1644 he
2mo i, 1:attempted a war of extermination. In 1675 the whole frontier was ablaze.
2mo i, 1:Nathaniel Bacon vainly attempted to stir the colonial governor to put up
2mo i, 1:an adequate defense and, failing in that plea, himself headed a revolt
2mo i, 1:and a successful expedition against the Indians. As the Virginia
2mo i, 1:outposts advanced into the Kentucky country, the strife with the natives
2mo i, 1:was transferred to that "dark and bloody ground"; while to the
2mo i, 1:southeast, a desperate struggle with the Tuscaroras called forth the
2mo i, 1:combined forces of the two Carolinas and Virginia.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:[Illustration: _From an old print._
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:VIRGINIANS DEFENDING THEMSELVES AGAINST THE INDIANS]
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:From such horrors New Jersey and Delaware were saved on account of their
2mo i, 1:geographical location. Pennsylvania, consistently following a policy of
2mo i, 1:conciliation, was likewise spared until her western vanguard came into
2mo i, 1:full conflict with the allied French and Indians. Georgia, by clever
2mo i, 1:negotiations and treaties of alliance, managed to keep on fair terms
2mo i, 1:with her belligerent Cherokees and Creeks. But neither diplomacy nor
2mo i, 1:generosity could stay the inevitable conflict as the frontier advanced,
2mo i, 1:especially after the French soldiers enlisted the Indians in their
2mo i, 1:imperial enterprises. It was then that desultory fighting became general
2mo i, 1:warfare.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:[Illustration: ENGLISH, FRENCH, AND SPANISH POSSESSIONS IN AMERICA,
2mo i, 1:1750]
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Early Relations with the French.=--During the first decades of French
2mo i, 1:exploration and settlement in the St. Lawrence country, the English
2mo i, 1:colonies, engrossed with their own problems, gave little or no thought
2mo i, 1:to their distant neighbors. Quebec, founded in 1608, and Montreal, in
2mo i, 1:1642, were too far away, too small in population, and too slight in
2mo i, 1:strength to be much of a menace to Boston, Hartford, or New York. It was
2mo i, 1:the statesmen in France and England, rather than the colonists in
2mo i, 1:America, who first grasped the significance of the slowly converging
2mo i, 1:empires in North America. It was the ambition of Louis XIV of France,
2mo i, 1:rather than the labors of Jesuit missionaries and French rangers, that
2mo i, 1:sounded the first note of colonial alarm.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Evidence of this lies in the fact that three conflicts between the
2mo i, 1:English and the French occurred before their advancing frontiers met on
2mo i, 1:the Pennsylvania border. King William's War (1689-1697), Queen Anne's
2mo i, 1:War (1701-1713), and King George's War (1744-1748) owed their origins
2mo i, 1:and their endings mainly to the intrigues and rivalries of European
2mo i, 1:powers, although they all involved the American colonies in struggles
2mo i, 1:with the French and their savage allies.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Clash in the Ohio Valley.=--The second of these wars had hardly
2mo i, 1:closed, however, before the English colonists themselves began to be
2mo i, 1:seriously alarmed about the rapidly expanding French dominion in the
2mo i, 1:West. Marquette and Joliet, who opened the Lake region, and La Salle,
2mo i, 1:who in 1682 had gone down the Mississippi to the Gulf, had been followed
2mo i, 1:by the builders of forts. In 1718, the French founded New Orleans, thus
2mo i, 1:taking possession of the gateway to the Mississippi as well as the St.
2mo i, 1:Lawrence. A few years later they built Fort Niagara; in 1731 they
2mo i, 1:occupied Crown Point; in 1749 they formally announced their dominion
2mo i, 1:over all the territory drained by the Ohio River. Having asserted this
2mo i, 1:lofty claim, they set out to make it good by constructing in the years
2mo i, 1:1752-1754 Fort Le Boeuf near Lake Erie, Fort Venango on the upper
2mo i, 1:waters of the Allegheny, and Fort Duquesne at the junction of the
2mo i, 1:streams forming the Ohio. Though they were warned by George Washington,
2mo i, 1:in the name of the governor of Virginia, to keep out of territory "so
2mo i, 1:notoriously known to be property of the crown of Great Britain," the
2mo i, 1:French showed no signs of relinquishing their pretensions.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:[Illustration: _From an old print_
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:BRADDOCK'S RETREAT]
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Final Phase--the French and Indian War.=--Thus it happened that the
2mo i, 1:shot which opened the Seven Years' War, known in America as the French
2mo i, 1:and Indian War, was fired in the wilds of Pennsylvania. There began the
2mo i, 1:conflict that spread to Europe and even Asia and finally involved
2mo i, 1:England and Prussia, on the one side, and France, Austria, Spain, and
2mo i, 1:minor powers on the other. On American soil, the defeat of Braddock in
2mo i, 1:1755 and Wolfe's exploit in capturing Quebec four years later were the
2mo i, 1:dramatic features. On the continent of Europe, England subsidized
2mo i, 1:Prussian arms to hold France at bay. In India, on the banks of the
2mo i, 1:Ganges, as on the banks of the St. Lawrence, British arms were
2mo i, 1:triumphant. Well could the historian write: "Conquests equaling in
2mo i, 1:rapidity and far surpassing in magnitude those of Cortes and Pizarro had
2mo i, 1:been achieved in the East." Well could the merchants of London declare
2mo i, 1:that under the administration of William Pitt, the imperial genius of
2mo i, 1:this world-wide conflict, commerce had been "united with and made to
2mo i, 1:flourish by war."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:From the point of view of the British empire, the results of the war
2mo i, 1:were momentous. By the peace of 1763, Canada and the territory east of
2mo i, 1:the Mississippi, except New Orleans, passed under the British flag. The
2mo i, 1:remainder of the Louisiana territory was transferred to Spain and French
2mo i, 1:imperial ambitions on the American continent were laid to rest. In
2mo i, 1:exchange for Havana, which the British had seized during the war, Spain
2mo i, 1:ceded to King George the colony of Florida. Not without warrant did
2mo i, 1:Macaulay write in after years that Pitt "was the first Englishman of his
2mo i, 1:time; and he had made England the first country in the world."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:THE EFFECTS OF WARFARE ON THE COLONIES
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The various wars with the French and the Indians, trivial in detail as
2mo i, 1:they seem to-day, had a profound influence on colonial life and on the
2mo i, 1:destiny of America. Circumstances beyond the control of popular
2mo i, 1:assemblies, jealous of their individual powers, compelled cooperation
2mo i, 1:among them, grudging and stingy no doubt, but still cooperation. The
2mo i, 1:American people, more eager to be busy in their fields or at their
2mo i, 1:trades, were simply forced to raise and support armies, to learn the
2mo i, 1:arts of warfare, and to practice, if in a small theater, the science of
2mo i, 1:statecraft. These forces, all cumulative, drove the colonists, so
2mo i, 1:tenaciously provincial in their habits, in the direction of nationalism.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The New England Confederation.=--It was in their efforts to deal with
2mo i, 1:the problems presented by the Indian and French menace that the
2mo i, 1:Americans took the first steps toward union. Though there were many
2mo i, 1:common ties among the settlers of New England, it required a deadly
2mo i, 1:fear of the Indians to produce in 1643 the New England Confederation,
2mo i, 1:composed of Massachusetts, Plymouth, Connecticut, and New Haven. The
2mo i, 1:colonies so united were bound together in "a firm and perpetual league
2mo i, 1:of friendship and amity for offense and defense, mutual service and
2mo i, 1:succor, upon all just occasions." They made provision for distributing
2mo i, 1:the burdens of wars among the members and provided for a congress of
2mo i, 1:commissioners from each colony to determine upon common policies. For
2mo i, 1:some twenty years the Confederation was active and it continued to hold
2mo i, 1:meetings until after the extinction of the Indian peril on the immediate
2mo i, 1:border.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Virginia, no less than Massachusetts, was aware of the importance of
2mo i, 1:intercolonial cooperation. In the middle of the seventeenth century, the
2mo i, 1:Old Dominion began treaties of commerce and amity with New York and the
2mo i, 1:colonies of New England. In 1684 delegates from Virginia met at Albany
2mo i, 1:with the agents of New York and Massachusetts to discuss problems of
2mo i, 1:mutual defense. A few years later the Old Dominion cooperated loyally
2mo i, 1:with the Carolinas in defending their borders against Indian forays.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Albany Plan of Union.=--An attempt at a general colonial union was
2mo i, 1:made in 1754. On the suggestion of the Lords of Trade in England, a
2mo i, 1:conference was held at Albany to consider Indian relations, to devise
2mo i, 1:measures of defense against the French, and to enter into "articles of
2mo i, 1:union and confederation for the general defense of his Majesty's
2mo i, 1:subjects and interests in North America as well in time of peace as of
2mo i, 1:war." New Hampshire, Massachusetts, Connecticut, Rhode Island, New York,
2mo i, 1:Pennsylvania, and Maryland were represented. After a long discussion, a
2mo i, 1:plan of union, drafted mainly, it seems, by Benjamin Franklin, was
2mo i, 1:adopted and sent to the colonies and the crown for approval. The
2mo i, 1:colonies, jealous of their individual rights, refused to accept the
2mo i, 1:scheme and the king disapproved it for the reason, Franklin said, that
2mo i, 1:it had "too much weight in the democratic part of the constitution."
2mo i, 1:Though the Albany union failed, the document is still worthy of study
2mo i, 1:because it forecast many of the perplexing problems that were not solved
2mo i, 1:until thirty-three years afterward, when another convention of which
2mo i, 1:also Franklin was a member drafted the Constitution of the United
2mo i, 1:States.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:[Illustration: BENJAMIN FRANKLIN]
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Military Education of the Colonists.=--The same wars that showed
2mo i, 1:the provincials the meaning of union likewise instructed them in the art
2mo i, 1:of defending their institutions. Particularly was this true of the last
2mo i, 1:French and Indian conflict, which stretched all the way from Maine to
2mo i, 1:the Carolinas and made heavy calls upon them all for troops. The answer,
2mo i, 1:it is admitted, was far from satisfactory to the British government and
2mo i, 1:the conduct of the militiamen was far from professional; but thousands
2mo i, 1:of Americans got a taste, a strong taste, of actual fighting in the
2mo i, 1:field. Men like George Washington and Daniel Morgan learned lessons that
2mo i, 1:were not forgotten in after years. They saw what American militiamen
2mo i, 1:could do under favorable circumstances and they watched British regulars
2mo i, 1:operating on American soil. "This whole transaction," shrewdly remarked
2mo i, 1:Franklin of Braddock's campaign, "gave us Americans the first suspicion
2mo i, 1:that our exalted ideas of the prowess of British regular troops had not
2mo i, 1:been well founded." It was no mere accident that the Virginia colonel
2mo i, 1:who drew his sword under the elm at Cambridge and took command of the
2mo i, 1:army of the Revolution was the brave officer who had "spurned the
2mo i, 1:whistle of bullets" at the memorable battle in western Pennsylvania.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Financial Burdens and Commercial Disorder.=--While the provincials were
2mo i, 1:learning lessons in warfare they were also paying the bills. All the
2mo i, 1:conflicts were costly in treasure as in blood. King Philip's war left
2mo i, 1:New England weak and almost bankrupt. The French and Indian struggle was
2mo i, 1:especially expensive. The twenty-five thousand men put in the field by
2mo i, 1:the colonies were sustained only by huge outlays of money. Paper
2mo i, 1:currency streamed from the press and debts were accumulated. Commerce
2mo i, 1:was driven from its usual channels and prices were enhanced. When the
2mo i, 1:end came, both England and America were staggering under heavy
2mo i, 1:liabilities, and to make matters worse there was a fall of prices
2mo i, 1:accompanied by a commercial depression which extended over a period of
2mo i, 1:ten years. It was in the midst of this crisis that measures of taxation
2mo i, 1:had to be devised to pay the cost of the war, precipitating the quarrel
2mo i, 1:which led to American independence.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Expulsion of French Power from North America.=--The effects of the
2mo i, 1:defeat administered to France, as time proved, were difficult to
2mo i, 1:estimate. Some British statesmen regarded it as a happy circumstance
2mo i, 1:that the colonists, already restive under their administration, had no
2mo i, 1:foreign power at hand to aid them in case they struck for independence.
2mo i, 1:American leaders, on the other hand, now that the soldiers of King Louis
2mo i, 1:were driven from the continent, thought that they had no other country
2mo i, 1:to fear if they cast off British sovereignty. At all events, France,
2mo i, 1:though defeated, was not out of the sphere of American influence; for,
2mo i, 1:as events proved, it was the fortunate French alliance negotiated by
2mo i, 1:Franklin that assured the triumph of American arms in the War of the
2mo i, 1:Revolution.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:COLONIAL RELATIONS WITH THE BRITISH GOVERNMENT
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:It was neither the Indian wars nor the French wars that finally brought
2mo i, 1:forth American nationality. That was the product of the long strife
2mo i, 1:with the mother country which culminated in union for the war of
2mo i, 1:independence. The forces that created this nation did not operate in the
2mo i, 1:colonies alone. The character of the English sovereigns, the course of
2mo i, 1:events in English domestic politics, and English measures of control
2mo i, 1:over the colonies--executive, legislative, and judicial--must all be
2mo i, 1:taken into account.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Last of the Stuarts.=--The struggles between Charles I (1625-49)
2mo i, 1:and the parliamentary party and the turmoil of the Puritan regime
2mo i, 1:(1649-60) so engrossed the attention of Englishmen at home that they had
2mo i, 1:little time to think of colonial policies or to interfere with colonial
2mo i, 1:affairs. The restoration of the monarchy in 1660, accompanied by
2mo i, 1:internal peace and the increasing power of the mercantile classes in the
2mo i, 1:House of Commons, changed all that. In the reign of Charles II
2mo i, 1:(1660-85), himself an easy-going person, the policy of regulating trade
2mo i, 1:by act of Parliament was developed into a closely knit system and
2mo i, 1:powerful agencies to supervise the colonies were created. At the same
2mo i, 1:time a system of stricter control over the dominions was ushered in by
2mo i, 1:the annulment of the old charter of Massachusetts which conferred so
2mo i, 1:much self-government on the Puritans.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Charles' successor, James II, a man of sterner stuff and jealous of his
2mo i, 1:authority in the colonies as well as at home, continued the policy thus
2mo i, 1:inaugurated and enlarged upon it. If he could have kept his throne, he
2mo i, 1:would have bent the Americans under a harsh rule or brought on in his
2mo i, 1:dominions a revolution like that which he precipitated at home in 1688.
2mo i, 1:He determined to unite the Northern colonies and introduce a more
2mo i, 1:efficient administration based on the pattern of the royal provinces. He
2mo i, 1:made a martinet, Sir Edmund Andros, governor of all New England, New
2mo i, 1:York, and New Jersey. The charter of Massachusetts, annulled in the last
2mo i, 1:days of his brother's reign, he continued to ignore, and that of
2mo i, 1:Connecticut would have been seized if it had not been spirited away and
2mo i, 1:hidden, according to tradition, in a hollow oak.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:For several months, Andros gave the Northern colonies a taste of
2mo i, 1:ill-tempered despotism. He wrung quit rents from land owners not
2mo i, 1:accustomed to feudal dues; he abrogated titles to land where, in his
2mo i, 1:opinion, they were unlawful; he forced the Episcopal service upon the
2mo i, 1:Old South Church in Boston; and he denied the writ of _habeas corpus_ to
2mo i, 1:a preacher who denounced taxation without representation. In the middle
2mo i, 1:of his arbitrary course, however, his hand was stayed. The news came
2mo i, 1:that King James had been dethroned by his angry subjects, and the people
2mo i, 1:of Boston, kindling a fire on Beacon Hill, summoned the countryside to
2mo i, 1:dispose of Andros. The response was prompt and hearty. The hated
2mo i, 1:governor was arrested, imprisoned, and sent back across the sea under
2mo i, 1:guard.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The overthrow of James, followed by the accession of William and Mary
2mo i, 1:and by assured parliamentary supremacy, had an immediate effect in the
2mo i, 1:colonies. The new order was greeted with thanksgiving. Massachusetts was
2mo i, 1:given another charter which, though not so liberal as the first,
2mo i, 1:restored the spirit if not the entire letter of self-government. In the
2mo i, 1:other colonies where Andros had been operating, the old course of
2mo i, 1:affairs was resumed.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Indifference of the First Two Georges.=--On the death in 1714 of
2mo i, 1:Queen Anne, the successor of King William, the throne passed to a
2mo i, 1:Hanoverian prince who, though grateful for English honors and revenues,
2mo i, 1:was more interested in Hanover than in England. George I and George II,
2mo i, 1:whose combined reigns extended from 1714 to 1760, never even learned to
2mo i, 1:speak the English language, at least without an accent. The necessity of
2mo i, 1:taking thought about colonial affairs bored both of them so that the
2mo i, 1:stoutest defender of popular privileges in Boston or Charleston had no
2mo i, 1:ground to complain of the exercise of personal prerogatives by the king.
2mo i, 1:Moreover, during a large part of this period, the direction of affairs
2mo i, 1:was in the hands of an astute leader, Sir Robert Walpole, who betrayed
2mo i, 1:his somewhat cynical view of politics by adopting as his motto: "Let
2mo i, 1:sleeping dogs lie." He revealed his appreciation of popular sentiment
2mo i, 1:by exclaiming: "I will not be the minister to enforce taxes at the
2mo i, 1:expense of blood." Such kings and such ministers were not likely to
2mo i, 1:arouse the slumbering resistance of the thirteen colonies across the
2mo i, 1:sea.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Control of the Crown over the Colonies.=--While no English ruler from
2mo i, 1:James II to George III ventured to interfere with colonial matters
2mo i, 1:personally, constant control over the colonies was exercised by royal
2mo i, 1:officers acting under the authority of the crown. Systematic supervision
2mo i, 1:began in 1660, when there was created by royal order a committee of the
2mo i, 1:king's council to meet on Mondays and Thursdays of each week to consider
2mo i, 1:petitions, memorials, and addresses respecting the plantations. In 1696
2mo i, 1:a regular board was established, known as the "Lords of Trade and
2mo i, 1:Plantations," which continued, until the American Revolution, to
2mo i, 1:scrutinize closely colonial business. The chief duties of the board were
2mo i, 1:to examine acts of colonial legislatures, to recommend measures to those
2mo i, 1:assemblies for adoption, and to hear memorials and petitions from the
2mo i, 1:colonies relative to their affairs.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The methods employed by this board were varied. All laws passed by
2mo i, 1:American legislatures came before it for review as a matter of routine.
2mo i, 1:If it found an act unsatisfactory, it recommended to the king the
2mo i, 1:exercise of his veto power, known as the royal disallowance. Any person
2mo i, 1:who believed his personal or property rights injured by a colonial law
2mo i, 1:could be heard by the board in person or by attorney; in such cases it
2mo i, 1:was the practice to hear at the same time the agent of the colony so
2mo i, 1:involved. The royal veto power over colonial legislation was not,
2mo i, 1:therefore, a formal affair, but was constantly employed on the
2mo i, 1:suggestion of a highly efficient agency of the crown. All this was in
2mo i, 1:addition to the powers exercised by the governors in the royal
2mo i, 1:provinces.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Judicial Control.=--Supplementing this administrative control over the
2mo i, 1:colonies was a constant supervision by the English courts of law. The
2mo i, 1:king, by virtue of his inherent authority, claimed and exercised high
2mo i, 1:appellate powers over all judicial tribunals in the empire. The right
2mo i, 1:of appeal from local courts, expressly set forth in some charters, was,
2mo i, 1:on the eve of the Revolution, maintained in every colony. Any subject in
2mo i, 1:England or America, who, in the regular legal course, was aggrieved by
2mo i, 1:any act of a colonial legislature or any decision of a colonial court,
2mo i, 1:had the right, subject to certain regulations, to carry his case to the
2mo i, 1:king in council, forcing his opponent to follow him across the sea. In
2mo i, 1:the exercise of appellate power, the king in council acting as a court
2mo i, 1:could, and frequently did, declare acts of colonial legislatures duly
2mo i, 1:enacted and approved, null and void, on the ground that they were
2mo i, 1:contrary to English law.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Imperial Control in Operation.=--Day after day, week after week, year
2mo i, 1:after year, the machinery for political and judicial control over
2mo i, 1:colonial affairs was in operation. At one time the British governors in
2mo i, 1:the colonies were ordered not to approve any colonial law imposing a
2mo i, 1:duty on European goods imported in English vessels. Again, when North
2mo i, 1:Carolina laid a tax on peddlers, the council objected to it as
2mo i, 1:"restrictive upon the trade and dispersion of English manufactures
2mo i, 1:throughout the continent." At other times, Indian trade was regulated in
2mo i, 1:the interests of the whole empire or grants of lands by a colonial
2mo i, 1:legislature were set aside. Virginia was forbidden to close her ports to
2mo i, 1:North Carolina lest there should be retaliation.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:In short, foreign and intercolonial trade were subjected to a control
2mo i, 1:higher than that of the colony, foreshadowing a day when the
2mo i, 1:Constitution of the United States was to commit to Congress the power to
2mo i, 1:regulate interstate and foreign commerce and commerce with the Indians.
2mo i, 1:A superior judicial power, towering above that of the colonies, as the
2mo i, 1:Supreme Court at Washington now towers above the states, kept the
2mo i, 1:colonial legislatures within the metes and bounds of established law. In
2mo i, 1:the thousands of appeals, memorials, petitions, and complaints, and the
2mo i, 1:rulings and decisions upon them, were written the real history of
2mo i, 1:British imperial control over the American colonies.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:So great was the business before the Lords of Trade that the colonies
2mo i, 1:had to keep skilled agents in London to protect their interests. As
2mo i, 1:common grievances against the operation of this machinery of control
2mo i, 1:arose, there appeared in each colony a considerable body of men, with
2mo i, 1:the merchants in the lead, who chafed at the restraints imposed on their
2mo i, 1:enterprise. Only a powerful blow was needed to weld these bodies into a
2mo i, 1:common mass nourishing the spirit of colonial nationalism. When to the
2mo i, 1:repeated minor irritations were added general and sweeping measures of
2mo i, 1:Parliament applying to every colony, the rebound came in the Revolution.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Parliamentary Control over Colonial Affairs.=--As soon as Parliament
2mo i, 1:gained in power at the expense of the king, it reached out to bring the
2mo i, 1:American colonies under its sway as well. Between the execution of
2mo i, 1:Charles I and the accession of George III, there was enacted an immense
2mo i, 1:body of legislation regulating the shipping, trade, and manufactures of
2mo i, 1:America. All of it, based on the "mercantile" theory then prevalent in
2mo i, 1:all countries of Europe, was designed to control the overseas
2mo i, 1:plantations in such a way as to foster the commercial and business
2mo i, 1:interests of the mother country, where merchants and men of finance had
2mo i, 1:got the upper hand. According to this theory, the colonies of the
2mo i, 1:British empire should be confined to agriculture and the production of
2mo i, 1:raw materials, and forced to buy their manufactured goods of England.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:_The Navigation Acts._--In the first rank among these measures of
2mo i, 1:British colonial policy must be placed the navigation laws framed for
2mo i, 1:the purpose of building up the British merchant marine and navy--arms so
2mo i, 1:essential in defending the colonies against the Spanish, Dutch, and
2mo i, 1:French. The beginning of this type of legislation was made in 1651 and
2mo i, 1:it was worked out into a system early in the reign of Charles II
2mo i, 1:(1660-85).
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The Navigation Acts, in effect, gave a monopoly of colonial commerce to
2mo i, 1:British ships. No trade could be carried on between Great Britain and
2mo i, 1:her dominions save in vessels built and manned by British subjects. No
2mo i, 1:European goods could be brought to America save in the ships of the
2mo i, 1:country that produced them or in English ships. These laws, which were
2mo i, 1:almost fatal to Dutch shipping in America, fell with severity upon the
2mo i, 1:colonists, compelling them to pay higher freight rates. The adverse
2mo i, 1:effect, however, was short-lived, for the measures stimulated
2mo i, 1:shipbuilding in the colonies, where the abundance of raw materials gave
2mo i, 1:the master builders of America an advantage over those of the mother
2mo i, 1:country. Thus the colonists in the end profited from the restrictive
2mo i, 1:policy written into the Navigation Acts.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:_The Acts against Manufactures._--The second group of laws was
2mo i, 1:deliberately aimed to prevent colonial industries from competing too
2mo i, 1:sharply with those of England. Among the earliest of these measures may
2mo i, 1:be counted the Woolen Act of 1699, forbidding the exportation of woolen
2mo i, 1:goods from the colonies and even the woolen trade between towns and
2mo i, 1:colonies. When Parliament learned, as the result of an inquiry, that New
2mo i, 1:England and New York were making thousands of hats a year and sending
2mo i, 1:large numbers annually to the Southern colonies and to Ireland, Spain,
2mo i, 1:and Portugal, it enacted in 1732 a law declaring that "no hats or felts,
2mo i, 1:dyed or undyed, finished or unfinished" should be "put upon any vessel
2mo i, 1:or laden upon any horse or cart with intent to export to any place
2mo i, 1:whatever." The effect of this measure upon the hat industry was almost
2mo i, 1:ruinous. A few years later a similar blow was given to the iron
2mo i, 1:industry. By an act of 1750, pig and bar iron from the colonies were
2mo i, 1:given free entry to England to encourage the production of the raw
2mo i, 1:material; but at the same time the law provided that "no mill or other
2mo i, 1:engine for slitting or rolling of iron, no plating forge to work with a
2mo i, 1:tilt hammer, and no furnace for making steel" should be built in the
2mo i, 1:colonies. As for those already built, they were declared public
2mo i, 1:nuisances and ordered closed. Thus three important economic interests of
2mo i, 1:the colonists, the woolen, hat, and iron industries, were laid under the
2mo i, 1:ban.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:_The Trade Laws._--The third group of restrictive measures passed by the
2mo i, 1:British Parliament related to the sale of colonial produce. An act of
2mo i, 1:1663 required the colonies to export certain articles to Great Britain
2mo i, 1:or to her dominions alone; while sugar, tobacco, and ginger consigned to
2mo i, 1:the continent of Europe had to pass through a British port paying custom
2mo i, 1:duties and through a British merchant's hands paying the usual
2mo i, 1:commission. At first tobacco was the only one of the "enumerated
2mo i, 1:articles" which seriously concerned the American colonies, the rest
2mo i, 1:coming mainly from the British West Indies. In the course of time,
2mo i, 1:however, other commodities were added to the list of enumerated
2mo i, 1:articles, until by 1764 it embraced rice, naval stores, copper, furs,
2mo i, 1:hides, iron, lumber, and pearl ashes. This was not all. The colonies
2mo i, 1:were compelled to bring their European purchases back through English
2mo i, 1:ports, paying duties to the government and commissions to merchants
2mo i, 1:again.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:_The Molasses Act._--Not content with laws enacted in the interest of
2mo i, 1:English merchants and manufacturers, Parliament sought to protect the
2mo i, 1:British West Indies against competition from their French and Dutch
2mo i, 1:neighbors. New England merchants had long carried on a lucrative trade
2mo i, 1:with the French islands in the West Indies and Dutch Guiana, where sugar
2mo i, 1:and molasses could be obtained in large quantities at low prices. Acting
2mo i, 1:on the protests of English planters in the Barbadoes and Jamaica,
2mo i, 1:Parliament, in 1733, passed the famous Molasses Act imposing duties on
2mo i, 1:sugar and molasses imported into the colonies from foreign
2mo i, 1:countries--rates which would have destroyed the American trade with the
2mo i, 1:French and Dutch if the law had been enforced. The duties, however, were
2mo i, 1:not collected. The molasses and sugar trade with the foreigners went on
2mo i, 1:merrily, smuggling taking the place of lawful traffic.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Effect of the Laws in America.=--As compared with the strict monopoly
2mo i, 1:of her colonial trade which Spain consistently sought to maintain, the
2mo i, 1:policy of England was both moderate and liberal. Furthermore, the
2mo i, 1:restrictive laws were supplemented by many measures intended to be
2mo i, 1:favorable to colonial prosperity. The Navigation Acts, for example,
2mo i, 1:redounded to the advantage of American shipbuilders and the producers
2mo i, 1:of hemp, tar, lumber, and ship stores in general. Favors in British
2mo i, 1:ports were granted to colonial producers as against foreign competitors
2mo i, 1:and in some instances bounties were paid by England to encourage
2mo i, 1:colonial enterprise. Taken all in all, there is much justification in
2mo i, 1:the argument advanced by some modern scholars to the effect that the
2mo i, 1:colonists gained more than they lost by British trade and industrial
2mo i, 1:legislation. Certainly after the establishment of independence, when
2mo i, 1:free from these old restrictions, the Americans found themselves
2mo i, 1:handicapped by being treated as foreigners rather than favored traders
2mo i, 1:and the recipients of bounties in English markets.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Be that as it may, it appears that the colonists felt little irritation
2mo i, 1:against the mother country on account of the trade and navigation laws
2mo i, 1:enacted previous to the close of the French and Indian war. Relatively
2mo i, 1:few were engaged in the hat and iron industries as compared with those
2mo i, 1:in farming and planting, so that England's policy of restricting America
2mo i, 1:to agriculture did not conflict with the interests of the majority of
2mo i, 1:the inhabitants. The woolen industry was largely in the hands of women
2mo i, 1:and carried on in connection with their domestic duties, so that it was
2mo i, 1:not the sole support of any considerable number of people.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:As a matter of fact, moreover, the restrictive laws, especially those
2mo i, 1:relating to trade, were not rigidly enforced. Cargoes of tobacco were
2mo i, 1:boldly sent to continental ports without even so much as a bow to the
2mo i, 1:English government, to which duties should have been paid. Sugar and
2mo i, 1:molasses from the French and Dutch colonies were shipped into New
2mo i, 1:England in spite of the law. Royal officers sometimes protested against
2mo i, 1:smuggling and sometimes connived at it; but at no time did they succeed
2mo i, 1:in stopping it. Taken all in all, very little was heard of "the galling
2mo i, 1:restraints of trade" until after the French war, when the British
2mo i, 1:government suddenly entered upon a new course.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:SUMMARY OF THE COLONIAL PERIOD
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:In the period between the landing of the English at Jamestown, Virginia,
2mo i, 1:in 1607, and the close of the French and Indian war in 1763--a period of
2mo i, 1:a century and a half--a new nation was being prepared on this continent
2mo i, 1:to take its place among the powers of the earth. It was an epoch of
2mo i, 1:migration. Western Europe contributed emigrants of many races and
2mo i, 1:nationalities. The English led the way. Next to them in numerical
2mo i, 1:importance were the Scotch-Irish and the Germans. Into the melting pot
2mo i, 1:were also cast Dutch, Swedes, French, Jews, Welsh, and Irish. Thousands
2mo i, 1:of negroes were brought from Africa to till Southern fields or labor as
2mo i, 1:domestic servants in the North.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Why did they come? The reasons are various. Some of them, the Pilgrims
2mo i, 1:and Puritans of New England, the French Huguenots, Scotch-Irish and
2mo i, 1:Irish, and the Catholics of Maryland, fled from intolerant governments
2mo i, 1:that denied them the right to worship God according to the dictates of
2mo i, 1:their consciences. Thousands came to escape the bondage of poverty in
2mo i, 1:the Old World and to find free homes in America. Thousands, like the
2mo i, 1:negroes from Africa, were dragged here against their will. The lure of
2mo i, 1:adventure appealed to the restless and the lure of profits to the
2mo i, 1:enterprising merchants.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:How did they come? In some cases religious brotherhoods banded together
2mo i, 1:and borrowed or furnished the funds necessary to pay the way. In other
2mo i, 1:cases great trading companies were organized to found colonies. Again it
2mo i, 1:was the wealthy proprietor, like Lord Baltimore or William Penn, who
2mo i, 1:undertook to plant settlements. Many immigrants were able to pay their
2mo i, 1:own way across the sea. Others bound themselves out for a term of years
2mo i, 1:in exchange for the cost of the passage. Negroes were brought on account
2mo i, 1:of the profits derived from their sale as slaves.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Whatever the motive for their coming, however, they managed to get
2mo i, 1:across the sea. The immigrants set to work with a will. They cut down
2mo i, 1:forests, built houses, and laid out fields. They founded churches,
2mo i, 1:schools, and colleges. They set up forges and workshops. They spun and
2mo i, 1:wove. They fashioned ships and sailed the seas. They bartered and
2mo i, 1:traded. Here and there on favorable harbors they established centers of
2mo i, 1:commerce--Boston, Providence, New York, Philadelphia, Baltimore, and
2mo i, 1:Charleston. As soon as a firm foothold was secured on the shore line
2mo i, 1:they pressed westward until, by the close of the colonial period, they
2mo i, 1:were already on the crest of the Alleghanies.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Though they were widely scattered along a thousand miles of seacoast,
2mo i, 1:the colonists were united in spirit by many common ties. The major
2mo i, 1:portion of them were Protestants. The language, the law, and the
2mo i, 1:literature of England furnished the basis of national unity. Most of the
2mo i, 1:colonists were engaged in the same hard task; that of conquering a
2mo i, 1:wilderness. To ties of kinship and language were added ties created by
2mo i, 1:necessity. They had to unite in defense; first, against the Indians and
2mo i, 1:later against the French. They were all subjects of the same
2mo i, 1:sovereign--the king of England. The English Parliament made laws for
2mo i, 1:them and the English government supervised their local affairs, their
2mo i, 1:trade, and their manufactures. Common forces assailed them. Common
2mo i, 1:grievances vexed them. Common hopes inspired them.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Many of the things which tended to unite them likewise tended to throw
2mo i, 1:them into opposition to the British Crown and Parliament. Most of them
2mo i, 1:were freeholders; that is, farmers who owned their own land and tilled
2mo i, 1:it with their own hands. A free soil nourished the spirit of freedom.
2mo i, 1:The majority of them were Dissenters, critics, not friends, of the
2mo i, 1:Church of England, that stanch defender of the British monarchy. Each
2mo i, 1:colony in time developed its own legislature elected by the voters; it
2mo i, 1:grew accustomed to making laws and laying taxes for itself. Here was a
2mo i, 1:people learning self-reliance and self-government. The attempts to
2mo i, 1:strengthen the Church of England in America and the transformation of
2mo i, 1:colonies into royal provinces only fanned the spirit of independence
2mo i, 1:which they were designed to quench.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Nevertheless, the Americans owed much of their prosperity to the
2mo i, 1:assistance of the government that irritated them. It was the protection
2mo i, 1:of the British navy that prevented Holland, Spain, and France from
2mo i, 1:wiping out their settlements. Though their manufacture and trade were
2mo i, 1:controlled in the interests of the mother country, they also enjoyed
2mo i, 1:great advantages in her markets. Free trade existed nowhere upon the
2mo i, 1:earth; but the broad empire of Britain was open to American ships and
2mo i, 1:merchandise. It could be said, with good reason, that the disadvantages
2mo i, 1:which the colonists suffered through British regulation of their
2mo i, 1:industry and trade were more than offset by the privileges they enjoyed.
2mo i, 1:Still that is somewhat beside the point, for mere economic advantage is
2mo i, 1:not necessarily the determining factor in the fate of peoples. A
2mo i, 1:thousand circumstances had helped to develop on this continent a nation,
2mo i, 1:to inspire it with a passion for independence, and to prepare it for a
2mo i, 1:destiny greater than that of a prosperous dominion of the British
2mo i, 1:empire. The economists, who tried to prove by logic unassailable that
2mo i, 1:America would be richer under the British flag, could not change the
2mo i, 1:spirit of Patrick Henry, Samuel Adams, Benjamin Franklin, or George
2mo i, 1:Washington.
