2mo i, 1:CHAPTER V
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:THE NEW COURSE IN BRITISH IMPERIAL POLICY
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:On October 25, 1760, King George II died and the British crown passed to
2mo i, 1:his young grandson. The first George, the son of the Elector of Hanover
2mo i, 1:and Sophia the granddaughter of James I, was a thorough German who never
2mo i, 1:even learned to speak the language of the land over which he reigned.
2mo i, 1:The second George never saw England until he was a man. He spoke English
2mo i, 1:with an accent and until his death preferred his German home. During
2mo i, 1:their reign, the principle had become well established that the king did
2mo i, 1:not govern but acted only through ministers representing the majority in
2mo i, 1:Parliament.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:GEORGE III AND HIS SYSTEM
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Character of the New King.=--The third George rudely broke the
2mo i, 1:German tradition of his family. He resented the imputation that he was a
2mo i, 1:foreigner and on all occasions made a display of his British sympathies.
2mo i, 1:To the draft of his first speech to Parliament, he added the popular
2mo i, 1:phrase: "Born and educated in this country, I glory in the name of
2mo i, 1:Briton." Macaulay, the English historian, certainly of no liking for
2mo i, 1:high royal prerogative, said of George: "The young king was a born
2mo i, 1:Englishman. All his tastes and habits, good and bad, were English. No
2mo i, 1:portion of his subjects had anything to reproach him with.... His age,
2mo i, 1:his appearance, and all that was known of his character conciliated
2mo i, 1:public favor. He was in the bloom of youth; his person and address were
2mo i, 1:pleasing; scandal imputed to him no vice; and flattery might without
2mo i, 1:glaring absurdity ascribe to him many princely virtues."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Nevertheless George III had been spoiled by his mother, his tutors, and
2mo i, 1:his courtiers. Under their influence he developed high and mighty
2mo i, 1:notions about the sacredness of royal authority and his duty to check
2mo i, 1:the pretensions of Parliament and the ministers dependent upon it. His
2mo i, 1:mother had dinned into his ears the slogan: "George, be king!" Lord
2mo i, 1:Bute, his teacher and adviser, had told him that his honor required him
2mo i, 1:to take an active part in the shaping of public policy and the making of
2mo i, 1:laws. Thus educated, he surrounded himself with courtiers who encouraged
2mo i, 1:him in the determination to rule as well as reign, to subdue all
2mo i, 1:parties, and to place himself at the head of the nation and empire.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:[Illustration: _From an old print._
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:GEORGE III]
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Political Parties and George III.=--The state of the political parties
2mo i, 1:favored the plans of the king to restore some of the ancient luster of
2mo i, 1:the crown. The Whigs, who were composed mainly of the smaller
2mo i, 1:freeholders, merchants, inhabitants of towns, and Protestant
2mo i, 1:non-conformists, had grown haughty and overbearing through long
2mo i, 1:continuance in power and had as a consequence raised up many enemies in
2mo i, 1:their own ranks. Their opponents, the Tories, had by this time given up
2mo i, 1:all hope of restoring to the throne the direct Stuart line; but they
2mo i, 1:still cherished their old notions about divine right. With the
2mo i, 1:accession of George III the coveted opportunity came to them to rally
2mo i, 1:around the throne again. George received his Tory friends with open
2mo i, 1:arms, gave them offices, and bought them seats in the House of Commons.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The British Parliamentary System.=--The peculiarities of the British
2mo i, 1:Parliament at the time made smooth the way for the king and his allies
2mo i, 1:with their designs for controlling the entire government. In the first
2mo i, 1:place, the House of Lords was composed mainly of hereditary nobles whose
2mo i, 1:number the king could increase by the appointment of his favorites, as
2mo i, 1:of old. Though the members of the House of Commons were elected by
2mo i, 1:popular vote, they did not speak for the mass of English people. Great
2mo i, 1:towns like Leeds, Manchester, and Birmingham, for example, had no
2mo i, 1:representatives at all. While there were about eight million inhabitants
2mo i, 1:in Great Britain, there were in 1768 only about 160,000 voters; that is
2mo i, 1:to say, only about one in every ten adult males had a voice in the
2mo i, 1:government. Many boroughs returned one or more members to the Commons
2mo i, 1:although they had merely a handful of voters or in some instances no
2mo i, 1:voters at all. Furthermore, these tiny boroughs were often controlled by
2mo i, 1:lords who openly sold the right of representation to the highest bidder.
2mo i, 1:The "rotten-boroughs," as they were called by reformers, were a public
2mo i, 1:scandal, but George III readily made use of them to get his friends into
2mo i, 1:the House of Commons.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:GEORGE III'S MINISTERS AND THEIR COLONIAL POLICIES
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Grenville and the War Debt.=--Within a year after the accession of
2mo i, 1:George III, William Pitt was turned out of office, the king treating him
2mo i, 1:with "gross incivility" and the crowds shouting "Pitt forever!" The
2mo i, 1:direction of affairs was entrusted to men enjoying the king's
2mo i, 1:confidence. Leadership in the House of Commons fell to George Grenville,
2mo i, 1:a grave and laborious man who for years had groaned over the increasing
2mo i, 1:cost of government.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The first task after the conclusion of peace in 1763 was the adjustment
2mo i, 1:of the disordered finances of the kingdom. The debt stood at the highest
2mo i, 1:point in the history of the country. More revenue was absolutely
2mo i, 1:necessary and Grenville began to search for it, turning his attention
2mo i, 1:finally to the American colonies. In this quest he had the aid of a
2mo i, 1:zealous colleague, Charles Townshend, who had long been in public
2mo i, 1:service and was familiar with the difficulties encountered by royal
2mo i, 1:governors in America. These two men, with the support of the entire
2mo i, 1:ministry, inaugurated in February, 1763, "a new system of colonial
2mo i, 1:government. It was announced by authority that there were to be no more
2mo i, 1:requisitions from the king to the colonial assemblies for supplies, but
2mo i, 1:that the colonies were to be taxed instead by act of Parliament.
2mo i, 1:Colonial governors and judges were to be paid by the Crown; they were to
2mo i, 1:be supported by a standing army of twenty regiments; and all the
2mo i, 1:expenses of this force were to be met by parliamentary taxation."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Restriction of Paper Money (1763).=--Among the many complaints filed
2mo i, 1:before the board of trade were vigorous protests against the issuance of
2mo i, 1:paper money by the colonial legislatures. The new ministry provided a
2mo i, 1:remedy in the act of 1763, which declared void all colonial laws
2mo i, 1:authorizing paper money or extending the life of outstanding bills. This
2mo i, 1:law was aimed at the "cheap money" which the Americans were fond of
2mo i, 1:making when specie was scarce--money which they tried to force on their
2mo i, 1:English creditors in return for goods and in payment of the interest and
2mo i, 1:principal of debts. Thus the first chapter was written in the long
2mo i, 1:battle over sound money on this continent.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Limitation on Western Land Sales.=--Later in the same year (1763)
2mo i, 1:George III issued a royal proclamation providing, among other things,
2mo i, 1:for the government of the territory recently acquired by the treaty of
2mo i, 1:Paris from the French. One of the provisions in this royal decree
2mo i, 1:touched frontiersmen to the quick. The contests between the king's
2mo i, 1:officers and the colonists over the disposition of western lands had
2mo i, 1:been long and sharp. The Americans chafed at restrictions on
2mo i, 1:settlement. The more adventurous were continually moving west and
2mo i, 1:"squatting" on land purchased from the Indians or simply seized without
2mo i, 1:authority. To put an end to this, the king forbade all further purchases
2mo i, 1:from the Indians, reserving to the crown the right to acquire such lands
2mo i, 1:and dispose of them for settlement. A second provision in the same
2mo i, 1:proclamation vested the power of licensing trade with the Indians,
2mo i, 1:including the lucrative fur business, in the hands of royal officers in
2mo i, 1:the colonies. These two limitations on American freedom and enterprise
2mo i, 1:were declared to be in the interest of the crown and for the
2mo i, 1:preservation of the rights of the Indians against fraud and abuses.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Sugar Act of 1764.=--King George's ministers next turned their
2mo i, 1:attention to measures of taxation and trade. Since the heavy debt under
2mo i, 1:which England was laboring had been largely incurred in the defense of
2mo i, 1:America, nothing seemed more reasonable to them than the proposition
2mo i, 1:that the colonies should help to bear the burden which fell so heavily
2mo i, 1:upon the English taxpayer. The Sugar Act of 1764 was the result of this
2mo i, 1:reasoning. There was no doubt about the purpose of this law, for it was
2mo i, 1:set forth clearly in the title: "An act for granting certain duties in
2mo i, 1:the British colonies and plantations in America ... for applying the
2mo i, 1:produce of such duties ... towards defraying the expenses of defending,
2mo i, 1:protecting and securing the said colonies and plantations ... and for
2mo i, 1:more effectually preventing the clandestine conveyance of goods to and
2mo i, 1:from the said colonies and plantations and improving and securing the
2mo i, 1:trade between the same and Great Britain." The old Molasses Act had been
2mo i, 1:prohibitive; the Sugar Act of 1764 was clearly intended as a revenue
2mo i, 1:measure. Specified duties were laid upon sugar, indigo, calico, silks,
2mo i, 1:and many other commodities imported into the colonies. The enforcement
2mo i, 1:of the Molasses Act had been utterly neglected; but this Sugar Act had
2mo i, 1:"teeth in it." Special precautions as to bonds, security, and
2mo i, 1:registration of ship masters, accompanied by heavy penalties, promised
2mo i, 1:a vigorous execution of the new revenue law.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The strict terms of the Sugar Act were strengthened by administrative
2mo i, 1:measures. Under a law of the previous year the commanders of armed
2mo i, 1:vessels stationed along the American coast were authorized to stop,
2mo i, 1:search, and, on suspicion, seize merchant ships approaching colonial
2mo i, 1:ports. By supplementary orders, the entire British official force in
2mo i, 1:America was instructed to be diligent in the execution of all trade and
2mo i, 1:navigation laws. Revenue collectors, officers of the army and navy, and
2mo i, 1:royal governors were curtly ordered to the front to do their full duty
2mo i, 1:in the matter of law enforcement. The ordinary motives for the discharge
2mo i, 1:of official obligations were sharpened by an appeal to avarice, for
2mo i, 1:naval officers who seized offenders against the law were rewarded by
2mo i, 1:large prizes out of the forfeitures and penalties.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Stamp Act (1765).=--The Grenville-Townshend combination moved
2mo i, 1:steadily towards its goal. While the Sugar Act was under consideration
2mo i, 1:in Parliament, Grenville announced a plan for a stamp bill. The next
2mo i, 1:year it went through both Houses with a speed that must have astounded
2mo i, 1:its authors. The vote in the Commons stood 205 in favor to 49 against;
2mo i, 1:while in the Lords it was not even necessary to go through the formality
2mo i, 1:of a count. As George III was temporarily insane, the measure received
2mo i, 1:royal assent by a commission acting as a board of regency. Protests of
2mo i, 1:colonial agents in London were futile. "We might as well have hindered
2mo i, 1:the sun's progress!" exclaimed Franklin. Protests of a few opponents in
2mo i, 1:the Commons were equally vain. The ministry was firm in its course and
2mo i, 1:from all appearances the Stamp Act hardly roused as much as a languid
2mo i, 1:interest in the city of London. In fact, it is recorded that the fateful
2mo i, 1:measure attracted less notice than a bill providing for a commission to
2mo i, 1:act for the king when he was incapacitated.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The Stamp Act, like the Sugar Act, declared the purpose of the British
2mo i, 1:government to raise revenue in America "towards defraying the expenses
2mo i, 1:of defending, protecting, and securing the British colonies and
2mo i, 1:plantations in America." It was a long measure of more than fifty
2mo i, 1:sections, carefully planned and skillfully drawn. By its provisions
2mo i, 1:duties were imposed on practically all papers used in legal
2mo i, 1:transactions,--deeds, mortgages, inventories, writs, bail bonds,--on
2mo i, 1:licenses to practice law and sell liquor, on college diplomas, playing
2mo i, 1:cards, dice, pamphlets, newspapers, almanacs, calendars, and
2mo i, 1:advertisements. The drag net was closely knit, for scarcely anything
2mo i, 1:escaped.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Quartering Act (1765).=--The ministers were aware that the Stamp
2mo i, 1:Act would rouse opposition in America--how great they could not
2mo i, 1:conjecture. While the measure was being debated, a friend of General
2mo i, 1:Wolfe, Colonel Barre, who knew America well, gave them an ominous
2mo i, 1:warning in the Commons. "Believe me--remember I this day told you so--"
2mo i, 1:he exclaimed, "the same spirit of freedom which actuated that people at
2mo i, 1:first will accompany them still ... a people jealous of their liberties
2mo i, 1:and who will vindicate them, if ever they should be violated." The
2mo i, 1:answer of the ministry to a prophecy of force was a threat of force.
2mo i, 1:Preparations were accordingly made to dispatch a larger number of
2mo i, 1:soldiers than usual to the colonies, and the ink was hardly dry on the
2mo i, 1:Stamp Act when Parliament passed the Quartering Act ordering the
2mo i, 1:colonists to provide accommodations for the soldiers who were to enforce
2mo i, 1:the new laws. "We have the power to tax them," said one of the ministry,
2mo i, 1:"and we will tax them."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:COLONIAL RESISTANCE FORCES REPEAL
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Popular Opposition.=--The Stamp Act was greeted in America by an
2mo i, 1:outburst of denunciation. The merchants of the seaboard cities took the
2mo i, 1:lead in making a dignified but unmistakable protest, agreeing not to
2mo i, 1:import British goods while the hated law stood upon the books. Lawyers,
2mo i, 1:some of them incensed at the heavy taxes on their operations and others
2mo i, 1:intimidated by patriots who refused to permit them to use stamped
2mo i, 1:papers, joined with the merchants. Aristocratic colonial Whigs, who had
2mo i, 1:long grumbled at the administration of royal governors, protested
2mo i, 1:against taxation without their consent, as the Whigs had done in old
2mo i, 1:England. There were Tories, however, in the colonies as in England--many
2mo i, 1:of them of the official class--who denounced the merchants, lawyers, and
2mo i, 1:Whig aristocrats as "seditious, factious and republican." Yet the
2mo i, 1:opposition to the Stamp Act and its accompanying measure, the Quartering
2mo i, 1:Act, grew steadily all through the summer of 1765.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:In a little while it was taken up in the streets and along the
2mo i, 1:countryside. All through the North and in some of the Southern colonies,
2mo i, 1:there sprang up, as if by magic, committees and societies pledged to
2mo i, 1:resist the Stamp Act to the bitter end. These popular societies were
2mo i, 1:known as Sons of Liberty and Daughters of Liberty: the former including
2mo i, 1:artisans, mechanics, and laborers; and the latter, patriotic women. Both
2mo i, 1:groups were alike in that they had as yet taken little part in public
2mo i, 1:affairs. Many artisans, as well as all the women, were excluded from the
2mo i, 1:right to vote for colonial assemblymen.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:While the merchants and Whig gentlemen confined their efforts chiefly to
2mo i, 1:drafting well-phrased protests against British measures, the Sons of
2mo i, 1:Liberty operated in the streets and chose rougher measures. They stirred
2mo i, 1:up riots in Boston, New York, Philadelphia, and Charleston when attempts
2mo i, 1:were made to sell the stamps. They sacked and burned the residences of
2mo i, 1:high royal officers. They organized committees of inquisition who by
2mo i, 1:threats and intimidation curtailed the sale of British goods and the use
2mo i, 1:of stamped papers. In fact, the Sons of Liberty carried their operations
2mo i, 1:to such excesses that many mild opponents of the stamp tax were
2mo i, 1:frightened and drew back in astonishment at the forces they had
2mo i, 1:unloosed. The Daughters of Liberty in a quieter way were making a very
2mo i, 1:effective resistance to the sale of the hated goods by spurring on
2mo i, 1:domestic industries, their own particular province being the manufacture
2mo i, 1:of clothing, and devising substitutes for taxed foods. They helped to
2mo i, 1:feed and clothe their families without buying British goods.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Legislative Action against the Stamp Act.=--Leaders in the colonial
2mo i, 1:assemblies, accustomed to battle against British policies, supported the
2mo i, 1:popular protest. The Stamp Act was signed on March 22, 1765. On May 30,
2mo i, 1:the Virginia House of Burgesses passed a set of resolutions declaring
2mo i, 1:that the General Assembly of the colony alone had the right to lay taxes
2mo i, 1:upon the inhabitants and that attempts to impose them otherwise were
2mo i, 1:"illegal, unconstitutional, and unjust." It was in support of these
2mo i, 1:resolutions that Patrick Henry uttered the immortal challenge: "Caesar
2mo i, 1:had his Brutus, Charles I his Cromwell, and George III...." Cries of
2mo i, 1:"Treason" were calmly met by the orator who finished: "George III may
2mo i, 1:profit by their example. If that be treason, make the most of it."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:[Illustration: PATRICK HENRY]
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Stamp Act Congress.=--The Massachusetts Assembly answered the call
2mo i, 1:of Virginia by inviting the colonies to elect delegates to a Congress to
2mo i, 1:be held in New York to discuss the situation. Nine colonies responded
2mo i, 1:and sent representatives. The delegates, while professing the warmest
2mo i, 1:affection for the king's person and government, firmly spread on record
2mo i, 1:a series of resolutions that admitted of no double meaning. They
2mo i, 1:declared that taxes could not be imposed without their consent, given
2mo i, 1:through their respective colonial assemblies; that the Stamp Act showed
2mo i, 1:a tendency to subvert their rights and liberties; that the recent trade
2mo i, 1:acts were burdensome and grievous; and that the right to petition the
2mo i, 1:king and Parliament was their heritage. They thereupon made "humble
2mo i, 1:supplication" for the repeal of the Stamp Act.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The Stamp Act Congress was more than an assembly of protest. It marked
2mo i, 1:the rise of a new agency of government to express the will of America.
2mo i, 1:It was the germ of a government which in time was to supersede the
2mo i, 1:government of George III in the colonies. It foreshadowed the Congress
2mo i, 1:of the United States under the Constitution. It was a successful attempt
2mo i, 1:at union. "There ought to be no New England men," declared Christopher
2mo i, 1:Gadsden, in the Stamp Act Congress, "no New Yorkers known on the
2mo i, 1:Continent, but all of us Americans."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Repeal of the Stamp Act and the Sugar Act.=--The effect of American
2mo i, 1:resistance on opinion in England was telling. Commerce with the colonies
2mo i, 1:had been effectively boycotted by the Americans; ships lay idly swinging
2mo i, 1:at the wharves; bankruptcy threatened hundreds of merchants in London,
2mo i, 1:Bristol, and Liverpool. Workingmen in the manufacturing towns of England
2mo i, 1:were thrown out of employment. The government had sown folly and was
2mo i, 1:reaping, in place of the coveted revenue, rebellion.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Perplexed by the storm they had raised, the ministers summoned to the
2mo i, 1:bar of the House of Commons, Benjamin Franklin, the agent for
2mo i, 1:Pennsylvania, who was in London. "Do you think it right," asked
2mo i, 1:Grenville, "that America should be protected by this country and pay no
2mo i, 1:part of the expenses?" The answer was brief: "That is not the case; the
2mo i, 1:colonies raised, clothed, and paid during the last war twenty-five
2mo i, 1:thousand men and spent many millions." Then came an inquiry whether the
2mo i, 1:colonists would accept a modified stamp act. "No, never," replied
2mo i, 1:Franklin, "never! They will never submit to it!" It was next suggested
2mo i, 1:that military force might compel obedience to law. Franklin had a ready
2mo i, 1:answer. "They cannot force a man to take stamps.... They may not find a
2mo i, 1:rebellion; they may, indeed, make one."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The repeal of the Stamp Act was moved in the House of Commons a few days
2mo i, 1:later. The sponsor for the repeal spoke of commerce interrupted, debts
2mo i, 1:due British merchants placed in jeopardy, Manchester industries closed,
2mo i, 1:workingmen unemployed, oppression instituted, and the loss of the
2mo i, 1:colonies threatened. Pitt and Edmund Burke, the former near the close
2mo i, 1:of his career, the latter just beginning his, argued cogently in favor
2mo i, 1:of retracing the steps taken the year before. Grenville refused.
2mo i, 1:"America must learn," he wailed, "that prayers are not to be brought to
2mo i, 1:Caesar through riot and sedition." His protests were idle. The Commons
2mo i, 1:agreed to the repeal on February 22, 1766, amid the cheers of the
2mo i, 1:victorious majority. It was carried through the Lords in the face of
2mo i, 1:strong opposition and, on March 18, reluctantly signed by the king, now
2mo i, 1:restored to his right mind.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:In rescinding the Stamp Act, Parliament did not admit the contention of
2mo i, 1:the Americans that it was without power to tax them. On the contrary, it
2mo i, 1:accompanied the repeal with a Declaratory Act. It announced that the
2mo i, 1:colonies were subordinate to the crown and Parliament of Great Britain;
2mo i, 1:that the king and Parliament therefore had undoubted authority to make
2mo i, 1:laws binding the colonies in all cases whatsoever; and that the
2mo i, 1:resolutions and proceedings of the colonists denying such authority were
2mo i, 1:null and void.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The repeal was greeted by the colonists with great popular
2mo i, 1:demonstrations. Bells were rung; toasts to the king were drunk; and
2mo i, 1:trade resumed its normal course. The Declaratory Act, as a mere paper
2mo i, 1:resolution, did not disturb the good humor of those who again cheered
2mo i, 1:the name of King George. Their confidence was soon strengthened by the
2mo i, 1:news that even the Sugar Act had been repealed, thus practically
2mo i, 1:restoring the condition of affairs before Grenville and Townshend
2mo i, 1:inaugurated their policy of "thoroughness."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:RESUMPTION OF BRITISH REVENUE AND COMMERCIAL POLICIES
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Townshend Acts (1767).=--The triumph of the colonists was brief.
2mo i, 1:Though Pitt, the friend of America, was once more prime minister, and
2mo i, 1:seated in the House of Lords as the Earl of Chatham, his severe illness
2mo i, 1:gave to Townshend and the Tory party practical control over Parliament.
2mo i, 1:Unconvinced by the experience with the Stamp Act, Townshend brought
2mo i, 1:forward and pushed through both Houses of Parliament three measures,
2mo i, 1:which to this day are associated with his name. First among his
2mo i, 1:restrictive laws was that of June 29, 1767, which placed the enforcement
2mo i, 1:of the collection of duties and customs on colonial imports and exports
2mo i, 1:in the hands of British commissioners appointed by the king, resident in
2mo i, 1:the colonies, paid from the British treasury, and independent of all
2mo i, 1:control by the colonists. The second measure of the same date imposed a
2mo i, 1:tax on lead, glass, paint, tea, and a few other articles imported into
2mo i, 1:the colonies, the revenue derived from the duties to be applied toward
2mo i, 1:the payment of the salaries and other expenses of royal colonial
2mo i, 1:officials. A third measure was the Tea Act of July 2, 1767, aimed at the
2mo i, 1:tea trade which the Americans carried on illegally with foreigners. This
2mo i, 1:law abolished the duty which the East India Company had to pay in
2mo i, 1:England on tea exported to America, for it was thought that English tea
2mo i, 1:merchants might thus find it possible to undersell American tea
2mo i, 1:smugglers.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Writs of Assistance Legalized by Parliament.=--Had Parliament been
2mo i, 1:content with laying duties, just as a manifestation of power and right,
2mo i, 1:and neglected their collection, perhaps little would have been heard of
2mo i, 1:the Townshend Acts. It provided, however, for the strict, even the
2mo i, 1:harsh, enforcement of the law. It ordered customs officers to remain at
2mo i, 1:their posts and put an end to smuggling. In the revenue act of June 29,
2mo i, 1:1767, it expressly authorized the superior courts of the colonies to
2mo i, 1:issue "writs of assistance," empowering customs officers to enter "any
2mo i, 1:house, warehouse, shop, cellar, or other place in the British colonies
2mo i, 1:or plantations in America to search for and seize" prohibited or
2mo i, 1:smuggled goods.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The writ of assistance, which was a general search warrant issued to
2mo i, 1:revenue officers, was an ancient device hateful to a people who
2mo i, 1:cherished the spirit of personal independence and who had made actual
2mo i, 1:gains in the practice of civil liberty. To allow a "minion of the law"
2mo i, 1:to enter a man's house and search his papers and premises, was too much
2mo i, 1:for the emotions of people who had fled to America in a quest for
2mo i, 1:self-government and free homes, who had braved such hardships to
2mo i, 1:establish them, and who wanted to trade without official interference.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The writ of assistance had been used in Massachusetts in 1755 to prevent
2mo i, 1:illicit trade with Canada and had aroused a violent hostility at that
2mo i, 1:time. In 1761 it was again the subject of a bitter controversy which
2mo i, 1:arose in connection with the application of a customs officer to a
2mo i, 1:Massachusetts court for writs of assistance "as usual." This application
2mo i, 1:was vainly opposed by James Otis in a speech of five hours' duration--a
2mo i, 1:speech of such fire and eloquence that it sent every man who heard it
2mo i, 1:away "ready to take up arms against writs of assistance." Otis denounced
2mo i, 1:the practice as an exercise of arbitrary power which had cost one king
2mo i, 1:his head and another his throne, a tyrant's device which placed the
2mo i, 1:liberty of every man in jeopardy, enabling any petty officer to work
2mo i, 1:possible malice on any innocent citizen on the merest suspicion, and to
2mo i, 1:spread terror and desolation through the land. "What a scene," he
2mo i, 1:exclaimed, "does this open! Every man, prompted by revenge, ill-humor,
2mo i, 1:or wantonness to inspect the inside of his neighbor's house, may get a
2mo i, 1:writ of assistance. Others will ask it from self-defense; one arbitrary
2mo i, 1:exertion will provoke another until society is involved in tumult and
2mo i, 1:blood." He did more than attack the writ itself. He said that Parliament
2mo i, 1:could not establish it because it was against the British constitution.
2mo i, 1:This was an assertion resting on slender foundation, but it was quickly
2mo i, 1:echoed by the people. Then and there James Otis sounded the call to
2mo i, 1:America to resist the exercise of arbitrary power by royal officers.
2mo i, 1:"Then and there," wrote John Adams, "the child Independence was born."
2mo i, 1:Such was the hated writ that Townshend proposed to put into the hands of
2mo i, 1:customs officers in his grim determination to enforce the law.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The New York Assembly Suspended.=--In the very month that Townshend's
2mo i, 1:Acts were signed by the king, Parliament took a still more drastic step.
2mo i, 1:The assembly of New York, protesting against the "ruinous and
2mo i, 1:insupportable" expense involved, had failed to make provision for the
2mo i, 1:care of British troops in accordance with the terms of the Quartering
2mo i, 1:Act. Parliament therefore suspended the assembly until it promised to
2mo i, 1:obey the law. It was not until a third election was held that compliance
2mo i, 1:with the Quartering Act was wrung from the reluctant province. In the
2mo i, 1:meantime, all the colonies had learned on how frail a foundation their
2mo i, 1:representative bodies rested.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:RENEWED RESISTANCE IN AMERICA
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Massachusetts Circular (1768).=--Massachusetts, under the
2mo i, 1:leadership of Samuel Adams, resolved to resist the policy of renewed
2mo i, 1:intervention in America. At his suggestion the assembly adopted a
2mo i, 1:Circular Letter addressed to the assemblies of the other colonies
2mo i, 1:informing them of the state of affairs in Massachusetts and roundly
2mo i, 1:condemning the whole British program. The Circular Letter declared that
2mo i, 1:Parliament had no right to lay taxes on Americans without their consent
2mo i, 1:and that the colonists could not, from the nature of the case, be
2mo i, 1:represented in Parliament. It went on shrewdly to submit to
2mo i, 1:consideration the question as to whether any people could be called free
2mo i, 1:who were subjected to governors and judges appointed by the crown and
2mo i, 1:paid out of funds raised independently. It invited the other colonies,
2mo i, 1:in the most temperate tones, to take thought about the common
2mo i, 1:predicament in which they were all placed.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:[Illustration: _From an old print._
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:SAMUEL ADAMS]
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Dissolution of Assemblies.=--The governor of Massachusetts, hearing
2mo i, 1:of the Circular Letter, ordered the assembly to rescind its appeal. On
2mo i, 1:meeting refusal, he promptly dissolved it. The Maryland, Georgia, and
2mo i, 1:South Carolina assemblies indorsed the Circular Letter and were also
2mo i, 1:dissolved at once. The Virginia House of Burgesses, thoroughly aroused,
2mo i, 1:passed resolutions on May 16, 1769, declaring that the sole right of
2mo i, 1:imposing taxes in Virginia was vested in its legislature, asserting anew
2mo i, 1:the right of petition to the crown, condemning the transportation of
2mo i, 1:persons accused of crimes or trial beyond the seas, and beseeching the
2mo i, 1:king for a redress of the general grievances. The immediate dissolution
2mo i, 1:of the Virginia assembly, in its turn, was the answer of the royal
2mo i, 1:governor.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Boston Massacre.=--American opposition to the British authorities
2mo i, 1:kept steadily rising as assemblies were dissolved, the houses of
2mo i, 1:citizens searched, and troops distributed in increasing numbers among
2mo i, 1:the centers of discontent. Merchants again agreed not to import British
2mo i, 1:goods, the Sons of Liberty renewed their agitation, and women set about
2mo i, 1:the patronage of home products still more loyally.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:On the night of March 5, 1770, a crowd on the streets of Boston began to
2mo i, 1:jostle and tease some British regulars stationed in the town. Things
2mo i, 1:went from bad to worse until some "boys and young fellows" began to
2mo i, 1:throw snowballs and stones. Then the exasperated soldiers fired into the
2mo i, 1:crowd, killing five and wounding half a dozen more. The day after the
2mo i, 1:"massacre," a mass meeting was held in the town and Samuel Adams was
2mo i, 1:sent to demand the withdrawal of the soldiers. The governor hesitated
2mo i, 1:and tried to compromise. Finding Adams relentless, the governor yielded
2mo i, 1:and ordered the regulars away.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The Boston Massacre stirred the country from New Hampshire to Georgia.
2mo i, 1:Popular passions ran high. The guilty soldiers were charged with murder.
2mo i, 1:Their defense was undertaken, in spite of the wrath of the populace, by
2mo i, 1:John Adams and Josiah Quincy, who as lawyers thought even the worst
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:offenders entitled to their full rights in law. In his speech to the
2mo i, 1:jury, however, Adams warned the British government against its course,
2mo i, 1:saying, that "from the nature of things soldiers quartered in a populous
2mo i, 1:town will always occasion two mobs where they will prevent one." Two of
2mo i, 1:the soldiers were convicted and lightly punished.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Resistance in the South.=--The year following the Boston Massacre some
2mo i, 1:citizens of North Carolina, goaded by the conduct of the royal governor,
2mo i, 1:openly resisted his authority. Many were killed as a result and seven
2mo i, 1:who were taken prisoners were hanged as traitors. A little later royal
2mo i, 1:troops and local militia met in a pitched battle near Alamance River,
2mo i, 1:called the "Lexington of the South."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The _Gaspee_ Affair and the Virginia Resolutions of 1773.=--On sea as
2mo i, 1:well as on land, friction between the royal officers and the colonists
2mo i, 1:broke out into overt acts. While patrolling Narragansett Bay looking for
2mo i, 1:smugglers one day in 1772, the armed ship, _Gaspee_, ran ashore and was
2mo i, 1:caught fast. During the night several men from Providence boarded the
2mo i, 1:vessel and, after seizing the crew, set it on fire. A royal commission,
2mo i, 1:sent to Rhode Island to discover the offenders and bring them to
2mo i, 1:account, failed because it could not find a single informer. The very
2mo i, 1:appointment of such a commission aroused the patriots of Virginia to
2mo i, 1:action; and in March, 1773, the House of Burgesses passed a resolution
2mo i, 1:creating a standing committee of correspondence to develop cooperation
2mo i, 1:among the colonies in resistance to British measures.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Boston Tea Party.=--Although the British government, finding the
2mo i, 1:Townshend revenue act a failure, repealed in 1770 all the duties except
2mo i, 1:that on tea, it in no way relaxed its resolve to enforce the other
2mo i, 1:commercial regulations it had imposed on the colonies. Moreover,
2mo i, 1:Parliament decided to relieve the British East India Company of the
2mo i, 1:financial difficulties into which it had fallen partly by reason of the
2mo i, 1:Tea Act and the colonial boycott that followed. In 1773 it agreed to
2mo i, 1:return to the Company the regular import duties, levied in England, on
2mo i, 1:all tea transshipped to America. A small impost of three pence, to be
2mo i, 1:collected in America, was left as a reminder of the principle laid down
2mo i, 1:in the Declaratory Act that Parliament had the right to tax the
2mo i, 1:colonists.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:This arrangement with the East India Company was obnoxious to the
2mo i, 1:colonists for several reasons. It was an act of favoritism for one
2mo i, 1:thing, in the interest of a great monopoly. For another thing, it
2mo i, 1:promised to dump on the American market, suddenly, an immense amount of
2mo i, 1:cheap tea and so cause heavy losses to American merchants who had large
2mo i, 1:stocks on hand. It threatened with ruin the business of all those who
2mo i, 1:were engaged in clandestine trade with the Dutch. It carried with it an
2mo i, 1:irritating tax of three pence on imports. In Charleston, Annapolis, New
2mo i, 1:York, and Boston, captains of ships who brought tea under this act were
2mo i, 1:roughly handled. One night in December, 1773, a band of Boston citizens,
2mo i, 1:disguised as Indians, boarded the hated tea ships and dumped the cargo
2mo i, 1:into the harbor. This was serious business, for it was open, flagrant,
2mo i, 1:determined violation of the law. As such the British government viewed
2mo i, 1:it.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:RETALIATION BY THE BRITISH GOVERNMENT
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Reception of the News of the Tea Riot.=--The news of the tea riot in
2mo i, 1:Boston confirmed King George in his conviction that there should be no
2mo i, 1:soft policy in dealing with his American subjects. "The die is cast," he
2mo i, 1:stated with evident satisfaction. "The colonies must either triumph or
2mo i, 1:submit.... If we take the resolute part, they will undoubtedly be very
2mo i, 1:meek." Lord George Germain characterized the tea party as "the
2mo i, 1:proceedings of a tumultuous and riotous rabble who ought, if they had
2mo i, 1:the least prudence, to follow their mercantile employments and not
2mo i, 1:trouble themselves with politics and government, which they do not
2mo i, 1:understand." This expressed, in concise form, exactly the sentiments of
2mo i, 1:Lord North, who had then for three years been the king's chief minister.
2mo i, 1:Even Pitt, Lord Chatham, was prepared to support the government in
2mo i, 1:upholding its authority.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Five Intolerable Acts.=--Parliament, beginning on March 31, 1774,
2mo i, 1:passed five stringent measures, known in American history as the five
2mo i, 1:"intolerable acts." They were aimed at curing the unrest in America. The
2mo i, 1:_first_ of them was a bill absolutely shutting the port of Boston to
2mo i, 1:commerce with the outside world. The _second_, following closely,
2mo i, 1:revoked the Massachusetts charter of 1691 and provided furthermore that
2mo i, 1:the councilors should be appointed by the king, that all judges should
2mo i, 1:be named by the royal governor, and that town meetings (except to elect
2mo i, 1:certain officers) could not be held without the governor's consent. A
2mo i, 1:_third_ measure, after denouncing the "utter subversion of all lawful
2mo i, 1:government" in the provinces, authorized royal agents to transfer to
2mo i, 1:Great Britain or to other colonies the trials of officers or other
2mo i, 1:persons accused of murder in connection with the enforcement of the law.
2mo i, 1:The _fourth_ act legalized the quartering of troops in Massachusetts
2mo i, 1:towns. The _fifth_ of the measures was the Quebec Act, which granted
2mo i, 1:religious toleration to the Catholics in Canada, extended the boundaries
2mo i, 1:of Quebec southward to the Ohio River, and established, in this western
2mo i, 1:region, government by a viceroy.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The intolerable acts went through Parliament with extraordinary
2mo i, 1:celerity. There was an opposition, alert and informed; but it was
2mo i, 1:ineffective. Burke spoke eloquently against the Boston port bill,
2mo i, 1:condemning it roundly for punishing the innocent with the guilty, and
2mo i, 1:showing how likely it was to bring grave consequences in its train. He
2mo i, 1:was heard with respect and his pleas were rejected. The bill passed both
2mo i, 1:houses without a division, the entry "unanimous" being made upon their
2mo i, 1:journals although it did not accurately represent the state of opinion.
2mo i, 1:The law destroying the charter of Massachusetts passed the Commons by a
2mo i, 1:vote of three to one; and the third intolerable act by a vote of four to
2mo i, 1:one. The triumph of the ministry was complete. "What passed in Boston,"
2mo i, 1:exclaimed the great jurist, Lord Mansfield, "is the overt act of High
2mo i, 1:Treason proceeding from our over lenity and want of foresight." The
2mo i, 1:crown and Parliament were united in resorting to punitive measures.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:In the colonies the laws were received with consternation. To the
2mo i, 1:American Protestants, the Quebec Act was the most offensive. That
2mo i, 1:project they viewed not as an act of grace or of mercy but as a direct
2mo i, 1:attempt to enlist French Canadians on the side of Great Britain. The
2mo i, 1:British government did not grant religious toleration to Catholics
2mo i, 1:either at home or in Ireland and the Americans could see no good motive
2mo i, 1:in granting it in North America. The act was also offensive because
2mo i, 1:Massachusetts, Connecticut, and Virginia had, under their charters,
2mo i, 1:large claims in the territory thus annexed to Quebec.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:To enforce these intolerable acts the military arm of the British
2mo i, 1:government was brought into play. The commander-in-chief of the armed
2mo i, 1:forces in America, General Gage, was appointed governor of
2mo i, 1:Massachusetts. Reinforcements were brought to the colonies, for now King
2mo i, 1:George was to give "the rebels," as he called them, a taste of strong
2mo i, 1:medicine. The majesty of his law was to be vindicated by force.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:FROM REFORM TO REVOLUTION IN AMERICA
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Doctrine of Natural Rights.=--The dissolution of assemblies, the
2mo i, 1:destruction of charters, and the use of troops produced in the colonies
2mo i, 1:a new phase in the struggle. In the early days of the contest with the
2mo i, 1:British ministry, the Americans spoke of their "rights as Englishmen"
2mo i, 1:and condemned the acts of Parliament as unlawful, as violating the
2mo i, 1:principles of the English constitution under which they all lived. When
2mo i, 1:they saw that such arguments had no effect on Parliament, they turned
2mo i, 1:for support to their "natural rights." The latter doctrine, in the form
2mo i, 1:in which it was employed by the colonists, was as English as the
2mo i, 1:constitutional argument. John Locke had used it with good effect in
2mo i, 1:defense of the English revolution in the seventeenth century. American
2mo i, 1:leaders, familiar with the writings of Locke, also took up his thesis in
2mo i, 1:the hour of their distress. They openly declared that their rights did
2mo i, 1:not rest after all upon the English constitution or a charter from the
2mo i, 1:crown. "Old Magna Carta was not the beginning of all things," retorted
2mo i, 1:Otis when the constitutional argument failed. "A time may come when
2mo i, 1:Parliament shall declare every American charter void, but the natural,
2mo i, 1:inherent, and inseparable rights of the colonists as men and as citizens
2mo i, 1:would remain and whatever became of charters can never be abolished
2mo i, 1:until the general conflagration." Of the same opinion was the young and
2mo i, 1:impetuous Alexander Hamilton. "The sacred rights of mankind," he
2mo i, 1:exclaimed, "are not to be rummaged for among old parchments or musty
2mo i, 1:records. They are written as with a sunbeam in the whole volume of human
2mo i, 1:destiny by the hand of divinity itself, and can never be erased or
2mo i, 1:obscured by mortal power."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Firm as the American leaders were in the statement and defense of their
2mo i, 1:rights, there is every reason for believing that in the beginning they
2mo i, 1:hoped to confine the conflict to the realm of opinion. They constantly
2mo i, 1:avowed that they were loyal to the king when protesting in the strongest
2mo i, 1:language against his policies. Even Otis, regarded by the loyalists as a
2mo i, 1:firebrand, was in fact attempting to avert revolution by winning
2mo i, 1:concessions from England. "I argue this cause with the greater
2mo i, 1:pleasure," he solemnly urged in his speech against the writs of
2mo i, 1:assistance, "as it is in favor of British liberty ... and as it is in
2mo i, 1:opposition to a kind of power, the exercise of which in former periods
2mo i, 1:cost one king of England his head and another his throne."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Burke Offers the Doctrine of Conciliation.=--The flooding tide of
2mo i, 1:American sentiment was correctly measured by one Englishman at least,
2mo i, 1:Edmund Burke, who quickly saw that attempts to restrain the rise of
2mo i, 1:American democracy were efforts to reverse the processes of nature. He
2mo i, 1:saw how fixed and rooted in the nature of things was the American
2mo i, 1:spirit--how inevitable, how irresistible. He warned his countrymen that
2mo i, 1:there were three ways of handling the delicate situation--and only
2mo i, 1:three. One was to remove the cause of friction by changing the spirit of
2mo i, 1:the colonists--an utter impossibility because that spirit was grounded
2mo i, 1:in the essential circumstances of American life. The second was to
2mo i, 1:prosecute American leaders as criminals; of this he begged his
2mo i, 1:countrymen to beware lest the colonists declare that "a government
2mo i, 1:against which a claim of liberty is tantamount to high treason is a
2mo i, 1:government to which submission is equivalent to slavery." The third and
2mo i, 1:right way to meet the problem, Burke concluded, was to accept the
2mo i, 1:American spirit, repeal the obnoxious measures, and receive the colonies
2mo i, 1:into equal partnership.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Events Produce the Great Decision.=--The right way, indicated by Burke,
2mo i, 1:was equally impossible to George III and the majority in Parliament. To
2mo i, 1:their narrow minds, American opinion was contemptible and American
2mo i, 1:resistance unlawful, riotous, and treasonable. The correct way, in their
2mo i, 1:view, was to dispatch more troops to crush the "rebels"; and that very
2mo i, 1:act took the contest from the realm of opinion. As John Adams said:
2mo i, 1:"Facts are stubborn things." Opinions were unseen, but marching soldiers
2mo i, 1:were visible to the veriest street urchin. "Now," said Gouverneur
2mo i, 1:Morris, "the sheep, simple as they are, cannot be gulled as heretofore."
2mo i, 1:It was too late to talk about the excellence of the British
2mo i, 1:constitution. If any one is bewildered by the controversies of modern
2mo i, 1:historians as to why the crisis came at last, he can clarify his
2mo i, 1:understanding by reading again Edmund Burke's stately oration, _On
2mo i, 1:Conciliation with America_.
