2mo i, 1:CHAPTER VI
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:THE AMERICAN REVOLUTION
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:RESISTANCE AND RETALIATION
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Continental Congress.=--When the news of the "intolerable acts"
2mo i, 1:reached America, every one knew what strong medicine Parliament was
2mo i, 1:prepared to administer to all those who resisted its authority. The
2mo i, 1:cause of Massachusetts became the cause of all the colonies. Opposition
2mo i, 1:to British policy, hitherto local and spasmodic, now took on a national
2mo i, 1:character. To local committees and provincial conventions was added a
2mo i, 1:Continental Congress, appropriately called by Massachusetts on June 17,
2mo i, 1:1774, at the instigation of Samuel Adams. The response to the summons
2mo i, 1:was electric. By hurried and irregular methods delegates were elected
2mo i, 1:during the summer, and on September 5 the Congress duly assembled in
2mo i, 1:Carpenter's Hall in Philadelphia. Many of the greatest men in America
2mo i, 1:were there--George Washington and Patrick Henry from Virginia and John
2mo i, 1:and Samuel Adams from Massachusetts. Every shade of opinion was
2mo i, 1:represented. Some were impatient with mild devices; the majority favored
2mo i, 1:moderation.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The Congress drew up a declaration of American rights and stated in
2mo i, 1:clear and dignified language the grievances of the colonists. It
2mo i, 1:approved the resistance to British measures offered by Massachusetts and
2mo i, 1:promised the united support of all sections. It prepared an address to
2mo i, 1:King George and another to the people of England, disavowing the idea of
2mo i, 1:independence but firmly attacking the policies pursued by the British
2mo i, 1:government.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Non-Importation Agreement.=--The Congress was not content, however,
2mo i, 1:with professions of faith and with petitions. It took one revolutionary
2mo i, 1:step. It agreed to stop the importation of British goods into America,
2mo i, 1:and the enforcement of this agreement it placed in the hands of local
2mo i, 1:"committees of safety and inspection," to be elected by the qualified
2mo i, 1:voters. The significance of this action is obvious. Congress threw
2mo i, 1:itself athwart British law. It made a rule to bind American citizens and
2mo i, 1:to be carried into effect by American officers. It set up a state within
2mo i, 1:the British state and laid down a test of allegiance to the new order.
2mo i, 1:The colonists, who up to this moment had been wavering, had to choose
2mo i, 1:one authority or the other. They were for the enforcement of the
2mo i, 1:non-importation agreement or they were against it. They either bought
2mo i, 1:English goods or they did not. In the spirit of the toast--"May Britain
2mo i, 1:be wise and America be free"--the first Continental Congress adjourned
2mo i, 1:in October, having appointed the tenth of May following for the meeting
2mo i, 1:of a second Congress, should necessity require.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Lord North's "Olive Branch."=--When the news of the action of the
2mo i, 1:American Congress reached England, Pitt and Burke warmly urged a repeal
2mo i, 1:of the obnoxious laws, but in vain. All they could wring from the prime
2mo i, 1:minister, Lord North, was a set of "conciliatory resolutions" proposing
2mo i, 1:to relieve from taxation any colony that would assume its share of
2mo i, 1:imperial defense and make provision for supporting the local officers of
2mo i, 1:the crown. This "olive branch" was accompanied by a resolution assuring
2mo i, 1:the king of support at all hazards in suppressing the rebellion and by
2mo i, 1:the restraining act of March 30, 1775, which in effect destroyed the
2mo i, 1:commerce of New England.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Bloodshed at Lexington and Concord (April 19, 1775).=--Meanwhile the
2mo i, 1:British authorities in Massachusetts relaxed none of their efforts in
2mo i, 1:upholding British sovereignty. General Gage, hearing that military
2mo i, 1:stores had been collected at Concord, dispatched a small force to seize
2mo i, 1:them. By this act he precipitated the conflict he had sought to avoid.
2mo i, 1:At Lexington, on the road to Concord, occurred "the little thing" that
2mo i, 1:produced "the great event." An unexpected collision beyond the thought
2mo i, 1:or purpose of any man had transferred the contest from the forum to the
2mo i, 1:battle field.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Second Continental Congress.=--Though blood had been shed and war
2mo i, 1:was actually at hand, the second Continental Congress, which met at
2mo i, 1:Philadelphia in May, 1775, was not yet convinced that conciliation was
2mo i, 1:beyond human power. It petitioned the king to interpose on behalf of the
2mo i, 1:colonists in order that the empire might avoid the calamities of civil
2mo i, 1:war. On the last day of July, it made a temperate but firm answer to
2mo i, 1:Lord North's offer of conciliation, stating that the proposal was
2mo i, 1:unsatisfactory because it did not renounce the right to tax or repeal
2mo i, 1:the offensive acts of Parliament.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Force, the British Answer.=--Just as the representatives of America
2mo i, 1:were about to present the last petition of Congress to the king on
2mo i, 1:August 23, 1775, George III issued a proclamation of rebellion. This
2mo i, 1:announcement declared that the colonists, "misled by dangerous and
2mo i, 1:ill-designing men," were in a state of insurrection; it called on the
2mo i, 1:civil and military powers to bring "the traitors to justice"; and it
2mo i, 1:threatened with "condign punishment the authors, perpetrators, and
2mo i, 1:abettors of such traitorous designs." It closed with the usual prayer:
2mo i, 1:"God, save the king." Later in the year, Parliament passed a sweeping
2mo i, 1:act destroying all trade and intercourse with America. Congress was
2mo i, 1:silent at last. Force was also America's answer.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:AMERICAN INDEPENDENCE
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Drifting into War.=--Although the Congress had not given up all hope of
2mo i, 1:reconciliation in the spring and summer of 1775, it had firmly resolved
2mo i, 1:to defend American rights by arms if necessary. It transformed the
2mo i, 1:militiamen who had assembled near Boston, after the battle of Lexington,
2mo i, 1:into a Continental army and selected Washington as commander-in-chief.
2mo i, 1:It assumed the powers of a government and prepared to raise money, wage
2mo i, 1:war, and carry on diplomatic relations with foreign countries.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:[Illustration: _From an old print_
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:SPIRIT OF 1776]
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Events followed thick and fast. On June 17, the American militia, by
2mo i, 1:the stubborn defense of Bunker Hill, showed that it could make British
2mo i, 1:regulars pay dearly for all they got. On July 3, Washington took command
2mo i, 1:of the army at Cambridge. In January, 1776, after bitter disappointments
2mo i, 1:in drumming up recruits for its army in England, Scotland, and Ireland,
2mo i, 1:the British government concluded a treaty with the Landgrave of
2mo i, 1:Hesse-Cassel in Germany contracting, at a handsome figure, for thousands
2mo i, 1:of soldiers and many pieces of cannon. This was the crowning insult to
2mo i, 1:America. Such was the view of all friends of the colonies on both sides
2mo i, 1:of the water. Such was, long afterward, the judgment of the conservative
2mo i, 1:historian Lecky: "The conduct of England in hiring German mercenaries to
2mo i, 1:subdue the essentially English population beyond the Atlantic made
2mo i, 1:reconciliation hopeless and independence inevitable." The news of this
2mo i, 1:wretched transaction in German soldiers had hardly reached America
2mo i, 1:before there ran all down the coast the thrilling story that Washington
2mo i, 1:had taken Boston, on March 17, 1776, compelling Lord Howe to sail with
2mo i, 1:his entire army for Halifax.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Growth of Public Sentiment in Favor of Independence.=--Events were
2mo i, 1:bearing the Americans away from their old position under the British
2mo i, 1:constitution toward a final separation. Slowly and against their
2mo i, 1:desires, prudent and honorable men, who cherished the ties that united
2mo i, 1:them to the old order and dreaded with genuine horror all thought of
2mo i, 1:revolution, were drawn into the path that led to the great decision. In
2mo i, 1:all parts of the country and among all classes, the question of the hour
2mo i, 1:was being debated. "American independence," as the historian Bancroft
2mo i, 1:says, "was not an act of sudden passion nor the work of one man or one
2mo i, 1:assembly. It had been discussed in every part of the country by farmers
2mo i, 1:and merchants, by mechanics and planters, by the fishermen along the
2mo i, 1:coast and the backwoodsmen of the West; in town meetings and from the
2mo i, 1:pulpit; at social gatherings and around the camp fires; in county
2mo i, 1:conventions and conferences or committees; in colonial congresses and
2mo i, 1:assemblies."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:[Illustration: _From an old print_
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:THOMAS PAINE]
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Paine's "Commonsense."=--In the midst of this ferment of American
2mo i, 1:opinion, a bold and eloquent pamphleteer broke in upon the hesitating
2mo i, 1:public with a program for absolute independence, without fears and
2mo i, 1:without apologies. In the early days of 1776, Thomas Paine issued the
2mo i, 1:first of his famous tracts, "Commonsense," a passionate attack upon the
2mo i, 1:British monarchy and an equally passionate plea for American liberty.
2mo i, 1:Casting aside the language of petition with which Americans had hitherto
2mo i, 1:addressed George III, Paine went to the other extreme and assailed him
2mo i, 1:with many a violent epithet. He condemned monarchy itself as a system
2mo i, 1:which had laid the world "in blood and ashes." Instead of praising the
2mo i, 1:British constitution under which colonists had been claiming their
2mo i, 1:rights, he brushed it aside as ridiculous, protesting that it was "owing
2mo i, 1:to the constitution of the people, not to the constitution of the
2mo i, 1:government, that the Crown is not as oppressive in England as in
2mo i, 1:Turkey."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Having thus summarily swept away the grounds of allegiance to the old
2mo i, 1:order, Paine proceeded relentlessly to an argument for immediate
2mo i, 1:separation from Great Britain. There was nothing in the sphere of
2mo i, 1:practical interest, he insisted, which should bind the colonies to the
2mo i, 1:mother country. Allegiance to her had been responsible for the many wars
2mo i, 1:in which they had been involved. Reasons of trade were not less weighty
2mo i, 1:in behalf of independence. "Our corn will fetch its price in any market
2mo i, 1:in Europe and our imported goods must be paid for, buy them where we
2mo i, 1:will." As to matters of government, "it is not in the power of Britain
2mo i, 1:to do this continent justice; the business of it will soon be too
2mo i, 1:weighty and intricate to be managed with any tolerable degree of
2mo i, 1:convenience by a power so distant from us and so very ignorant of us."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:There is accordingly no alternative to independence for America.
2mo i, 1:"Everything that is right or natural pleads for separation. The blood of
2mo i, 1:the slain, the weeping voice of nature cries ''tis time to part.' ...
2mo i, 1:Arms, the last resort, must decide the contest; the appeal was the
2mo i, 1:choice of the king and the continent hath accepted the challenge.... The
2mo i, 1:sun never shone on a cause of greater worth. 'Tis not the affair of a
2mo i, 1:city, a county, a province or a kingdom, but of a continent.... 'Tis not
2mo i, 1:the concern of a day, a year or an age; posterity is involved in the
2mo i, 1:contest and will be more or less affected to the end of time by the
2mo i, 1:proceedings now. Now is the seed-time of Continental union, faith, and
2mo i, 1:honor.... O! ye that love mankind! Ye that dare oppose not only the
2mo i, 1:tyranny, but the tyrant, stand forth.... Let names of Whig and Tory be
2mo i, 1:extinct. Let none other be heard among us than those of a good citizen,
2mo i, 1:an open and resolute friend, and a virtuous supporter of the rights of
2mo i, 1:mankind and of the free and independent states of America." As more than
2mo i, 1:100,000 copies were scattered broadcast over the country, patriots
2mo i, 1:exclaimed with Washington: "Sound doctrine and unanswerable reason!"
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Drift of Events toward Independence.=--Official support for the
2mo i, 1:idea of independence began to come from many quarters. On the tenth of
2mo i, 1:February, 1776, Gadsden, in the provincial convention of South Carolina,
2mo i, 1:advocated a new constitution for the colony and absolute independence
2mo i, 1:for all America. The convention balked at the latter but went half way
2mo i, 1:by abolishing the system of royal administration and establishing a
2mo i, 1:complete plan of self-government. A month later, on April 12, the
2mo i, 1:neighboring state of North Carolina uttered the daring phrase from which
2mo i, 1:others shrank. It empowered its representatives in the Congress to
2mo i, 1:concur with the delegates of the other colonies in declaring
2mo i, 1:independence. Rhode Island, Massachusetts, and Virginia quickly
2mo i, 1:responded to the challenge. The convention of the Old Dominion, on May
2mo i, 1:15, instructed its delegates at Philadelphia to propose the independence
2mo i, 1:of the United Colonies and to give the assent of Virginia to the act of
2mo i, 1:separation. When the resolution was carried the British flag on the
2mo i, 1:state house was lowered for all time.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Meanwhile the Continental Congress was alive to the course of events
2mo i, 1:outside. The subject of independence was constantly being raised. "Are
2mo i, 1:we rebels?" exclaimed Wyeth of Virginia during a debate in February.
2mo i, 1:"No: we must declare ourselves a free people." Others hesitated and
2mo i, 1:spoke of waiting for the arrival of commissioners of conciliation. "Is
2mo i, 1:not America already independent?" asked Samuel Adams a few weeks later.
2mo i, 1:"Why not then declare it?" Still there was uncertainty and delegates
2mo i, 1:avoided the direct word. A few more weeks elapsed. At last, on May 10,
2mo i, 1:Congress declared that the authority of the British crown in America
2mo i, 1:must be suppressed and advised the colonies to set up governments of
2mo i, 1:their own.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:[Illustration: _From an old print_
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:THOMAS JEFFERSON READING HIS DRAFT OF THE DECLARATION OF
2mo i, 1:INDEPENDENCE TO THE COMMITTEE OF CONGRESS]
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Independence Declared.=--The way was fully prepared, therefore, when,
2mo i, 1:on June 7, the Virginia delegation in the Congress moved that "these
2mo i, 1:united colonies are and of right ought to be free and independent
2mo i, 1:states." A committee was immediately appointed to draft a formal
2mo i, 1:document setting forth the reasons for the act, and on July 2 all the
2mo i, 1:states save New York went on record in favor of severing their political
2mo i, 1:connection with Great Britain. Two days later, July 4, Jefferson's draft
2mo i, 1:of the Declaration of Independence, changed in some slight particulars,
2mo i, 1:was adopted. The old bell in Independence Hall, as it is now known, rang
2mo i, 1:out the glad tidings; couriers swiftly carried the news to the uttermost
2mo i, 1:hamlet and farm. A new nation announced its will to have a place among
2mo i, 1:the powers of the world.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:To some documents is given immortality. The Declaration of Independence
2mo i, 1:is one of them. American patriotism is forever associated with it; but
2mo i, 1:patriotism alone does not make it immortal. Neither does the vigor of
2mo i, 1:its language or the severity of its indictment give it a secure place in
2mo i, 1:the records of time. The secret of its greatness lies in the simple fact
2mo i, 1:that it is one of the memorable landmarks in the history of a political
2mo i, 1:ideal which for three centuries has been taking form and spreading
2mo i, 1:throughout the earth, challenging kings and potentates, shaking down
2mo i, 1:thrones and aristocracies, breaking the armies of irresponsible power on
2mo i, 1:battle fields as far apart as Marston Moor and Chateau-Thierry. That
2mo i, 1:ideal, now so familiar, then so novel, is summed up in the simple
2mo i, 1:sentence: "Governments derive their just powers from the consent of the
2mo i, 1:governed."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Written in a "decent respect for the opinions of mankind," to set forth
2mo i, 1:the causes which impelled the American colonists to separate from
2mo i, 1:Britain, the Declaration contained a long list of "abuses and
2mo i, 1:usurpations" which had induced them to throw off the government of King
2mo i, 1:George. That section of the Declaration has passed into "ancient"
2mo i, 1:history and is seldom read. It is the part laying down a new basis for
2mo i, 1:government and giving a new dignity to the common man that has become a
2mo i, 1:household phrase in the Old World as in the New.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:In the more enduring passages there are four fundamental ideas which,
2mo i, 1:from the standpoint of the old system of government, were the essence of
2mo i, 1:revolution: (1) all men are created equal and are endowed by their
2mo i, 1:Creator with certain unalienable rights including life, liberty, and the
2mo i, 1:pursuit of happiness; (2) the purpose of government is to secure these
2mo i, 1:rights; (3) governments derive their just powers from the consent of the
2mo i, 1:governed; (4) whenever any form of government becomes destructive of
2mo i, 1:these ends it is the right of the people to alter or abolish it and
2mo i, 1:institute new government, laying its foundations on such principles and
2mo i, 1:organizing its powers in such form as to them shall seem most likely to
2mo i, 1:effect their safety and happiness. Here was the prelude to the historic
2mo i, 1:drama of democracy--a challenge to every form of government and every
2mo i, 1:privilege not founded on popular assent.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:THE ESTABLISHMENT OF GOVERNMENT AND THE NEW ALLEGIANCE
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Committees of Correspondence.=--As soon as debate had passed into
2mo i, 1:armed resistance, the patriots found it necessary to consolidate their
2mo i, 1:forces by organizing civil government. This was readily effected, for
2mo i, 1:the means were at hand in town meetings, provincial legislatures, and
2mo i, 1:committees of correspondence. The working tools of the Revolution were
2mo i, 1:in fact the committees of correspondence--small, local, unofficial
2mo i, 1:groups of patriots formed to exchange views and create public sentiment.
2mo i, 1:As early as November, 1772, such a committee had been created in Boston
2mo i, 1:under the leadership of Samuel Adams. It held regular meetings, sent
2mo i, 1:emissaries to neighboring towns, and carried on a campaign of education
2mo i, 1:in the doctrines of liberty.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:[Illustration: THE COLONIES OF NORTH AMERICA AT THE TIME OF THE
2mo i, 1:DECLARATION OF INDEPENDENCE]
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Upon local organizations similar in character to the Boston committee
2mo i, 1:were built county committees and then the larger colonial committees,
2mo i, 1:congresses, and conventions, all unofficial and representing the
2mo i, 1:revolutionary elements. Ordinarily the provincial convention was merely
2mo i, 1:the old legislative assembly freed from all royalist sympathizers and
2mo i, 1:controlled by patriots. Finally, upon these colonial assemblies was
2mo i, 1:built the Continental Congress, the precursor of union under the
2mo i, 1:Articles of Confederation and ultimately under the Constitution of the
2mo i, 1:United States. This was the revolutionary government set up within the
2mo i, 1:British empire in America.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=State Constitutions Framed.=--With the rise of these new assemblies of
2mo i, 1:the people, the old colonial governments broke down. From the royal
2mo i, 1:provinces the governor, the judges, and the high officers fled in haste,
2mo i, 1:and it became necessary to substitute patriot authorities. The appeal to
2mo i, 1:the colonies advising them to adopt a new form of government for
2mo i, 1:themselves, issued by the Congress in May, 1776, was quickly acted upon.
2mo i, 1:Before the expiration of a year, Virginia, New Jersey, Pennsylvania,
2mo i, 1:Delaware, Maryland, Georgia, and New York had drafted new constitutions
2mo i, 1:as states, not as colonies uncertain of their destinies. Connecticut and
2mo i, 1:Rhode Island, holding that their ancient charters were equal to their
2mo i, 1:needs, merely renounced their allegiance to the king and went on as
2mo i, 1:before so far as the form of government was concerned. South Carolina,
2mo i, 1:which had drafted a temporary plan early in 1776, drew up a new and more
2mo i, 1:complete constitution in 1778. Two years later Massachusetts with much
2mo i, 1:deliberation put into force its fundamental law, which in most of its
2mo i, 1:essential features remains unchanged to-day.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The new state constitutions in their broad outlines followed colonial
2mo i, 1:models. For the royal governor was substituted a governor or president
2mo i, 1:chosen usually by the legislature; but in two instances, New York and
2mo i, 1:Massachusetts, by popular vote. For the provincial council there was
2mo i, 1:substituted, except in Georgia, a senate; while the lower house, or
2mo i, 1:assembly, was continued virtually without change. The old property
2mo i, 1:restriction on the suffrage, though lowered slightly in some states, was
2mo i, 1:continued in full force to the great discontent of the mechanics thus
2mo i, 1:deprived of the ballot. The special qualifications, laid down in several
2mo i, 1:constitutions, for governors, senators, and representatives, indicated
2mo i, 1:that the revolutionary leaders were not prepared for any radical
2mo i, 1:experiments in democracy. The protests of a few women, like Mrs. John
2mo i, 1:Adams of Massachusetts and Mrs. Henry Corbin of Virginia, against a
2mo i, 1:government which excluded them from political rights were treated as
2mo i, 1:mild curiosities of no significance, although in New Jersey women were
2mo i, 1:allowed to vote for many years on the same terms as men.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:By the new state constitutions the signs and symbols of royal power, of
2mo i, 1:authority derived from any source save "the people," were swept aside
2mo i, 1:and republican governments on an imposing scale presented for the first
2mo i, 1:time to the modern world. Copies of these remarkable documents prepared
2mo i, 1:by plain citizens were translated into French and widely circulated in
2mo i, 1:Europe. There they were destined to serve as a guide and inspiration to
2mo i, 1:a generation of constitution-makers whose mission it was to begin the
2mo i, 1:democratic revolution in the Old World.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Articles of Confederation.=--The formation of state constitutions
2mo i, 1:was an easy task for the revolutionary leaders. They had only to build
2mo i, 1:on foundations already laid. The establishment of a national system of
2mo i, 1:government was another matter. There had always been, it must be
2mo i, 1:remembered, a system of central control over the colonies, but Americans
2mo i, 1:had had little experience in its operation. When the supervision of the
2mo i, 1:crown of Great Britain was suddenly broken, the patriot leaders,
2mo i, 1:accustomed merely to provincial statesmanship, were poorly trained for
2mo i, 1:action on a national stage.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Many forces worked against those who, like Franklin, had a vision of
2mo i, 1:national destiny. There were differences in economic interest--commerce
2mo i, 1:and industry in the North and the planting system of the South. There
2mo i, 1:were contests over the apportionment of taxes and the quotas of troops
2mo i, 1:for common defense. To these practical difficulties were added local
2mo i, 1:pride, the vested rights of state and village politicians in their
2mo i, 1:provincial dignity, and the scarcity of men with a large outlook upon
2mo i, 1:the common enterprise.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Nevertheless, necessity compelled them to consider some sort of
2mo i, 1:federation. The second Continental Congress had hardly opened its work
2mo i, 1:before the most sagacious leaders began to urge the desirability of a
2mo i, 1:permanent connection. As early as July, 1775, Congress resolved to go
2mo i, 1:into a committee of the whole on the state of the union, and Franklin,
2mo i, 1:undaunted by the fate of his Albany plan of twenty years before, again
2mo i, 1:presented a draft of a constitution. Long and desultory debates followed
2mo i, 1:and it was not until late in 1777 that Congress presented to the states
2mo i, 1:the Articles of Confederation. Provincial jealousies delayed
2mo i, 1:ratification, and it was the spring of 1781, a few months before the
2mo i, 1:surrender of Cornwallis at Yorktown, when Maryland, the last of the
2mo i, 1:states, approved the Articles. This plan of union, though it was all
2mo i, 1:that could be wrung from the reluctant states, provided for neither a
2mo i, 1:chief executive nor a system of federal courts. It created simply a
2mo i, 1:Congress of delegates in which each state had an equal voice and gave it
2mo i, 1:the right to call upon the state legislatures for the sinews of
2mo i, 1:government--money and soldiers.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Application of Tests of Allegiance.=--As the successive steps were
2mo i, 1:taken in the direction of independent government, the patriots devised
2mo i, 1:and applied tests designed to discover who were for and who were against
2mo i, 1:the new nation in the process of making. When the first Continental
2mo i, 1:Congress agreed not to allow the importation of British goods, it
2mo i, 1:provided for the creation of local committees to enforce the rules. Such
2mo i, 1:agencies were duly formed by the choice of men favoring the scheme, all
2mo i, 1:opponents being excluded from the elections. Before these bodies those
2mo i, 1:who persisted in buying British goods were summoned and warned or
2mo i, 1:punished according to circumstances. As soon as the new state
2mo i, 1:constitutions were put into effect, local committees set to work in the
2mo i, 1:same way to ferret out all who were not outspoken in their support of
2mo i, 1:the new order of things.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:[Illustration: MOBBING THE TORIES]
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:These patriot agencies, bearing different names in different sections,
2mo i, 1:were sometimes ruthless in their methods. They called upon all men to
2mo i, 1:sign the test of loyalty, frequently known as the "association test."
2mo i, 1:Those who refused were promptly branded as outlaws, while some of the
2mo i, 1:more dangerous were thrown into jail. The prison camp in Connecticut at
2mo i, 1:one time held the former governor of New Jersey and the mayor of New
2mo i, 1:York. Thousands were black-listed and subjected to espionage. The
2mo i, 1:black-list of Pennsylvania contained the names of nearly five hundred
2mo i, 1:persons of prominence who were under suspicion. Loyalists or Tories who
2mo i, 1:were bold enough to speak and write against the Revolution were
2mo i, 1:suppressed and their pamphlets burned. In many places, particularly in
2mo i, 1:the North, the property of the loyalists was confiscated and the
2mo i, 1:proceeds applied to the cause of the Revolution.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The work of the official agencies for suppression of opposition was
2mo i, 1:sometimes supplemented by mob violence. A few Tories were hanged without
2mo i, 1:trial, and others were tarred and feathered. One was placed upon a cake
2mo i, 1:of ice and held there "until his loyalty to King George might cool."
2mo i, 1:Whole families were driven out of their homes to find their way as best
2mo i, 1:they could within the British lines or into Canada, where the British
2mo i, 1:government gave them lands. Such excesses were deplored by Washington,
2mo i, 1:but they were defended on the ground that in effect a civil war, as well
2mo i, 1:as a war for independence, was being waged.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Patriots and Tories.=--Thus, by one process or another, those who
2mo i, 1:were to be citizens of the new republic were separated from those who
2mo i, 1:preferred to be subjects of King George. Just what proportion of the
2mo i, 1:Americans favored independence and what share remained loyal to the
2mo i, 1:British monarchy there is no way of knowing. The question of revolution
2mo i, 1:was not submitted to popular vote, and on the point of numbers we have
2mo i, 1:conflicting evidence. On the patriot side, there is the testimony of a
2mo i, 1:careful and informed observer, John Adams, who asserted that two-thirds
2mo i, 1:of the people were for the American cause and not more than one-third
2mo i, 1:opposed the Revolution at all stages.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:On behalf of the loyalists, or Tories as they were popularly known,
2mo i, 1:extravagant claims were made. Joseph Galloway, who had been a member of
2mo i, 1:the first Continental Congress and had fled to England when he saw its
2mo i, 1:temper, testified before a committee of Parliament in 1779 that not
2mo i, 1:one-fifth of the American people supported the insurrection and that
2mo i, 1:"many more than four-fifths of the people prefer a union with Great
2mo i, 1:Britain upon constitutional principles to independence." At the same
2mo i, 1:time General Robertson, who had lived in America twenty-four years,
2mo i, 1:declared that "more than two-thirds of the people would prefer the
2mo i, 1:king's government to the Congress' tyranny." In an address to the king
2mo i, 1:in that year a committee of American loyalists asserted that "the number
2mo i, 1:of Americans in his Majesty's army exceeded the number of troops
2mo i, 1:enlisted by Congress to oppose them."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Character of the Loyalists.=--When General Howe evacuated Boston,
2mo i, 1:more than a thousand people fled with him. This great company, according
2mo i, 1:to a careful historian, "formed the aristocracy of the province by
2mo i, 1:virtue of their official rank; of their dignified callings and
2mo i, 1:professions; of their hereditary wealth and of their culture." The act
2mo i, 1:of banishment passed by Massachusetts in 1778, listing over 300 Tories,
2mo i, 1:"reads like the social register of the oldest and noblest families of
2mo i, 1:New England," more than one out of five being graduates of Harvard
2mo i, 1:College. The same was true of New York and Philadelphia; namely, that
2mo i, 1:the leading loyalists were prominent officials of the old order,
2mo i, 1:clergymen and wealthy merchants. With passion the loyalists fought
2mo i, 1:against the inevitable or with anguish of heart they left as refugees
2mo i, 1:for a life of uncertainty in Canada or the mother country.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Tories Assail the Patriots.=--The Tories who remained in America joined
2mo i, 1:the British army by the thousands or in other ways aided the royal
2mo i, 1:cause. Those who were skillful with the pen assailed the patriots in
2mo i, 1:editorials, rhymes, satires, and political catechisms. They declared
2mo i, 1:that the members of Congress were "obscure, pettifogging attorneys,
2mo i, 1:bankrupt shopkeepers, outlawed smugglers, etc." The people and their
2mo i, 1:leaders they characterized as "wretched banditti ... the refuse and
2mo i, 1:dregs of mankind." The generals in the army they sneered at as "men of
2mo i, 1:rank and honor nearly on a par with those of the Congress."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Patriot Writers Arouse the National Spirit.=--Stung by Tory taunts,
2mo i, 1:patriot writers devoted themselves to creating and sustaining a public
2mo i, 1:opinion favorable to the American cause. Moreover, they had to combat
2mo i, 1:the depression that grew out of the misfortunes in the early days of the
2mo i, 1:war. A terrible disaster befell Generals Arnold and Montgomery in the
2mo i, 1:winter of 1775 as they attempted to bring Canada into the revolution--a
2mo i, 1:disaster that cost 5000 men; repeated calamities harassed Washington in
2mo i, 1:1776 as he was defeated on Long Island, driven out of New York City, and
2mo i, 1:beaten at Harlem Heights and White Plains. These reverses were almost
2mo i, 1:too great for the stoutest patriots.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Pamphleteers, preachers, and publicists rose, however, to meet the needs
2mo i, 1:of the hour. John Witherspoon, provost of the College of New Jersey,
2mo i, 1:forsook the classroom for the field of political controversy. The poet,
2mo i, 1:Philip Freneau, flung taunts of cowardice at the Tories and celebrated
2mo i, 1:the spirit of liberty in many a stirring poem. Songs, ballads, plays,
2mo i, 1:and satires flowed from the press in an unending stream. Fast days,
2mo i, 1:battle anniversaries, celebrations of important steps taken by Congress
2mo i, 1:afforded to patriotic clergymen abundant opportunities for sermons.
2mo i, 1:"Does Mr. Wiberd preach against oppression?" anxiously inquired John
2mo i, 1:Adams in a letter to his wife. The answer was decisive. "The clergy of
2mo i, 1:every denomination, not excepting the Episcopalian, thunder and lighten
2mo i, 1:every Sabbath. They pray for Boston and Massachusetts. They thank God
2mo i, 1:most explicitly and fervently for our remarkable successes. They pray
2mo i, 1:for the American army."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Thomas Paine never let his pen rest. He had been with the forces of
2mo i, 1:Washington when they retreated from Fort Lee and were harried from New
2mo i, 1:Jersey into Pennsylvania. He knew the effect of such reverses on the
2mo i, 1:army as well as on the public. In December, 1776, he made a second great
2mo i, 1:appeal to his countrymen in his pamphlet, "The Crisis," the first part
2mo i, 1:of which he had written while defeat and gloom were all about him. This
2mo i, 1:tract was a cry for continued support of the Revolution. "These are the
2mo i, 1:times that try men's souls," he opened. "The summer soldier and the
2mo i, 1:sunshine patriot will, in this crisis, shrink from the service of his
2mo i, 1:country; but he that stands it now deserves the love and thanks of men
2mo i, 1:and women." Paine laid his lash fiercely on the Tories, branding every
2mo i, 1:one as a coward grounded in "servile, slavish, self-interested fear." He
2mo i, 1:deplored the inadequacy of the militia and called for a real army. He
2mo i, 1:refuted the charge that the retreat through New Jersey was a disaster
2mo i, 1:and he promised victory soon. "By perseverance and fortitude," he
2mo i, 1:concluded, "we have the prospect of a glorious issue; by cowardice and
2mo i, 1:submission the sad choice of a variety of evils--a ravaged country, a
2mo i, 1:depopulated city, habitations without safety and slavery without
2mo i, 1:hope.... Look on this picture and weep over it." His ringing call to
2mo i, 1:arms was followed by another and another until the long contest was
2mo i, 1:over.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:MILITARY AFFAIRS
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Two Phases of the War.=--The war which opened with the battle of
2mo i, 1:Lexington, on April 19, 1775, and closed with the surrender of
2mo i, 1:Cornwallis at Yorktown on October 19, 1781, passed through two distinct
2mo i, 1:phases--the first lasting until the treaty of alliance with France, in
2mo i, 1:1778, and the second until the end of the struggle. During the first
2mo i, 1:phase, the war was confined mainly to the North. The outstanding
2mo i, 1:features of the contest were the evacuation of Boston by the British,
2mo i, 1:the expulsion of American forces from New York and their retreat through
2mo i, 1:New Jersey, the battle of Trenton, the seizure of Philadelphia by the
2mo i, 1:British (September, 1777), the invasion of New York by Burgoyne and his
2mo i, 1:capture at Saratoga in October, 1777, and the encampment of American
2mo i, 1:forces at Valley Forge for the terrible winter of 1777-78.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The final phase of the war, opening with the treaty of alliance with
2mo i, 1:France on February 6, 1778, was confined mainly to the Middle states,
2mo i, 1:the West, and the South. In the first sphere of action the chief events
2mo i, 1:were the withdrawal of the British from Philadelphia, the battle of
2mo i, 1:Monmouth, and the inclosure of the British in New York by deploying
2mo i, 1:American forces from Morristown, New Jersey, up to West Point. In the
2mo i, 1:West, George Rogers Clark, by his famous march into the Illinois
2mo i, 1:country, secured Kaskaskia and Vincennes and laid a firm grip on the
2mo i, 1:country between the Ohio and the Great Lakes. In the South, the second
2mo i, 1:period opened with successes for the British. They captured Savannah,
2mo i, 1:conquered Georgia, and restored the royal governor. In 1780 they seized
2mo i, 1:Charleston, administered a crushing defeat to the American forces under
2mo i, 1:Gates at Camden, and overran South Carolina, though meeting reverses at
2mo i, 1:Cowpens and King's Mountain. Then came the closing scenes. Cornwallis
2mo i, 1:began the last of his operations. He pursued General Greene far into
2mo i, 1:North Carolina, clashed with him at Guilford Court House, retired to the
2mo i, 1:coast, took charge of British forces engaged in plundering Virginia, and
2mo i, 1:fortified Yorktown, where he was penned up by the French fleet from the
2mo i, 1:sea and the combined French and American forces on land.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Geographical Aspects of the War.=--For the British the theater of
2mo i, 1:the war offered many problems. From first to last it extended from
2mo i, 1:Massachusetts to Georgia, a distance of almost a thousand miles. It was
2mo i, 1:nearly three thousand miles from the main base of supplies and, though
2mo i, 1:the British navy kept the channel open, transports were constantly
2mo i, 1:falling prey to daring privateers and fleet American war vessels. The
2mo i, 1:sea, on the other hand, offered an easy means of transportation between
2mo i, 1:points along the coast and gave ready access to the American centers of
2mo i, 1:wealth and population. Of this the British made good use. Though early
2mo i, 1:forced to give up Boston, they seized New York and kept it until the end
2mo i, 1:of the war; they took Philadelphia and retained it until threatened by
2mo i, 1:the approach of the French fleet; and they captured and held both
2mo i, 1:Savannah and Charleston. Wars, however, are seldom won by the conquest
2mo i, 1:of cities.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Particularly was this true in the case of the Revolution. Only a small
2mo i, 1:portion of the American people lived in towns. Countrymen back from the
2mo i, 1:coast were in no way dependent upon them for a livelihood. They lived on
2mo i, 1:the produce of the soil, not upon the profits of trade. This very fact
2mo i, 1:gave strength to them in the contest. Whenever the British ventured far
2mo i, 1:from the ports of entry, they encountered reverses. Burgoyne was forced
2mo i, 1:to surrender at Saratoga because he was surrounded and cut off from his
2mo i, 1:base of supplies. As soon as the British got away from Charleston, they
2mo i, 1:were harassed and worried by the guerrilla warriors of Marion, Sumter,
2mo i, 1:and Pickens. Cornwallis could technically defeat Greene at Guilford far
2mo i, 1:in the interior; but he could not hold the inland region he had invaded.
2mo i, 1:Sustained by their own labor, possessing the interior to which their
2mo i, 1:armies could readily retreat, supplied mainly from native resources, the
2mo i, 1:Americans could not be hemmed in, penned up, and destroyed at one fell
2mo i, 1:blow.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Sea Power.=--The British made good use of their fleet in cutting
2mo i, 1:off American trade, but control of the sea did not seriously affect the
2mo i, 1:United States. As an agricultural country, the ruin of its commerce was
2mo i, 1:not such a vital matter. All the materials for a comfortable though
2mo i, 1:somewhat rude life were right at hand. It made little difference to a
2mo i, 1:nation fighting for existence, if silks, fine linens, and chinaware were
2mo i, 1:cut off. This was an evil to which submission was necessary.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Nor did the brilliant exploits of John Paul Jones and Captain John Barry
2mo i, 1:materially change the situation. They demonstrated the skill of American
2mo i, 1:seamen and their courage as fighting men. They raised the rates of
2mo i, 1:British marine insurance, but they did not dethrone the mistress of the
2mo i, 1:seas. Less spectacular, and more distinctive, were the deeds of the
2mo i, 1:hundreds of privateers and minor captains who overhauled British supply
2mo i, 1:ships and kept British merchantmen in constant anxiety. Not until the
2mo i, 1:French fleet was thrown into the scale, were the British compelled to
2mo i, 1:reckon seriously with the enemy on the sea and make plans based upon the
2mo i, 1:possibilities of a maritime disaster.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Commanding Officers.=--On the score of military leadership it is
2mo i, 1:difficult to compare the contending forces in the revolutionary contest.
2mo i, 1:There is no doubt that all the British commanders were men of experience
2mo i, 1:in the art of warfare. Sir William Howe had served in America during the
2mo i, 1:French War and was accounted an excellent officer, a strict
2mo i, 1:disciplinarian, and a gallant gentleman. Nevertheless he loved ease,
2mo i, 1:society, and good living, and his expulsion from Boston, his failure to
2mo i, 1:overwhelm Washington by sallies from his comfortable bases at New York
2mo i, 1:and Philadelphia, destroyed every shred of his military reputation. John
2mo i, 1:Burgoyne, to whom was given the task of penetrating New York from
2mo i, 1:Canada, had likewise seen service in the French War both in America and
2mo i, 1:Europe. He had, however, a touch of the theatrical in his nature and
2mo i, 1:after the collapse of his plans and the surrender of his army in 1777,
2mo i, 1:he devoted his time mainly to light literature. Sir Henry Clinton, who
2mo i, 1:directed the movement which ended in the capture of Charleston in 1780,
2mo i, 1:had "learned his trade on the continent," and was regarded as a man of
2mo i, 1:discretion and understanding in military matters. Lord Cornwallis, whose
2mo i, 1:achievements at Camden and Guilford were blotted out by his surrender at
2mo i, 1:Yorktown, had seen service in the Seven Years' War and had undoubted
2mo i, 1:talents which he afterward displayed with great credit to himself in
2mo i, 1:India. Though none of them, perhaps, were men of first-rate ability,
2mo i, 1:they all had training and experience to guide them.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:[Illustration: GEORGE WASHINGTON]
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The Americans had a host in Washington himself. He had long been
2mo i, 1:interested in military strategy and had tested his coolness under fire
2mo i, 1:during the first clashes with the French nearly twenty years before. He
2mo i, 1:had no doubts about the justice of his cause, such as plagued some of
2mo i, 1:the British generals. He was a stern but reasonable disciplinarian. He
2mo i, 1:was reserved and patient, little given to exaltation at success or
2mo i, 1:depression at reverses. In the dark hour of the Revolution, "what held
2mo i, 1:the patriot forces together?" asks Beveridge in his _Life of John
2mo i, 1:Marshall_. Then he answers: "George Washington and he alone. Had he
2mo i, 1:died or been seriously disabled, the Revolution would have ended....
2mo i, 1:Washington was the soul of the American cause. Washington was the
2mo i, 1:government. Washington was the Revolution." The weakness of Congress in
2mo i, 1:furnishing men and supplies, the indolence of civilians, who lived at
2mo i, 1:ease while the army starved, the intrigues of army officers against him
2mo i, 1:such as the "Conway cabal," the cowardice of Lee at Monmouth, even the
2mo i, 1:treason of Benedict Arnold, while they stirred deep emotions in his
2mo i, 1:breast and aroused him to make passionate pleas to his countrymen, did
2mo i, 1:not shake his iron will or his firm determination to see the war through
2mo i, 1:to the bitter end. The weight of Washington's moral force was
2mo i, 1:immeasurable.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Of the generals who served under him, none can really be said to have
2mo i, 1:been experienced military men when the war opened. Benedict Arnold, the
2mo i, 1:unhappy traitor but brave and daring soldier, was a druggist, book
2mo i, 1:seller, and ship owner at New Haven when the news of Lexington called
2mo i, 1:him to battle. Horatio Gates was looked upon as a "seasoned soldier"
2mo i, 1:because he had entered the British army as a youth, had been wounded at
2mo i, 1:Braddock's memorable defeat, and had served with credit during the Seven
2mo i, 1:Years' War; but he was the most conspicuous failure of the Revolution.
2mo i, 1:The triumph over Burgoyne was the work of other men; and his crushing
2mo i, 1:defeat at Camden put an end to his military pretensions. Nathanael
2mo i, 1:Greene was a Rhode Island farmer and smith without military experience
2mo i, 1:who, when convinced that war was coming, read Caesar's _Commentaries_ and
2mo i, 1:took up the sword. Francis Marion was a shy and modest planter of South
2mo i, 1:Carolina whose sole passage at arms had been a brief but desperate brush
2mo i, 1:with the Indians ten or twelve years earlier. Daniel Morgan, one of the
2mo i, 1:heroes of Cowpens, had been a teamster with Braddock's army and had seen
2mo i, 1:some fighting during the French and Indian War, but his military
2mo i, 1:knowledge, from the point of view of a trained British officer, was
2mo i, 1:negligible. John Sullivan was a successful lawyer at Durham, New
2mo i, 1:Hampshire, and a major in the local militia when duty summoned him to
2mo i, 1:lay down his briefs and take up the sword. Anthony Wayne was a
2mo i, 1:Pennsylvania farmer and land surveyor who, on hearing the clash of arms,
2mo i, 1:read a few books on war, raised a regiment, and offered himself for
2mo i, 1:service. Such is the story of the chief American military leaders, and
2mo i, 1:it is typical of them all. Some had seen fighting with the French and
2mo i, 1:Indians, but none of them had seen warfare on a large scale with regular
2mo i, 1:troops commanded according to the strategy evolved in European
2mo i, 1:experience. Courage, native ability, quickness of mind, and knowledge of
2mo i, 1:the country they had in abundance, and in battles such as were fought
2mo i, 1:during the Revolution all those qualities counted heavily in the
2mo i, 1:balance.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Foreign Officers in American Service.=--To native genius was added
2mo i, 1:military talent from beyond the seas. Baron Steuben, well schooled in
2mo i, 1:the iron regime of Frederick the Great, came over from Prussia, joined
2mo i, 1:Washington at Valley Forge, and day after day drilled and manoeuvered the
2mo i, 1:men, laughing and cursing as he turned raw countrymen into regular
2mo i, 1:soldiers. From France came young Lafayette and the stern De Kalb, from
2mo i, 1:Poland came Pulaski and Kosciusko;--all acquainted with the arts of war
2mo i, 1:as waged in Europe and fitted for leadership as well as teaching.
2mo i, 1:Lafayette came early, in 1776, in a ship of his own, accompanied by
2mo i, 1:several officers of wide experience, and remained loyally throughout the
2mo i, 1:war sharing the hardships of American army life. Pulaski fell at the
2mo i, 1:siege of Savannah and De Kalb at Camden. Kosciusko survived the American
2mo i, 1:war to defend in vain the independence of his native land. To these
2mo i, 1:distinguished foreigners, who freely threw in their lot with American
2mo i, 1:revolutionary fortunes, was due much of that spirit and discipline which
2mo i, 1:fitted raw recruits and temperamental militiamen to cope with a military
2mo i, 1:power of the first rank.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Soldiers.=--As far as the British soldiers were concerned their
2mo i, 1:annals are short and simple. The regulars from the standing army who
2mo i, 1:were sent over at the opening of the contest, the recruits drummed up
2mo i, 1:by special efforts at home, and the thousands of Hessians bought
2mo i, 1:outright by King George presented few problems of management to the
2mo i, 1:British officers. These common soldiers were far away from home and
2mo i, 1:enlisted for the war. Nearly all of them were well disciplined and many
2mo i, 1:of them experienced in actual campaigns. The armies of King George
2mo i, 1:fought bravely, as the records of Bunker Hill, Brandywine, and Monmouth
2mo i, 1:demonstrate. Many a man and subordinate officer and, for that matter,
2mo i, 1:some of the high officers expressed a reluctance at fighting against
2mo i, 1:their own kin; but they obeyed orders.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The Americans, on the other hand, while they fought with grim
2mo i, 1:determination, as men fighting for their homes, were lacking in
2mo i, 1:discipline and in the experience of regular troops. When the war broke
2mo i, 1:in upon them, there were no common preparations for it. There was no
2mo i, 1:continental army; there were only local bands of militiamen, many of
2mo i, 1:them experienced in fighting but few of them "regulars" in the military
2mo i, 1:sense. Moreover they were volunteers serving for a short time,
2mo i, 1:unaccustomed to severe discipline, and impatient at the restraints
2mo i, 1:imposed on them by long and arduous campaigns. They were continually
2mo i, 1:leaving the service just at the most critical moments. "The militia,"
2mo i, 1:lamented Washington, "come in, you cannot tell how; go, you cannot tell
2mo i, 1:where; consume your provisions; exhaust your stores; and leave you at
2mo i, 1:last at a critical moment."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Again and again Washington begged Congress to provide for an army of
2mo i, 1:regulars enlisted for the war, thoroughly trained and paid according to
2mo i, 1:some definite plan. At last he was able to overcome, in part at least,
2mo i, 1:the chronic fear of civilians in Congress and to wring from that
2mo i, 1:reluctant body an agreement to grant half pay to all officers and a
2mo i, 1:bonus to all privates who served until the end of the war. Even this
2mo i, 1:scheme, which Washington regarded as far short of justice to the
2mo i, 1:soldiers, did not produce quick results. It was near the close of the
2mo i, 1:conflict before he had an army of well-disciplined veterans capable of
2mo i, 1:meeting British regulars on equal terms.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Though there were times when militiamen and frontiersmen did valiant and
2mo i, 1:effective work, it is due to historical accuracy to deny the
2mo i, 1:time-honored tradition that a few minutemen overwhelmed more numerous
2mo i, 1:forces of regulars in a seven years' war for independence. They did
2mo i, 1:nothing of the sort. For the victories of Bennington, Trenton, Saratoga,
2mo i, 1:and Yorktown there were the defeats of Bunker Hill, Long Island, White
2mo i, 1:Plains, Germantown, and Camden. Not once did an army of militiamen
2mo i, 1:overcome an equal number of British regulars in an open trial by battle.
2mo i, 1:"To bring men to be well acquainted with the duties of a soldier," wrote
2mo i, 1:Washington, "requires time.... To expect the same service from raw and
2mo i, 1:undisciplined recruits as from veteran soldiers is to expect what never
2mo i, 1:did and perhaps never will happen."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=How the War Was Won.=--Then how did the American army win the war? For
2mo i, 1:one thing there were delays and blunders on the part of the British
2mo i, 1:generals who, in 1775 and 1776, dallied in Boston and New York with
2mo i, 1:large bodies of regular troops when they might have been dealing
2mo i, 1:paralyzing blows at the scattered bands that constituted the American
2mo i, 1:army. "Nothing but the supineness or folly of the enemy could have saved
2mo i, 1:us," solemnly averred Washington in 1780. Still it is fair to say that
2mo i, 1:this apparent supineness was not all due to the British generals. The
2mo i, 1:ministers behind them believed that a large part of the colonists were
2mo i, 1:loyal and that compromise would be promoted by inaction rather than by a
2mo i, 1:war vigorously prosecuted. Victory by masterly inactivity was obviously
2mo i, 1:better than conquest, and the slighter the wounds the quicker the
2mo i, 1:healing. Later in the conflict when the seasoned forces of France were
2mo i, 1:thrown into the scale, the Americans themselves had learned many things
2mo i, 1:about the practical conduct of campaigns. All along, the British were
2mo i, 1:embarrassed by the problem of supplies. Their troops could not forage
2mo i, 1:with the skill of militiamen, as they were in unfamiliar territory. The
2mo i, 1:long oversea voyages were uncertain at best and doubly so when the
2mo i, 1:warships of France joined the American privateers in preying on supply
2mo i, 1:boats.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The British were in fact battered and worn down by a guerrilla war and
2mo i, 1:outdone on two important occasions by superior forces--at Saratoga and
2mo i, 1:Yorktown. Stern facts convinced them finally that an immense army, which
2mo i, 1:could be raised only by a supreme effort, would be necessary to subdue
2mo i, 1:the colonies if that hazardous enterprise could be accomplished at all.
2mo i, 1:They learned also that America would then be alienated, fretful, and the
2mo i, 1:scene of endless uprisings calling for an army of occupation. That was a
2mo i, 1:price which staggered even Lord North and George III. Moreover, there
2mo i, 1:were forces of opposition at home with which they had to reckon.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Women and the War.=--At no time were the women of America indifferent
2mo i, 1:to the struggle for independence. When it was confined to the realm of
2mo i, 1:opinion they did their part in creating public sentiment. Mrs. Elizabeth
2mo i, 1:Timothee, for example, founded in Charleston, in 1773, a newspaper to
2mo i, 1:espouse the cause of the province. Far to the north the sister of James
2mo i, 1:Otis, Mrs. Mercy Warren, early begged her countrymen to rest their case
2mo i, 1:upon their natural rights, and in influential circles she urged the
2mo i, 1:leaders to stand fast by their principles. While John Adams was tossing
2mo i, 1:about with uncertainty at the Continental Congress, his wife was writing
2mo i, 1:letters to him declaring her faith in "independency."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:When the war came down upon the country, women helped in every field. In
2mo i, 1:sustaining public sentiment they were active. Mrs. Warren with a
2mo i, 1:tireless pen combatted loyalist propaganda in many a drama and satire.
2mo i, 1:Almost every revolutionary leader had a wife or daughter who rendered
2mo i, 1:service in the "second line of defense." Mrs. Washington managed the
2mo i, 1:plantation while the General was at the front and went north to face the
2mo i, 1:rigors of the awful winter at Valley Forge--an inspiration to her
2mo i, 1:husband and his men. The daughter of Benjamin Franklin, Mrs. Sarah
2mo i, 1:Bache, while her father was pleading the American cause in France, set
2mo i, 1:the women of Pennsylvania to work sewing and collecting supplies. Even
2mo i, 1:near the firing line women were to be found, aiding the wounded, hauling
2mo i, 1:powder to the front, and carrying dispatches at the peril of their
2mo i, 1:lives.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:In the economic sphere, the work of women was invaluable. They harvested
2mo i, 1:crops without enjoying the picturesque title of "farmerettes" and they
2mo i, 1:canned and preserved for the wounded and the prisoners of war. Of their
2mo i, 1:labor in spinning and weaving it is recorded: "Immediately on being cut
2mo i, 1:off from the use of English manufactures, the women engaged within their
2mo i, 1:own families in manufacturing various kinds of cloth for domestic use.
2mo i, 1:They thus kept their households decently clad and the surplus of their
2mo i, 1:labors they sold to such as chose to buy rather than make for
2mo i, 1:themselves. In this way the female part of families by their industry
2mo i, 1:and strict economy frequently supported the whole domestic circle,
2mo i, 1:evincing the strength of their attachment and the value of their
2mo i, 1:service."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:For their war work, women were commended by high authorities on more
2mo i, 1:than one occasion. They were given medals and public testimonials even
2mo i, 1:as in our own day. Washington thanked them for their labors and paid
2mo i, 1:tribute to them for the inspiration and material aid which they had
2mo i, 1:given to the cause of independence.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:THE FINANCES OF THE REVOLUTION
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:When the Revolution opened, there were thirteen little treasuries in
2mo i, 1:America but no common treasury, and from first to last the Congress was
2mo i, 1:in the position of a beggar rather than a sovereign. Having no authority
2mo i, 1:to lay and collect taxes directly and knowing the hatred of the
2mo i, 1:provincials for taxation, it resorted mainly to loans and paper money to
2mo i, 1:finance the war. "Do you think," boldly inquired one of the delegates,
2mo i, 1:"that I will consent to load my constituents with taxes when we can send
2mo i, 1:to the printer and get a wagon load of money, one quire of which will
2mo i, 1:pay for the whole?"
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Paper Money and Loans.=--Acting on this curious but appealing political
2mo i, 1:economy, Congress issued in June, 1776, two million dollars in bills of
2mo i, 1:credit to be redeemed by the states on the basis of their respective
2mo i, 1:populations. Other issues followed in quick succession. In all about
2mo i, 1:$241,000,000 of continental paper was printed, to which the several
2mo i, 1:states added nearly $210,000,000 of their own notes. Then came
2mo i, 1:interest-bearing bonds in ever increasing quantities. Several millions
2mo i, 1:were also borrowed from France and small sums from Holland and Spain. In
2mo i, 1:desperation a national lottery was held, producing meager results. The
2mo i, 1:property of Tories was confiscated and sold, bringing in about
2mo i, 1:$16,000,000. Begging letters were sent to the states asking them to
2mo i, 1:raise revenues for the continental treasury, but the states, burdened
2mo i, 1:with their own affairs, gave little heed.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Inflation and Depreciation.=--As paper money flowed from the press, it
2mo i, 1:rapidly declined in purchasing power until in 1779 a dollar was worth
2mo i, 1:only two or three cents in gold or silver. Attempts were made by
2mo i, 1:Congress and the states to compel people to accept the notes at face
2mo i, 1:value; but these were like attempts to make water flow uphill.
2mo i, 1:Speculators collected at once to fatten on the calamities of the
2mo i, 1:republic. Fortunes were made and lost gambling on the prices of public
2mo i, 1:securities while the patriot army, half clothed, was freezing at Valley
2mo i, 1:Forge. "Speculation, peculation, engrossing, forestalling," exclaimed
2mo i, 1:Washington, "afford too many melancholy proofs of the decay of public
2mo i, 1:virtue. Nothing, I am convinced, but the depreciation of our currency
2mo i, 1:... aided by stock jobbing and party dissensions has fed the hopes of
2mo i, 1:the enemy."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Patriot Financiers.=--To the efforts of Congress in financing the
2mo i, 1:war were added the labors of private citizens. Hayn Solomon, a merchant
2mo i, 1:of Philadelphia, supplied members of Congress, including Madison,
2mo i, 1:Jefferson, and Monroe, and army officers, like Lee and Steuben, with
2mo i, 1:money for their daily needs. All together he contributed the huge sum of
2mo i, 1:half a million dollars to the American cause and died broken in purse,
2mo i, 1:if not in spirit, a British prisoner of war. Another Philadelphia
2mo i, 1:merchant, Robert Morris, won for himself the name of the "patriot
2mo i, 1:financier" because he labored night and day to find the money to meet
2mo i, 1:the bills which poured in upon the bankrupt government. When his own
2mo i, 1:funds were exhausted, he borrowed from his friends. Experienced in the
2mo i, 1:handling of merchandise, he created agencies at important points to
2mo i, 1:distribute supplies to the troops, thus displaying administrative as
2mo i, 1:well as financial talents.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:[Illustration: ROBERT MORRIS]
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Women organized "drives" for money, contributed their plate and their
2mo i, 1:jewels, and collected from door to door. Farmers took worthless paper in
2mo i, 1:return for their produce, and soldiers saw many a pay day pass without
2mo i, 1:yielding them a penny. Thus by the labors and sacrifices of citizens,
2mo i, 1:the issuance of paper money, lotteries, the floating of loans,
2mo i, 1:borrowings in Europe, and the impressment of supplies, the Congress
2mo i, 1:staggered through the Revolution like a pauper who knows not how his
2mo i, 1:next meal is to be secured but is continuously relieved at a crisis by a
2mo i, 1:kindly fate.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:THE DIPLOMACY OF THE REVOLUTION
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:When the full measure of honor is given to the soldiers and sailors and
2mo i, 1:their commanding officers, the civilians who managed finances and
2mo i, 1:supplies, the writers who sustained the American spirit, and the women
2mo i, 1:who did well their part, there yet remains the duty of recognizing the
2mo i, 1:achievements of diplomacy. The importance of this field of activity was
2mo i, 1:keenly appreciated by the leaders in the Continental Congress. They were
2mo i, 1:fairly well versed in European history. They knew of the balance of
2mo i, 1:power and the sympathies, interests, and prejudices of nations and their
2mo i, 1:rulers. All this information they turned to good account, in opening
2mo i, 1:relations with continental countries and seeking money, supplies, and
2mo i, 1:even military assistance. For the transaction of this delicate business,
2mo i, 1:they created a secret committee on foreign correspondence as early as
2mo i, 1:1775 and prepared to send agents abroad.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=American Agents Sent Abroad.=--Having heard that France was inclining a
2mo i, 1:friendly ear to the American cause, the Congress, in March, 1776, sent a
2mo i, 1:commissioner to Paris, Silas Deane of Connecticut, often styled the
2mo i, 1:"first American diplomat." Later in the year a form of treaty to be
2mo i, 1:presented to foreign powers was drawn up, and Franklin, Arthur Lee, and
2mo i, 1:Deane were selected as American representatives at the court of "His
2mo i, 1:Most Christian Majesty the King of France." John Jay of New York was
2mo i, 1:chosen minister to Spain in 1779; John Adams was sent to Holland the
2mo i, 1:same year; and other agents were dispatched to Florence, Vienna, and
2mo i, 1:Berlin. The representative selected for St. Petersburg spent two
2mo i, 1:fruitless years there, "ignored by the court, living in obscurity and
2mo i, 1:experiencing nothing but humiliation and failure." Frederick the Great,
2mo i, 1:king of Prussia, expressed a desire to find in America a market for
2mo i, 1:Silesian linens and woolens, but, fearing England's command of the sea,
2mo i, 1:he refused to give direct aid to the Revolutionary cause.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Early French Interest.=--The great diplomatic triumph of the Revolution
2mo i, 1:was won at Paris, and Benjamin Franklin was the hero of the occasion,
2mo i, 1:although many circumstances prepared the way for his success. Louis
2mo i, 1:XVI's foreign minister, Count de Vergennes, before the arrival of any
2mo i, 1:American representative, had brought to the attention of the king the
2mo i, 1:opportunity offered by the outbreak of the war between England and her
2mo i, 1:colonies. He showed him how France could redress her grievances and
2mo i, 1:"reduce the power and greatness of England"--the empire that in 1763 had
2mo i, 1:forced upon her a humiliating peace "at the price of our possessions,
2mo i, 1:of our commerce, and our credit in the Indies, at the price of Canada,
2mo i, 1:Louisiana, Isle Royale, Acadia, and Senegal." Equally successful in
2mo i, 1:gaining the king's interest was a curious French adventurer,
2mo i, 1:Beaumarchais, a man of wealth, a lover of music, and the author of two
2mo i, 1:popular plays, "Figaro" and "The Barber of Seville." These two men had
2mo i, 1:already urged upon the king secret aid for America before Deane appeared
2mo i, 1:on the scene. Shortly after his arrival they made confidential
2mo i, 1:arrangements to furnish money, clothing, powder, and other supplies to
2mo i, 1:the struggling colonies, although official requests for them were
2mo i, 1:officially refused by the French government.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Franklin at Paris.=--When Franklin reached Paris, he was received only
2mo i, 1:in private by the king's minister, Vergennes. The French people,
2mo i, 1:however, made manifest their affection for the "plain republican" in
2mo i, 1:"his full dress suit of spotted Manchester velvet." He was known among
2mo i, 1:men of letters as an author, a scientist, and a philosopher of
2mo i, 1:extraordinary ability. His "Poor Richard" had thrice been translated
2mo i, 1:into French and was scattered in numerous editions throughout the
2mo i, 1:kingdom. People of all ranks--ministers, ladies at court, philosophers,
2mo i, 1:peasants, and stable boys--knew of Franklin and wished him success in
2mo i, 1:his mission. The queen, Marie Antoinette, fated to lose her head in a
2mo i, 1:revolution soon to follow, played with fire by encouraging "our dear
2mo i, 1:republican."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:For the king of France, however, this was more serious business. England
2mo i, 1:resented the presence of this "traitor" in Paris, and Louis had to be
2mo i, 1:cautious about plunging into another war that might also end
2mo i, 1:disastrously. Moreover, the early period of Franklin's sojourn in Paris
2mo i, 1:was a dark hour for the American Revolution. Washington's brilliant
2mo i, 1:exploit at Trenton on Christmas night, 1776, and the battle with
2mo i, 1:Cornwallis at Princeton had been followed by the disaster at Brandywine,
2mo i, 1:the loss of Philadelphia, the defeat at Germantown, and the retirement
2mo i, 1:to Valley Forge for the winter of 1777-78. New York City and
2mo i, 1:Philadelphia--two strategic ports--were in British hands; the Hudson
2mo i, 1:and Delaware rivers were blocked; and General Burgoyne with his British
2mo i, 1:troops was on his way down through the heart of northern New York,
2mo i, 1:cutting New England off from the rest of the colonies. No wonder the
2mo i, 1:king was cautious. Then the unexpected happened. Burgoyne, hemmed in
2mo i, 1:from all sides by the American forces, his flanks harried, his foraging
2mo i, 1:parties beaten back, his supplies cut off, surrendered on October 17,
2mo i, 1:1777, to General Gates, who had superseded General Schuyler in time to
2mo i, 1:receive the honor.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Treaties of Alliance and Commerce (1778).=--News of this victory,
2mo i, 1:placed by historians among the fifteen decisive battles of the world,
2mo i, 1:reached Franklin one night early in December while he and some friends
2mo i, 1:sat gloomily at dinner. Beaumarchais, who was with him, grasped at once
2mo i, 1:the meaning of the situation and set off to the court at Versailles with
2mo i, 1:such haste that he upset his coach and dislocated his arm. The king and
2mo i, 1:his ministers were at last convinced that the hour had come to aid the
2mo i, 1:Revolution. Treaties of commerce and alliance were drawn up and signed
2mo i, 1:in February, 1778. The independence of the United States was recognized
2mo i, 1:by France and an alliance was formed to guarantee that independence.
2mo i, 1:Combined military action was agreed upon and Louis then formally
2mo i, 1:declared war on England. Men who had, a few short years before, fought
2mo i, 1:one another in the wilderness of Pennsylvania or on the Plains of
2mo i, 1:Abraham, were now ranged side by side in a war on the Empire that Pitt
2mo i, 1:had erected and that George III was pulling down.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Spain and Holland Involved.=--Within a few months, Spain, remembering
2mo i, 1:the steady decline of her sea power since the days of the Armada and
2mo i, 1:hoping to drive the British out of Gibraltar, once more joined the
2mo i, 1:concert of nations against England. Holland, a member of a league of
2mo i, 1:armed neutrals formed in protest against British searches on the high
2mo i, 1:seas, sent her fleet to unite with the forces of Spain, France, and
2mo i, 1:America to prey upon British commerce. To all this trouble for England
2mo i, 1:was added the danger of a possible revolt in Ireland, where the spirit
2mo i, 1:of independence was flaming up.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The British Offer Terms to America.=--Seeing the colonists about to be
2mo i, 1:joined by France in a common war on the English empire, Lord North
2mo i, 1:proposed, in February, 1778, a renewal of negotiations. By solemn
2mo i, 1:enactment, Parliament declared its intention not to exercise the right
2mo i, 1:of imposing taxes within the colonies; at the same time it authorized
2mo i, 1:the opening of negotiations through commissioners to be sent to America.
2mo i, 1:A truce was to be established, pardons granted, objectionable laws
2mo i, 1:suspended, and the old imperial constitution, as it stood before the
2mo i, 1:opening of hostilities, restored to full vigor. It was too late. Events
2mo i, 1:had taken the affairs of America out of the hands of British
2mo i, 1:commissioners and diplomats.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Effects of French Aid.=--The French alliance brought ships of war,
2mo i, 1:large sums of gold and silver, loads of supplies, and a considerable
2mo i, 1:body of trained soldiers to the aid of the Americans. Timely as was this
2mo i, 1:help, it meant no sudden change in the fortunes of war. The British
2mo i, 1:evacuated Philadelphia in the summer following the alliance, and
2mo i, 1:Washington's troops were encouraged to come out of Valley Forge. They
2mo i, 1:inflicted a heavy blow on the British at Monmouth, but the treasonable
2mo i, 1:conduct of General Charles Lee prevented a triumph. The recovery of
2mo i, 1:Philadelphia was offset by the treason of Benedict Arnold, the loss of
2mo i, 1:Savannah and Charleston (1780), and the defeat of Gates at Camden.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The full effect of the French alliance was not felt until 1781, when
2mo i, 1:Cornwallis went into Virginia and settled at Yorktown. Accompanied by
2mo i, 1:French troops Washington swept rapidly southward and penned the British
2mo i, 1:to the shore while a powerful French fleet shut off their escape by sea.
2mo i, 1:It was this movement, which certainly could not have been executed
2mo i, 1:without French aid, that put an end to all chance of restoring British
2mo i, 1:dominion in America. It was the surrender of Cornwallis at Yorktown that
2mo i, 1:caused Lord North to pace the floor and cry out: "It is all over! It is
2mo i, 1:all over!" What might have been done without the French alliance lies
2mo i, 1:hidden from mankind. What was accomplished with the help of French
2mo i, 1:soldiers, sailors, officers, money, and supplies, is known to all the
2mo i, 1:earth. "All the world agree," exultantly wrote Franklin from Paris to
2mo i, 1:General Washington, "that no expedition was ever better planned or
2mo i, 1:better executed. It brightens the glory that must accompany your name to
2mo i, 1:the latest posterity." Diplomacy as well as martial valor had its
2mo i, 1:reward.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:PEACE AT LAST
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=British Opposition to the War.=--In measuring the forces that led to
2mo i, 1:the final discomfiture of King George and Lord North, it is necessary to
2mo i, 1:remember that from the beginning to the end the British ministry at home
2mo i, 1:faced a powerful, informed, and relentless opposition. There were
2mo i, 1:vigorous protests, first against the obnoxious acts which precipitated
2mo i, 1:the unhappy quarrel, then against the way in which the war was waged,
2mo i, 1:and finally against the futile struggle to retain a hold upon the
2mo i, 1:American dominions. Among the members of Parliament who thundered
2mo i, 1:against the government were the first statesmen and orators of the land.
2mo i, 1:William Pitt, Earl of Chatham, though he deplored the idea of American
2mo i, 1:independence, denounced the government as the aggressor and rejoiced in
2mo i, 1:American resistance. Edmund Burke leveled his heavy batteries against
2mo i, 1:every measure of coercion and at last strove for a peace which, while
2mo i, 1:giving independence to America, would work for reconciliation rather
2mo i, 1:than estrangement. Charles James Fox gave the colonies his generous
2mo i, 1:sympathy and warmly championed their rights. Outside of the circle of
2mo i, 1:statesmen there were stout friends of the American cause like David
2mo i, 1:Hume, the philosopher and historian, and Catherine Macaulay, an author
2mo i, 1:of wide fame and a republican bold enough to encourage Washington in
2mo i, 1:seeing it through.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Against this powerful opposition, the government enlisted a whole army
2mo i, 1:of scribes and journalists to pour out criticism on the Americans and
2mo i, 1:their friends. Dr. Samuel Johnson, whom it employed in this business,
2mo i, 1:was so savage that even the ministers had to tone down his pamphlets
2mo i, 1:before printing them. Far more weighty was Edward Gibbon, who was in
2mo i, 1:time to win fame as the historian of the _Decline and Fall of the Roman
2mo i, 1:Empire_. He had at first opposed the government; but, on being given a
2mo i, 1:lucrative post, he used his sharp pen in its support, causing his
2mo i, 1:friends to ridicule him in these lines:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:    "King George, in a fright
2mo i, 1:     Lest Gibbon should write
2mo i, 1:       The story of England's disgrace,
2mo i, 1:     Thought no way so sure
2mo i, 1:     His pen to secure
2mo i, 1:       As to give the historian a place."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Lord North Yields.=--As time wore on, events bore heavily on the side
2mo i, 1:of the opponents of the government's measures. They had predicted that
2mo i, 1:conquest was impossible, and they had urged the advantages of a peace
2mo i, 1:which would in some measure restore the affections of the Americans.
2mo i, 1:Every day's news confirmed their predictions and lent support to their
2mo i, 1:arguments. Moreover, the war, which sprang out of an effort to relieve
2mo i, 1:English burdens, made those burdens heavier than ever. Military expenses
2mo i, 1:were daily increasing. Trade with the colonies, the greatest single
2mo i, 1:outlet for British goods and capital, was paralyzed. The heavy debts due
2mo i, 1:British merchants in America were not only unpaid but postponed into an
2mo i, 1:indefinite future. Ireland was on the verge of revolution. The French
2mo i, 1:had a dangerous fleet on the high seas. In vain did the king assert in
2mo i, 1:December, 1781, that no difficulties would ever make him consent to a
2mo i, 1:peace that meant American independence. Parliament knew better, and on
2mo i, 1:February 27, 1782, in the House of Commons was carried an address to the
2mo i, 1:throne against continuing the war. Burke, Fox, the younger Pitt, Barre,
2mo i, 1:and other friends of the colonies voted in the affirmative. Lord North
2mo i, 1:gave notice then that his ministry was at an end. The king moaned:
2mo i, 1:"Necessity made me yield."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:In April, 1782, Franklin received word from the English government that
2mo i, 1:it was prepared to enter into negotiations leading to a settlement. This
2mo i, 1:was embarrassing. In the treaty of alliance with France, the United
2mo i, 1:States had promised that peace should be a joint affair agreed to by
2mo i, 1:both nations in open conference. Finding France, however, opposed to
2mo i, 1:some of their claims respecting boundaries and fisheries, the American
2mo i, 1:commissioners conferred with the British agents at Paris without
2mo i, 1:consulting the French minister. They actually signed a preliminary peace
2mo i, 1:draft before they informed him of their operations. When Vergennes
2mo i, 1:reproached him, Franklin replied that they "had been guilty of
2mo i, 1:neglecting _bienseance_ [good manners] but hoped that the great work
2mo i, 1:would not be ruined by a single indiscretion."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Terms of Peace (1783).=--The general settlement at Paris in 1783
2mo i, 1:was a triumph for America. England recognized the independence of the
2mo i, 1:United States, naming each state specifically, and agreed to boundaries
2mo i, 1:extending from the Atlantic to the Mississippi and from the Great Lakes
2mo i, 1:to the Floridas. England held Canada, Newfoundland, and the West Indies
2mo i, 1:intact, made gains in India, and maintained her supremacy on the seas.
2mo i, 1:Spain won Florida and Minorca but not the coveted Gibraltar. France
2mo i, 1:gained nothing important save the satisfaction of seeing England humbled
2mo i, 1:and the colonies independent.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The generous terms secured by the American commission at Paris called
2mo i, 1:forth surprise and gratitude in the United States and smoothed the way
2mo i, 1:for a renewal of commercial relations with the mother country. At the
2mo i, 1:same time they gave genuine anxiety to European diplomats. "This federal
2mo i, 1:republic is born a pigmy," wrote the Spanish ambassador to his royal
2mo i, 1:master. "A day will come when it will be a giant; even a colossus
2mo i, 1:formidable to these countries. Liberty of conscience and the facility
2mo i, 1:for establishing a new population on immense lands, as well as the
2mo i, 1:advantages of the new government, will draw thither farmers and artisans
2mo i, 1:from all the nations. In a few years we shall watch with grief the
2mo i, 1:tyrannical existence of the same colossus."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:[Illustration: NORTH AMERICA ACCORDING TO THE TREATY OF 1783]
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:SUMMARY OF THE REVOLUTIONARY PERIOD
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The independence of the American colonies was foreseen by many European
2mo i, 1:statesmen as they watched the growth of their population, wealth, and
2mo i, 1:power; but no one could fix the hour of the great event. Until 1763 the
2mo i, 1:American colonists lived fairly happily under British dominion. There
2mo i, 1:were collisions from time to time, of course. Royal governors clashed
2mo i, 1:with stiff-necked colonial legislatures. There were protests against the
2mo i, 1:exercise of the king's veto power in specific cases. Nevertheless, on
2mo i, 1:the whole, the relations between America and the mother country were
2mo i, 1:more amicable in 1763 than at any period under the Stuart regime which
2mo i, 1:closed in 1688.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The crash, when it came, was not deliberately willed by any one. It was
2mo i, 1:the product of a number of forces that happened to converge about 1763.
2mo i, 1:Three years before, there had come to the throne George III, a young,
2mo i, 1:proud, inexperienced, and stubborn king. For nearly fifty years his
2mo i, 1:predecessors, Germans as they were in language and interest, had allowed
2mo i, 1:things to drift in England and America. George III decided that he would
2mo i, 1:be king in fact as well as in name. About the same time England brought
2mo i, 1:to a close the long and costly French and Indian War and was staggering
2mo i, 1:under a heavy burden of debt and taxes. The war had been fought partly
2mo i, 1:in defense of the American colonies and nothing seemed more reasonable
2mo i, 1:to English statesmen than the idea that the colonies should bear part of
2mo i, 1:the cost of their own defense. At this juncture there came into
2mo i, 1:prominence, in royal councils, two men bent on taxing America and
2mo i, 1:controlling her trade, Grenville and Townshend. The king was willing,
2mo i, 1:the English taxpayers were thankful for any promise of relief, and
2mo i, 1:statesmen were found to undertake the experiment. England therefore set
2mo i, 1:out upon a new course. She imposed taxes upon the colonists, regulated
2mo i, 1:their trade and set royal officers upon them to enforce the law. This
2mo i, 1:action evoked protests from the colonists. They held a Stamp Act
2mo i, 1:Congress to declare their rights and petition for a redress of
2mo i, 1:grievances. Some of the more restless spirits rioted in the streets,
2mo i, 1:sacked the houses of the king's officers, and tore up the stamped paper.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Frightened by uprising, the English government drew back and repealed
2mo i, 1:the Stamp Act. Then it veered again and renewed its policy of
2mo i, 1:interference. Interference again called forth American protests.
2mo i, 1:Protests aroused sharper retaliation. More British regulars were sent
2mo i, 1:over to keep order. More irritating laws were passed by Parliament.
2mo i, 1:Rioting again appeared: tea was dumped in the harbor of Boston and
2mo i, 1:seized in the harbor of Charleston. The British answer was more force.
2mo i, 1:The response of the colonists was a Continental Congress for defense. An
2mo i, 1:unexpected and unintended clash of arms at Lexington and Concord in the
2mo i, 1:spring of 1775 brought forth from the king of England a proclamation:
2mo i, 1:"The Americans are rebels!"
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The die was cast. The American Revolution had begun. Washington was made
2mo i, 1:commander-in-chief. Armies were raised, money was borrowed, a huge
2mo i, 1:volume of paper currency was issued, and foreign aid was summoned.
2mo i, 1:Franklin plied his diplomatic arts at Paris until in 1778 he induced
2mo i, 1:France to throw her sword into the balance. Three years later,
2mo i, 1:Cornwallis surrendered at Yorktown. In 1783, by the formal treaty of
2mo i, 1:peace, George III acknowledged the independence of the United States.
2mo i, 1:The new nation, endowed with an imperial domain stretching from the
2mo i, 1:Atlantic Ocean to the Mississippi River, began its career among the
2mo i, 1:sovereign powers of the earth.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:In the sphere of civil government, the results of the Revolution were
2mo i, 1:equally remarkable. Royal officers and royal authorities were driven
2mo i, 1:from the former dominions. All power was declared to be in the people.
2mo i, 1:All the colonies became states, each with its own constitution or plan
2mo i, 1:of government. The thirteen states were united in common bonds under the
2mo i, 1:Articles of Confederation. A republic on a large scale was instituted.
2mo i, 1:Thus there was begun an adventure in popular government such as the
2mo i, 1:world had never seen. Could it succeed or was it destined to break down
2mo i, 1:and be supplanted by a monarchy? The fate of whole continents hung upon
2mo i, 1:the answer.
2mo i, 1:
