2mo i, 1:PART III. THE UNION AND NATIONAL POLITICS
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:CHAPTER VII
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:THE FORMATION OF THE CONSTITUTION
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:THE PROMISE AND THE DIFFICULTIES OF AMERICA
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The rise of a young republic composed of thirteen states, each governed
2mo i, 1:by officials popularly elected under constitutions drafted by "the plain
2mo i, 1:people," was the most significant feature of the eighteenth century. The
2mo i, 1:majority of the patriots whose labors and sacrifices had made this
2mo i, 1:possible naturally looked upon their work and pronounced it good. Those
2mo i, 1:Americans, however, who peered beneath the surface of things, saw that
2mo i, 1:the Declaration of Independence, even if splendidly phrased, and paper
2mo i, 1:constitutions, drawn by finest enthusiasm "uninstructed by experience,"
2mo i, 1:could not alone make the republic great and prosperous or even free. All
2mo i, 1:around them they saw chaos in finance and in industry and perils for the
2mo i, 1:immediate future.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Weakness of the Articles of Confederation.=--The government under
2mo i, 1:the Articles of Confederation had neither the strength nor the resources
2mo i, 1:necessary to cope with the problems of reconstruction left by the war.
2mo i, 1:The sole organ of government was a Congress composed of from two to
2mo i, 1:seven members from each state chosen as the legislature might direct and
2mo i, 1:paid by the state. In determining all questions, each state had one
2mo i, 1:vote--Delaware thus enjoying the same weight as Virginia. There was no
2mo i, 1:president to enforce the laws. Congress was given power to select a
2mo i, 1:committee of thirteen--one from each state--to act as an executive body
2mo i, 1:when it was not in session; but this device, on being tried out, proved
2mo i, 1:a failure. There was no system of national courts to which citizens and
2mo i, 1:states could appeal for the protection of their rights or through which
2mo i, 1:they could compel obedience to law. The two great powers of government,
2mo i, 1:military and financial, were withheld. Congress, it is true, could
2mo i, 1:authorize expenditures but had to rely upon the states for the payment
2mo i, 1:of contributions to meet its bills. It could also order the
2mo i, 1:establishment of an army, but it could only request the states to supply
2mo i, 1:their respective quotas of soldiers. It could not lay taxes nor bring
2mo i, 1:any pressure to bear upon a single citizen in the whole country. It
2mo i, 1:could act only through the medium of the state governments.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Financial and Commercial Disorders.=--In the field of public finance,
2mo i, 1:the disorders were pronounced. The huge debt incurred during the war was
2mo i, 1:still outstanding. Congress was unable to pay either the interest or the
2mo i, 1:principal. Public creditors were in despair, as the market value of
2mo i, 1:their bonds sank to twenty-five or even ten cents on the dollar. The
2mo i, 1:current bills of Congress were unpaid. As some one complained, there was
2mo i, 1:not enough money in the treasury to buy pen and ink with which to record
2mo i, 1:the transactions of the shadow legislature. The currency was in utter
2mo i, 1:chaos. Millions of dollars in notes issued by Congress had become mere
2mo i, 1:trash worth a cent or two on the dollar. There was no other expression
2mo i, 1:of contempt so forceful as the popular saying: "not worth a
2mo i, 1:Continental." To make matters worse, several of the states were pouring
2mo i, 1:new streams of paper money from the press. Almost the only good money in
2mo i, 1:circulation consisted of English, French, and Spanish coins, and the
2mo i, 1:public was even defrauded by them because money changers were busy
2mo i, 1:clipping and filing away the metal. Foreign commerce was unsettled. The
2mo i, 1:entire British system of trade discrimination was turned against the
2mo i, 1:Americans, and Congress, having no power to regulate foreign commerce,
2mo i, 1:was unable to retaliate or to negotiate treaties which it could enforce.
2mo i, 1:Domestic commerce was impeded by the jealousies of the states, which
2mo i, 1:erected tariff barriers against their neighbors. The condition of the
2mo i, 1:currency made the exchange of money and goods extremely difficult, and,
2mo i, 1:as if to increase the confusion, backward states enacted laws hindering
2mo i, 1:the prompt collection of debts within their borders--an evil which
2mo i, 1:nothing but a national system of courts could cure.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Congress in Disrepute.=--With treaties set at naught by the states, the
2mo i, 1:laws unenforced, the treasury empty, and the public credit gone, the
2mo i, 1:Congress of the United States fell into utter disrepute. It called upon
2mo i, 1:the states to pay their quotas of money into the treasury, only to be
2mo i, 1:treated with contempt. Even its own members looked upon it as a solemn
2mo i, 1:futility. Some of the ablest men refused to accept election to it, and
2mo i, 1:many who did take the doubtful honor failed to attend the sessions.
2mo i, 1:Again and again it was impossible to secure a quorum for the transaction
2mo i, 1:of business.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Troubles of the State Governments.=--The state governments, free to
2mo i, 1:pursue their own course with no interference from without, had almost as
2mo i, 1:many difficulties as the Congress. They too were loaded with
2mo i, 1:revolutionary debts calling for heavy taxes upon an already restive
2mo i, 1:population. Oppressed by their financial burdens and discouraged by the
2mo i, 1:fall in prices which followed the return of peace, the farmers of
2mo i, 1:several states joined in a concerted effort and compelled their
2mo i, 1:legislatures to issue large sums of paper money. The currency fell in
2mo i, 1:value, but nevertheless it was forced on unwilling creditors to square
2mo i, 1:old accounts.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:In every part of the country legislative action fluctuated violently.
2mo i, 1:Laws were made one year only to be repealed the next and reenacted the
2mo i, 1:third year. Lands were sold by one legislature and the sales were
2mo i, 1:canceled by its successor. Uncertainty and distrust were the natural
2mo i, 1:consequences. Men of substance longed for some power that would forbid
2mo i, 1:states to issue bills of credit, to make paper money legal tender in
2mo i, 1:payment of debts, or to impair the obligation of contracts. Men heavily
2mo i, 1:in debt, on the other hand, urged even more drastic action against
2mo i, 1:creditors.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:So great did the discontent of the farmers in New Hampshire become in
2mo i, 1:1786 that a mob surrounded the legislature, demanding a repeal of the
2mo i, 1:taxes and the issuance of paper money. It was with difficulty that an
2mo i, 1:armed rebellion was avoided. In Massachusetts the malcontents, under the
2mo i, 1:leadership of Daniel Shays, a captain in the Revolutionary army,
2mo i, 1:organized that same year open resistance to the government of the state.
2mo i, 1:Shays and his followers protested against the conduct of creditors in
2mo i, 1:foreclosing mortgages upon the debt-burdened farmers, against the
2mo i, 1:lawyers for increasing the costs of legal proceedings, against the
2mo i, 1:senate of the state the members of which were apportioned among the
2mo i, 1:towns on the basis of the amount of taxes paid, against heavy taxes, and
2mo i, 1:against the refusal of the legislature to issue paper money. They seized
2mo i, 1:the towns of Worcester and Springfield and broke up the courts of
2mo i, 1:justice. All through the western part of the state the revolt spread,
2mo i, 1:sending a shock of alarm to every center and section of the young
2mo i, 1:republic. Only by the most vigorous action was Governor Bowdoin able to
2mo i, 1:quell the uprising; and when that task was accomplished, the state
2mo i, 1:government did not dare to execute any of the prisoners because they had
2mo i, 1:so many sympathizers. Moreover, Bowdoin and several members of the
2mo i, 1:legislature who had been most zealous in their attacks on the insurgents
2mo i, 1:were defeated at the ensuing election. The need of national assistance
2mo i, 1:for state governments in times of domestic violence was everywhere
2mo i, 1:emphasized by men who were opposed to revolutionary acts.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Alarm over Dangers to the Republic.=--Leading American citizens,
2mo i, 1:watching the drift of affairs, were slowly driven to the conclusion that
2mo i, 1:the new ship of state so proudly launched a few years before was
2mo i, 1:careening into anarchy. "The facts of our peace and independence," wrote
2mo i, 1:a friend of Washington, "do not at present wear so promising an
2mo i, 1:appearance as I had fondly painted in my mind. The prejudices,
2mo i, 1:jealousies, and turbulence of the people at times almost stagger my
2mo i, 1:confidence in our political establishments; and almost occasion me to
2mo i, 1:think that they will show themselves unworthy of the noble prize for
2mo i, 1:which we have contended."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Washington himself was profoundly discouraged. On hearing of Shays's
2mo i, 1:rebellion, he exclaimed: "What, gracious God, is man that there should
2mo i, 1:be such inconsistency and perfidiousness in his conduct! It is but the
2mo i, 1:other day that we were shedding our blood to obtain the constitutions
2mo i, 1:under which we now live--constitutions of our own choice and making--and
2mo i, 1:now we are unsheathing our sword to overturn them." The same year he
2mo i, 1:burst out in a lament over rumors of restoring royal government. "I am
2mo i, 1:told that even respectable characters speak of a monarchical government
2mo i, 1:without horror. From thinking proceeds speaking. Hence to acting is
2mo i, 1:often but a single step. But how irresistible and tremendous! What a
2mo i, 1:triumph for our enemies to verify their predictions! What a triumph for
2mo i, 1:the advocates of despotism to find that we are incapable of governing
2mo i, 1:ourselves!"
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Congress Attempts Some Reforms.=--The Congress was not indifferent to
2mo i, 1:the events that disturbed Washington. On the contrary it put forth many
2mo i, 1:efforts to check tendencies so dangerous to finance, commerce,
2mo i, 1:industries, and the Confederation itself. In 1781, even before the
2mo i, 1:treaty of peace was signed, the Congress, having found out how futile
2mo i, 1:were its taxing powers, carried a resolution of amendment to the
2mo i, 1:Articles of Confederation, authorizing the levy of a moderate duty on
2mo i, 1:imports. Yet this mild measure was rejected by the states. Two years
2mo i, 1:later the Congress prepared another amendment sanctioning the levy of
2mo i, 1:duties on imports, to be collected this time by state officers and
2mo i, 1:applied to the payment of the public debt. This more limited proposal,
2mo i, 1:designed to save public credit, likewise failed. In 1786, the Congress
2mo i, 1:made a third appeal to the states for help, declaring that they had been
2mo i, 1:so irregular and so negligent in paying their quotas that further
2mo i, 1:reliance upon that mode of raising revenues was dishonorable and
2mo i, 1:dangerous.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:THE CALLING OF A CONSTITUTIONAL CONVENTION
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Hamilton and Washington Urge Reform.=--The attempts at reform by the
2mo i, 1:Congress were accompanied by demand for, both within and without that
2mo i, 1:body, a convention to frame a new plan of government. In 1780, the
2mo i, 1:youthful Alexander Hamilton, realizing the weakness of the Articles, so
2mo i, 1:widely discussed, proposed a general convention for the purpose of
2mo i, 1:drafting a new constitution on entirely different principles. With
2mo i, 1:tireless energy he strove to bring his countrymen to his view.
2mo i, 1:Washington, agreeing with him on every point, declared, in a circular
2mo i, 1:letter to the governors, that the duration of the union would be short
2mo i, 1:unless there was lodged somewhere a supreme power "to regulate and
2mo i, 1:govern the general concerns of the confederated republic." The governor
2mo i, 1:of Massachusetts, disturbed by the growth of discontent all about him,
2mo i, 1:suggested to the state legislature in 1785 the advisability of a
2mo i, 1:national convention to enlarge the powers of the Congress. The
2mo i, 1:legislature approved the plan, but did not press it to a conclusion.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:[Illustration: ALEXANDER HAMILTON]
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Annapolis Convention.=--Action finally came from the South. The
2mo i, 1:Virginia legislature, taking things into its own hands, called a
2mo i, 1:conference of delegates at Annapolis to consider matters of taxation and
2mo i, 1:commerce. When the convention assembled in 1786, it was found that only
2mo i, 1:five states had taken the trouble to send representatives. The leaders
2mo i, 1:were deeply discouraged, but the resourceful Hamilton, a delegate from
2mo i, 1:New York, turned the affair to good account. He secured the adoption of
2mo i, 1:a resolution, calling upon the Congress itself to summon another
2mo i, 1:convention, to meet at Philadelphia.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=A National Convention Called (1787).=--The Congress, as tardy as ever,
2mo i, 1:at last decided in February, 1787, to issue the call. Fearing drastic
2mo i, 1:changes, however, it restricted the convention to "the sole and express
2mo i, 1:purpose of revising the Articles of Confederation." Jealous of its own
2mo i, 1:powers, it added that any alterations proposed should be referred to the
2mo i, 1:Congress and the states for their approval.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Every state in the union, except Rhode Island, responded to this call.
2mo i, 1:Indeed some of the states, having the Annapolis resolution before them,
2mo i, 1:had already anticipated the Congress by selecting delegates before the
2mo i, 1:formal summons came. Thus, by the persistence of governors,
2mo i, 1:legislatures, and private citizens, there was brought about the
2mo i, 1:long-desired national convention. In May, 1787, it assembled in
2mo i, 1:Philadelphia.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Eminent Men of the Convention.=--On the roll of that memorable
2mo i, 1:convention were fifty-five men, at least half of whom were acknowledged
2mo i, 1:to be among the foremost statesmen and thinkers in America. Every field
2mo i, 1:of statecraft was represented by them: war and practical management in
2mo i, 1:Washington, who was chosen president of the convention; diplomacy in
2mo i, 1:Franklin, now old and full of honor in his own land as well as abroad;
2mo i, 1:finance in Alexander Hamilton and Robert Morris; law in James Wilson of
2mo i, 1:Pennsylvania; the philosophy of government in James Madison, called the
2mo i, 1:"father of the Constitution." They were not theorists but practical men,
2mo i, 1:rich in political experience and endowed with deep insight into the
2mo i, 1:springs of human action. Three of them had served in the Stamp Act
2mo i, 1:Congress: Dickinson of Delaware, William Samuel Johnson of Connecticut,
2mo i, 1:and John Rutledge of South Carolina. Eight had been signers of the
2mo i, 1:Declaration of Independence: Read of Delaware, Sherman of Connecticut,
2mo i, 1:Wythe of Virginia, Gerry of Massachusetts, Franklin, Robert Morris,
2mo i, 1:George Clymer, and James Wilson of Pennsylvania. All but twelve had at
2mo i, 1:some time served in the Continental Congress and eighteen were members
2mo i, 1:of that body in the spring of 1787. Washington, Hamilton, Mifflin, and
2mo i, 1:Charles Pinckney had been officers in the Revolutionary army. Seven of
2mo i, 1:the delegates had gained political experience as governors of states.
2mo i, 1:"The convention as a whole," according to the historian Hildreth,
2mo i, 1:"represented in a marked manner the talent, intelligence, and
2mo i, 1:especially the conservative sentiment of the country."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:THE FRAMING OF THE CONSTITUTION
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Problems Involved.=--The great problems before the convention were nine
2mo i, 1:in number: (1) Shall the Articles of Confederation be revised or a new
2mo i, 1:system of government constructed? (2) Shall the government be founded on
2mo i, 1:states equal in power as under the Articles or on the broader and deeper
2mo i, 1:foundation of population? (3) What direct share shall the people have in
2mo i, 1:the election of national officers? (4) What shall be the qualifications
2mo i, 1:for the suffrage? (5) How shall the conflicting interests of the
2mo i, 1:commercial and the planting states be balanced so as to safeguard the
2mo i, 1:essential rights of each? (6) What shall be the form of the new
2mo i, 1:government? (7) What powers shall be conferred on it? (8) How shall the
2mo i, 1:state legislatures be restrained from their attacks on property rights
2mo i, 1:such as the issuance of paper money? (9) Shall the approval of all the
2mo i, 1:states be necessary, as under the Articles, for the adoption and
2mo i, 1:amendment of the Constitution?
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Revision of the Articles or a New Government?=--The moment the first
2mo i, 1:problem was raised, representatives of the small states, led by William
2mo i, 1:Paterson of New Jersey, were on their feet. They feared that, if the
2mo i, 1:Articles were overthrown, the equality and rights of the states would be
2mo i, 1:put in jeopardy. Their protest was therefore vigorous. They cited the
2mo i, 1:call issued by the Congress in summoning the convention which
2mo i, 1:specifically stated that they were assembled for "the sole and express
2mo i, 1:purpose of revising the Articles of Confederation." They cited also
2mo i, 1:their instructions from their state legislatures, which authorized them
2mo i, 1:to "revise and amend" the existing scheme of government, not to make a
2mo i, 1:revolution in it. To depart from the authorization laid down by the
2mo i, 1:Congress and the legislatures would be to exceed their powers, they
2mo i, 1:argued, and to betray the trust reposed in them by their countrymen.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:To their contentions, Randolph of Virginia replied: "When the salvation
2mo i, 1:of the republic is at stake, it would be treason to our trust not to
2mo i, 1:propose what we find necessary." Hamilton, reminding the delegates that
2mo i, 1:their work was still subject to the approval of the states, frankly said
2mo i, 1:that on the point of their powers he had no scruples. With the issue
2mo i, 1:clear, the convention cast aside the Articles as if they did not exist
2mo i, 1:and proceeded to the work of drawing up a new constitution, "laying its
2mo i, 1:foundations on such principles and organizing its powers in such form"
2mo i, 1:as to the delegates seemed "most likely to affect their safety and
2mo i, 1:happiness."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=A Government Founded on States or on People?--The
2mo i, 1:Compromise.=--Defeated in their attempt to limit the convention to a
2mo i, 1:mere revision of the Articles, the spokesmen of the smaller states
2mo i, 1:redoubled their efforts to preserve the equality of the states. The
2mo i, 1:signal for a radical departure from the Articles on this point was given
2mo i, 1:early in the sessions when Randolph presented "the Virginia plan." He
2mo i, 1:proposed that the new national legislature consist of two houses, the
2mo i, 1:members of which were to be apportioned among the states according to
2mo i, 1:their wealth or free white population, as the convention might decide.
2mo i, 1:This plan was vehemently challenged. Paterson of New Jersey flatly
2mo i, 1:avowed that neither he nor his state would ever bow to such tyranny. As
2mo i, 1:an alternative, he presented "the New Jersey plan" calling for a
2mo i, 1:national legislature of one house representing states as such, not
2mo i, 1:wealth or people--a legislature in which all states, large or small,
2mo i, 1:would have equal voice. Wilson of Pennsylvania, on behalf of the more
2mo i, 1:populous states, took up the gauntlet which Paterson had thrown down. It
2mo i, 1:was absurd, he urged, for 180,000 men in one state to have the same
2mo i, 1:weight in national counsels as 750,000 men in another state. "The
2mo i, 1:gentleman from New Jersey," he said, "is candid. He declares his opinion
2mo i, 1:boldly.... I will be equally candid.... I will never confederate on his
2mo i, 1:principles." So the bitter controversy ran on through many exciting
2mo i, 1:sessions.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Greek had met Greek. The convention was hopelessly deadlocked and on the
2mo i, 1:verge of dissolution, "scarce held together by the strength of a hair,"
2mo i, 1:as one of the delegates remarked. A crash was averted only by a
2mo i, 1:compromise. Instead of a Congress of one house as provided by the
2mo i, 1:Articles, the convention agreed upon a legislature of two houses. In the
2mo i, 1:Senate, the aspirations of the small states were to be satisfied, for
2mo i, 1:each state was given two members in that body. In the formation of the
2mo i, 1:House of Representatives, the larger states were placated, for it was
2mo i, 1:agreed that the members of that chamber were to be apportioned among the
2mo i, 1:states on the basis of population, counting three-fifths of the slaves.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Question of Popular Election.=--The method of selecting federal
2mo i, 1:officers and members of Congress also produced an acrimonious debate
2mo i, 1:which revealed how deep-seated was the distrust of the capacity of the
2mo i, 1:people to govern themselves. Few there were who believed that no branch
2mo i, 1:of the government should be elected directly by the voters; still fewer
2mo i, 1:were there, however, who desired to see all branches so chosen. One or
2mo i, 1:two even expressed a desire for a monarchy. The dangers of democracy
2mo i, 1:were stressed by Gerry of Massachusetts: "All the evils we experience
2mo i, 1:flow from an excess of democracy. The people do not want virtue but are
2mo i, 1:the dupes of pretended patriots.... I have been too republican
2mo i, 1:heretofore but have been taught by experience the danger of a leveling
2mo i, 1:spirit." To the "democratic licentiousness of the state legislatures,"
2mo i, 1:Randolph sought to oppose a "firm senate." To check the excesses of
2mo i, 1:popular government Charles Pinckney of South Carolina declared that no
2mo i, 1:one should be elected President who was not worth $100,000 and that high
2mo i, 1:property qualifications should be placed on members of Congress and
2mo i, 1:judges. Other members of the convention were stoutly opposed to such
2mo i, 1:"high-toned notions of government." Franklin and Wilson, both from
2mo i, 1:Pennsylvania, vigorously championed popular election; while men like
2mo i, 1:Madison insisted that at least one part of the government should rest on
2mo i, 1:the broad foundation of the people.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Out of this clash of opinion also came compromise. One branch, the House
2mo i, 1:of Representatives, it was agreed, was to be elected directly by the
2mo i, 1:voters, while the Senators were to be elected indirectly by the state
2mo i, 1:legislatures. The President was to be chosen by electors selected as the
2mo i, 1:legislatures of the states might determine, and the judges of the
2mo i, 1:federal courts, supreme and inferior, by the President and the Senate.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Question of the Suffrage.=--The battle over the suffrage was sharp
2mo i, 1:but brief. Gouverneur Morris proposed that only land owners should be
2mo i, 1:permitted to vote. Madison replied that the state legislatures, which
2mo i, 1:had made so much trouble with radical laws, were elected by freeholders.
2mo i, 1:After the debate, the delegates, unable to agree on any property
2mo i, 1:limitations on the suffrage, decided that the House of Representatives
2mo i, 1:should be elected by voters having the "qualifications requisite for
2mo i, 1:electors of the most numerous branch of the state legislature." Thus
2mo i, 1:they accepted the suffrage provisions of the states.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Balance between the Planting and the Commercial States.=--After the
2mo i, 1:debates had gone on for a few weeks, Madison came to the conclusion that
2mo i, 1:the real division in the convention was not between the large and the
2mo i, 1:small states but between the planting section founded on slave labor and
2mo i, 1:the commercial North. Thus he anticipated by nearly three-quarters of a
2mo i, 1:century "the irrepressible conflict." The planting states had neither
2mo i, 1:the free white population nor the wealth of the North. There were,
2mo i, 1:counting Delaware, six of them as against seven commercial states.
2mo i, 1:Dependent for their prosperity mainly upon the sale of tobacco, rice,
2mo i, 1:and other staples abroad, they feared that Congress might impose
2mo i, 1:restraints upon their enterprise. Being weaker in numbers, they were
2mo i, 1:afraid that the majority might lay an unfair burden of taxes upon them.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:_Representation and Taxation._--The Southern members of the convention
2mo i, 1:were therefore very anxious to secure for their section the largest
2mo i, 1:possible representation in Congress, and at the same time to restrain
2mo i, 1:the taxing power of that body. Two devices were thought adapted to these
2mo i, 1:ends. One was to count the slaves as people when apportioning
2mo i, 1:representatives among the states according to their respective
2mo i, 1:populations; the other was to provide that direct taxes should be
2mo i, 1:apportioned among the states, in proportion not to their wealth but to
2mo i, 1:the number of their free white inhabitants. For obvious reasons the
2mo i, 1:Northern delegates objected to these proposals. Once more a compromise
2mo i, 1:proved to be the solution. It was agreed that not all the slaves but
2mo i, 1:three-fifths of them should be counted for both purposes--representation
2mo i, 1:and direct taxation.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:_Commerce and the Slave Trade._--Southern interests were also involved
2mo i, 1:in the project to confer upon Congress the power to regulate interstate
2mo i, 1:and foreign commerce. To the manufacturing and trading states this was
2mo i, 1:essential. It would prevent interstate tariffs and trade jealousies; it
2mo i, 1:would enable Congress to protect American manufactures and to break
2mo i, 1:down, by appropriate retaliations, foreign discriminations against
2mo i, 1:American commerce. To the South the proposal was menacing because
2mo i, 1:tariffs might interfere with the free exchange of the produce of
2mo i, 1:plantations in European markets, and navigation acts might confine the
2mo i, 1:carrying trade to American, that is Northern, ships. The importation of
2mo i, 1:slaves, moreover, it was feared might be heavily taxed or immediately
2mo i, 1:prohibited altogether.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The result of this and related controversies was a debate on the merits
2mo i, 1:of slavery. Gouverneur Morris delivered his mind and heart on that
2mo i, 1:subject, denouncing slavery as a nefarious institution and the curse of
2mo i, 1:heaven on the states in which it prevailed. Mason of Virginia, a
2mo i, 1:slaveholder himself, was hardly less outspoken, saying: "Slavery
2mo i, 1:discourages arts and manufactures. The poor despise labor when performed
2mo i, 1:by slaves. They prevent the migration of whites who really strengthen
2mo i, 1:and enrich a country."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The system, however, had its defenders. Representatives from South
2mo i, 1:Carolina argued that their entire economic life rested on slave labor
2mo i, 1:and that the high death rate in the rice swamps made continuous
2mo i, 1:importation necessary. Ellsworth of Connecticut took the ground that
2mo i, 1:the convention should not meddle with slavery. "The morality or wisdom
2mo i, 1:of slavery," he said, "are considerations belonging to the states. What
2mo i, 1:enriches a part enriches the whole." To the future he turned an
2mo i, 1:untroubled face: "As population increases, poor laborers will be so
2mo i, 1:plenty as to render slaves useless. Slavery in time will not be a speck
2mo i, 1:in our country." Virginia and North Carolina, already overstocked with
2mo i, 1:slaves, favored prohibiting the traffic in them; but South Carolina was
2mo i, 1:adamant. She must have fresh supplies of slaves or she would not
2mo i, 1:federate.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:So it was agreed that, while Congress might regulate foreign trade by
2mo i, 1:majority vote, the importation of slaves should not be forbidden before
2mo i, 1:the lapse of twenty years, and that any import tax should not exceed $10
2mo i, 1:a head. At the same time, in connection with the regulation of foreign
2mo i, 1:trade, it was stipulated that a two-thirds vote in the Senate should be
2mo i, 1:necessary in the ratification of treaties. A further concession to the
2mo i, 1:South was made in the provision for the return of runaway slaves--a
2mo i, 1:provision also useful in the North, where indentured servants were about
2mo i, 1:as troublesome as slaves in escaping from their masters.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Form of the Government.=--As to the details of the frame of
2mo i, 1:government and the grand principles involved, the opinion of the
2mo i, 1:convention ebbed and flowed, decisions being taken in the heat of
2mo i, 1:debate, only to be revoked and taken again.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:_The Executive._--There was general agreement that there should be an
2mo i, 1:executive branch; for reliance upon Congress to enforce its own laws and
2mo i, 1:treaties had been a broken reed. On the character and functions of the
2mo i, 1:executive, however, there were many views. The New Jersey plan called
2mo i, 1:for a council selected by the Congress; the Virginia plan provided that
2mo i, 1:the executive branch should be chosen by the Congress but did not state
2mo i, 1:whether it should be composed of one or several persons. On this matter
2mo i, 1:the convention voted first one way and then another; finally it agreed
2mo i, 1:on a single executive chosen indirectly by electors selected as the
2mo i, 1:state legislatures might decide, serving for four years, subject to
2mo i, 1:impeachment, and endowed with regal powers in the command of the army
2mo i, 1:and the navy and in the enforcement of the laws.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:_The Legislative Branch--Congress._--After the convention had made the
2mo i, 1:great compromise between the large and small commonwealths by giving
2mo i, 1:representation to states in the Senate and to population in the House,
2mo i, 1:the question of methods of election had to be decided. As to the House
2mo i, 1:of Representatives it was readily agreed that the members should be
2mo i, 1:elected by direct popular vote. There was also easy agreement on the
2mo i, 1:proposition that a strong Senate was needed to check the "turbulence" of
2mo i, 1:the lower house. Four devices were finally selected to accomplish this
2mo i, 1:purpose. In the first place, the Senators were not to be chosen directly
2mo i, 1:by the voters but by the legislatures of the states, thus removing their
2mo i, 1:election one degree from the populace. In the second place, their term
2mo i, 1:was fixed at six years instead of two, as in the case of the House. In
2mo i, 1:the third place, provision was made for continuity by having only
2mo i, 1:one-third of the members go out at a time while two-thirds remained in
2mo i, 1:service. Finally, it was provided that Senators must be at least thirty
2mo i, 1:years old while Representatives need be only twenty-five.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:_The Judiciary._--The need for federal courts to carry out the law was
2mo i, 1:hardly open to debate. The feebleness of the Articles of Confederation
2mo i, 1:was, in a large measure, attributed to the want of a judiciary to hold
2mo i, 1:states and individuals in obedience to the laws and treaties of the
2mo i, 1:union. Nevertheless on this point the advocates of states' rights were
2mo i, 1:extremely sensitive. They looked with distrust upon judges appointed at
2mo i, 1:the national capital and emancipated from local interests and
2mo i, 1:traditions; they remembered with what insistence they had claimed
2mo i, 1:against Britain the right of local trial by jury and with what
2mo i, 1:consternation they had viewed the proposal to make colonial judges
2mo i, 1:independent of the assemblies in the matter of their salaries.
2mo i, 1:Reluctantly they yielded to the demand for federal courts, consenting at
2mo i, 1:first only to a supreme court to review cases heard in lower state
2mo i, 1:courts and finally to such additional inferior courts as Congress might
2mo i, 1:deem necessary.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:_The System of Checks and Balances._--It is thus apparent that the
2mo i, 1:framers of the Constitution, in shaping the form of government, arranged
2mo i, 1:for a distribution of power among three branches, executive,
2mo i, 1:legislative, and judicial. Strictly speaking we might say four branches,
2mo i, 1:for the legislature, or Congress, was composed of two houses, elected in
2mo i, 1:different ways, and one of them, the Senate, was made a check on the
2mo i, 1:President through its power of ratifying treaties and appointments. "The
2mo i, 1:accumulation of all powers, legislative, executive, and judicial, in the
2mo i, 1:same hands," wrote Madison, "whether of one, a few, or many, and whether
2mo i, 1:hereditary, self-appointed, or elective, may justly be pronounced the
2mo i, 1:very definition of tyranny." The devices which the convention adopted to
2mo i, 1:prevent such a centralization of authority were exceedingly ingenious
2mo i, 1:and well calculated to accomplish the purposes of the authors.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The legislature consisted of two houses, the members of which were to be
2mo i, 1:apportioned on a different basis, elected in different ways, and to
2mo i, 1:serve for different terms. A veto on all its acts was vested in a
2mo i, 1:President elected in a manner not employed in the choice of either
2mo i, 1:branch of the legislature, serving for four years, and subject to
2mo i, 1:removal only by the difficult process of impeachment. After a law had
2mo i, 1:run the gantlet of both houses and the executive, it was subject to
2mo i, 1:interpretation and annulment by the judiciary, appointed by the
2mo i, 1:President with the consent of the Senate and serving for life. Thus it
2mo i, 1:was made almost impossible for any political party to get possession of
2mo i, 1:all branches of the government at a single popular election. As Hamilton
2mo i, 1:remarked, the friends of good government considered "every institution
2mo i, 1:calculated to restrain the excess of law making and to keep things in
2mo i, 1:the same state in which they happen to be at any given period as more
2mo i, 1:likely to do good than harm."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Powers of the Federal Government.=--On the question of the powers
2mo i, 1:to be conferred upon the new government there was less occasion for a
2mo i, 1:serious dispute. Even the delegates from the small states agreed with
2mo i, 1:those from Massachusetts, Pennsylvania, and Virginia that new powers
2mo i, 1:should be added to those intrusted to Congress by the Articles of
2mo i, 1:Confederation. The New Jersey plan as well as the Virginia plan
2mo i, 1:recognized this fact. Some of the delegates, like Hamilton and Madison,
2mo i, 1:even proposed to give Congress a general legislative authority covering
2mo i, 1:all national matters; but others, frightened by the specter of
2mo i, 1:nationalism, insisted on specifying each power to be conferred and
2mo i, 1:finally carried the day.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:_Taxation and Commerce._--There were none bold enough to dissent from
2mo i, 1:the proposition that revenue must be provided to pay current expenses
2mo i, 1:and discharge the public debt. When once the dispute over the
2mo i, 1:apportionment of direct taxes among the slave states was settled, it was
2mo i, 1:an easy matter to decide that Congress should have power to lay and
2mo i, 1:collect taxes, duties, imposts, and excises. In this way the national
2mo i, 1:government was freed from dependence upon stubborn and tardy
2mo i, 1:legislatures and enabled to collect funds directly from citizens. There
2mo i, 1:were likewise none bold enough to contend that the anarchy of state
2mo i, 1:tariffs and trade discriminations should be longer endured. When the
2mo i, 1:fears of the planting states were allayed and the "bargain" over the
2mo i, 1:importation of slaves was reached, the convention vested in Congress the
2mo i, 1:power to regulate foreign and interstate commerce.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:_National Defense._--The necessity for national defense was realized,
2mo i, 1:though the fear of huge military establishments was equally present. The
2mo i, 1:old practice of relying on quotas furnished by the state legislatures
2mo i, 1:was completely discredited. As in the case of taxes a direct authority
2mo i, 1:over citizens was demanded. Congress was therefore given full power to
2mo i, 1:raise and support armies and a navy. It could employ the state militia
2mo i, 1:when desirable; but it could at the same time maintain a regular army
2mo i, 1:and call directly upon all able-bodied males if the nature of a crisis
2mo i, 1:was thought to require it.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:_The "Necessary and Proper" Clause._--To the specified power vested in
2mo i, 1:Congress by the Constitution, the advocates of a strong national
2mo i, 1:government added a general clause authorizing it to make all laws
2mo i, 1:"necessary and proper" for carrying into effect any and all of the
2mo i, 1:enumerated powers. This clause, interpreted by that master mind, Chief
2mo i, 1:Justice Marshall, was later construed to confer powers as wide as the
2mo i, 1:requirements of a vast country spanning a continent and taking its place
2mo i, 1:among the mighty nations of the earth.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Restraints on the States.=--Framing a government and endowing it with
2mo i, 1:large powers were by no means the sole concern of the convention. Its
2mo i, 1:very existence had been due quite as much to the conduct of the state
2mo i, 1:legislatures as to the futilities of a paralyzed Continental Congress.
2mo i, 1:In every state, explains Marshall in his _Life of Washington_, there was
2mo i, 1:a party of men who had "marked out for themselves a more indulgent
2mo i, 1:course. Viewing with extreme tenderness the case of the debtor, their
2mo i, 1:efforts were unceasingly directed to his relief. To exact a faithful
2mo i, 1:compliance with contracts was, in their opinion, a harsh measure which
2mo i, 1:the people could not bear. They were uniformly in favor of relaxing the
2mo i, 1:administration of justice, of affording facilities for the payment of
2mo i, 1:debts, or of suspending their collection, and remitting taxes."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The legislatures under the dominance of these men had enacted paper
2mo i, 1:money laws enabling debtors to discharge their obligations more easily.
2mo i, 1:The convention put an end to such practices by providing that no state
2mo i, 1:should emit bills of credit or make anything but gold or silver legal
2mo i, 1:tender in the payment of debts. The state legislatures had enacted laws
2mo i, 1:allowing men to pay their debts by turning over to creditors land or
2mo i, 1:personal property; they had repealed the charter of an endowed college
2mo i, 1:and taken the management from the hands of the lawful trustees; and they
2mo i, 1:had otherwise interfered with the enforcement of private agreements. The
2mo i, 1:convention, taking notice of such matters, inserted a clause forbidding
2mo i, 1:states "to impair the obligation of contracts." The more venturous of
2mo i, 1:the radicals had in Massachusetts raised the standard of revolt against
2mo i, 1:the authorities of the state. The convention answered by a brief
2mo i, 1:sentence to the effect that the President of the United States, to be
2mo i, 1:equipped with a regular army, would send troops to suppress domestic
2mo i, 1:insurrections whenever called upon by the legislature or, if it was not
2mo i, 1:in session, by the governor of the state. To make sure that the
2mo i, 1:restrictions on the states would not be dead letters, the federal
2mo i, 1:Constitution, laws, and treaties were made the supreme law of the land,
2mo i, 1:to be enforced whenever necessary by a national judiciary and executive
2mo i, 1:against violations on the part of any state authorities.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Provisions for Ratification and Amendment.=--When the frame of
2mo i, 1:government had been determined, the powers to be vested in it had been
2mo i, 1:enumerated, and the restrictions upon the states had been written into
2mo i, 1:the bond, there remained three final questions. How shall the
2mo i, 1:Constitution be ratified? What number of states shall be necessary to
2mo i, 1:put it into effect? How shall it be amended in the future?
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:On the first point, the mandate under which the convention was sitting
2mo i, 1:seemed positive. The Articles of Confederation were still in effect.
2mo i, 1:They provided that amendments could be made only by unanimous adoption
2mo i, 1:in Congress and the approval of all the states. As if to give force to
2mo i, 1:this provision of law, the call for the convention had expressly stated
2mo i, 1:that all alterations and revisions should be reported to Congress for
2mo i, 1:adoption or rejection, Congress itself to transmit the document
2mo i, 1:thereafter to the states for their review.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:To have observed the strict letter of the law would have defeated the
2mo i, 1:purposes of the delegates, because Congress and the state legislatures
2mo i, 1:were openly hostile to such drastic changes as had been made. Unanimous
2mo i, 1:ratification, as events proved, would have been impossible. Therefore
2mo i, 1:the delegates decided that the Constitution should be sent to Congress
2mo i, 1:with the recommendation that it, in turn, transmit the document, not to
2mo i, 1:the state legislatures, but to conventions held in the states for the
2mo i, 1:special object of deciding upon ratification. This process was followed.
2mo i, 1:It was their belief that special conventions would be more friendly than
2mo i, 1:the state legislatures.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The convention was equally positive in dealing with the problem of the
2mo i, 1:number of states necessary to establish the new Constitution. Attempts
2mo i, 1:to change the Articles had failed because amendment required the
2mo i, 1:approval of every state and there was always at least one recalcitrant
2mo i, 1:member of the union. The opposition to a new Constitution was
2mo i, 1:undoubtedly formidable. Rhode Island had even refused to take part in
2mo i, 1:framing it, and her hostility was deep and open. So the convention cast
2mo i, 1:aside the provision of the Articles of Confederation which required
2mo i, 1:unanimous approval for any change in the plan of government; it decreed
2mo i, 1:that the new Constitution should go into effect when ratified by nine
2mo i, 1:states.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:In providing for future changes in the Constitution itself the
2mo i, 1:convention also thrust aside the old rule of unanimous approval, and
2mo i, 1:decided that an amendment could be made on a two-thirds vote in both
2mo i, 1:houses of Congress and ratification by three-fourths of the states. This
2mo i, 1:change was of profound significance. Every state agreed to be bound in
2mo i, 1:the future by amendments duly adopted even in case it did not approve
2mo i, 1:them itself. America in this way set out upon the high road that led
2mo i, 1:from a league of states to a nation.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:THE STRUGGLE OVER RATIFICATION
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:On September 17, 1787, the Constitution, having been finally drafted in
2mo i, 1:clear and simple language, a model to all makers of fundamental law, was
2mo i, 1:adopted. The convention, after nearly four months of debate in secret
2mo i, 1:session, flung open the doors and presented to the Americans the
2mo i, 1:finished plan for the new government. Then the great debate passed to
2mo i, 1:the people.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Opposition.=--Storms of criticism at once descended upon the
2mo i, 1:Constitution. "Fraudulent usurpation!" exclaimed Gerry, who had refused
2mo i, 1:to sign it. "A monster" out of the "thick veil of secrecy," declaimed a
2mo i, 1:Pennsylvania newspaper. "An iron-handed despotism will be the result,"
2mo i, 1:protested a third. "We, 'the low-born,'" sarcastically wrote a fourth,
2mo i, 1:"will now admit the 'six hundred well-born' immediately to establish
2mo i, 1:this most noble, most excellent, and truly divine constitution." The
2mo i, 1:President will become a king; Congress will be as tyrannical as
2mo i, 1:Parliament in the old days; the states will be swallowed up; the rights
2mo i, 1:of the people will be trampled upon; the poor man's justice will be lost
2mo i, 1:in the endless delays of the federal courts--such was the strain of the
2mo i, 1:protests against ratification.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:[Illustration: AN ADVERTISEMENT OF _The Federalist_]
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Defense of the Constitution.=--Moved by the tempest of opposition,
2mo i, 1:Hamilton, Madison, and Jay took up their pens in defense of the
2mo i, 1:Constitution. In a series of newspaper articles they discussed and
2mo i, 1:expounded with eloquence, learning, and dignity every important clause
2mo i, 1:and provision of the proposed plan. These papers, afterwards collected
2mo i, 1:and published in a volume known as _The Federalist_, form the finest
2mo i, 1:textbook on the Constitution that has ever been printed. It takes its
2mo i, 1:place, moreover, among the wisest and weightiest treatises on government
2mo i, 1:ever written in any language in any time. Other men, not so gifted, were
2mo i, 1:no less earnest in their support of ratification. In private
2mo i, 1:correspondence, editorials, pamphlets, and letters to the newspapers,
2mo i, 1:they urged their countrymen to forget their partisanship and accept a
2mo i, 1:Constitution which, in spite of any defects great or small, was the
2mo i, 1:only guarantee against dissolution and warfare at home and dishonor and
2mo i, 1:weakness abroad.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:[Illustration: CELEBRATING THE RATIFICATION]
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Action of the State Conventions.=--Before the end of the year,
2mo i, 1:1787, three states had ratified the Constitution: Delaware and New
2mo i, 1:Jersey unanimously and Pennsylvania after a short, though savage,
2mo i, 1:contest. Connecticut and Georgia followed early the next year. Then came
2mo i, 1:the battle royal in Massachusetts, ending in ratification in February by
2mo i, 1:the narrow margin of 187 votes to 168. In the spring came the news that
2mo i, 1:Maryland and South Carolina were "under the new roof." On June 21, New
2mo i, 1:Hampshire, where the sentiment was at first strong enough to defeat the
2mo i, 1:Constitution, joined the new republic, influenced by the favorable
2mo i, 1:decision in Massachusetts. Swift couriers were sent to carry the news to
2mo i, 1:New York and Virginia, where the question of ratification was still
2mo i, 1:undecided. Nine states had accepted it and were united, whether more saw
2mo i, 1:fit to join or not.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Meanwhile, however, Virginia, after a long and searching debate, had
2mo i, 1:given her approval by a narrow margin, leaving New York as the next seat
2mo i, 1:of anxiety. In that state the popular vote for the delegates to the
2mo i, 1:convention had been clearly and heavily against ratification. Events
2mo i, 1:finally demonstrated the futility of resistance, and Hamilton by good
2mo i, 1:judgment and masterly arguments was at last able to marshal a majority
2mo i, 1:of thirty to twenty-seven votes in favor of ratification.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The great contest was over. All the states, except North Carolina and
2mo i, 1:Rhode Island, had ratified. "The sloop Anarchy," wrote an ebullient
2mo i, 1:journalist, "when last heard from was ashore on Union rocks."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The First Election.=--In the autumn of 1788, elections were held to
2mo i, 1:fill the places in the new government. Public opinion was overwhelmingly
2mo i, 1:in favor of Washington as the first President. Yielding to the
2mo i, 1:importunities of friends, he accepted the post in the spirit of public
2mo i, 1:service. On April 30, 1789, he took the oath of office at Federal Hall
2mo i, 1:in New York City. "Long live George Washington, President of the United
2mo i, 1:States!" cried Chancellor Livingston as soon as the General had kissed
2mo i, 1:the Bible. The cry was caught by the assembled multitude and given back.
2mo i, 1:A new experiment in popular government was launched.
