2mo i, 1:=Source Study.=--Compare the Constitution and Articles of Confederation
2mo i, 1:under the following heads: (1) frame of government; (2) powers of
2mo i, 1:Congress; (3) limits on states; and (4) methods of amendment. Every line
2mo i, 1:of the Constitution should be read and re-read in the light of the
2mo i, 1:historical circumstances set forth in this chapter.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:CHAPTER VIII
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:THE CLASH OF POLITICAL PARTIES
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:THE MEN AND MEASURES OF THE NEW GOVERNMENT
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Friends of the Constitution in Power.=--In the first Congress that
2mo i, 1:assembled after the adoption of the Constitution, there were eleven
2mo i, 1:Senators, led by Robert Morris, the financier, who had been delegates to
2mo i, 1:the national convention. Several members of the House of
2mo i, 1:Representatives, headed by James Madison, had also been at Philadelphia
2mo i, 1:in 1787. In making his appointments, Washington strengthened the new
2mo i, 1:system of government still further by a judicious selection of
2mo i, 1:officials. He chose as Secretary of the Treasury, Alexander Hamilton,
2mo i, 1:who had been the most zealous for its success; General Knox, head of the
2mo i, 1:War Department, and Edmund Randolph, the Attorney-General, were likewise
2mo i, 1:conspicuous friends of the experiment. Every member of the federal
2mo i, 1:judiciary whom Washington appointed, from the Chief Justice, John Jay,
2mo i, 1:down to the justices of the district courts, had favored the
2mo i, 1:ratification of the Constitution; and a majority of them had served as
2mo i, 1:members of the national convention that framed the document or of the
2mo i, 1:state ratifying conventions. Only one man of influence in the new
2mo i, 1:government, Thomas Jefferson, the Secretary of State, was reckoned as a
2mo i, 1:doubter in the house of the faithful. He had expressed opinions both for
2mo i, 1:and against the Constitution; but he had been out of the country acting
2mo i, 1:as the minister at Paris when the Constitution was drafted and ratified.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=An Opposition to Conciliate.=--The inauguration of Washington amid the
2mo i, 1:plaudits of his countrymen did not set at rest all the political turmoil
2mo i, 1:which had been aroused by the angry contest over ratification. "The
2mo i, 1:interesting nature of the question," wrote John Marshall, "the equality
2mo i, 1:of the parties, the animation produced inevitably by ardent debate had a
2mo i, 1:necessary tendency to embitter the dispositions of the vanquished and to
2mo i, 1:fix more deeply in many bosoms their prejudices against a plan of
2mo i, 1:government in opposition to which all their passions were enlisted." The
2mo i, 1:leaders gathered around Washington were well aware of the excited state
2mo i, 1:of the country. They saw Rhode Island and North Carolina still outside
2mo i, 1:of the union.[1] They knew by what small margins the Constitution had
2mo i, 1:been approved in the great states of Massachusetts, Virginia, and New
2mo i, 1:York. They were equally aware that a majority of the state conventions,
2mo i, 1:in yielding reluctant approval to the Constitution, had drawn a number
2mo i, 1:of amendments for immediate submission to the states.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The First Amendments--a Bill of Rights.=--To meet the opposition,
2mo i, 1:Madison proposed, and the first Congress adopted, a series of amendments
2mo i, 1:to the Constitution. Ten of them were soon ratified and became in 1791 a
2mo i, 1:part of the law of the land. These amendments provided, among other
2mo i, 1:things, that Congress could make no law respecting the establishment of
2mo i, 1:religion, abridging the freedom of speech or of the press or the right
2mo i, 1:of the people peaceably to assemble and petition the government for a
2mo i, 1:redress of grievances. They also guaranteed indictment by grand jury and
2mo i, 1:trial by jury for all persons charged by federal officers with serious
2mo i, 1:crimes. To reassure those who still feared that local rights might be
2mo i, 1:invaded by the federal government, the tenth amendment expressly
2mo i, 1:provided that the powers not delegated to the United States by the
2mo i, 1:Constitution, nor prohibited by it to the states, are reserved to the
2mo i, 1:states respectively or to the people. Seven years later, the eleventh
2mo i, 1:amendment was written in the same spirit as the first ten, after a
2mo i, 1:heated debate over the action of the Supreme Court in permitting a
2mo i, 1:citizen to bring a suit against "the sovereign state" of Georgia. The
2mo i, 1:new amendment was designed to protect states against the federal
2mo i, 1:judiciary by forbidding it to hear any case in which a state was sued by
2mo i, 1:a citizen.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Funding the National Debt.=--Paper declarations of rights, however,
2mo i, 1:paid no bills. To this task Hamilton turned all his splendid genius. At
2mo i, 1:the very outset he addressed himself to the problem of the huge public
2mo i, 1:debt, daily mounting as the unpaid interest accumulated. In a _Report on
2mo i, 1:Public Credit_ under date of January 9, 1790, one of the first and
2mo i, 1:greatest of American state papers, he laid before Congress the outlines
2mo i, 1:of his plan. He proposed that the federal government should call in all
2mo i, 1:the old bonds, certificates of indebtedness, and other promises to pay
2mo i, 1:which had been issued by the Congress since the beginning of the
2mo i, 1:Revolution. These national obligations, he urged, should be put into one
2mo i, 1:consolidated debt resting on the credit of the United States; to the
2mo i, 1:holders of the old paper should be issued new bonds drawing interest at
2mo i, 1:fixed rates. This process was called "funding the debt." Such a
2mo i, 1:provision for the support of public credit, Hamilton insisted, would
2mo i, 1:satisfy creditors, restore landed property to its former value, and
2mo i, 1:furnish new resources to agriculture and commerce in the form of credit
2mo i, 1:and capital.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Assumption and Funding of State Debts.=--Hamilton then turned to the
2mo i, 1:obligations incurred by the several states in support of the Revolution.
2mo i, 1:These debts he proposed to add to the national debt. They were to be
2mo i, 1:"assumed" by the United States government and placed on the same secure
2mo i, 1:foundation as the continental debt. This measure he defended not merely
2mo i, 1:on grounds of national honor. It would, as he foresaw, give strength to
2mo i, 1:the new national government by making all public creditors, men of
2mo i, 1:substance in their several communities, look to the federal, rather than
2mo i, 1:the state government, for the satisfaction of their claims.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Funding at Face Value.=--On the question of the terms of consolidation,
2mo i, 1:assumption, and funding, Hamilton had a firm conviction. That millions
2mo i, 1:of dollars' worth of the continental and state bonds had passed out of
2mo i, 1:the hands of those who had originally subscribed their funds to the
2mo i, 1:support of the government or had sold supplies for the Revolutionary
2mo i, 1:army was well known. It was also a matter of common knowledge that a
2mo i, 1:very large part of these bonds had been bought by speculators at ruinous
2mo i, 1:figures--ten, twenty, and thirty cents on the dollar. Accordingly, it
2mo i, 1:had been suggested, even in very respectable quarters, that a
2mo i, 1:discrimination should be made between original holders and speculative
2mo i, 1:purchasers. Some who held this opinion urged that the speculators who
2mo i, 1:had paid nominal sums for their bonds should be reimbursed for their
2mo i, 1:outlays and the original holders paid the difference; others said that
2mo i, 1:the government should "scale the debt" by redeeming, not at full value
2mo i, 1:but at a figure reasonably above the market price. Against the
2mo i, 1:proposition Hamilton set his face like flint. He maintained that the
2mo i, 1:government was honestly bound to redeem every bond at its face value,
2mo i, 1:although the difficulty of securing revenue made necessary a lower rate
2mo i, 1:of interest on a part of the bonds and the deferring of interest on
2mo i, 1:another part.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Funding and Assumption Carried.=--There was little difficulty in
2mo i, 1:securing the approval of both houses of Congress for the funding of the
2mo i, 1:national debt at full value. The bill for the assumption of state debts,
2mo i, 1:however, brought the sharpest division of opinions. To the Southern
2mo i, 1:members of Congress assumption was a gross violation of states' rights,
2mo i, 1:without any warrant in the Constitution and devised in the interest of
2mo i, 1:Northern speculators who, anticipating assumption and funding, had
2mo i, 1:bought up at low prices the Southern bonds and other promises to pay.
2mo i, 1:New England, on the other hand, was strongly in favor of assumption;
2mo i, 1:several representatives from that section were rash enough to threaten a
2mo i, 1:dissolution of the union if the bill was defeated. To this dispute was
2mo i, 1:added an equally bitter quarrel over the location of the national
2mo i, 1:capital, then temporarily at New York City.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:[Illustration: FIRST UNITED STATES BANK AT PHILADELPHIA]
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:A deadlock, accompanied by the most surly feelings on both sides,
2mo i, 1:threatened the very existence of the young government. Washington and
2mo i, 1:Hamilton were thoroughly alarmed. Hearing of the extremity to which the
2mo i, 1:contest had been carried and acting on the appeal from the Secretary of
2mo i, 1:the Treasury, Jefferson intervened at this point. By skillful management
2mo i, 1:at a good dinner he brought the opposing leaders together; and thus once
2mo i, 1:more, as on many other occasions, peace was purchased and the union
2mo i, 1:saved by compromise. The bargain this time consisted of an exchange of
2mo i, 1:votes for assumption in return for votes for the capital. Enough
2mo i, 1:Southern members voted for assumption to pass the bill, and a majority
2mo i, 1:was mustered in favor of building the capital on the banks of the
2mo i, 1:Potomac, after locating it for a ten-year period at Philadelphia to
2mo i, 1:satisfy Pennsylvania members.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The United States Bank.=--Encouraged by the success of his funding and
2mo i, 1:assumption measures, Hamilton laid before Congress a project for a great
2mo i, 1:United States Bank. He proposed that a private corporation be chartered
2mo i, 1:by Congress, authorized to raise a capital stock of $10,000,000
2mo i, 1:(three-fourths in new six per cent federal bonds and one-fourth in
2mo i, 1:specie) and empowered to issue paper currency under proper safeguards.
2mo i, 1:Many advantages, Hamilton contended, would accrue to the government from
2mo i, 1:this institution. The price of the government bonds would be increased,
2mo i, 1:thus enhancing public credit. A national currency would be created of
2mo i, 1:uniform value from one end of the land to the other. The branches of the
2mo i, 1:bank in various cities would make easy the exchange of funds so vital to
2mo i, 1:commercial transactions on a national scale. Finally, through the issue
2mo i, 1:of bank notes, the money capital available for agriculture and industry
2mo i, 1:would be increased, thus stimulating business enterprise. Jefferson
2mo i, 1:hotly attacked the bank on the ground that Congress had no power
2mo i, 1:whatever under the Constitution to charter such a private corporation.
2mo i, 1:Hamilton defended it with great cogency. Washington, after weighing all
2mo i, 1:opinions, decided in favor of the proposal. In 1791 the bill
2mo i, 1:establishing the first United States Bank for a period of twenty years
2mo i, 1:became a law.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Protective Tariff.=--A third part of Hamilton's program was the
2mo i, 1:protection of American industries. The first revenue act of 1789, though
2mo i, 1:designed primarily to bring money into the empty treasury, declared in
2mo i, 1:favor of the principle. The following year Washington referred to the
2mo i, 1:subject in his address to Congress. Thereupon Hamilton was instructed to
2mo i, 1:prepare recommendations for legislative action. The result, after a
2mo i, 1:delay of more than a year, was his _Report on Manufactures_, another
2mo i, 1:state paper worthy, in closeness of reasoning and keenness of
2mo i, 1:understanding, of a place beside his report on public credit. Hamilton
2mo i, 1:based his argument on the broadest national grounds: the protective
2mo i, 1:tariff would, by encouraging the building of factories, create a home
2mo i, 1:market for the produce of farms and plantations; by making the United
2mo i, 1:States independent of other countries in times of peace, it would double
2mo i, 1:its security in time of war; by making use of the labor of women and
2mo i, 1:children, it would turn to the production of goods persons otherwise
2mo i, 1:idle or only partly employed; by increasing the trade between the North
2mo i, 1:and South it would strengthen the links of union and add to political
2mo i, 1:ties those of commerce and intercourse. The revenue measure of 1792 bore
2mo i, 1:the impress of these arguments.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:THE RISE OF POLITICAL PARTIES
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Dissensions over Hamilton's Measures.=--Hamilton's plans, touching
2mo i, 1:deeply as they did the resources of individuals and the interests of the
2mo i, 1:states, awakened alarm and opposition. Funding at face value, said his
2mo i, 1:critics, was a government favor to speculators; the assumption of state
2mo i, 1:debts was a deep design to undermine the state governments; Congress had
2mo i, 1:no constitutional power to create a bank; the law creating the bank
2mo i, 1:merely allowed a private corporation to make paper money and lend it at
2mo i, 1:a high rate of interest; and the tariff was a tax on land and labor for
2mo i, 1:the benefit of manufacturers.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Hamilton's reply to this bill of indictment was simple and
2mo i, 1:straightforward. Some rascally speculators had profited from the funding
2mo i, 1:of the debt at face value, but that was only an incident in the
2mo i, 1:restoration of public credit. In view of the jealousies of the states it
2mo i, 1:was a good thing to reduce their powers and pretensions. The
2mo i, 1:Constitution was not to be interpreted narrowly but in the full light of
2mo i, 1:national needs. The bank would enlarge the amount of capital so sorely
2mo i, 1:needed to start up American industries, giving markets to farmers and
2mo i, 1:planters. The tariff by creating a home market and increasing
2mo i, 1:opportunities for employment would benefit both land and labor. Out of
2mo i, 1:such wise policies firmly pursued by the government, he concluded, were
2mo i, 1:bound to come strength and prosperity for the new government at home,
2mo i, 1:credit and power abroad. This view Washington fully indorsed, adding
2mo i, 1:the weight of his great name to the inherent merits of the measures
2mo i, 1:adopted under his administration.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Sharpness of the Partisan Conflict.=--As a result of the clash of
2mo i, 1:opinion, the people of the country gradually divided into two parties:
2mo i, 1:Federalists and Anti-Federalists, the former led by Hamilton, the latter
2mo i, 1:by Jefferson. The strength of the Federalists lay in the cities--Boston,
2mo i, 1:Providence, Hartford, New York, Philadelphia, Charleston--among the
2mo i, 1:manufacturing, financial, and commercial groups of the population who
2mo i, 1:were eager to extend their business operations. The strength of the
2mo i, 1:Anti-Federalists lay mainly among the debt-burdened farmers who feared
2mo i, 1:the growth of what they called "a money power" and planters in all
2mo i, 1:sections who feared the dominance of commercial and manufacturing
2mo i, 1:interests. The farming and planting South, outside of the few towns,
2mo i, 1:finally presented an almost solid front against assumption, the bank,
2mo i, 1:and the tariff. The conflict between the parties grew steadily in
2mo i, 1:bitterness, despite the conciliatory and engaging manner in which
2mo i, 1:Hamilton presented his cause in his state papers and despite the
2mo i, 1:constant efforts of Washington to soften the asperity of the
2mo i, 1:contestants.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Leadership and Doctrines of Jefferson.=--The party dispute had not
2mo i, 1:gone far before the opponents of the administration began to look to
2mo i, 1:Jefferson as their leader. Some of Hamilton's measures he had approved,
2mo i, 1:declaring afterward that he did not at the time understand their
2mo i, 1:significance. Others, particularly the bank, he fiercely assailed. More
2mo i, 1:than once, he and Hamilton, shaking violently with anger, attacked each
2mo i, 1:other at cabinet meetings, and nothing short of the grave and dignified
2mo i, 1:pleas of Washington prevented an early and open break between them. In
2mo i, 1:1794 it finally came. Jefferson resigned as Secretary of State and
2mo i, 1:retired to his home in Virginia to assume, through correspondence and
2mo i, 1:negotiation, the leadership of the steadily growing party of opposition.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Shy and modest in manner, halting in speech, disliking the turmoil of
2mo i, 1:public debate, and deeply interested in science and philosophy,
2mo i, 1:Jefferson was not very well fitted for the strenuous life of political
2mo i, 1:contest. Nevertheless, he was an ambitious and shrewd negotiator. He was
2mo i, 1:also by honest opinion and matured conviction the exact opposite of
2mo i, 1:Hamilton. The latter believed in a strong, active, "high-toned"
2mo i, 1:government, vigorously compelling in all its branches. Jefferson looked
2mo i, 1:upon such government as dangerous to the liberties of citizens and
2mo i, 1:openly avowed his faith in the desirability of occasional popular
2mo i, 1:uprisings. Hamilton distrusted the people. "Your people is a great
2mo i, 1:beast," he is reported to have said. Jefferson professed his faith in
2mo i, 1:the people with an abandon that was considered reckless in his time.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:On economic matters, the opinions of the two leaders were also
2mo i, 1:hopelessly at variance. Hamilton, while cherishing agriculture, desired
2mo i, 1:to see America a great commercial and industrial nation. Jefferson was
2mo i, 1:equally set against this course for his country. He feared the
2mo i, 1:accumulation of riches and the growth of a large urban working class.
2mo i, 1:The mobs of great cities, he said, are sores on the body politic;
2mo i, 1:artisans are usually the dangerous element that make revolutions;
2mo i, 1:workshops should be kept in Europe and with them the artisans with their
2mo i, 1:insidious morals and manners. The only substantial foundation for a
2mo i, 1:republic, Jefferson believed to be agriculture. The spirit of
2mo i, 1:independence could be kept alive only by free farmers, owning the land
2mo i, 1:they tilled and looking to the sun in heaven and the labor of their
2mo i, 1:hands for their sustenance. Trusting as he did in the innate goodness of
2mo i, 1:human nature when nourished on a free soil, Jefferson advocated those
2mo i, 1:measures calculated to favor agriculture and to enlarge the rights of
2mo i, 1:persons rather than the powers of government. Thus he became the
2mo i, 1:champion of the individual against the interference of the government,
2mo i, 1:and an ardent advocate of freedom of the press, freedom of speech, and
2mo i, 1:freedom of scientific inquiry. It was, accordingly, no mere factious
2mo i, 1:spirit that drove him into opposition to Hamilton.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Whisky Rebellion.=--The political agitation of the Anti-Federalists
2mo i, 1:was accompanied by an armed revolt against the government in 1794. The
2mo i, 1:occasion for this uprising was another of Hamilton's measures, a law
2mo i, 1:laying an excise tax on distilled spirits, for the purpose of increasing
2mo i, 1:the revenue needed to pay the interest on the funded debt. It so
2mo i, 1:happened that a very considerable part of the whisky manufactured in the
2mo i, 1:country was made by the farmers, especially on the frontier, in their
2mo i, 1:own stills. The new revenue law meant that federal officers would now
2mo i, 1:come into the homes of the people, measure their liquor, and take the
2mo i, 1:tax out of their pockets. All the bitterness which farmers felt against
2mo i, 1:the fiscal measures of the government was redoubled. In the western
2mo i, 1:districts of Pennsylvania, Virginia, and North Carolina, they refused to
2mo i, 1:pay the tax. In Pennsylvania, some of them sacked and burned the houses
2mo i, 1:of the tax collectors, as the Revolutionists thirty years before had
2mo i, 1:mobbed the agents of King George sent over to sell stamps. They were in
2mo i, 1:a fair way to nullify the law in whole districts when Washington called
2mo i, 1:out the troops to suppress "the Whisky Rebellion." Then the movement
2mo i, 1:collapsed; but it left behind a deep-seated resentment which flared up
2mo i, 1:in the election of several obdurate Anti-Federalist Congressmen from the
2mo i, 1:disaffected regions.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:FOREIGN INFLUENCES AND DOMESTIC POLITICS
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The French Revolution.=--In this exciting period, when all America was
2mo i, 1:distracted by partisan disputes, a storm broke in Europe--the
2mo i, 1:epoch-making French Revolution--which not only shook the thrones of the
2mo i, 1:Old World but stirred to its depths the young republic of the New World.
2mo i, 1:The first scene in this dramatic affair occurred in the spring of 1789,
2mo i, 1:a few days after Washington was inaugurated. The king of France, Louis
2mo i, 1:XVI, driven into bankruptcy by extravagance and costly wars, was forced
2mo i, 1:to resort to his people for financial help. Accordingly he called, for
2mo i, 1:the first time in more than one hundred fifty years, a meeting of the
2mo i, 1:national parliament, the "Estates General," composed of representatives
2mo i, 1:of the "three estates"--the clergy, nobility, and commoners. Acting
2mo i, 1:under powerful leaders, the commoners, or "third estate," swept aside
2mo i, 1:the clergy and nobility and resolved themselves into a national
2mo i, 1:assembly. This stirred the country to its depths.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:[Illustration: _From an old print_
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:LOUIS XVI IN THE HANDS OF THE MOB]
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Great events followed in swift succession. On July 14, 1789, the
2mo i, 1:Bastille, an old royal prison, symbol of the king's absolutism, was
2mo i, 1:stormed by a Paris crowd and destroyed. On the night of August 4, the
2mo i, 1:feudal privileges of the nobility were abolished by the national
2mo i, 1:assembly amid great excitement. A few days later came the famous
2mo i, 1:Declaration of the Rights of Man, proclaiming the sovereignty of the
2mo i, 1:people and the privileges of citizens. In the autumn of 1791, Louis XVI
2mo i, 1:was forced to accept a new constitution for France vesting the
2mo i, 1:legislative power in a popular assembly. Little disorder accompanied
2mo i, 1:these startling changes. To all appearances a peaceful revolution had
2mo i, 1:stripped the French king of his royal prerogatives and based the
2mo i, 1:government of his country on the consent of the governed.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=American Influence in France.=--In undertaking their great political
2mo i, 1:revolt the French had been encouraged by the outcome of the American
2mo i, 1:Revolution. Officers and soldiers, who had served in the American war,
2mo i, 1:reported to their French countrymen marvelous tales. At the frugal table
2mo i, 1:of General Washington, in council with the unpretentious Franklin, or at
2mo i, 1:conferences over the strategy of war, French noblemen of ancient lineage
2mo i, 1:learned to respect both the talents and the simple character of the
2mo i, 1:leaders in the great republican commonwealth beyond the seas. Travelers,
2mo i, 1:who had gone to see the experiment in republicanism with their own eyes,
2mo i, 1:carried home to the king and ruling class stories of an astounding
2mo i, 1:system of popular government.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:On the other hand the dalliance with American democracy was regarded by
2mo i, 1:French conservatives as playing with fire. "When we think of the false
2mo i, 1:ideas of government and philanthropy," wrote one of Lafayette's aides,
2mo i, 1:"which these youths acquired in America and propagated in France with so
2mo i, 1:much enthusiasm and such deplorable success--for this mania of imitation
2mo i, 1:powerfully aided the Revolution, though it was not the sole cause of
2mo i, 1:it--we are bound to confess that it would have been better, both for
2mo i, 1:themselves and for us, if these young philosophers in red-heeled shoes
2mo i, 1:had stayed at home in attendance on the court."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Early American Opinion of the French Revolution.=--So close were the
2mo i, 1:ties between the two nations that it is not surprising to find every
2mo i, 1:step in the first stages of the French Revolution greeted with applause
2mo i, 1:in the United States. "Liberty will have another feather in her cap,"
2mo i, 1:exultantly wrote a Boston editor. "In no part of the globe," soberly
2mo i, 1:wrote John Marshall, "was this revolution hailed with more joy than in
2mo i, 1:America.... But one sentiment existed." The main key to the Bastille,
2mo i, 1:sent to Washington as a memento, was accepted as "a token of the
2mo i, 1:victory gained by liberty." Thomas Paine saw in the great event "the
2mo i, 1:first ripe fruits of American principles transplanted into Europe."
2mo i, 1:Federalists and Anti-Federalists regarded the new constitution of France
2mo i, 1:as another vindication of American ideals.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Reign of Terror.=--While profuse congratulations were being
2mo i, 1:exchanged, rumors began to come that all was not well in France. Many
2mo i, 1:noblemen, enraged at the loss of their special privileges, fled into
2mo i, 1:Germany and plotted an invasion of France to overthrow the new system of
2mo i, 1:government. Louis XVI entered into negotiations with his brother
2mo i, 1:monarchs on the continent to secure their help in the same enterprise,
2mo i, 1:and he finally betrayed to the French people his true sentiments by
2mo i, 1:attempting to escape from his kingdom, only to be captured and taken
2mo i, 1:back to Paris in disgrace.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:A new phase of the revolution now opened. The working people, excluded
2mo i, 1:from all share in the government by the first French constitution,
2mo i, 1:became restless, especially in Paris. Assembling on the Champs de Mars,
2mo i, 1:a great open field, they signed a petition calling for another
2mo i, 1:constitution giving them the suffrage. When told to disperse, they
2mo i, 1:refused and were fired upon by the national guard. This "massacre," as
2mo i, 1:it was called, enraged the populace. A radical party, known as
2mo i, 1:"Jacobins," then sprang up, taking its name from a Jacobin monastery in
2mo i, 1:which it held its sessions. In a little while it became the master of
2mo i, 1:the popular convention convoked in September, 1792. The monarchy was
2mo i, 1:immediately abolished and a republic established. On January 21, 1793,
2mo i, 1:Louis was sent to the scaffold. To the war on Austria, already raging,
2mo i, 1:was added a war on England. Then came the Reign of Terror, during which
2mo i, 1:radicals in possession of the convention executed in large numbers
2mo i, 1:counter-revolutionists and those suspected of sympathy with the
2mo i, 1:monarchy. They shot down peasants who rose in insurrection against their
2mo i, 1:rule and established a relentless dictatorship. Civil war followed.
2mo i, 1:Terrible atrocities were committed on both sides in the name of liberty,
2mo i, 1:and in the name of monarchy. To Americans of conservative temper it now
2mo i, 1:seemed that the Revolution, so auspiciously begun, had degenerated into
2mo i, 1:anarchy and mere bloodthirsty strife.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Burke Summons the World to War on France.=--In England, Edmund Burke
2mo i, 1:led the fight against the new French principles which he feared might
2mo i, 1:spread to all Europe. In his _Reflections on the French Revolution_,
2mo i, 1:written in 1790, he attacked with terrible wrath the whole program of
2mo i, 1:popular government; he called for war, relentless war, upon the French
2mo i, 1:as monsters and outlaws; he demanded that they be reduced to order by
2mo i, 1:the restoration of the king to full power under the protection of the
2mo i, 1:arms of European nations.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Paine's Defense of the French Revolution.=--To counteract the campaign
2mo i, 1:of hate against the French, Thomas Paine replied to Burke in another of
2mo i, 1:his famous tracts, _The Rights of Man_, which was given to the American
2mo i, 1:public in an edition containing a letter of approval from Jefferson.
2mo i, 1:Burke, said Paine, had been mourning about the glories of the French
2mo i, 1:monarchy and aristocracy but had forgotten the starving peasants and the
2mo i, 1:oppressed people; had wept over the plumage and neglected the dying
2mo i, 1:bird. Burke had denied the right of the French people to choose their
2mo i, 1:own governors, blandly forgetting that the English government in which
2mo i, 1:he saw final perfection itself rested on two revolutions. He had boasted
2mo i, 1:that the king of England held his crown in contempt of the democratic
2mo i, 1:societies. Paine answered: "If I ask a man in America if he wants a
2mo i, 1:king, he retorts and asks me if I take him for an idiot." To the charge
2mo i, 1:that the doctrines of the rights of man were "new fangled," Paine
2mo i, 1:replied that the question was not whether they were new or old but
2mo i, 1:whether they were right or wrong. As to the French disorders and
2mo i, 1:difficulties, he bade the world wait to see what would be brought forth
2mo i, 1:in due time.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Effect of the French Revolution on American Politics.=--The course
2mo i, 1:of the French Revolution and the controversies accompanying it,
2mo i, 1:exercised a profound influence on the formation of the first political
2mo i, 1:parties in America. The followers of Hamilton, now proud of the name
2mo i, 1:"Federalists," drew back in fright as they heard of the cruel deeds
2mo i, 1:committed during the Reign of Terror. They turned savagely upon the
2mo i, 1:revolutionists and their friends in America, denouncing as "Jacobin"
2mo i, 1:everybody who did not condemn loudly enough the proceedings of the
2mo i, 1:French Republic. A Massachusetts preacher roundly assailed "the
2mo i, 1:atheistical, anarchical, and in other respects immoral principles of the
2mo i, 1:French Republicans"; he then proceeded with equal passion to attack
2mo i, 1:Jefferson and the Anti-Federalists, whom he charged with spreading false
2mo i, 1:French propaganda and betraying America. "The editors, patrons, and
2mo i, 1:abettors of these vehicles of slander," he exclaimed, "ought to be
2mo i, 1:considered and treated as enemies to their country.... Of all traitors
2mo i, 1:they are the most aggravatedly criminal; of all villains, they are the
2mo i, 1:most infamous and detestable."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The Anti-Federalists, as a matter of fact, were generally favorable to
2mo i, 1:the Revolution although they deplored many of the events associated with
2mo i, 1:it. Paine's pamphlet, indorsed by Jefferson, was widely read. Democratic
2mo i, 1:societies, after the fashion of French political clubs, arose in the
2mo i, 1:cities; the coalition of European monarchs against France was denounced
2mo i, 1:as a coalition against the very principles of republicanism; and the
2mo i, 1:execution of Louis XVI was openly celebrated at a banquet in
2mo i, 1:Philadelphia. Harmless titles, such as "Sir," "the Honorable," and "His
2mo i, 1:Excellency," were decried as aristocratic and some of the more excited
2mo i, 1:insisted on adopting the French title, "Citizen," speaking, for example,
2mo i, 1:of "Citizen Judge" and "Citizen Toastmaster." Pamphlets in defense of
2mo i, 1:the French streamed from the press, while subsidized newspapers kept the
2mo i, 1:propaganda in full swing.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The European War Disturbs American Commerce.=--This battle of wits, or
2mo i, 1:rather contest in calumny, might have gone on indefinitely in America
2mo i, 1:without producing any serious results, had it not been for the war
2mo i, 1:between England and France, then raging. The English, having command of
2mo i, 1:the seas, claimed the right to seize American produce bound for French
2mo i, 1:ports and to confiscate American ships engaged in carrying French goods.
2mo i, 1:Adding fuel to a fire already hot enough, they began to search American
2mo i, 1:ships and to carry off British-born sailors found on board American
2mo i, 1:vessels.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The French Appeal for Help.=--At the same time the French Republic
2mo i, 1:turned to the United States for aid in its war on England and sent over
2mo i, 1:as its diplomatic representative "Citizen" Genet, an ardent supporter of
2mo i, 1:the new order. On his arrival at Charleston, he was greeted with fervor
2mo i, 1:by the Anti-Federalists. As he made his way North, he was wined and
2mo i, 1:dined and given popular ovations that turned his head. He thought the
2mo i, 1:whole country was ready to join the French Republic in its contest with
2mo i, 1:England. Genet therefore attempted to use the American ports as the base
2mo i, 1:of operations for French privateers preying on British merchant ships;
2mo i, 1:and he insisted that the United States was in honor bound to help France
2mo i, 1:under the treaty of 1778.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Proclamation of Neutrality and the Jay Treaty.=--Unmoved by the
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:rising tide of popular sympathy for France, Washington took a firm
2mo i, 1:course. He received Genet coldly. The demand that the United States aid
2mo i, 1:France under the old treaty of alliance he answered by proclaiming the
2mo i, 1:neutrality of America and warning American citizens against hostile acts
2mo i, 1:toward either France or England. When Genet continued to hold meetings,
2mo i, 1:issue manifestoes, and stir up the people against England, Washington
2mo i, 1:asked the French government to recall him. This act he followed up by
2mo i, 1:sending the Chief Justice, John Jay, on a pacific mission to England.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The result was the celebrated Jay treaty of 1794. By its terms Great
2mo i, 1:Britain agreed to withdraw her troops from the western forts where they
2mo i, 1:had been since the war for independence and to grant certain slight
2mo i, 1:trade concessions. The chief sources of bitterness--the failure of the
2mo i, 1:British to return slaves carried off during the Revolution, the seizure
2mo i, 1:of American ships, and the impressment of sailors--were not touched,
2mo i, 1:much to the distress of everybody in America, including loyal
2mo i, 1:Federalists. Nevertheless, Washington, dreading an armed conflict with
2mo i, 1:England, urged the Senate to ratify the treaty. The weight of his
2mo i, 1:influence carried the day.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:At this, the hostility of the Anti-Federalists knew no bounds. Jefferson
2mo i, 1:declared the Jay treaty "an infamous act which is really nothing more
2mo i, 1:than an alliance between England and the Anglo-men of this country,
2mo i, 1:against the legislature and the people of the United States." Hamilton,
2mo i, 1:defending it with his usual courage, was stoned by a mob in New York and
2mo i, 1:driven from the platform with blood streaming from his face. Jay was
2mo i, 1:burned in effigy. Even Washington was not spared. The House of
2mo i, 1:Representatives was openly hostile. To display its feelings, it called
2mo i, 1:upon the President for the papers relative to the treaty negotiations,
2mo i, 1:only to be more highly incensed by his flat refusal to present them, on
2mo i, 1:the ground that the House did not share in the treaty-making power.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Washington Retires from Politics.=--Such angry contests confirmed the
2mo i, 1:President in his slowly maturing determination to retire at the end of
2mo i, 1:his second term in office. He did not believe that a third term was
2mo i, 1:unconstitutional or improper; but, worn out by his long and arduous
2mo i, 1:labors in war and in peace and wounded by harsh attacks from former
2mo i, 1:friends, he longed for the quiet of his beautiful estate at Mount
2mo i, 1:Vernon.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:In September, 1796, on the eve of the presidential election, Washington
2mo i, 1:issued his Farewell Address, another state paper to be treasured and
2mo i, 1:read by generations of Americans to come. In this address he directed
2mo i, 1:the attention of the people to three subjects of lasting interest. He
2mo i, 1:warned them against sectional jealousies. He remonstrated against the
2mo i, 1:spirit of partisanship, saying that in government "of the popular
2mo i, 1:character, in government purely elective, it is a spirit not to be
2mo i, 1:encouraged." He likewise cautioned the people against "the insidious
2mo i, 1:wiles of foreign influence," saying: "Europe has a set of primary
2mo i, 1:interests which to us have none or a very remote relation. Hence she
2mo i, 1:must be engaged in frequent controversies, the causes of which are
2mo i, 1:essentially foreign to our concerns. Hence, therefore, it would be
2mo i, 1:unwise in us to implicate ourselves, by artificial ties, in the ordinary
2mo i, 1:vicissitudes of her politics or the ordinary combinations and collisions
2mo i, 1:of her friendships or enmities.... Why forego the advantages of so
2mo i, 1:peculiar a situation?... It is our true policy to steer clear of
2mo i, 1:permanent alliances with any portion of the foreign world.... Taking
2mo i, 1:care always to keep ourselves, by suitable establishments, on a
2mo i, 1:respectable defensive posture, we may safely trust to temporary
2mo i, 1:alliances for extraordinary emergencies."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Campaign of 1796--Adams Elected.=--On hearing of the retirement of
2mo i, 1:Washington, the Anti-Federalists cast off all restraints. In honor of
2mo i, 1:France and in opposition to what they were pleased to call the
2mo i, 1:monarchical tendencies of the Federalists, they boldly assumed the name
2mo i, 1:"Republican"; the term "Democrat," then applied only to obscure and
2mo i, 1:despised radicals, had not come into general use. They selected
2mo i, 1:Jefferson as their candidate for President against John Adams, the
2mo i, 1:Federalist nominee, and carried on such a spirited campaign that they
2mo i, 1:came within four votes of electing him.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The successful candidate, Adams, was not fitted by training or opinion
2mo i, 1:for conciliating a determined opposition. He was a reserved and studious
2mo i, 1:man. He was neither a good speaker nor a skillful negotiator. In one of
2mo i, 1:his books he had declared himself in favor of "government by an
2mo i, 1:aristocracy of talents and wealth"--an offense which the Republicans
2mo i, 1:never forgave. While John Marshall found him "a sensible, plain, candid,
2mo i, 1:good-tempered man," Jefferson could see in him nothing but a "monocrat"
2mo i, 1:and "Anglo-man." Had it not been for the conduct of the French
2mo i, 1:government, Adams would hardly have enjoyed a moment's genuine
2mo i, 1:popularity during his administration.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Quarrel with France.=--The French Directory, the executive
2mo i, 1:department established under the constitution of 1795, managed, however,
2mo i, 1:to stir the anger of Republicans and Federalists alike. It regarded the
2mo i, 1:Jay treaty as a rebuke to France and a flagrant violation of obligations
2mo i, 1:solemnly registered in the treaty of 1778. Accordingly it refused to
2mo i, 1:receive the American minister, treated him in a humiliating way, and
2mo i, 1:finally told him to leave the country. Overlooking this affront in his
2mo i, 1:anxiety to maintain peace, Adams dispatched to France a commission of
2mo i, 1:eminent men with instructions to reach an understanding with the French
2mo i, 1:Republic. On their arrival, they were chagrined to find, instead of a
2mo i, 1:decent reception, an indirect demand for an apology respecting the past
2mo i, 1:conduct of the American government, a payment in cash, and an annual
2mo i, 1:tribute as the price of continued friendship. When the news of this
2mo i, 1:affair reached President Adams, he promptly laid it before Congress,
2mo i, 1:referring to the Frenchmen who had made the demands as "Mr. X, Mr. Y,
2mo i, 1:and Mr. Z."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:This insult, coupled with the fact that French privateers, like the
2mo i, 1:British, were preying upon American commerce, enraged even the
2mo i, 1:Republicans who had been loudest in the profession of their French
2mo i, 1:sympathies. They forgot their wrath over the Jay treaty and joined with
2mo i, 1:the Federalists in shouting: "Millions for defense, not a cent for
2mo i, 1:tribute!" Preparations for war were made on every hand. Washington was
2mo i, 1:once more called from Mount Vernon to take his old position at the head
2mo i, 1:of the army. Indeed, fighting actually began upon the high seas and went
2mo i, 1:on without a formal declaration of war until the year 1800. By that time
2mo i, 1:the Directory had been overthrown. A treaty was readily made with
2mo i, 1:Napoleon, the First Consul, who was beginning his remarkable career as
2mo i, 1:chief of the French Republic, soon to be turned into an empire.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Alien and Sedition Laws.=--Flushed with success, the Federalists
2mo i, 1:determined, if possible, to put an end to radical French influence in
2mo i, 1:America and to silence Republican opposition. They therefore passed two
2mo i, 1:drastic laws in the summer of 1798: the Alien and Sedition Acts.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The first of these measures empowered the President to expel from the
2mo i, 1:country or to imprison any alien whom he regarded as "dangerous" or "had
2mo i, 1:reasonable grounds to suspect" of "any treasonable or secret
2mo i, 1:machinations against the government."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The second of the measures, the Sedition Act, penalized not only those
2mo i, 1:who attempted to stir up unlawful combinations against the government
2mo i, 1:but also every one who wrote, uttered, or published "any false,
2mo i, 1:scandalous, and malicious writing ... against the government of the
2mo i, 1:United States or either House of Congress, or the President of the
2mo i, 1:United States, with intent to defame said government ... or to bring
2mo i, 1:them or either of them into contempt or disrepute." This measure was
2mo i, 1:hurried through Congress in spite of the opposition and the clear
2mo i, 1:provision in the Constitution that Congress shall make no law abridging
2mo i, 1:the freedom of speech or of the press. Even many Federalists feared the
2mo i, 1:consequences of the action. Hamilton was alarmed when he read the bill,
2mo i, 1:exclaiming: "Let us not establish a tyranny. Energy is a very different
2mo i, 1:thing from violence." John Marshall told his friends in Virginia that,
2mo i, 1:had he been in Congress, he would have opposed the two bills because he
2mo i, 1:thought them "useless" and "calculated to create unnecessary discontents
2mo i, 1:and jealousies."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The Alien law was not enforced; but it gave great offense to the Irish
2mo i, 1:and French whose activities against the American government's policy
2mo i, 1:respecting Great Britain put them in danger of prison. The Sedition law,
2mo i, 1:on the other hand, was vigorously applied. Several editors of Republican
2mo i, 1:newspapers soon found themselves in jail or broken by ruinous fines for
2mo i, 1:their caustic criticisms of the Federalist President and his policies.
2mo i, 1:Bystanders at political meetings, who uttered sentiments which, though
2mo i, 1:ungenerous and severe, seem harmless enough now, were hurried before
2mo i, 1:Federalist judges and promptly fined and imprisoned. Although the
2mo i, 1:prosecutions were not numerous, they aroused a keen resentment. The
2mo i, 1:Republicans were convinced that their political opponents, having
2mo i, 1:saddled upon the country Hamilton's fiscal system and the British
2mo i, 1:treaty, were bent on silencing all censure. The measures therefore had
2mo i, 1:exactly the opposite effect from that which their authors intended.
2mo i, 1:Instead of helping the Federalist party, they made criticism of it more
2mo i, 1:bitter than ever.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Kentucky and Virginia Resolutions.=--Jefferson was quick to take
2mo i, 1:advantage of the discontent. He drafted a set of resolutions declaring
2mo i, 1:the Sedition law null and void, as violating the federal Constitution.
2mo i, 1:His resolutions were passed by the Kentucky legislature late in 1798,
2mo i, 1:signed by the governor, and transmitted to the other states for their
2mo i, 1:consideration. Though receiving unfavorable replies from a number of
2mo i, 1:Northern states, Kentucky the following year reaffirmed its position and
2mo i, 1:declared that the nullification of all unconstitutional acts of Congress
2mo i, 1:was the rightful remedy to be used by the states in the redress of
2mo i, 1:grievances. It thus defied the federal government and announced a
2mo i, 1:doctrine hostile to nationality and fraught with terrible meaning for
2mo i, 1:the future. In the neighboring state of Virginia, Madison led a movement
2mo i, 1:against the Alien and Sedition laws. He induced the legislature to pass
2mo i, 1:resolutions condemning the acts as unconstitutional and calling upon the
2mo i, 1:other states to take proper means to preserve their rights and the
2mo i, 1:rights of the people.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Republican Triumph in 1800.=--Thus the way was prepared for the
2mo i, 1:election of 1800. The Republicans left no stone unturned in their
2mo i, 1:efforts to place on the Federalist candidate, President Adams, all the
2mo i, 1:odium of the Alien and Sedition laws, in addition to responsibility for
2mo i, 1:approving Hamilton's measures and policies. The Federalists, divided in
2mo i, 1:councils and cold in their affection for Adams, made a poor campaign.
2mo i, 1:They tried to discredit their opponents with epithets of "Jacobins" and
2mo i, 1:"Anarchists"--terms which had been weakened by excessive use. When the
2mo i, 1:vote was counted, it was found that Adams had been defeated; while the
2mo i, 1:Republicans had carried the entire South and New York also and secured
2mo i, 1:eight of the fifteen electoral votes cast by Pennsylvania. "Our beloved
2mo i, 1:Adams will now close his bright career," lamented a Federalist
2mo i, 1:newspaper. "Sons of faction, demagogues and high priests of anarchy, now
2mo i, 1:you have cause to triumph!"
2mo i, 1:
