2mo i, 1:REPRESENTATIVES]
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Jefferson's election, however, was still uncertain. By a curious
2mo i, 1:provision in the Constitution, presidential electors were required to
2mo i, 1:vote for two persons without indicating which office each was to fill,
2mo i, 1:the one receiving the highest number of votes to be President and the
2mo i, 1:candidate standing next to be Vice President. It so happened that Aaron
2mo i, 1:Burr, the Republican candidate for Vice President, had received the same
2mo i, 1:number of votes as Jefferson; as neither had a majority the election was
2mo i, 1:thrown into the House of Representatives, where the Federalists held the
2mo i, 1:balance of power. Although it was well known that Burr was not even a
2mo i, 1:candidate for President, his friends and many Federalists began
2mo i, 1:intriguing for his election to that high office. Had it not been for the
2mo i, 1:vigorous action of Hamilton the prize might have been snatched out of
2mo i, 1:Jefferson's hands. Not until the thirty-sixth ballot on February 17,
2mo i, 1:1801, was the great issue decided in his favor.[2]
