2mo i, 1:CHAPTER IX
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:THE JEFFERSONIAN REPUBLICANS IN POWER
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:REPUBLICAN PRINCIPLES AND POLICIES
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Opposition to Strong Central Government.=--Cherishing especially the
2mo i, 1:agricultural interest, as Jefferson said, the Republicans were in the
2mo i, 1:beginning provincial in their concern and outlook. Their attachment to
2mo i, 1:America was, certainly, as strong as that of Hamilton; but they regarded
2mo i, 1:the state, rather than the national government, as the proper center of
2mo i, 1:power and affection. Indeed, a large part of the rank and file had been
2mo i, 1:among the opponents of the Constitution in the days of its adoption.
2mo i, 1:Jefferson had entertained doubts about it and Monroe, destined to be the
2mo i, 1:fifth President, had been one of the bitter foes of ratification. The
2mo i, 1:former went so far in the direction of local autonomy that he exalted
2mo i, 1:the state above the nation in the Kentucky resolutions of 1798,
2mo i, 1:declaring the Constitution to be a mere compact and the states competent
2mo i, 1:to interpret and nullify federal law. This was provincialism with a
2mo i, 1:vengeance. "It is jealousy, not confidence, which prescribes limited
2mo i, 1:constitutions," wrote Jefferson for the Kentucky legislature. Jealousy
2mo i, 1:of the national government, not confidence in it--this is the ideal that
2mo i, 1:reflected the provincial and agricultural interest.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Republican Simplicity.=--Every act of the Jeffersonian party during its
2mo i, 1:early days of power was in accord with the ideals of government which it
2mo i, 1:professed. It had opposed all pomp and ceremony, calculated to give
2mo i, 1:weight and dignity to the chief executive of the nation, as symbols of
2mo i, 1:monarchy and high prerogative. Appropriately, therefore, Jefferson's
2mo i, 1:inauguration on March 4, 1801, the first at the new capital at
2mo i, 1:Washington, was marked by extreme simplicity. In keeping with this
2mo i, 1:procedure he quit the practice, followed by Washington and Adams, of
2mo i, 1:reading presidential addresses to Congress in joint assembly and adopted
2mo i, 1:in its stead the plan of sending his messages in writing--a custom that
2mo i, 1:was continued unbroken until 1913 when President Wilson returned to the
2mo i, 1:example set by the first chief magistrate.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Republican Measures.=--The Republicans had complained of a great
2mo i, 1:national debt as the source of a dangerous "money power," giving
2mo i, 1:strength to the federal government; accordingly they began to pay it off
2mo i, 1:as rapidly as possible. They had held commerce in low esteem and looked
2mo i, 1:upon a large navy as a mere device to protect it; consequently they
2mo i, 1:reduced the number of warships. They had objected to excise taxes,
2mo i, 1:particularly on whisky; these they quickly abolished, to the intense
2mo i, 1:satisfaction of the farmers. They had protested against the heavy cost
2mo i, 1:of the federal government; they reduced expenses by discharging hundreds
2mo i, 1:of men from the army and abolishing many offices.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:They had savagely criticized the Sedition law and Jefferson refused to
2mo i, 1:enforce it. They had been deeply offended by the assault on freedom of
2mo i, 1:speech and press and they promptly impeached Samuel Chase, a justice of
2mo i, 1:the Supreme Court, who had been especially severe in his attacks upon
2mo i, 1:offenders under the Sedition Act. Their failure to convict Justice Chase
2mo i, 1:by a narrow margin was due to no lack of zeal on their part but to the
2mo i, 1:Federalist strength in the Senate where the trial was held. They had
2mo i, 1:regarded the appointment of a large number of federal judges during the
2mo i, 1:last hours of Adams' administration as an attempt to intrench
2mo i, 1:Federalists in the judiciary and to enlarge the sphere of the national
2mo i, 1:government. Accordingly, they at once repealed the act creating the new
2mo i, 1:judgeships, thus depriving the "midnight appointees" of their posts.
2mo i, 1:They had considered the federal offices, civil and military, as sources
2mo i, 1:of great strength to the Federalists and Jefferson, though committed to
2mo i, 1:the principle that offices should be open to all and distributed
2mo i, 1:according to merit, was careful to fill most of the vacancies as they
2mo i, 1:occurred with trusted Republicans. To his credit, however, it must be
2mo i, 1:said that he did not make wholesale removals to find room for party
2mo i, 1:workers.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The Republicans thus hewed to the line of their general policy of
2mo i, 1:restricting the weight, dignity, and activity of the national
2mo i, 1:government. Yet there were no Republicans, as the Federalists asserted,
2mo i, 1:prepared to urge serious modifications in the Constitution. "If there be
2mo i, 1:any among us who wish to dissolve this union or to change its republican
2mo i, 1:form," wrote Jefferson in his first inaugural, "let them stand
2mo i, 1:undisturbed as monuments of the safety with which error of opinion may
2mo i, 1:be tolerated where reason is left free to combat it." After reciting the
2mo i, 1:fortunate circumstances of climate, soil, and isolation which made the
2mo i, 1:future of America so full of promise, Jefferson concluded: "A wise and
2mo i, 1:frugal government which shall restrain men from injuring one another,
2mo i, 1:shall leave them otherwise free to regulate their own pursuits of
2mo i, 1:industry and improvement and shall not take from the mouth of labour the
2mo i, 1:bread it has earned. This is the sum of good government; and this is
2mo i, 1:necessary to close the circle of our felicities."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:In all this the Republicans had not reckoned with destiny. In a few
2mo i, 1:short years that lay ahead it was their fate to double the territory of
2mo i, 1:the country, making inevitable a continental nation; to give the
2mo i, 1:Constitution a generous interpretation that shocked many a Federalist;
2mo i, 1:to wage war on behalf of American commerce; to reestablish the hated
2mo i, 1:United States Bank; to enact a high protective tariff; to see their
2mo i, 1:Federalist opponents in their turn discredited as nullifiers and
2mo i, 1:provincials; to announce high national doctrines in foreign affairs; and
2mo i, 1:to behold the Constitution exalted and defended against the pretensions
2mo i, 1:of states by a son of old Virginia, John Marshall, Chief Justice of the
2mo i, 1:Supreme Court of the United States.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:THE REPUBLICANS AND THE GREAT WEST
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Expansion and Land Hunger.=--The first of the great measures which
2mo i, 1:drove the Republicans out upon this new national course--the purchase
2mo i, 1:of the Louisiana territory--was the product of circumstances rather than
2mo i, 1:of their deliberate choosing. It was not the lack of land for his
2mo i, 1:cherished farmers that led Jefferson to add such an immense domain to
2mo i, 1:the original possessions of the United States. In the Northwest
2mo i, 1:territory, now embracing Ohio, Indiana, Illinois, Michigan, Wisconsin,
2mo i, 1:and a portion of Minnesota, settlements were mainly confined to the
2mo i, 1:north bank of the Ohio River. To the south, in Kentucky and Tennessee,
2mo i, 1:where there were more than one hundred thousand white people who had
2mo i, 1:pushed over the mountains from Virginia and the Carolinas, there were
2mo i, 1:still wide reaches of untilled soil. The Alabama and Mississippi regions
2mo i, 1:were vast Indian frontiers of the state of Georgia, unsettled and almost
2mo i, 1:unexplored. Even to the wildest imagination there seemed to be territory
2mo i, 1:enough to satisfy the land hunger of the American people for a century
2mo i, 1:to come.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Significance of the Mississippi River.=--At all events the East,
2mo i, 1:then the center of power, saw no good reason for expansion. The planters
2mo i, 1:of the Carolinas, the manufacturers of Pennsylvania, the importers of
2mo i, 1:New York, the shipbuilders of New England, looking to the seaboard and
2mo i, 1:to Europe for trade, refinements, and sometimes their ideas of
2mo i, 1:government, were slow to appreciate the place of the West in national
2mo i, 1:economy. The better educated the Easterners were, the less, it seems,
2mo i, 1:they comprehended the destiny of the nation. Sons of Federalist fathers
2mo i, 1:at Williams College, after a long debate decided by a vote of fifteen to
2mo i, 1:one that the purchase of Louisiana was undesirable.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:On the other hand, the pioneers of Kentucky, Ohio, and Tennessee,
2mo i, 1:unlearned in books, saw with their own eyes the resources of the
2mo i, 1:wilderness. Many of them had been across the Mississippi and had beheld
2mo i, 1:the rich lands awaiting the plow of the white man. Down the great river
2mo i, 1:they floated their wheat, corn, and bacon to ocean-going ships bound for
2mo i, 1:the ports of the seaboard or for Europe. The land journeys over the
2mo i, 1:mountain barriers with bulky farm produce, they knew from experience,
2mo i, 1:were almost impossible, and costly at best. Nails, bolts of cloth, tea,
2mo i, 1:and coffee could go or come that way, but not corn and bacon. A free
2mo i, 1:outlet to the sea by the Mississippi was as essential to the pioneers of
2mo i, 1:the Kentucky region as the harbor of Boston to the merchant princes of
2mo i, 1:that metropolis.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Louisiana under Spanish Rule.=--For this reason they watched with deep
2mo i, 1:solicitude the fortunes of the Spanish king to whom, at the close of the
2mo i, 1:Seven Years' War, had fallen the Louisiana territory stretching from New
2mo i, 1:Orleans to the Rocky Mountains. While he controlled the mouth of the
2mo i, 1:Mississippi there was little to fear, for he had neither the army nor
2mo i, 1:the navy necessary to resist any invasion of American trade. Moreover,
2mo i, 1:Washington had been able, by the exercise of great tact, to secure from
2mo i, 1:Spain in 1795 a trading privilege through New Orleans which satisfied
2mo i, 1:the present requirements of the frontiersmen even if it did not allay
2mo i, 1:their fears for the future. So things stood when a swift succession of
2mo i, 1:events altered the whole situation.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Louisiana Transferred to France.=--In July, 1802, a royal order from
2mo i, 1:Spain instructed the officials at New Orleans to close the port to
2mo i, 1:American produce. About the same time a disturbing rumor, long current,
2mo i, 1:was confirmed--Napoleon had coerced Spain into returning Louisiana to
2mo i, 1:France by a secret treaty signed in 1800. "The scalers of the Alps and
2mo i, 1:conquerors of Venice" now looked across the sea for new scenes of
2mo i, 1:adventure. The West was ablaze with excitement. A call for war ran
2mo i, 1:through the frontier; expeditions were organized to prevent the landing
2mo i, 1:of the French; and petitions for instant action flooded in upon
2mo i, 1:Jefferson.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Jefferson Sees the Danger.=--Jefferson, the friend of France and sworn
2mo i, 1:enemy of England, compelled to choose in the interest of America, never
2mo i, 1:winced. "The cession of Louisiana and the Floridas by Spain to France,"
2mo i, 1:he wrote to Livingston, the American minister in Paris, "works sorely on
2mo i, 1:the United States. It completely reverses all the political relations of
2mo i, 1:the United States and will form a new epoch in our political course....
2mo i, 1:There is on the globe one single spot, the possessor of which is our
2mo i, 1:natural and habitual enemy. It is New Orleans through which the produce
2mo i, 1:of three-eighths of our territory must pass to market.... France,
2mo i, 1:placing herself in that door, assumes to us an attitude of defiance.
2mo i, 1:Spain might have retained it quietly for years. Her pacific
2mo i, 1:dispositions, her feeble state would induce her to increase our
2mo i, 1:facilities there.... Not so can it ever be in the hands of France....
2mo i, 1:The day that France takes possession of New Orleans fixes the sentence
2mo i, 1:which is to restrain her forever within her low water mark.... It seals
2mo i, 1:the union of the two nations who in conjunction can maintain exclusive
2mo i, 1:possession of the ocean. From that moment we must marry ourselves to the
2mo i, 1:British fleet and nation.... This is not a state of things we seek or
2mo i, 1:desire. It is one which this measure, if adopted by France, forces on us
2mo i, 1:as necessarily as any other cause by the laws of nature brings on its
2mo i, 1:necessary effect."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Louisiana Purchased.=--Acting on this belief, but apparently seeing
2mo i, 1:only the Mississippi outlet at stake, Jefferson sent his friend, James
2mo i, 1:Monroe, to France with the power to buy New Orleans and West Florida.
2mo i, 1:Before Monroe arrived, the regular minister, Livingston, had already
2mo i, 1:convinced Napoleon that it would be well to sell territory which might
2mo i, 1:be wrested from him at any moment by the British sea power, especially
2mo i, 1:as the war, temporarily stopped by the peace of Amiens, was once more
2mo i, 1:raging in Europe. Wise as he was in his day, Livingston had at first no
2mo i, 1:thought of buying the whole Louisiana country. He was simply dazed when
2mo i, 1:Napoleon offered to sell the entire domain and get rid of the business
2mo i, 1:altogether. Though staggered by the proposal, he and Monroe decided to
2mo i, 1:accept. On April 30, they signed the treaty of cession, agreeing to pay
2mo i, 1:$11,250,000 in six per cent bonds and to discharge certain debts due
2mo i, 1:French citizens, making in all approximately fifteen millions. Spain
2mo i, 1:protested, Napoleon's brother fumed, French newspapers objected; but the
2mo i, 1:deed was done.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Jefferson and His Constitutional Scruples.=--When the news of this
2mo i, 1:extraordinary event reached the United States, the people were filled
2mo i, 1:with astonishment, and no one was more surprised than Jefferson himself.
2mo i, 1:He had thought of buying New Orleans and West Florida for a small sum,
2mo i, 1:and now a vast domain had been dumped into the lap of the nation. He was
2mo i, 1:puzzled. On looking into the Constitution he found not a line
2mo i, 1:authorizing the purchase of more territory and so he drafted an
2mo i, 1:amendment declaring "Louisiana, as ceded by France,--a part of the
2mo i, 1:United States." He had belabored the Federalists for piling up a big
2mo i, 1:national debt and he could hardly endure the thought of issuing more
2mo i, 1:bonds himself.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:In the midst of his doubts came the news that Napoleon might withdraw
2mo i, 1:from the bargain. Thoroughly alarmed by that, Jefferson pressed the
2mo i, 1:Senate for a ratification of the treaty. He still clung to his original
2mo i, 1:idea that the Constitution did not warrant the purchase; but he lamely
2mo i, 1:concluded: "If our friends shall think differently, I shall certainly
2mo i, 1:acquiesce with satisfaction; confident that the good sense of our
2mo i, 1:country will correct the evil of construction when it shall produce ill
2mo i, 1:effects." Thus the stanch advocate of "strict interpretation" cut loose
2mo i, 1:from his own doctrine and intrusted the construction of the Constitution
2mo i, 1:to "the good sense" of his countrymen.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Treaty Ratified.=--This unusual transaction, so favorable to the
2mo i, 1:West, aroused the ire of the seaboard Federalists. Some denounced it as
2mo i, 1:unconstitutional, easily forgetting Hamilton's masterly defense of the
2mo i, 1:bank, also not mentioned in the Constitution. Others urged that, if "the
2mo i, 1:howling wilderness" ever should be settled, it would turn against the
2mo i, 1:East, form new commercial connections, and escape from federal control.
2mo i, 1:Still others protested that the purchase would lead inevitably to the
2mo i, 1:dominance of a "hotch potch of wild men from the Far West." Federalists,
2mo i, 1:who thought "the broad back of America" could readily bear Hamilton's
2mo i, 1:consolidated debt, now went into agonies over a bond issue of less than
2mo i, 1:one-sixth of that amount. But in vain. Jefferson's party with a high
2mo i, 1:hand carried the day. The Senate, after hearing the Federalist protest,
2mo i, 1:ratified the treaty. In December, 1803, the French flag was hauled down
2mo i, 1:from the old government buildings in New Orleans and the Stars and
2mo i, 1:Stripes were hoisted as a sign that the land of Coronado, De Soto,
2mo i, 1:Marquette, and La Salle had passed forever to the United States.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:[Illustration: THE UNITED STATES IN 1805]
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:By a single stroke, the original territory of the United States was more
2mo i, 1:than doubled. While the boundaries of the purchase were uncertain, it is
2mo i, 1:safe to say that the Louisiana territory included what is now Arkansas,
2mo i, 1:Missouri, Iowa, Oklahoma, Kansas, Nebraska, South Dakota, and large
2mo i, 1:portions of Louisiana, Minnesota, North Dakota, Colorado, Montana, and
2mo i, 1:Wyoming. The farm lands that the friends of "a little America" on the
2mo i, 1:seacoast declared a hopeless wilderness were, within a hundred years,
2mo i, 1:fully occupied and valued at nearly seven billion dollars--almost five
2mo i, 1:hundred times the price paid to Napoleon.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Western Explorations.=--Having taken the fateful step, Jefferson wisely
2mo i, 1:began to make the most of it. He prepared for the opening of the new
2mo i, 1:country by sending the Lewis and Clark expedition to explore it,
2mo i, 1:discover its resources, and lay out an overland route through the
2mo i, 1:Missouri Valley and across the Great Divide to the Pacific. The story of
2mo i, 1:this mighty exploit, which began in the spring of 1804 and ended in the
2mo i, 1:autumn of 1806, was set down with skill and pains in the journal of
2mo i, 1:Lewis and Clark; when published even in a short form, it invited the
2mo i, 1:forward-looking men of the East to take thought about the western
2mo i, 1:empire. At the same time Zebulon Pike, in a series of journeys, explored
2mo i, 1:the sources of the Mississippi River and penetrated the Spanish
2mo i, 1:territories of the far Southwest. Thus scouts and pioneers continued the
2mo i, 1:work of diplomats.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:THE REPUBLICAN WAR FOR COMMERCIAL INDEPENDENCE
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The English and French Blockades.=--In addition to bringing Louisiana
2mo i, 1:to the United States, the reopening of the European War in 1803, after a
2mo i, 1:short lull, renewed in an acute form the commercial difficulties that
2mo i, 1:had plagued the country all during the administrations of Washington and
2mo i, 1:Adams. The Republicans were now plunged into the hornets' nest. The
2mo i, 1:party whose ardent spirits had burned Jay in effigy, stoned Hamilton for
2mo i, 1:defending his treaty, jeered Washington's proclamation of neutrality,
2mo i, 1:and spoken bitterly of "timid traders," could no longer take refuge in
2mo i, 1:criticism. It had to act.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Its troubles took a serious turn in 1806. England, in a determined
2mo i, 1:effort to bring France to her knees by starvation, declared the coast of
2mo i, 1:Europe blockaded from Brest to the mouth of the Elbe River. Napoleon
2mo i, 1:retaliated by his Berlin Decree of November, 1806, blockading the
2mo i, 1:British Isles--a measure terrifying to American ship owners whose
2mo i, 1:vessels were liable to seizure by any French rover, though Napoleon had
2mo i, 1:no navy to make good his proclamation. Great Britain countered with a
2mo i, 1:still more irritating decree--the Orders in Council of 1807. It modified
2mo i, 1:its blockade, but in so doing merely authorized American ships not
2mo i, 1:carrying munitions of war to complete their voyage to the Continent, on
2mo i, 1:condition of their stopping at a British port, securing a license, and
2mo i, 1:paying a tax. This, responded Napoleon, was the height of insolence, and
2mo i, 1:he denounced it as a gross violation of international law. He then
2mo i, 1:closed the circle of American troubles by issuing his Milan Decree of
2mo i, 1:December, 1807. This order declared that any ship which complied with
2mo i, 1:the British rules would be subject to seizure and confiscation by French
2mo i, 1:authorities.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Impressment of Seamen.=--That was not all. Great Britain, in dire
2mo i, 1:need of men for her navy, adopted the practice of stopping American
2mo i, 1:ships, searching them, and carrying away British-born sailors found on
2mo i, 1:board. British sailors were so badly treated, so cruelly flogged for
2mo i, 1:trivial causes, and so meanly fed that they fled in crowds to the
2mo i, 1:American marine. In many cases it was difficult to tell whether seamen
2mo i, 1:were English or American. They spoke the same language, so that language
2mo i, 1:was no test. Rovers on the deep and stragglers in the ports of both
2mo i, 1:countries, they frequently had no papers to show their nativity.
2mo i, 1:Moreover, Great Britain held to the old rule--"Once an Englishman,
2mo i, 1:always an Englishman"--a doctrine rejected by the United States in
2mo i, 1:favor of the principle that a man could choose the nation to which he
2mo i, 1:would give allegiance. British sea captains, sometimes by mistake, and
2mo i, 1:often enough with reckless indifference, carried away into servitude in
2mo i, 1:their own navy genuine American citizens. The process itself, even when
2mo i, 1:executed with all the civilities of law, was painful enough, for it
2mo i, 1:meant that American ships were forced to "come to," and compelled to
2mo i, 1:rest submissively under British guns until the searching party had pried
2mo i, 1:into records, questioned seamen, seized and handcuffed victims. Saints
2mo i, 1:could not have done this work without raising angry passions, and only
2mo i, 1:saints could have endured it with patience and fortitude.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Had the enactment of the scenes been confined to the high seas and
2mo i, 1:knowledge of them to rumors and newspaper stories, American resentment
2mo i, 1:might not have been so intense; but many a search and seizure was made
2mo i, 1:in sight of land. British and French vessels patrolled the coasts,
2mo i, 1:firing on one another and chasing one another in American waters within
2mo i, 1:the three-mile limit. When, in the summer of 1807, the American frigate
2mo i, 1:_Chesapeake_ refused to surrender men alleged to be deserters from King
2mo i, 1:George's navy, the British warship _Leopard_ opened fire, killing three
2mo i, 1:men and wounding eighteen more--an act which even the British ministry
2mo i, 1:could hardly excuse. If the French were less frequently the offenders,
2mo i, 1:it was not because of their tenderness about American rights but because
2mo i, 1:so few of their ships escaped the hawk-eyed British navy to operate in
2mo i, 1:American waters.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Losses in American Commerce.=--This high-handed conduct on the part
2mo i, 1:of European belligerents was very injurious to American trade. By their
2mo i, 1:enterprise, American shippers had become the foremost carriers on the
2mo i, 1:Atlantic Ocean. In a decade they had doubled the tonnage of American
2mo i, 1:merchant ships under the American flag, taking the place of the French
2mo i, 1:marine when Britain swept that from the seas, and supplying Britain with
2mo i, 1:the sinews of war for the contest with the Napoleonic empire. The
2mo i, 1:American shipping engaged in foreign trade embraced 363,110 tons in
2mo i, 1:1791; 669,921 tons in 1800; and almost 1,000,000 tons in 1810. Such was
2mo i, 1:the enterprise attacked by the British and French decrees. American
2mo i, 1:ships bound for Great Britain were liable to be captured by French
2mo i, 1:privateers which, in spite of the disasters of the Nile and Trafalgar,
2mo i, 1:ranged the seas. American ships destined for the Continent, if they
2mo i, 1:failed to stop at British ports and pay tribute, were in great danger of
2mo i, 1:capture by the sleepless British navy and its swarm of auxiliaries.
2mo i, 1:American sea captains who, in fear of British vengeance, heeded the
2mo i, 1:Orders in Council and paid the tax were almost certain to fall a prey to
2mo i, 1:French vengeance, for the French were vigorous in executing the Milan
2mo i, 1:Decree.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Jefferson's Policy.=--The President's dilemma was distressing. Both the
2mo i, 1:belligerents in Europe were guilty of depredations on American commerce.
2mo i, 1:War on both of them was out of the question. War on France was
2mo i, 1:impossible because she had no territory on this side of the water which
2mo i, 1:could be reached by American troops and her naval forces had been
2mo i, 1:shattered at the battles of the Nile and Trafalgar. War on Great
2mo i, 1:Britain, a power which Jefferson's followers feared and distrusted, was
2mo i, 1:possible but not inviting. Jefferson shrank from it. A man of peace, he
2mo i, 1:disliked war's brazen clamor; a man of kindly spirit, he was startled at
2mo i, 1:the death and destruction which it brought in its train. So for the
2mo i, 1:eight years Jefferson steered an even course, suggesting measure after
2mo i, 1:measure with a view to avoiding bloodshed. He sent, it is true,
2mo i, 1:Commodore Preble in 1803 to punish Mediterranean pirates preying upon
2mo i, 1:American commerce; but a great war he evaded with passionate
2mo i, 1:earnestness, trying in its place every other expedient to protect
2mo i, 1:American rights.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Embargo and Non-intercourse Acts.=--In 1806, Congress passed and
2mo i, 1:Jefferson approved a non-importation act closing American ports to
2mo i, 1:certain products from British dominions--a measure intended as a club
2mo i, 1:over the British government's head. This law, failing in its purpose,
2mo i, 1:Jefferson proposed and Congress adopted in December, 1807, the Embargo
2mo i, 1:Act forbidding all vessels to leave American harbors for foreign ports.
2mo i, 1:France and England were to be brought to terms by cutting off their
2mo i, 1:supplies.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The result of the embargo was pathetic. England and France refused to
2mo i, 1:give up search and seizure. American ship owners who, lured by huge
2mo i, 1:profits, had formerly been willing to take the risk were now restrained
2mo i, 1:by law to their home ports. Every section suffered. The South and West
2mo i, 1:found their markets for cotton, rice, tobacco, corn, and bacon
2mo i, 1:curtailed. Thus they learned by bitter experience the national
2mo i, 1:significance of commerce. Ship masters, ship builders, longshoremen, and
2mo i, 1:sailors were thrown out of employment while the prices of foreign goods
2mo i, 1:doubled. Those who obeyed the law were ruined; violators of the law
2mo i, 1:smuggled goods into Canada and Florida for shipment abroad.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Jefferson's friends accepted the medicine with a wry face as the only
2mo i, 1:alternative to supine submission or open war. His opponents, without
2mo i, 1:offering any solution of their own, denounced it as a contemptible plan
2mo i, 1:that brought neither relief nor honor. Beset by the clamor that arose on
2mo i, 1:all sides, Congress, in the closing days of Jefferson's administration,
2mo i, 1:repealed the Embargo law and substituted a Non-intercourse act
2mo i, 1:forbidding trade with England and France while permitting it with other
2mo i, 1:countries--a measure equally futile in staying the depredations on
2mo i, 1:American shipping.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Jefferson Retires in Favor of Madison.=--Jefferson, exhausted by
2mo i, 1:endless wrangling and wounded, as Washington had been, by savage
2mo i, 1:criticism, welcomed March 4, 1809. His friends urged him to "stay by the
2mo i, 1:ship" and accept a third term. He declined, saying that election for
2mo i, 1:life might result from repeated reelection. In following Washington's
2mo i, 1:course and defending it on principle, he set an example to all his
2mo i, 1:successors, making the "third term doctrine" a part of American
2mo i, 1:unwritten law.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:His intimate friend, James Madison, to whom he turned over the burdens
2mo i, 1:of his high office was, like himself, a man of peace. Madison had been a
2mo i, 1:leader since the days of the Revolution, but in legislative halls and
2mo i, 1:council chambers, not on the field of battle. Small in stature,
2mo i, 1:sensitive in feelings, studious in habits, he was no man for the rough
2mo i, 1:and tumble of practical politics. He had taken a prominent and
2mo i, 1:distinguished part in the framing and the adoption of the Constitution.
2mo i, 1:He had served in the first Congress as a friend of Hamilton's measures.
2mo i, 1:Later he attached himself to Jefferson's fortunes and served for eight
2mo i, 1:years as his first counselor, the Secretary of State. The principles of
2mo i, 1:the Constitution, which he had helped to make and interpret, he was now
2mo i, 1:as President called upon to apply in one of the most perplexing moments
2mo i, 1:in all American history. In keeping with his own traditions and
2mo i, 1:following in the footsteps of Jefferson, he vainly tried to solve the
2mo i, 1:foreign problem by negotiation.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Trend of Events.=--Whatever difficulties Madison had in making up
2mo i, 1:his mind on war and peace were settled by events beyond his own control.
2mo i, 1:In the spring of 1811, a British frigate held up an American ship near
2mo i, 1:the harbor of New York and impressed a seaman alleged to be an American
2mo i, 1:citizen. Burning with resentment, the captain of the _President_, an
2mo i, 1:American warship, acting under orders, poured several broadsides into
2mo i, 1:the _Little Belt_, a British sloop, suspected of being the guilty party.
2mo i, 1:The British also encouraged the Indian chief Tecumseh, who welded
2mo i, 1:together the Indians of the Northwest under British protection and gave
2mo i, 1:signs of restlessness presaging a revolt. This sent a note of alarm
2mo i, 1:along the frontier that was not checked even when, in November,
2mo i, 1:Tecumseh's men were badly beaten at Tippecanoe by William Henry
2mo i, 1:Harrison. The Indians stood in the way of the advancing frontier, and it
2mo i, 1:seemed to the pioneers that, without support from the British in Canada,
2mo i, 1:the Red Men would soon be subdued.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Clay and Calhoun.=--While events were moving swiftly and rumors were
2mo i, 1:flying thick and fast, the mastery of the government passed from the
2mo i, 1:uncertain hands of Madison to a party of ardent young men in Congress,
2mo i, 1:dubbed "Young Republicans," under the leadership of two members destined
2mo i, 1:to be mighty figures in American history: Henry Clay of Kentucky and
2mo i, 1:John C. Calhoun of South Carolina. The former contended, in a flair of
2mo i, 1:folly, that "the militia of Kentucky alone are competent to place
2mo i, 1:Montreal and Upper Canada at your feet." The latter with a light heart
2mo i, 1:spoke of conquering Canada in a four weeks' campaign. "It must not be
2mo i, 1:inferred," says Channing, "that in advocating conquest, the Westerners
2mo i, 1:were actuated merely by desire for land; they welcomed war because they
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:thought it would be the easiest way to abate Indian troubles. The
2mo i, 1:savages were supported by the fur-trading interests that centred at
2mo i, 1:Quebec and London.... The Southerners on their part wished for Florida
2mo i, 1:and they thought that the conquest of Canada would obviate some Northern
2mo i, 1:opposition to this acquisition of slave territory." While Clay and
2mo i, 1:Calhoun, spokesmen of the West and South, were not unmindful of what
2mo i, 1:Napoleon had done to American commerce, they knew that their followers
2mo i, 1:still remembered with deep gratitude the aid of the French in the war
2mo i, 1:for independence and that the embers of the old hatred for George III,
2mo i, 1:still on the throne, could be readily blown into flame.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Madison Accepts War as Inevitable.=--The conduct of the British
2mo i, 1:ministers with whom Madison had to deal did little to encourage him in
2mo i, 1:adhering to the policy of "watchful waiting." One of them, a high Tory,
2mo i, 1:believed that all Americans were alike "except that a few are less
2mo i, 1:knaves than others" and his methods were colored by his belief. On the
2mo i, 1:recall of this minister the British government selected another no less
2mo i, 1:high and mighty in his principles and opinions. So Madison became
2mo i, 1:thoroughly discouraged about the outcome of pacific measures. When the
2mo i, 1:pressure from Congress upon him became too heavy, he gave way, signing
2mo i, 1:on June 18, 1812, the declaration of war on Great Britain. In
2mo i, 1:proclaiming hostilities, the administration set forth the causes which
2mo i, 1:justified the declaration; namely, the British had been encouraging the
2mo i, 1:Indians to attack American citizens on the frontier; they had ruined
2mo i, 1:American trade by blockades; they had insulted the American flag by
2mo i, 1:stopping and searching our ships; they had illegally seized American
2mo i, 1:sailors and driven them into the British navy.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Course of the War.=--The war lasted for nearly three years without
2mo i, 1:bringing victory to either side. The surrender of Detroit by General
2mo i, 1:Hull to the British and the failure of the American invasion of Canada
2mo i, 1:were offset by Perry's victory on Lake Erie and a decisive blow
2mo i, 1:administered to British designs for an invasion of New York by way of
2mo i, 1:Plattsburgh. The triumph of Jackson at New Orleans helped to atone for
2mo i, 1:the humiliation suffered in the burning of the Capitol by the British.
2mo i, 1:The stirring deeds of the _Constitution_, the _United States_, and the
2mo i, 1:_Argus_ on the seas, the heroic death of Lawrence and the victories of a
2mo i, 1:hundred privateers furnished consolation for those who suffered from the
2mo i, 1:iron blockade finally established by the British government when it came
2mo i, 1:to appreciate the gravity of the situation. While men love the annals of
2mo i, 1:the sea, they will turn to the running battles, the narrow escapes, and
2mo i, 1:the reckless daring of American sailors in that naval contest with Great
2mo i, 1:Britain.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:All this was exciting but it was inconclusive. In fact, never was a
2mo i, 1:government less prepared than was that of the United States in 1812. It
2mo i, 1:had neither the disciplined troops, the ships of war, nor the supplies
2mo i, 1:required by the magnitude of the military task. It was fortune that
2mo i, 1:favored the American cause. Great Britain, harassed, worn, and
2mo i, 1:financially embarrassed by nearly twenty years of fighting in Europe,
2mo i, 1:was in no mood to gather her forces for a titanic effort in America even
2mo i, 1:after Napoleon was overthrown and sent into exile at Elba in the spring
2mo i, 1:of 1814. War clouds still hung on the European horizon and the conflict
2mo i, 1:temporarily halted did again break out. To be rid of American anxieties
2mo i, 1:and free for European eventualities, England was ready to settle with
2mo i, 1:the United States, especially as that could be done without conceding
2mo i, 1:anything or surrendering any claims.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Treaty of Peace.=--Both countries were in truth sick of a war that
2mo i, 1:offered neither glory nor profit. Having indulged in the usual
2mo i, 1:diplomatic skirmishing, they sent representatives to Ghent to discuss
2mo i, 1:terms of peace. After long negotiations an agreement was reached on
2mo i, 1:Christmas eve, 1814, a few days before Jackson's victory at New Orleans.
2mo i, 1:When the treaty reached America the people were surprised to find that
2mo i, 1:it said nothing about the seizure of American sailors, the destruction
2mo i, 1:of American trade, the searching of American ships, or the support of
2mo i, 1:Indians on the frontier. Nevertheless, we are told, the people "passed
2mo i, 1:from gloom to glory" when the news of peace arrived. The bells were
2mo i, 1:rung; schools were closed; flags were displayed; and many a rousing
2mo i, 1:toast was drunk in tavern and private home. The rejoicing could
2mo i, 1:continue. With Napoleon definitely beaten at Waterloo in June, 1815,
2mo i, 1:Great Britain had no need to impress sailors, search ships, and
2mo i, 1:confiscate American goods bound to the Continent. Once more the terrible
2mo i, 1:sea power sank into the background and the ocean was again white with
2mo i, 1:the sails of merchantmen.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:THE REPUBLICANS NATIONALIZED
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Federalists Discredited.=--By a strange turn of fortune's wheel,
2mo i, 1:the party of Hamilton, Washington, Adams, the party of the grand nation,
2mo i, 1:became the party of provincialism and nullification. New England,
2mo i, 1:finding its shipping interests crippled in the European conflict and
2mo i, 1:then penalized by embargoes, opposed the declaration of war on Great
2mo i, 1:Britain, which meant the completion of the ruin already begun. In the
2mo i, 1:course of the struggle, the Federalist leaders came perilously near to
2mo i, 1:treason in their efforts to hamper the government of the United States;
2mo i, 1:and in their desperation they fell back upon the doctrine of
2mo i, 1:nullification so recently condemned by them when it came from Kentucky.
2mo i, 1:The Senate of Massachusetts, while the war was in progress, resolved
2mo i, 1:that it was waged "without justifiable cause," and refused to approve
2mo i, 1:military and naval projects not connected with "the defense of our
2mo i, 1:seacoast and soil." A Boston newspaper declared that the union was
2mo i, 1:nothing but a treaty among sovereign states, that states could decide
2mo i, 1:for themselves the question of obeying federal law, and that armed
2mo i, 1:resistance under the banner of a state would not be rebellion or
2mo i, 1:treason. The general assembly of Connecticut reminded the administration
2mo i, 1:at Washington that "the state of Connecticut is a free, sovereign, and
2mo i, 1:independent state." Gouverneur Morris, a member of the convention which
2mo i, 1:had drafted the Constitution, suggested the holding of another
2mo i, 1:conference to consider whether the Northern states should remain in the
2mo i, 1:union.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:[Illustration: _From an old cartoon_
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:NEW ENGLAND JUMPING INTO THE HANDS OF GEORGE III]
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:In October, 1814, a convention of delegates from Connecticut,
2mo i, 1:Massachusetts, Rhode Island, and certain counties of New Hampshire and
2mo i, 1:Vermont was held at Hartford, on the call of Massachusetts. The counsels
2mo i, 1:of the extremists were rejected but the convention solemnly went on
2mo i, 1:record to the effect that acts of Congress in violation of the
2mo i, 1:Constitution are void; that in cases of deliberate, dangerous, and
2mo i, 1:palpable infractions the state is duty bound to interpose its authority
2mo i, 1:for the protection of its citizens; and that when emergencies occur the
2mo i, 1:states must be their own judges and execute their own decisions. Thus
2mo i, 1:New England answered the challenge of Calhoun and Clay. Fortunately its
2mo i, 1:actions were not as rash as its words. The Hartford convention merely
2mo i, 1:proposed certain amendments to the Constitution and adjourned. At the
2mo i, 1:close of the war, its proposals vanished harmlessly; but the men who
2mo i, 1:made them were hopelessly discredited.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Second United States Bank.=--In driving the Federalists towards
2mo i, 1:nullification and waging a national war themselves, the Republicans lost
2mo i, 1:all their old taint of provincialism. Moreover, in turning to measures
2mo i, 1:of reconstruction called forth by the war, they resorted to the national
2mo i, 1:devices of the Federalists. In 1816, they chartered for a period of
2mo i, 1:twenty years a second United States Bank--the institution which
2mo i, 1:Jefferson and Madison once had condemned as unsound and
2mo i, 1:unconstitutional. The Constitution remained unchanged; times and
2mo i, 1:circumstances had changed. Calhoun dismissed the vexed question of
2mo i, 1:constitutionality with a scant reference to an ancient dispute, while
2mo i, 1:Madison set aside his scruples and signed the bill.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Protective Tariff of 1816.=--The Republicans supplemented the Bank
2mo i, 1:by another Federalist measure--a high protective tariff. Clay viewed it
2mo i, 1:as the beginning of his "American system" of protection. Calhoun
2mo i, 1:defended it on national principles. For this sudden reversal of policy
2mo i, 1:the young Republicans were taunted by some of their older party
2mo i, 1:colleagues with betraying the "agricultural interest" that Jefferson had
2mo i, 1:fostered; but Calhoun refused to listen to their criticisms. "When the
2mo i, 1:seas are open," he said, "the produce of the South may pour anywhere
2mo i, 1:into the markets of the Old World.... What are the effects of a war with
2mo i, 1:a maritime power--with England? Our commerce annihilated ... our
2mo i, 1:agriculture cut off from its accustomed markets, the surplus of the
2mo i, 1:farmer perishes on his hands.... The recent war fell with peculiar
2mo i, 1:pressure on the growers of cotton and tobacco and the other great
2mo i, 1:staples of the country; and the same state of things will recur in the
2mo i, 1:event of another war unless prevented by the foresight of this body....
2mo i, 1:When our manufactures are grown to a certain perfection, as they soon
2mo i, 1:will be under the fostering care of the government, we shall no longer
2mo i, 1:experience these evils." With the Republicans nationalized, the
2mo i, 1:Federalist party, as an organization, disappeared after a crushing
2mo i, 1:defeat in the presidential campaign of 1816.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Monroe and the Florida Purchase.=--To the victor in that political
2mo i, 1:contest, James Monroe of Virginia, fell two tasks of national
2mo i, 1:importance, adding to the prestige of the whole country and deepening
2mo i, 1:the sense of patriotism that weaned men away from mere allegiance to
2mo i, 1:states. The first of these was the purchase of Florida from Spain. The
2mo i, 1:acquisition of Louisiana let the Mississippi flow "unvexed to the sea";
2mo i, 1:but it left all the states east of the river cut off from the Gulf,
2mo i, 1:affording them ground for discontent akin to that which had moved the
2mo i, 1:pioneers of Kentucky to action a generation earlier. The uncertainty as
2mo i, 1:to the boundaries of Louisiana gave the United States a claim to West
2mo i, 1:Florida, setting on foot a movement for occupation. The Florida swamps
2mo i, 1:were a basis for Indian marauders who periodically swept into the
2mo i, 1:frontier settlements, and hiding places for runaway slaves. Thus the
2mo i, 1:sanction of international law was given to punitive expeditions into
2mo i, 1:alien territory.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The pioneer leaders stood waiting for the signal. It came. President
2mo i, 1:Monroe, on the occasion of an Indian outbreak, ordered General Jackson
2mo i, 1:to seize the offenders, in the Floridas, if necessary. The high-spirited
2mo i, 1:warrior, taking this as a hint that he was to occupy the coveted region,
2mo i, 1:replied that, if possession was the object of the invasion, he could
2mo i, 1:occupy the Floridas within sixty days. Without waiting for an answer to
2mo i, 1:this letter, he launched his expedition, and in the spring of 1818 was
2mo i, 1:master of the Spanish king's domain to the south.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:There was nothing for the king to do but to make the best of the
2mo i, 1:inevitable by ceding the Floridas to the United States in return for
2mo i, 1:five million dollars to be paid to American citizens having claims
2mo i, 1:against Spain. On Washington's birthday, 1819, the treaty was signed. It
2mo i, 1:ceded the Floridas to the United States and defined the boundary between
2mo i, 1:Mexico and the United States by drawing a line from the mouth of the
2mo i, 1:Sabine River in a northwesterly direction to the Pacific. On this
2mo i, 1:occasion even Monroe, former opponent of the Constitution, forgot to
2mo i, 1:inquire whether new territory could be constitutionally acquired and
2mo i, 1:incorporated into the American union. The Republicans seemed far away
2mo i, 1:from the days of "strict construction." And Jefferson still lived!
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Monroe Doctrine.=--Even more effective in fashioning the national
2mo i, 1:idea was Monroe's enunciation of the famous doctrine that bears his
2mo i, 1:name. The occasion was another European crisis. During the Napoleonic
2mo i, 1:upheaval and the years of dissolution that ensued, the Spanish colonies
2mo i, 1:in America, following the example set by their English neighbors in
2mo i, 1:1776, declared their independence. Unable to conquer them alone, the
2mo i, 1:king of Spain turned for help to the friendly powers of Europe that
2mo i, 1:looked upon revolution and republics with undisguised horror.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:_The Holy Alliance._--He found them prepared to view his case with
2mo i, 1:sympathy. Three of them, Austria, Prussia, and Russia, under the
2mo i, 1:leadership of the Czar, Alexander I, in the autumn of 1815, had entered
2mo i, 1:into a Holy Alliance to sustain by reciprocal service the autocratic
2mo i, 1:principle in government. Although the effusive, almost maudlin, language
2mo i, 1:of the treaty did not express their purpose explicitly, the Alliance was
2mo i, 1:later regarded as a mere union of monarchs to prevent the rise and
2mo i, 1:growth of popular government.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The American people thought their worst fears confirmed when, in 1822, a
2mo i, 1:conference of delegates from Russia, Austria, Prussia, and France met at
2mo i, 1:Verona to consider, among other things, revolutions that had just broken
2mo i, 1:out in Spain and Italy. The spirit of the conference is reflected in the
2mo i, 1:first article of the agreement reached by the delegates: "The high
2mo i, 1:contracting powers, being convinced that the system of representative
2mo i, 1:government is equally incompatible with the monarchical principle and
2mo i, 1:the maxim of the sovereignty of the people with the divine right,
2mo i, 1:mutually engage in the most solemn manner to use all their efforts to
2mo i, 1:put an end to the system of representative government in whatever
2mo i, 1:country it may exist in Europe and to prevent its being introduced in
2mo i, 1:those countries where it is not yet known." The Czar, who incidentally
2mo i, 1:coveted the west coast of North America, proposed to send an army to aid
2mo i, 1:the king of Spain in his troubles at home, thus preparing the way for
2mo i, 1:intervention in Spanish America. It was material weakness not want of
2mo i, 1:spirit, that prevented the grand union of monarchs from making open war
2mo i, 1:on popular government.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:_The Position of England._--Unfortunately, too, for the Holy Alliance,
2mo i, 1:England refused to cooperate. English merchants had built up a large
2mo i, 1:trade with the independent Latin-American colonies and they protested
2mo i, 1:against the restoration of Spanish sovereignty, which meant a renewal of
2mo i, 1:Spain's former trade monopoly. Moreover, divine right doctrines had been
2mo i, 1:laid to rest in England and the representative principle thoroughly
2mo i, 1:established. Already there were signs of the coming democratic flood
2mo i, 1:which was soon to carry the first reform bill of 1832, extending the
2mo i, 1:suffrage, and sweep on to even greater achievements. British statesmen,
2mo i, 1:therefore, had to be cautious. In such circumstances, instead of
2mo i, 1:cooperating with the autocrats of Russia, Austria, and Prussia, they
2mo i, 1:turned to the minister of the United States in London. The British prime
2mo i, 1:minister, Canning, proposed that the two countries join in declaring
2mo i, 1:their unwillingness to see the Spanish colonies transferred to any other
2mo i, 1:power.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:_Jefferson's Advice._--The proposal was rejected; but President Monroe
2mo i, 1:took up the suggestion with Madison and Jefferson as well as with his
2mo i, 1:Secretary of State, John Quincy Adams. They favored the plan. Jefferson
2mo i, 1:said: "One nation, most of all, could disturb us in this pursuit [of
2mo i, 1:freedom]; she now offers to lead, aid, and accompany us in it. By
2mo i, 1:acceding to her proposition we detach her from the bands, bring her
2mo i, 1:mighty weight into the scale of free government and emancipate a
2mo i, 1:continent at one stroke.... With her on our side we need not fear the
2mo i, 1:whole world. With her then we should most sedulously cherish a cordial
2mo i, 1:friendship."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:_Monroe's Statement of the Doctrine._--Acting on the advice of trusted
2mo i, 1:friends, President Monroe embodied in his message to Congress, on
2mo i, 1:December 2, 1823, a statement of principles now famous throughout the
2mo i, 1:world as the Monroe Doctrine. To the autocrats of Europe he announced
2mo i, 1:that he would regard "any attempt on their part to extend their system
2mo i, 1:to any portion of this hemisphere as dangerous to our peace and safety."
2mo i, 1:While he did not propose to interfere with existing colonies dependent
2mo i, 1:on European powers, he ranged himself squarely on the side of those that
2mo i, 1:had declared their independence. Any attempt by a European power to
2mo i, 1:oppress them or control their destiny in any manner he characterized as
2mo i, 1:"a manifestation of an unfriendly disposition toward the United States."
2mo i, 1:Referring in another part of his message to a recent claim which the
2mo i, 1:Czar had made to the Pacific coast, President Monroe warned the Old
2mo i, 1:World that "the American continents, by the free and independent
2mo i, 1:condition which they have assumed and maintained, are henceforth not to
2mo i, 1:be considered as subjects for future colonization by any European
2mo i, 1:powers." The effect of this declaration was immediate and profound. Men
2mo i, 1:whose political horizon had been limited to a community or state were
2mo i, 1:led to consider their nation as a great power among the sovereignties of
2mo i, 1:the earth, taking its part in shaping their international relations.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Missouri Compromise.=--Respecting one other important measure of
2mo i, 1:this period, the Republicans also took a broad view of their obligations
2mo i, 1:under the Constitution; namely, the Missouri Compromise. It is true,
2mo i, 1:they insisted on the admission of Missouri as a slave state, balanced
2mo i, 1:against the free state of Maine; but at the same time they assented to
2mo i, 1:the prohibition of slavery in the Louisiana territory north of the line
2mo i, 1:36 o 30'. During the debate on the subject an extreme view had been
2mo i, 1:presented, to the effect that Congress had no constitutional warrant for
2mo i, 1:abolishing slavery in the territories. The precedent of the Northwest
2mo i, 1:Ordinance, ratified by Congress in 1789, seemed a conclusive answer from
2mo i, 1:practice to this contention; but Monroe submitted the issue to his
2mo i, 1:cabinet, which included Calhoun of South Carolina, Crawford of Georgia,
2mo i, 1:and Wirt of Virginia, all presumably adherents to the Jeffersonian
2mo i, 1:principle of strict construction. He received in reply a unanimous
2mo i, 1:verdict to the effect that Congress did have the power to prohibit
2mo i, 1:slavery in the territories governed by it. Acting on this advice he
2mo i, 1:approved, on March 6, 1820, the bill establishing freedom north of the
2mo i, 1:compromise line. This generous interpretation of the powers of Congress
2mo i, 1:stood for nearly forty years, until repudiated by the Supreme Court in
2mo i, 1:the Dred Scott case.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:THE NATIONAL DECISIONS OF CHIEF JUSTICE MARSHALL
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=John Marshall, the Nationalist.=--The Republicans in the lower ranges
2mo i, 1:of state politics, who did not catch the grand national style of their
2mo i, 1:leaders charged with responsibilities in the national field, were
2mo i, 1:assisted in their education by a Federalist from the Old Dominion, John
2mo i, 1:Marshall, who, as Chief Justice of the Supreme Court of the United
2mo i, 1:States from 1801 to 1835, lost no occasion to exalt the Constitution
2mo i, 1:above the claims of the provinces. No differences of opinion as to his
2mo i, 1:political views have ever led even his warmest opponents to deny his
2mo i, 1:superb abilities or his sincere devotion to the national idea. All will
2mo i, 1:likewise agree that for talents, native and acquired, he was an ornament
2mo i, 1:to the humble democracy that brought him forth. His whole career was
2mo i, 1:American. Born on the frontier of Virginia, reared in a log cabin,
2mo i, 1:granted only the barest rudiments of education, inured to hardship and
2mo i, 1:rough life, he rose by masterly efforts to the highest judicial honor
2mo i, 1:America can bestow.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:On him the bitter experience of the Revolution and of later days made a
2mo i, 1:lasting impression. He was no "summer patriot." He had been a soldier in
2mo i, 1:the Revolutionary army. He had suffered with Washington at Valley Forge.
2mo i, 1:He had seen his comrades in arms starving and freezing because the
2mo i, 1:Continental Congress had neither the power nor the inclination to force
2mo i, 1:the states to do their full duty. To him the Articles of Confederation
2mo i, 1:were the symbol of futility. Into the struggle for the formation of the
2mo i, 1:Constitution and its ratification in Virginia he had thrown himself with
2mo i, 1:the ardor of a soldier. Later, as a member of Congress, a representative
2mo i, 1:to France, and Secretary of State, he had aided the Federalists in
2mo i, 1:establishing the new government. When at length they were driven from
2mo i, 1:power in the executive and legislative branches of the government, he
2mo i, 1:was chosen for their last stronghold, the Supreme Court. By historic
2mo i, 1:irony he administered the oath of office to his bitterest enemy, Thomas
2mo i, 1:Jefferson; and, long after the author of the Declaration of Independence
2mo i, 1:had retired to private life, the stern Chief Justice continued to
2mo i, 1:announce the old Federalist principles from the Supreme Bench.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:[Illustration: JOHN MARSHALL]
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Marbury _vs._ Madison--An Act of Congress Annulled.=--He had been in
2mo i, 1:his high office only two years when he laid down for the first time in
2mo i, 1:the name of the entire Court the doctrine that the judges have the power
2mo i, 1:to declare an act of Congress null and void when in their opinion it
2mo i, 1:violates the Constitution. This power was not expressly conferred on the
2mo i, 1:Court. Though many able men held that the judicial branch of the
2mo i, 1:government enjoyed it, the principle was not positively established
2mo i, 1:until 1803 when the case of Marbury _vs._ Madison was decided. In
2mo i, 1:rendering the opinion of the Court, Marshall cited no precedents. He
2mo i, 1:sought no foundations for his argument in ancient history. He rested it
2mo i, 1:on the general nature of the American system. The Constitution, ran his
2mo i, 1:reasoning, is the supreme law of the land; it limits and binds all who
2mo i, 1:act in the name of the United States; it limits the powers of Congress
2mo i, 1:and defines the rights of citizens. If Congress can ignore its
2mo i, 1:limitations and trespass upon the rights of citizens, Marshall argued,
2mo i, 1:then the Constitution disappears and Congress is supreme. Since,
2mo i, 1:however, the Constitution is supreme and superior to Congress, it is the
2mo i, 1:duty of judges, under their oath of office, to sustain it against
2mo i, 1:measures which violate it. Therefore, from the nature of the American
2mo i, 1:constitutional system the courts must declare null and void all acts
2mo i, 1:which are not authorized. "A law repugnant to the Constitution," he
2mo i, 1:closed, "is void and the courts as well as other departments are bound
2mo i, 1:by that instrument." From that day to this the practice of federal and
2mo i, 1:state courts in passing upon the constitutionality of laws has remained
2mo i, 1:unshaken.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:This doctrine was received by Jefferson and many of his followers with
2mo i, 1:consternation. If the idea was sound, he exclaimed, "then indeed is our
2mo i, 1:Constitution a complete _felo de se_ [legally, a suicide]. For,
2mo i, 1:intending to establish three departments, coordinate and independent
2mo i, 1:that they might check and balance one another, it has given, according
2mo i, 1:to this opinion, to one of them alone the right to prescribe rules for
2mo i, 1:the government of the others, and to that one, too, which is unelected
2mo i, 1:by and independent of the nation.... The Constitution, on this
2mo i, 1:hypothesis, is a mere thing of wax in the hands of the judiciary which
2mo i, 1:they may twist and shape into any form they please. It should be
2mo i, 1:remembered, as an axiom of eternal truth in politics, that whatever
2mo i, 1:power in any government is independent, is absolute also.... A judiciary
2mo i, 1:independent of a king or executive alone is a good thing; but
2mo i, 1:independence of the will of the nation is a solecism, at least in a
2mo i, 1:republican government." But Marshall was mighty and his view prevailed,
2mo i, 1:though from time to time other men, clinging to Jefferson's opinion,
2mo i, 1:likewise opposed the exercise by the Courts of the high power of passing
2mo i, 1:upon the constitutionality of acts of Congress.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Acts of State Legislatures Declared Unconstitutional.=--Had Marshall
2mo i, 1:stopped with annulling an act of Congress, he would have heard less
2mo i, 1:criticism from Republican quarters; but, with the same firmness, he set
2mo i, 1:aside acts of state legislatures as well, whenever, in his opinion, they
2mo i, 1:violated the federal Constitution. In 1810, in the case of Fletcher
2mo i, 1:_vs._ Peck, he annulled an act of the Georgia legislature, informing the
2mo i, 1:state that it was not sovereign, but "a part of a large empire, ... a
2mo i, 1:member of the American union; and that union has a constitution ...
2mo i, 1:which imposes limits to the legislatures of the several states." In the
2mo i, 1:case of McCulloch _vs._ Maryland, decided in 1819, he declared void an
2mo i, 1:act of the Maryland legislature designed to paralyze the branches of the
2mo i, 1:United States Bank established in that state. In the same year, in the
2mo i, 1:still more memorable Dartmouth College case, he annulled an act of the
2mo i, 1:New Hampshire legislature which infringed upon the charter received by
2mo i, 1:the college from King George long before. That charter, he declared, was
2mo i, 1:a contract between the state and the college, which the legislature
2mo i, 1:under the federal Constitution could not impair. Two years later he
2mo i, 1:stirred the wrath of Virginia by summoning her to the bar of the Supreme
2mo i, 1:Court to answer in a case in which the validity of one of her laws was
2mo i, 1:involved and then justified his action in a powerful opinion rendered in
2mo i, 1:the case of Cohens _vs._ Virginia.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:All these decisions aroused the legislatures of the states. They passed
2mo i, 1:sheaves of resolutions protesting and condemning; but Marshall never
2mo i, 1:turned and never stayed. The Constitution of the United States, he
2mo i, 1:fairly thundered at them, is the supreme law of the land; the Supreme
2mo i, 1:Court is the proper tribunal to pass finally upon the validity of the
2mo i, 1:laws of the states; and "those sovereignties," far from possessing the
2mo i, 1:right of review and nullification, are irrevocably bound by the
2mo i, 1:decisions of that Court. This was strong medicine for the authors of the
2mo i, 1:Kentucky and Virginia Resolutions and for the members of the Hartford
2mo i, 1:convention; but they had to take it.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Doctrine of Implied Powers.=--While restraining Congress in the
2mo i, 1:Marbury case and the state legislatures in a score of cases, Marshall
2mo i, 1:also laid the judicial foundation for a broad and liberal view of the
2mo i, 1:Constitution as opposed to narrow and strict construction. In McCulloch
2mo i, 1:_vs._ Maryland, he construed generously the words "necessary and proper"
2mo i, 1:in such a way as to confer upon Congress a wide range of "implied
2mo i, 1:powers" in addition to their express powers. That case involved, among
2mo i, 1:other things, the question whether the act establishing the second
2mo i, 1:United States Bank was authorized by the Constitution. Marshall answered
2mo i, 1:in the affirmative. Congress, ran his reasoning, has large powers over
2mo i, 1:taxation and the currency; a bank is of appropriate use in the exercise
2mo i, 1:of these enumerated powers; and therefore, though not absolutely
2mo i, 1:necessary, a bank is entirely proper and constitutional. "With respect
2mo i, 1:to the means by which the powers that the Constitution confers are to be
2mo i, 1:carried into execution," he said, Congress must be allowed the
2mo i, 1:discretion which "will enable that body to perform the high duties
2mo i, 1:assigned to it, in the manner most beneficial to the people." In short,
2mo i, 1:the Constitution of the United States is not a strait jacket but a
2mo i, 1:flexible instrument vesting in Congress the powers necessary to meet
2mo i, 1:national problems as they arise. In delivering this opinion Marshall
2mo i, 1:used language almost identical with that employed by Lincoln when,
2mo i, 1:standing on the battle field of a war waged to preserve the nation, he
2mo i, 1:said that "a government of the people, by the people, for the people
2mo i, 1:shall not perish from the earth."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:SUMMARY OF THE UNION AND NATIONAL POLITICS
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:During the strenuous period between the establishment of American
2mo i, 1:independence and the advent of Jacksonian democracy the great American
2mo i, 1:experiment was under the direction of the men who had launched it. All
2mo i, 1:the Presidents in that period, except John Quincy Adams, had taken part
2mo i, 1:in the Revolution. James Madison, the chief author of the Constitution,
2mo i, 1:lived until 1836. This age, therefore, was the "age of the fathers." It
2mo i, 1:saw the threatened ruin of the country under the Articles of
2mo i, 1:Confederation, the formation of the Constitution, the rise of political
2mo i, 1:parties, the growth of the West, the second war with England, and the
2mo i, 1:apparent triumph of the national spirit over sectionalism.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The new republic had hardly been started in 1783 before its troubles
2mo i, 1:began. The government could not raise money to pay its debts or running
2mo i, 1:expenses; it could not protect American commerce and manufactures
2mo i, 1:against European competition; it could not stop the continual issues of
2mo i, 1:paper money by the states; it could not intervene to put down domestic
2mo i, 1:uprisings that threatened the existence of the state governments.
2mo i, 1:Without money, without an army, without courts of law, the union under
2mo i, 1:the Articles of Confederation was drifting into dissolution. Patriots,
2mo i, 1:who had risked their lives for independence, began to talk of monarchy
2mo i, 1:again. Washington, Hamilton, and Madison insisted that a new
2mo i, 1:constitution alone could save America from disaster.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:By dint of much labor the friends of a new form of government induced
2mo i, 1:the Congress to call a national convention to take into account the
2mo i, 1:state of America. In May, 1787, it assembled at Philadelphia and for
2mo i, 1:months it debated and wrangled over plans for a constitution. The small
2mo i, 1:states clamored for equal rights in the union. The large states vowed
2mo i, 1:that they would never grant it. A spirit of conciliation, fair play, and
2mo i, 1:compromise saved the convention from breaking up. In addition, there
2mo i, 1:were jealousies between the planting states and the commercial states.
2mo i, 1:Here, too, compromises had to be worked out. Some of the delegates
2mo i, 1:feared the growth of democracy and others cherished it. These factions
2mo i, 1:also had to be placated. At last a plan of government was drafted--the
2mo i, 1:Constitution of the United States--and submitted to the states for
2mo i, 1:approval. Only after a long and acrimonious debate did enough states
2mo i, 1:ratify the instrument to put it into effect. On April 30, 1789, George
2mo i, 1:Washington was inaugurated first President.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The new government proceeded to fund the old debt of the nation, assume
2mo i, 1:the debts of the states, found a national bank, lay heavy taxes to pay
2mo i, 1:the bills, and enact laws protecting American industry and commerce.
2mo i, 1:Hamilton led the way, but he had not gone far before he encountered
2mo i, 1:opposition. He found a formidable antagonist in Jefferson. In time two
2mo i, 1:political parties appeared full armed upon the scene: the Federalists
2mo i, 1:and the Republicans. For ten years they filled the country with
2mo i, 1:political debate. In 1800 the Federalists were utterly vanquished by the
2mo i, 1:Republicans with Jefferson in the lead.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:By their proclamations of faith the Republicans favored the states
2mo i, 1:rather than the new national government, but in practice they added
2mo i, 1:immensely to the prestige and power of the nation. They purchased
2mo i, 1:Louisiana from France, they waged a war for commercial independence
2mo i, 1:against England, they created a second United States Bank, they enacted
2mo i, 1:the protective tariff of 1816, they declared that Congress had power to
2mo i, 1:abolish slavery north of the Missouri Compromise line, and they spread
2mo i, 1:the shield of the Monroe Doctrine between the Western Hemisphere and
2mo i, 1:Europe.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Still America was a part of European civilization. Currents of opinion
2mo i, 1:flowed to and fro across the Atlantic. Friends of popular government in
2mo i, 1:Europe looked to America as the great exemplar of their ideals. Events
2mo i, 1:in Europe reacted upon thought in the United States. The French
2mo i, 1:Revolution exerted a profound influence on the course of political
2mo i, 1:debate. While it was in the stage of mere reform all Americans favored
2mo i, 1:it. When the king was executed and a radical democracy set up, American
2mo i, 1:opinion was divided. When France fell under the military dominion of
2mo i, 1:Napoleon and preyed upon American commerce, the United States made ready
2mo i, 1:for war.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The conduct of England likewise affected American affairs. In 1793 war
2mo i, 1:broke out between England and France and raged with only a slight
2mo i, 1:intermission until 1815. England and France both ravaged American
2mo i, 1:commerce, but England was the more serious offender because she had
2mo i, 1:command of the seas. Though Jefferson and Madison strove for peace, the
2mo i, 1:country was swept into war by the vehemence of the "Young Republicans,"
2mo i, 1:headed by Clay and Calhoun.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:When the armed conflict was closed, one in diplomacy opened. The
2mo i, 1:autocratic powers of Europe threatened to intervene on behalf of Spain
2mo i, 1:in her attempt to recover possession of her Latin-American colonies.
2mo i, 1:Their challenge to America brought forth the Monroe Doctrine. The powers
2mo i, 1:of Europe were warned not to interfere with the independence or the
2mo i, 1:republican policies of this hemisphere or to attempt any new
2mo i, 1:colonization in it. It seemed that nationalism was to have a peaceful
2mo i, 1:triumph over sectionalism.
