2mo i, 1:PART IV. THE WEST AND JACKSONIAN DEMOCRACY
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:CHAPTER X
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:THE FARMERS BEYOND THE APPALACHIANS
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The nationalism of Hamilton was undemocratic. The democracy of Jefferson
2mo i, 1:was, in the beginning, provincial. The historic mission of uniting
2mo i, 1:nationalism and democracy was in the course of time given to new leaders
2mo i, 1:from a region beyond the mountains, peopled by men and women from all
2mo i, 1:sections and free from those state traditions which ran back to the
2mo i, 1:early days of colonization. The voice of the democratic nationalism
2mo i, 1:nourished in the West was heard when Clay of Kentucky advocated his
2mo i, 1:American system of protection for industries; when Jackson of Tennessee
2mo i, 1:condemned nullification in a ringing proclamation that has taken its
2mo i, 1:place among the great American state papers; and when Lincoln of
2mo i, 1:Illinois, in a fateful hour, called upon a bewildered people to meet the
2mo i, 1:supreme test whether this was a nation destined to survive or to perish.
2mo i, 1:And it will be remembered that Lincoln's party chose for its banner that
2mo i, 1:earlier device--Republican--which Jefferson had made a sign of power.
2mo i, 1:The "rail splitter" from Illinois united the nationalism of Hamilton
2mo i, 1:with the democracy of Jefferson, and his appeal was clothed in the
2mo i, 1:simple language of the people, not in the sonorous rhetoric which
2mo i, 1:Webster learned in the schools.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:PREPARATION FOR WESTERN SETTLEMENT
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The West and the American Revolution.=--The excessive attention devoted
2mo i, 1:by historians to the military operations along the coast has obscured
2mo i, 1:the role played by the frontier in the American Revolution. The action
2mo i, 1:of Great Britain in closing western land to easy settlement in 1763 was
2mo i, 1:more than an incident in precipitating the war for independence.
2mo i, 1:Americans on the frontier did not forget it; when Indians were employed
2mo i, 1:by England to defend that land, zeal for the patriot cause set the
2mo i, 1:interior aflame. It was the members of the western vanguard, like Daniel
2mo i, 1:Boone, John Sevier, and George Rogers Clark, who first understood the
2mo i, 1:value of the far-away country under the guns of the English forts, where
2mo i, 1:the Red Men still wielded the tomahawk and the scalping knife. It was
2mo i, 1:they who gave the East no rest until their vision was seen by the
2mo i, 1:leaders on the seaboard who directed the course of national policy. It
2mo i, 1:was one of their number, a seasoned Indian fighter, George Rogers Clark,
2mo i, 1:who with aid from Virginia seized Kaskaskia and Vincennes and secured
2mo i, 1:the whole Northwest to the union while the fate of Washington's army was
2mo i, 1:still hanging in the balance.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Western Problems at the End of the Revolution.=--The treaty of peace,
2mo i, 1:signed with Great Britain in 1783, brought the definite cession of the
2mo i, 1:coveted territory west to the Mississippi River, but it left unsolved
2mo i, 1:many problems. In the first place, tribes of resentful Indians in the
2mo i, 1:Ohio region, even though British support was withdrawn at last, had to
2mo i, 1:be reckoned with; and it was not until after the establishment of the
2mo i, 1:federal Constitution that a well-equipped army could be provided to
2mo i, 1:guarantee peace on the border. In the second place, British garrisons
2mo i, 1:still occupied forts on Lake Erie pending the execution of the terms of
2mo i, 1:the treaty of 1783--terms which were not fulfilled until after the
2mo i, 1:ratification of the Jay treaty twelve years later. In the third place,
2mo i, 1:Virginia, Connecticut, and Massachusetts had conflicting claims to the
2mo i, 1:land in the Northwest based on old English charters and Indian treaties.
2mo i, 1:It was only after a bitter contest that the states reached an agreement
2mo i, 1:to transfer their rights to the government of the United States,
2mo i, 1:Virginia executing her deed of cession on March 1, 1784. In the fourth
2mo i, 1:place, titles to lands bought by individuals remained uncertain in the
2mo i, 1:absence of official maps and records. To meet this last situation,
2mo i, 1:Congress instituted a systematic survey of the Ohio country, laying it
2mo i, 1:out into townships, sections of 640 acres each, and quarter sections. In
2mo i, 1:every township one section of land was set aside for the support of
2mo i, 1:public schools.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Northwest Ordinance.=--The final problem which had to be solved
2mo i, 1:before settlement on a large scale could be begun was that of governing
2mo i, 1:the territory. Pioneers who looked with hungry eyes on the fertile
2mo i, 1:valley of the Ohio could hardly restrain their impatience. Soldiers of
2mo i, 1:the Revolution, who had been paid for their services in land warrants
2mo i, 1:entitling them to make entries in the West, called for action.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Congress answered by passing in 1787 the famous Northwest Ordinance
2mo i, 1:providing for temporary territorial government to be followed by the
2mo i, 1:creation of a popular assembly as soon as there were five thousand free
2mo i, 1:males in any district. Eventual admission to the union on an equal
2mo i, 1:footing with the original states was promised to the new territories.
2mo i, 1:Religious freedom was guaranteed. The safeguards of trial by jury,
2mo i, 1:regular judicial procedure, and _habeas corpus_ were established, in order
2mo i, 1:that the methods of civilized life might take the place of the
2mo i, 1:rough-and-ready justice of lynch law. During the course of the debate on
2mo i, 1:the Ordinance, Congress added the sixth article forbidding slavery and
2mo i, 1:involuntary servitude.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:This Charter of the Northwest, so well planned by the Congress under the
2mo i, 1:Articles of Confederation, was continued in force by the first Congress
2mo i, 1:under the Constitution in 1789. The following year its essential
2mo i, 1:provisions, except the ban on slavery, were applied to the territory
2mo i, 1:south of the Ohio, ceded by North Carolina to the national government,
2mo i, 1:and in 1798 to the Mississippi territory, once held by Georgia. Thus it
2mo i, 1:was settled for all time that "the new colonies were not to be exploited
2mo i, 1:for the benefit of the parent states (any more than for the benefit of
2mo i, 1:England) but were to be autonomous and coordinate commonwealths." This
2mo i, 1:outcome, bitterly opposed by some Eastern leaders who feared the triumph
2mo i, 1:of Western states over the seaboard, completed the legal steps necessary
2mo i, 1:by way of preparation for the flood of settlers.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Land Companies, Speculators, and Western Land Tenure.=--As in the
2mo i, 1:original settlement of America, so in the opening of the West, great
2mo i, 1:companies and single proprietors of large grants early figured. In 1787
2mo i, 1:the Ohio Land Company, a New England concern, acquired a million and a
2mo i, 1:half acres on the Ohio and began operations by planting the town of
2mo i, 1:Marietta. A professional land speculator, J.C. Symmes, secured a million
2mo i, 1:acres lower down where the city of Cincinnati was founded. Other
2mo i, 1:individuals bought up soldiers' claims and so acquired enormous holdings
2mo i, 1:for speculative purposes. Indeed, there was such a rush to make fortunes
2mo i, 1:quickly through the rise in land values that Washington was moved to cry
2mo i, 1:out against the "rage for speculating in and forestalling of land on the
2mo i, 1:North West of the Ohio," protesting that "scarce a valuable spot within
2mo i, 1:any tolerable distance of it is left without a claimant." He therefore
2mo i, 1:urged Congress to fix a reasonable price for the land, not "too
2mo i, 1:exorbitant and burdensome for real occupiers, but high enough to
2mo i, 1:discourage monopolizers."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Congress, however, was not prepared to use the public domain for the
2mo i, 1:sole purpose of developing a body of small freeholders in the West. It
2mo i, 1:still looked upon the sale of public lands as an important source of
2mo i, 1:revenue with which to pay off the public debt; consequently it thought
2mo i, 1:more of instant income than of ultimate results. It placed no limit on
2mo i, 1:the amount which could be bought when it fixed the price at $2 an acre
2mo i, 1:in 1796, and it encouraged the professional land operator by making the
2mo i, 1:first installment only twenty cents an acre in addition to the small
2mo i, 1:registration and survey fee. On such terms a speculator with a few
2mo i, 1:thousand dollars could get possession of an enormous plot of land. If he
2mo i, 1:was fortunate in disposing of it, he could meet the installments, which
2mo i, 1:were spread over a period of four years, and make a handsome profit for
2mo i, 1:himself. Even when the credit or installment feature was abolished in
2mo i, 1:1821 and the price of the land lowered to a cash price of $1.75 an acre,
2mo i, 1:the opportunity for large speculative purchases continued to attract
2mo i, 1:capital to land ventures.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Development of the Small Freehold.=--The cheapness of land and the
2mo i, 1:scarcity of labor, nevertheless, made impossible the triumph of the huge
2mo i, 1:estate with its semi-servile tenantry. For about $45 a man could get a
2mo i, 1:farm of 160 acres on the installment plan; another payment of $80 was
2mo i, 1:due in forty days; but a four-year term was allowed for the discharge of
2mo i, 1:the balance. With a capital of from two to three hundred dollars a
2mo i, 1:family could embark on a land venture. If it had good crops, it could
2mo i, 1:meet the deferred payments. It was, however, a hard battle at best. Many
2mo i, 1:a man forfeited his land through failure to pay the final installment;
2mo i, 1:yet in the end, in spite of all the handicaps, the small freehold of a
2mo i, 1:few hundred acres at most became the typical unit of Western
2mo i, 1:agriculture, except in the planting states of the Gulf. Even the lands
2mo i, 1:of the great companies were generally broken up and sold in small lots.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The tendency toward moderate holdings, so favored by Western conditions,
2mo i, 1:was also promoted by a clause in the Northwest Ordinance declaring that
2mo i, 1:the land of any person dying intestate--that is, without any will
2mo i, 1:disposing of it--should be divided equally among his descendants.
2mo i, 1:Hildreth says of this provision: "It established the important
2mo i, 1:republican principle, not then introduced into all the states, of the
2mo i, 1:equal distribution of landed as well as personal property." All these
2mo i, 1:forces combined made the wide dispersion of wealth, in the early days of
2mo i, 1:the nineteenth century, an American characteristic, in marked contrast
2mo i, 1:with the European system of family prestige and vast estates based on
2mo i, 1:the law of primogeniture.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:THE WESTERN MIGRATION AND NEW STATES
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The People.=--With government established, federal arms victorious over
2mo i, 1:the Indians, and the lands surveyed for sale, the way was prepared for
2mo i, 1:the immigrants. They came with a rush. Young New Englanders, weary of
2mo i, 1:tilling the stony soil of their native states, poured through New York
2mo i, 1:and Pennsylvania, some settling on the northern bank of the Ohio but
2mo i, 1:most of them in the Lake region. Sons and daughters of German farmers in
2mo i, 1:Pennsylvania and many a redemptioner who had discharged his bond of
2mo i, 1:servitude pressed out into Ohio, Kentucky, Tennessee, or beyond. From
2mo i, 1:the exhausted fields and the clay hills of the Southern states came
2mo i, 1:pioneers of English and Scotch-Irish descent, the latter in great
2mo i, 1:numbers. Indeed one historian of high authority has ventured to say that
2mo i, 1:"the rapid expansion of the United States from a coast strip to a
2mo i, 1:continental area is largely a Scotch-Irish achievement." While native
2mo i, 1:Americans of mixed stocks led the way into the West, it was not long
2mo i, 1:before immigrants direct from Europe, under the stimulus of company
2mo i, 1:enterprise, began to filter into the new settlements in increasing
2mo i, 1:numbers.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The types of people were as various as the nations they represented.
2mo i, 1:Timothy Flint, who published his entertaining _Recollections_ in 1826,
2mo i, 1:found the West a strange mixture of all sorts and conditions of people.
2mo i, 1:Some of them, he relates, had been hunters in the upper world of the
2mo i, 1:Mississippi, above the falls of St. Anthony. Some had been still farther
2mo i, 1:north, in Canada. Still others had wandered from the South--the Gulf of
2mo i, 1:Mexico, the Red River, and the Spanish country. French boatmen and
2mo i, 1:trappers, Spanish traders from the Southwest, Virginia planters with
2mo i, 1:their droves of slaves mingled with English, German, and Scotch-Irish
2mo i, 1:farmers. Hunters, forest rangers, restless bordermen, and squatters,
2mo i, 1:like the foaming combers of an advancing tide, went first. Then followed
2mo i, 1:the farmers, masters of the ax and plow, with their wives who shared
2mo i, 1:every burden and hardship and introduced some of the features of
2mo i, 1:civilized life. The hunters and rangers passed on to new scenes; the
2mo i, 1:home makers built for all time.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Number of Immigrants.=--There were no official stations on the
2mo i, 1:frontier to record the number of immigrants who entered the West during
2mo i, 1:the decades following the American Revolution. But travelers of the time
2mo i, 1:record that every road was "crowded" with pioneers and their families,
2mo i, 1:their wagons and cattle; and that they were seldom out of the sound of
2mo i, 1:the snapping whip of the teamster urging forward his horses or the crack
2mo i, 1:of the hunter's rifle as he brought down his evening meal. "During the
2mo i, 1:latter half of 1787," says Coman, "more than nine hundred boats floated
2mo i, 1:down the Ohio carrying eighteen thousand men, women, and children, and
2mo i, 1:twelve thousand horses, sheep, and cattle, and six hundred and fifty
2mo i, 1:wagons." Other lines of travel were also crowded and with the passing
2mo i, 1:years the flooding tide of home seekers rose higher and higher.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Western Routes.=--Four main routes led into the country beyond the
2mo i, 1:Appalachians. The Genesee road, beginning at Albany, ran almost due west
2mo i, 1:to the present site of Buffalo on Lake Erie, through a level country. In
2mo i, 1:the dry season, wagons laden with goods could easily pass along it into
2mo i, 1:northern Ohio. A second route, through Pittsburgh, was fed by three
2mo i, 1:eastern branches, one starting at Philadelphia, one at Baltimore, and
2mo i, 1:another at Alexandria. A third main route wound through the mountains
2mo i, 1:from Alexandria to Boonesboro in Kentucky and then westward across the
2mo i, 1:Ohio to St. Louis. A fourth, the most famous of them all, passed through
2mo i, 1:the Cumberland Gap and by branches extended into the Cumberland valley
2mo i, 1:and the Kentucky country.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Of these four lines of travel, the Pittsburgh route offered the most
2mo i, 1:advantages. Pioneers, no matter from what section they came, when once
2mo i, 1:they were on the headwaters of the Ohio and in possession of a flatboat,
2mo i, 1:could find a quick and easy passage into all parts of the West and
2mo i, 1:Southwest. Whether they wanted to settle in Ohio, Kentucky, or western
2mo i, 1:Tennessee they could find their way down the drifting flood to their
2mo i, 1:destination or at least to some spot near it. Many people from the South
2mo i, 1:as well as the Northern and Middle states chose this route; so it came
2mo i, 1:about that the sons and daughters of Virginia and the Carolinas mingled
2mo i, 1:with those of New York, Pennsylvania, and New England in the settlement
2mo i, 1:of the Northwest territory.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Methods of Travel into the West.=--Many stories giving exact
2mo i, 1:descriptions of methods of travel into the West in the early days have
2mo i, 1:been preserved. The country was hardly opened before visitors from the
2mo i, 1:Old World and from the Eastern states, impelled by curiosity, made their
2mo i, 1:way to the very frontier of civilization and wrote books to inform or
2mo i, 1:amuse the public. One of them, Gilbert Imlay, an English traveler, has
2mo i, 1:given us an account of the Pittsburgh route as he found it in 1791. "If
2mo i, 1:a man ... " he writes, "has a family or goods of any sort to remove, his
2mo i, 1:best way, then, would be to purchase a waggon and team of horses to
2mo i, 1:carry his property to Redstone Old Fort or to Pittsburgh, according as
2mo i, 1:he may come from the Northern or Southern states. A good waggon will
2mo i, 1:cost, at Philadelphia, about $10 ... and the horses about $12 each; they
2mo i, 1:would cost something more both at Baltimore and Alexandria. The waggon
2mo i, 1:may be covered with canvass, and if it is the choice of the people, they
2mo i, 1:may sleep in it of nights with the greatest safety. But if they dislike
2mo i, 1:that, there are inns of accommodation the whole distance on the
2mo i, 1:different roads.... The provisions I would purchase in the same manner
2mo i, 1:[that is, from the farmers along the road]; and by having two or three
2mo i, 1:camp kettles and stopping every evening when the weather is fine upon
2mo i, 1:the brink of some rivulet and by kindling a fire they may soon dress
2mo i, 1:their own food.... This manner of journeying is so far from being
2mo i, 1:disagreeable that in a fine season it is extremely pleasant." The
2mo i, 1:immigrant once at Pittsburgh or Wheeling could then buy a flatboat of a
2mo i, 1:size required for his goods and stock, and drift down the current to his
2mo i, 1:journey's end.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:[Illustration: ROADS AND TRAILS INTO THE WESTERN TERRITORY]
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Admission of Kentucky and Tennessee.=--When the eighteenth century
2mo i, 1:drew to a close, Kentucky had a population larger than Delaware, Rhode
2mo i, 1:Island, or New Hampshire. Tennessee claimed 60,000 inhabitants. In 1792
2mo i, 1:Kentucky took her place as a state beside her none too kindly parent,
2mo i, 1:Virginia. The Eastern Federalists resented her intrusion; but they took
2mo i, 1:some consolation in the admission of Vermont because the balance of
2mo i, 1:Eastern power was still retained.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:As if to assert their independence of old homes and conservative ideas
2mo i, 1:the makers of Kentucky's first constitution swept aside the landed
2mo i, 1:qualification on the suffrage and gave the vote to all free white males.
2mo i, 1:Four years later, Kentucky's neighbor to the south, Tennessee, followed
2mo i, 1:this step toward a wider democracy. After encountering fierce opposition
2mo i, 1:from the Federalists, Tennessee was accepted as the sixteenth state.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Ohio.=--The door of the union had hardly opened for Tennessee when
2mo i, 1:another appeal was made to Congress, this time from the pioneers in
2mo i, 1:Ohio. The little posts founded at Marietta and Cincinnati had grown into
2mo i, 1:flourishing centers of trade. The stream of immigrants, flowing down the
2mo i, 1:river, added daily to their numbers and the growing settlements all
2mo i, 1:around poured produce into their markets to be exchanged for "store
2mo i, 1:goods." After the Indians were disposed of in 1794 and the last British
2mo i, 1:soldier left the frontier forts under the terms of the Jay treaty of
2mo i, 1:1795, tiny settlements of families appeared on Lake Erie in the "Western
2mo i, 1:Reserve," a region that had been retained by Connecticut when she
2mo i, 1:surrendered her other rights in the Northwest.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:At the close of the century, Ohio, claiming a population of more than
2mo i, 1:50,000, grew discontented with its territorial status. Indeed, two years
2mo i, 1:before the enactment of the Northwest Ordinance, squatters in that
2mo i, 1:region had been invited by one John Emerson to hold a convention after
2mo i, 1:the fashion of the men of Hartford, Windsor, and Wethersfield in old
2mo i, 1:Connecticut and draft a frame of government for themselves. This true
2mo i, 1:son of New England declared that men "have an undoubted right to pass
2mo i, 1:into every vacant country and there to form their constitution and that
2mo i, 1:from the confederation of the whole United States Congress is not
2mo i, 1:empowered to forbid them." This grand convention was never held because
2mo i, 1:the heavy hand of the government fell upon the leaders; but the spirit
2mo i, 1:of John Emerson did not perish. In November, 1802, a convention chosen
2mo i, 1:by voters, assembled under the authority of Congress at Chillicothe,
2mo i, 1:drew up a constitution. It went into force after a popular ratification.
2mo i, 1:The roll of the convention bore such names as Abbot, Baldwin, Cutler,
2mo i, 1:Huntington, Putnam, and Sargent, and the list of counties from which
2mo i, 1:they came included Adams, Fairfield, Hamilton, Jefferson, Trumbull, and
2mo i, 1:Washington, showing that the new America in the West was peopled and led
2mo i, 1:by the old stock. In 1803 Ohio was admitted to the union.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Indiana and Illinois.=--As in the neighboring state, the frontier in
2mo i, 1:Indiana advanced northward from the Ohio, mainly under the leadership,
2mo i, 1:however, of settlers from the South--restless Kentuckians hoping for
2mo i, 1:better luck in a newer country and pioneers from the far frontiers of
2mo i, 1:Virginia and North Carolina. As soon as a tier of counties swinging
2mo i, 1:upward like the horns of the moon against Ohio on the east and in the
2mo i, 1:Wabash Valley on the west was fairly settled, a clamor went up for
2mo i, 1:statehood. Under the authority of an act of Congress in 1816 the
2mo i, 1:Indianians drafted a constitution and inaugurated their government at
2mo i, 1:Corydon. "The majority of the members of the convention," we are told by
2mo i, 1:a local historian, "were frontier farmers who had a general idea of what
2mo i, 1:they wanted and had sense enough to let their more erudite colleagues
2mo i, 1:put it into shape."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Two years later, the pioneers of Illinois, also settled upward from the
2mo i, 1:Ohio, like Indiana, elected their delegates to draft a constitution.
2mo i, 1:Leadership in the convention, quite properly, was taken by a man born in
2mo i, 1:New York and reared in Tennessee; and the constitution as finally
2mo i, 1:drafted "was in its principal provisions a copy of the then existing
2mo i, 1:constitutions of Kentucky, Ohio, and Indiana.... Many of the articles
2mo i, 1:are exact copies in wording although differently arranged and
2mo i, 1:numbered."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Louisiana, Mississippi, and Alabama.=--Across the Mississippi to the
2mo i, 1:far south, clearing and planting had gone on with much bustle and
2mo i, 1:enterprise. The cotton and sugar lands of Louisiana, opened by French
2mo i, 1:and Spanish settlers, were widened in every direction by planters with
2mo i, 1:their armies of slaves from the older states. New Orleans, a good market
2mo i, 1:and a center of culture not despised even by the pioneer, grew apace. In
2mo i, 1:1810 the population of lower Louisiana was over 75,000. The time had
2mo i, 1:come, said the leaders of the people, to fulfill the promise made to
2mo i, 1:France in the treaty of cession; namely, to grant to the inhabitants of
2mo i, 1:the territory statehood and the rights of American citizens. Federalists
2mo i, 1:from New England still having a voice in Congress, if somewhat weaker,
2mo i, 1:still protested in tones of horror. "I am compelled to declare it as my
2mo i, 1:deliberate opinion," pronounced Josiah Quincy in the House of
2mo i, 1:Representatives, "that if this bill [to admit Louisiana] passes, the
2mo i, 1:bonds of this Union are virtually dissolved ... that as it will be the
2mo i, 1:right of all, so it will be the duty of some [states] to prepare
2mo i, 1:definitely for a separation; amicably if they can, violently if they
2mo i, 1:must.... It is a death blow to the Constitution. It may afterwards
2mo i, 1:linger; but lingering, its fate will, at no very distant period, be
2mo i, 1:consummated." Federalists from New York like those from New England had
2mo i, 1:their doubts about the wisdom of admitting Western states; but the party
2mo i, 1:of Jefferson and Madison, having the necessary majority, granted the
2mo i, 1:coveted statehood to Louisiana in 1812.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:When, a few years later, Mississippi and Alabama knocked at the doors of
2mo i, 1:the union, the Federalists had so little influence, on account of their
2mo i, 1:conduct during the second war with England, that spokesmen from the
2mo i, 1:Southwest met a kindlier reception at Washington. Mississippi, in 1817,
2mo i, 1:and Alabama, in 1819, took their places among the United States of
2mo i, 1:America. Both of them, while granting white manhood suffrage, gave their
2mo i, 1:constitutions the tone of the old East by providing landed
2mo i, 1:qualifications for the governor and members of the legislature.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Missouri.=--Far to the north in the Louisiana purchase, a new
2mo i, 1:commonwealth was rising to power. It was peopled by immigrants who came
2mo i, 1:down the Ohio in fleets of boats or crossed the Mississippi from
2mo i, 1:Kentucky and Tennessee. Thrifty Germans from Pennsylvania, hardy farmers
2mo i, 1:from Virginia ready to work with their own hands, freemen seeking
2mo i, 1:freemen's homes, planters with their slaves moving on from worn-out
2mo i, 1:fields on the seaboard, came together in the widening settlements of the
2mo i, 1:Missouri country. Peoples from the North and South flowed together,
2mo i, 1:small farmers and big planters mingling in one community. When their
2mo i, 1:numbers had reached sixty thousand or more, they precipitated a contest
2mo i, 1:over their admission to the union, "ringing an alarm bell in the night,"
2mo i, 1:as Jefferson phrased it. The favorite expedient of compromise with
2mo i, 1:slavery was brought forth in Congress once more. Maine consequently was
2mo i, 1:brought into the union without slavery and Missouri with slavery. At the
2mo i, 1:same time there was drawn westward through the rest of the Louisiana
2mo i, 1:territory a line separating servitude from slavery.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:THE SPIRIT OF THE FRONTIER
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Land Tenure and Liberty.=--Over an immense western area there developed
2mo i, 1:an unbroken system of freehold farms. In the Gulf states and the lower
2mo i, 1:Mississippi Valley, it is true, the planter with his many slaves even
2mo i, 1:led in the pioneer movement; but through large sections of Tennessee and
2mo i, 1:Kentucky, as well as upper Georgia and Alabama, and all throughout the
2mo i, 1:Northwest territory the small farmer reigned supreme. In this immense
2mo i, 1:dominion there sprang up a civilization without caste or class--a body
2mo i, 1:of people all having about the same amount of this world's goods and
2mo i, 1:deriving their livelihood from one source: the labor of their own hands
2mo i, 1:on the soil. The Northwest territory alone almost equaled in area all
2mo i, 1:the original thirteen states combined, except Georgia, and its system of
2mo i, 1:agricultural economy was unbroken by plantations and feudal estates. "In
2mo i, 1:the subdivision of the soil and the great equality of condition," as
2mo i, 1:Webster said on more than one occasion, "lay the true basis, most
2mo i, 1:certainly, of popular government." There was the undoubted source of
2mo i, 1:Jacksonian democracy.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:[Illustration: A LOG CABIN--LINCOLN'S BIRTHPLACE]
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Characteristics of the Western People.=--Travelers into the
2mo i, 1:Northwest during the early years of the nineteenth century were agreed
2mo i, 1:that the people of that region were almost uniformly marked by the
2mo i, 1:characteristics common to an independent yeomanry. A close observer thus
2mo i, 1:recorded his impressions: "A spirit of adventurous enterprise, a
2mo i, 1:willingness to go through any hardship to accomplish an object....
2mo i, 1:Independence of thought and action. They have felt the influence of
2mo i, 1:these principles from their childhood. Men who can endure anything; that
2mo i, 1:have lived almost without restraint, free as the mountain air or as the
2mo i, 1:deer and the buffalo of their forests, and who know they are Americans
2mo i, 1:all.... An apparent roughness which some would deem rudeness of
2mo i, 1:manner.... Where there is perfect equality in a neighborhood of people
2mo i, 1:who know little about each other's previous history or ancestry but
2mo i, 1:where each is lord of the soil he cultivates. Where a log cabin is all
2mo i, 1:that the best of families can expect to have for years and of course can
2mo i, 1:possess few of the external decorations which have so much influence in
2mo i, 1:creating a diversity of rank in society. These circumstances have laid
2mo i, 1:the foundation for that equality of intercourse, simplicity of manners,
2mo i, 1:want of deference, want of reserve, great readiness to make
2mo i, 1:acquaintances, freedom of speech, indisposition to brook real or
2mo i, 1:imaginary insults which one witnesses among people of the West."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:This equality, this independence, this rudeness so often described by
2mo i, 1:the traveler as marking a new country, were all accentuated by the
2mo i, 1:character of the settlers themselves. Traces of the fierce, unsociable,
2mo i, 1:eagle-eyed, hard-drinking hunter remained. The settlers who followed the
2mo i, 1:hunter were, with some exceptions, soldiers of the Revolutionary army,
2mo i, 1:farmers of the "middling order," and mechanics from the towns,--English,
2mo i, 1:Scotch-Irish, Germans,--poor in possessions and thrown upon the labor of
2mo i, 1:their own hands for support. Sons and daughters from well-to-do Eastern
2mo i, 1:homes sometimes brought softer manners; but the equality of life and the
2mo i, 1:leveling force of labor in forest and field soon made them one in spirit
2mo i, 1:with their struggling neighbors. Even the preachers and teachers, who
2mo i, 1:came when the cabins were raised in the clearings and rude churches and
2mo i, 1:schoolhouses were built, preached sermons and taught lessons that
2mo i, 1:savored of the frontier, as any one may know who reads Peter
2mo i, 1:Cartwright's _A Muscular Christian_ or Eggleston's _The Hoosier
2mo i, 1:Schoolmaster_.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:THE WEST AND THE EAST MEET
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The East Alarmed.=--A people so independent as the Westerners and so
2mo i, 1:attached to local self-government gave the conservative East many a rude
2mo i, 1:shock, setting gentlemen in powdered wigs and knee breeches agog with
2mo i, 1:the idea that terrible things might happen in the Mississippi Valley.
2mo i, 1:Not without good grounds did Washington fear that "a touch of a feather
2mo i, 1:would turn" the Western settlers away from the seaboard to the
2mo i, 1:Spaniards; and seriously did he urge the East not to neglect them, lest
2mo i, 1:they be "drawn into the arms of, or be dependent upon foreigners."
2mo i, 1:Taking advantage of the restless spirit in the Southwest, Aaron Burr,
2mo i, 1:having disgraced himself by killing Alexander Hamilton in a duel, laid
2mo i, 1:wild plans, if not to bring about a secession in that region, at least
2mo i, 1:to build a state of some kind out of the Spanish dominions adjoining
2mo i, 1:Louisiana. Frightened at such enterprises and fearing the dominance of
2mo i, 1:the West, the Federalists, with a few conspicuous exceptions, opposed
2mo i, 1:equality between the sections. Had their narrow views prevailed, the
2mo i, 1:West, with its new democracy, would have been held in perpetual tutelage
2mo i, 1:to the seaboard or perhaps been driven into independence as the thirteen
2mo i, 1:colonies had been not long before.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Eastern Friends of the West.=--Fortunately for the nation, there were
2mo i, 1:many Eastern leaders, particularly from the South, who understood the
2mo i, 1:West, approved its spirit, and sought to bring the two sections together
2mo i, 1:by common bonds. Washington kept alive and keen the zeal for Western
2mo i, 1:advancement which he acquired in his youth as a surveyor. He never grew
2mo i, 1:tired of urging upon his Eastern friends the importance of the lands
2mo i, 1:beyond the mountains. He pressed upon the governor of Virginia a project
2mo i, 1:for a wagon road connecting the seaboard with the Ohio country and was
2mo i, 1:active in a movement to improve the navigation of the Potomac. He
2mo i, 1:advocated strengthening the ties of commerce. "Smooth the roads," he
2mo i, 1:said, "and make easy the way for them, and then see what an influx of
2mo i, 1:articles will be poured upon us; how amazingly our exports will be
2mo i, 1:increased by them; and how amply we shall be compensated for any trouble
2mo i, 1:and expense we may encounter to effect it." Jefferson, too, was
2mo i, 1:interested in every phase of Western development--the survey of lands,
2mo i, 1:the exploration of waterways, the opening of trade, and even the
2mo i, 1:discovery of the bones of prehistoric animals. Robert Fulton, the
2mo i, 1:inventor of the steamboat, was another man of vision who for many years
2mo i, 1:pressed upon his countrymen the necessity of uniting East and West by a
2mo i, 1:canal which would cement the union, raise the value of the public lands,
2mo i, 1:and extend the principles of confederate and republican government.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Difficulties of Early Transportation.=--Means of communication
2mo i, 1:played an important part in the strategy of all those who sought to
2mo i, 1:bring together the seaboard and the frontier. The produce of the
2mo i, 1:West--wheat, corn, bacon, hemp, cattle, and tobacco--was bulky and the
2mo i, 1:cost of overland transportation was prohibitive. In the Eastern market,
2mo i, 1:"a cow and her calf were given for a bushel of salt, while a suit of
2mo i, 1:'store clothes' cost as much as a farm." In such circumstances, the
2mo i, 1:inhabitants of the Mississippi Valley were forced to ship their produce
2mo i, 1:over a long route by way of New Orleans and to pay high freight rates
2mo i, 1:for everything that was brought across the mountains. Scows of from five
2mo i, 1:to fifty tons were built at the towns along the rivers and piloted down
2mo i, 1:the stream to the Crescent City. In a few cases small ocean-going
2mo i, 1:vessels were built to transport goods to the West Indies or to the
2mo i, 1:Eastern coast towns. Salt, iron, guns, powder, and the absolute
2mo i, 1:essentials which the pioneers had to buy mainly in Eastern markets were
2mo i, 1:carried over narrow wagon trails that were almost impassable in the
2mo i, 1:rainy season.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The National Road.=--To far-sighted men, like Albert Gallatin, "the
2mo i, 1:father of internal improvements," the solution of this problem was the
2mo i, 1:construction of roads and canals. Early in Jefferson's administration,
2mo i, 1:Congress dedicated a part of the proceeds from the sale of lands to
2mo i, 1:building highways from the headwaters of the navigable waters emptying
2mo i, 1:into the Atlantic to the Ohio River and beyond into the Northwest
2mo i, 1:territory. In 1806, after many misgivings, it authorized a great
2mo i, 1:national highway binding the East and the West. The Cumberland Road, as
2mo i, 1:it was called, began in northwestern Maryland, wound through southern
2mo i, 1:Pennsylvania, crossed the narrow neck of Virginia at Wheeling, and then
2mo i, 1:shot almost straight across Ohio, Indiana, and Illinois, into Missouri.
2mo i, 1:By 1817, stagecoaches were running between Washington and Wheeling; by
2mo i, 1:1833 contractors had carried their work to Columbus, Ohio, and by 1852,
2mo i, 1:to Vandalia, Illinois. Over this ballasted road mail and passenger
2mo i, 1:coaches could go at high speed, and heavy freight wagons proceed in
2mo i, 1:safety at a steady pace.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:[Illustration: THE CUMBERLAND ROAD]
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Canals and Steamboats.=--A second epoch in the economic union of the
2mo i, 1:East and West was reached with the opening of the Erie Canal in 1825,
2mo i, 1:offering an all-water route from New York City to the Great Lakes and
2mo i, 1:the Mississippi Valley. Pennsylvania, alarmed by the advantages
2mo i, 1:conferred on New York by this enterprise, began her system of canals and
2mo i, 1:portages from Philadelphia to Pittsburgh, completing the last link in
2mo i, 1:1834. In the South, the Chesapeake and Ohio Company, chartered in 1825,
2mo i, 1:was busy with a project to connect Georgetown and Cumberland when
2mo i, 1:railways broke in upon the undertaking before it was half finished.
2mo i, 1:About the same time, Ohio built a canal across the state, affording
2mo i, 1:water communication between Lake Erie and the Ohio River through a rich
2mo i, 1:wheat belt. Passengers could now travel by canal boat into the West with
2mo i, 1:comparative ease and comfort, if not at a rapid speed, and the bulkiest
2mo i, 1:of freight could be easily handled. Moreover, the rate charged for
2mo i, 1:carrying goods was cut by the Erie Canal from $32 a ton per hundred
2mo i, 1:miles to $1. New Orleans was destined to lose her primacy in the
2mo i, 1:Mississippi Valley.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The diversion of traffic to Eastern markets was also stimulated by
2mo i, 1:steamboats which appeared on the Ohio about 1810, three years after
2mo i, 1:Fulton had made his famous trip on the Hudson. It took twenty men to
2mo i, 1:sail and row a five-ton scow up the river at a speed of from ten to
2mo i, 1:twenty miles a day. In 1825, Timothy Flint traveled a hundred miles a
2mo i, 1:day on the new steamer _Grecian_ "against the whole weight of the
2mo i, 1:Mississippi current." Three years later the round trip from Louisville
2mo i, 1:to New Orleans was cut to eight days. Heavy produce that once had to
2mo i, 1:float down to New Orleans could be carried upstream and sent to the East
2mo i, 1:by way of the canal systems.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:[Illustration: _From an old print_
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:AN EARLY MISSISSIPPI STEAMBOAT]
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Thus the far country was brought near. The timid no longer hesitated at
2mo i, 1:the thought of the perilous journey. All routes were crowded with
2mo i, 1:Western immigrants. The forests fell before the ax like grain before the
2mo i, 1:sickle. Clearings scattered through the woods spread out into a great
2mo i, 1:mosaic of farms stretching from the Southern Appalachians to Lake
2mo i, 1:Michigan. The national census of 1830 gave 937,000 inhabitants to Ohio;
2mo i, 1:343,000 to Indiana; 157,000 to Illinois; 687,000 to Kentucky; and
2mo i, 1:681,000 to Tennessee.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:[Illustration: DISTRIBUTION OF POPULATION, 1830]
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:With the increase in population and the growth of agriculture came
2mo i, 1:political influence. People who had once petitioned Congress now sent
2mo i, 1:their own representatives. Men who had hitherto accepted without
2mo i, 1:protests Presidents from the seaboard expressed a new spirit of dissent
2mo i, 1:in 1824 by giving only three electoral votes for John Quincy Adams; and
2mo i, 1:four years later they sent a son of the soil from Tennessee, Andrew
2mo i, 1:Jackson, to take Washington's chair as chief executive of the
2mo i, 1:nation--the first of a long line of Presidents from the Mississippi
2mo i, 1:basin.
