2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:CHAPTER XI
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:JACKSONIAN DEMOCRACY
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The New England Federalists, at the Hartford convention, prophesied that
2mo i, 1:in time the West would dominate the East. "At the adoption of the
2mo i, 1:Constitution," they said, "a certain balance of power among the original
2mo i, 1:states was considered to exist, and there was at that time and yet is
2mo i, 1:among those parties a strong affinity between their great and general
2mo i, 1:interests. By the admission of these [new] states that balance has been
2mo i, 1:materially affected and unless the practice be modified must ultimately
2mo i, 1:be destroyed. The Southern states will first avail themselves of their
2mo i, 1:new confederates to govern the East, and finally the Western states,
2mo i, 1:multiplied in number, and augmented in population, will control the
2mo i, 1:interests of the whole." Strangely enough the fulfillment of this
2mo i, 1:prophecy was being prepared even in Federalist strongholds by the rise
2mo i, 1:of a new urban democracy that was to make common cause with the farmers
2mo i, 1:beyond the mountains.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:THE DEMOCRATIC MOVEMENT IN THE EAST
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Aristocratic Features of the Old Order.=--The Revolutionary
2mo i, 1:fathers, in setting up their first state constitutions, although they
2mo i, 1:often spoke of government as founded on the consent of the governed, did
2mo i, 1:not think that consistency required giving the vote to all adult males.
2mo i, 1:On the contrary they looked upon property owners as the only safe
2mo i, 1:"depositary" of political power. They went back to the colonial
2mo i, 1:tradition that related taxation and representation. This, they argued,
2mo i, 1:was not only just but a safeguard against the "excesses of democracy."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:In carrying their theory into execution they placed taxpaying or
2mo i, 1:property qualifications on the right to vote. Broadly speaking, these
2mo i, 1:limitations fell into three classes. Three states, Pennsylvania (1776),
2mo i, 1:New Hampshire (1784), and Georgia (1798), gave the ballot to all who
2mo i, 1:paid taxes, without reference to the value of their property. Three,
2mo i, 1:Virginia, Delaware, and Rhode Island, clung firmly to the ancient
2mo i, 1:principles that only freeholders could be intrusted with electoral
2mo i, 1:rights. Still other states, while closely restricting the suffrage,
2mo i, 1:accepted the ownership of other things as well as land in fulfillment of
2mo i, 1:the requirements. In Massachusetts, for instance, the vote was granted
2mo i, 1:to all men who held land yielding an annual income of three pounds or
2mo i, 1:possessed other property worth sixty pounds.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The electors thus enfranchised, numerous as they were, owing to the wide
2mo i, 1:distribution of land, often suffered from a very onerous disability. In
2mo i, 1:many states they were able to vote only for persons of wealth because
2mo i, 1:heavy property qualifications were imposed on public officers. In New
2mo i, 1:Hampshire, the governor had to be worth five hundred pounds, one-half in
2mo i, 1:land; in Massachusetts, one thousand pounds, all freehold; in Maryland,
2mo i, 1:five thousand pounds, one thousand of which was freehold; in North
2mo i, 1:Carolina, one thousand pounds freehold; and in South Carolina, ten
2mo i, 1:thousand pounds freehold. A state senator in Massachusetts had to be the
2mo i, 1:owner of a freehold worth three hundred pounds or personal property
2mo i, 1:worth six hundred pounds; in New Jersey, one thousand pounds' worth of
2mo i, 1:property; in North Carolina, three hundred acres of land; in South
2mo i, 1:Carolina, two thousand pounds freehold. For members of the lower house
2mo i, 1:of the legislature lower qualifications were required.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:In most of the states the suffrage or office holding or both were
2mo i, 1:further restricted by religious provisions. No single sect was powerful
2mo i, 1:enough to dominate after the Revolution, but, for the most part,
2mo i, 1:Catholics and Jews were either disfranchised or excluded from office.
2mo i, 1:North Carolina and Georgia denied the ballot to any one who was not a
2mo i, 1:Protestant. Delaware withheld it from all who did not believe in the
2mo i, 1:Trinity and the inspiration of the Scriptures. Massachusetts and
2mo i, 1:Maryland limited it to Christians. Virginia and New York, advanced for
2mo i, 1:their day, made no discrimination in government on account of religious
2mo i, 1:opinion.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Defense of the Old Order.=--It must not be supposed that property
2mo i, 1:qualifications were thoughtlessly imposed at the outset or considered of
2mo i, 1:little consequence in practice. In the beginning they were viewed as
2mo i, 1:fundamental. As towns grew in size and the number of landless citizens
2mo i, 1:increased, the restrictions were defended with even more vigor. In
2mo i, 1:Massachusetts, the great Webster upheld the rights of property in
2mo i, 1:government, saying: "It is entirely just that property should have its
2mo i, 1:due weight and consideration in political arrangements.... The
2mo i, 1:disastrous revolutions which the world has witnessed, those political
2mo i, 1:thunderstorms and earthquakes which have shaken the pillars of society
2mo i, 1:to their deepest foundations, have been revolutions against property."
2mo i, 1:In Pennsylvania, a leader in local affairs cried out against a plan to
2mo i, 1:remove the taxpaying limitation on the suffrage: "What does the delegate
2mo i, 1:propose? To place the vicious vagrant, the wandering Arabs, the Tartar
2mo i, 1:hordes of our large cities on the level with the virtuous and good man?"
2mo i, 1:In Virginia, Jefferson himself had first believed in property
2mo i, 1:qualifications and had feared with genuine alarm the "mobs of the great
2mo i, 1:cities." It was near the end of the eighteenth century before he
2mo i, 1:accepted the idea of manhood suffrage. Even then he was unable to
2mo i, 1:convince the constitution-makers of his own state. "It is not an idle
2mo i, 1:chimera of the brain," urged one of them, "that the possession of land
2mo i, 1:furnishes the strongest evidence of permanent, common interest with, and
2mo i, 1:attachment to, the community.... It is upon this foundation I wish to
2mo i, 1:place the right of suffrage. This is the best general standard which can
2mo i, 1:be resorted to for the purpose of determining whether the persons to be
2mo i, 1:invested with the right of suffrage are such persons as could be,
2mo i, 1:consistently with the safety and well-being of the community, intrusted
2mo i, 1:with the exercise of that right."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Attacks on the Restricted Suffrage.=--The changing circumstances of
2mo i, 1:American life, however, soon challenged the rule of those with property.
2mo i, 1:Prominent among the new forces were the rising mercantile and business
2mo i, 1:interests. Where the freehold qualification was applied, business men
2mo i, 1:who did not own land were deprived of the vote and excluded from office.
2mo i, 1:In New York, for example, the most illiterate farmer who had one hundred
2mo i, 1:pounds' worth of land could vote for state senator and governor, while
2mo i, 1:the landless banker or merchant could not. It is not surprising,
2mo i, 1:therefore, to find business men taking the lead in breaking down
2mo i, 1:freehold limitations on the suffrage. The professional classes also were
2mo i, 1:interested in removing the barriers which excluded many of them from
2mo i, 1:public affairs. It was a schoolmaster, Thomas Dorr, who led the popular
2mo i, 1:uprising in Rhode Island which brought the exclusive rule by freeholders
2mo i, 1:to an end.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:In addition to the business and professional classes, the mechanics of
2mo i, 1:the towns showed a growing hostility to a system of government that
2mo i, 1:generally barred them from voting or holding office. Though not
2mo i, 1:numerous, they had early begun to exercise an influence on the course of
2mo i, 1:public affairs. They had led the riots against the Stamp Act, overturned
2mo i, 1:King George's statue, and "crammed stamps down the throats of
2mo i, 1:collectors." When the state constitutions were framed they took a lively
2mo i, 1:interest, particularly in New York City and Philadelphia. In June, 1776,
2mo i, 1:the "mechanicks in union" in New York protested against putting the new
2mo i, 1:state constitution into effect without their approval, declaring that
2mo i, 1:the right to vote on the acceptance or rejection of a fundamental law
2mo i, 1:"is the birthright of every man to whatever state he may belong." Though
2mo i, 1:their petition was rejected, their spirit remained. When, a few years
2mo i, 1:later, the federal Constitution was being framed, the mechanics watched
2mo i, 1:the process with deep concern; they knew that one of its main objects
2mo i, 1:was to promote trade and commerce, affecting directly their daily bread.
2mo i, 1:During the struggle over ratification, they passed resolutions approving
2mo i, 1:its provisions and they often joined in parades organized to stir up
2mo i, 1:sentiment for the Constitution, even though they could not vote for
2mo i, 1:members of the state conventions and so express their will directly.
2mo i, 1:After the organization of trade unions they collided with the courts of
2mo i, 1:law and thus became interested in the election of judges and lawmakers.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Those who attacked the old system of class rule found a strong moral
2mo i, 1:support in the Declaration of Independence. Was it not said that all men
2mo i, 1:are created equal? Whoever runs may read. Was it not declared that
2mo i, 1:governments derive their just power from the consent of the governed?
2mo i, 1:That doctrine was applied with effect to George III and seemed
2mo i, 1:appropriate for use against the privileged classes of Massachusetts or
2mo i, 1:Virginia. "How do the principles thus proclaimed," asked the
2mo i, 1:non-freeholders of Richmond, in petitioning for the ballot, "accord with
2mo i, 1:the existing regulation of the suffrage? A regulation which, instead of
2mo i, 1:the equality nature ordains, creates an odious distinction between
2mo i, 1:members of the same community ... and vests in a favored class, not in
2mo i, 1:consideration of their public services but of their private possessions,
2mo i, 1:the highest of all privileges."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Abolition of Property Qualifications.=--By many minor victories rather
2mo i, 1:than by any spectacular triumphs did the advocates of manhood suffrage
2mo i, 1:carry the day. Slight gains were made even during the Revolution or
2mo i, 1:shortly afterward. In Pennsylvania, the mechanics, by taking an active
2mo i, 1:part in the contest over the Constitution of 1776, were able to force
2mo i, 1:the qualification down to the payment of a small tax. Vermont came into
2mo i, 1:the union in 1792 without any property restrictions. In the same year
2mo i, 1:Delaware gave the vote to all men who paid taxes. Maryland, reckoned one
2mo i, 1:of the most conservative of states, embarked on the experiment of
2mo i, 1:manhood suffrage in 1809; and nine years later, Connecticut, equally
2mo i, 1:conservative, decided that all taxpayers were worthy of the ballot.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Five states, Massachusetts, New York, Virginia, Rhode Island, and North
2mo i, 1:Carolina, remained obdurate while these changes were going on around
2mo i, 1:them; finally they had to yield themselves. The last struggle in
2mo i, 1:Massachusetts took place in the constitutional convention of 1820. There
2mo i, 1:Webster, in the prime of his manhood, and John Adams, in the closing
2mo i, 1:years of his old age, alike protested against such radical innovations
2mo i, 1:as manhood suffrage. Their protests were futile. The property test was
2mo i, 1:abolished and a small tax-paying qualification was substituted. New York
2mo i, 1:surrendered the next year and, after trying some minor restrictions for
2mo i, 1:five years, went completely over to white manhood suffrage in 1826.
2mo i, 1:Rhode Island clung to her freehold qualification through thirty years of
2mo i, 1:agitation. Then Dorr's Rebellion, almost culminating in bloodshed,
2mo i, 1:brought about a reform in 1843 which introduced a slight tax-paying
2mo i, 1:qualification as an alternative to the freehold. Virginia and North
2mo i, 1:Carolina were still unconvinced. The former refused to abandon ownership
2mo i, 1:of land as the test for political rights until 1850 and the latter until
2mo i, 1:1856. Although religious discriminations and property qualifications for
2mo i, 1:office holders were sometimes retained after the establishment of
2mo i, 1:manhood suffrage, they were usually abolished along with the monopoly of
2mo i, 1:government enjoyed by property owners and taxpayers.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:[Illustration: THOMAS DORR AROUSING HIS FOLLOWERS]
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:At the end of the first quarter of the nineteenth century, the white
2mo i, 1:male industrial workers and the mechanics of the Northern cities, at
2mo i, 1:least, could lay aside the petition for the ballot and enjoy with the
2mo i, 1:free farmer a voice in the government of their common country.
2mo i, 1:"Universal democracy," sighed Carlyle, who was widely read in the United
2mo i, 1:States, "whatever we may think of it has declared itself the inevitable
2mo i, 1:fact of the days in which we live; and he who has any chance to instruct
2mo i, 1:or lead in these days must begin by admitting that ... Where no
2mo i, 1:government is wanted, save that of the parish constable, as in America
2mo i, 1:with its boundless soil, every man being able to find work and
2mo i, 1:recompense for himself, democracy may subsist; not elsewhere." Amid the
2mo i, 1:grave misgivings of the first generation of statesmen, America was
2mo i, 1:committed to the great adventure, in the populous towns of the East as
2mo i, 1:well as in the forests and fields of the West.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:THE NEW DEMOCRACY ENTERS THE ARENA
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The spirit of the new order soon had a pronounced effect on the
2mo i, 1:machinery of government and the practice of politics. The enfranchised
2mo i, 1:electors were not long in demanding for themselves a larger share in
2mo i, 1:administration.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Spoils System and Rotation in Office.=--First of all they wanted
2mo i, 1:office for themselves, regardless of their fitness. They therefore
2mo i, 1:extended the system of rewarding party workers with government
2mo i, 1:positions--a system early established in several states, notably New
2mo i, 1:York and Pennsylvania. Closely connected with it was the practice of
2mo i, 1:fixing short terms for officers and making frequent changes in
2mo i, 1:personnel. "Long continuance in office," explained a champion of this
2mo i, 1:idea in Pennsylvania in 1837, "unfits a man for the discharge of its
2mo i, 1:duties, by rendering him arbitrary and aristocratic, and tends to beget,
2mo i, 1:first life office, and then hereditary office, which leads to the
2mo i, 1:destruction of free government." The solution offered was the historic
2mo i, 1:doctrine of "rotation in office." At the same time the principle of
2mo i, 1:popular election was extended to an increasing number of officials who
2mo i, 1:had once been appointed either by the governor or the legislature. Even
2mo i, 1:geologists, veterinarians, surveyors, and other technical officers were
2mo i, 1:declared elective on the theory that their appointment "smacked of
2mo i, 1:monarchy."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Popular Election of Presidential Electors.=--In a short time the spirit
2mo i, 1:of democracy, while playing havoc with the old order in state
2mo i, 1:government, made its way upward into the federal system. The framers of
2mo i, 1:the Constitution, bewildered by many proposals and unable to agree on
2mo i, 1:any single plan, had committed the choice of presidential electors to
2mo i, 1:the discretion of the state legislatures. The legislatures, in turn,
2mo i, 1:greedy of power, early adopted the practice of choosing the electors
2mo i, 1:themselves; but they did not enjoy it long undisturbed. Democracy,
2mo i, 1:thundering at their doors, demanded that they surrender the privilege to
2mo i, 1:the people. Reluctantly they yielded, sometimes granting popular
2mo i, 1:election and then withdrawing it. The drift was inevitable, and the
2mo i, 1:climax came with the advent of Jacksonian democracy. In 1824, Vermont,
2mo i, 1:New York, Delaware, South Carolina, Georgia, and Louisiana, though some
2mo i, 1:had experimented with popular election, still left the choice of
2mo i, 1:electors with the legislature. Eight years later South Carolina alone
2mo i, 1:held to the old practice. Popular election had become the final word.
2mo i, 1:The fanciful idea of an electoral college of "good and wise men,"
2mo i, 1:selected without passion or partisanship by state legislatures acting as
2mo i, 1:deliberative bodies, was exploded for all time; the election of the
2mo i, 1:nation's chief magistrate was committed to the tempestuous methods of
2mo i, 1:democracy.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Nominating Convention.=--As the suffrage was widened and the
2mo i, 1:popular choice of presidential electors extended, there arose a violent
2mo i, 1:protest against the methods used by the political parties in nominating
2mo i, 1:candidates. After the retirement of Washington, both the Republicans and
2mo i, 1:the Federalists found it necessary to agree upon their favorites before
2mo i, 1:the election, and they adopted a colonial device--the pre-election
2mo i, 1:caucus. The Federalist members of Congress held a conference and
2mo i, 1:selected their candidate, and the Republicans followed the example. In
2mo i, 1:a short time the practice of nominating by a "congressional caucus"
2mo i, 1:became a recognized institution. The election still remained with the
2mo i, 1:people; but the power of picking candidates for their approval passed
2mo i, 1:into the hands of a small body of Senators and Representatives.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:A reaction against this was unavoidable. To friends of "the plain
2mo i, 1:people," like Andrew Jackson, it was intolerable, all the more so
2mo i, 1:because the caucus never favored him with the nomination. More
2mo i, 1:conservative men also found grave objections to it. They pointed out
2mo i, 1:that, whereas the Constitution intended the President to be an
2mo i, 1:independent officer, he had now fallen under the control of a caucus of
2mo i, 1:congressmen. The supremacy of the legislative branch had been obtained
2mo i, 1:by an extra-legal political device. To such objections were added
2mo i, 1:practical considerations. In 1824, when personal rivalry had taken the
2mo i, 1:place of party conflicts, the congressional caucus selected as the
2mo i, 1:candidate, William H. Crawford, of Georgia, a man of distinction but no
2mo i, 1:great popularity, passing by such an obvious hero as General Jackson.
2mo i, 1:The followers of the General were enraged and demanded nothing short of
2mo i, 1:the death of "King Caucus." Their clamor was effective. Under their
2mo i, 1:attacks, the caucus came to an ignominious end.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:In place of it there arose in 1831 a new device, the national nominating
2mo i, 1:convention, composed of delegates elected by party voters for the sole
2mo i, 1:purpose of nominating candidates. Senators and Representatives were
2mo i, 1:still prominent in the party councils, but they were swamped by hundreds
2mo i, 1:of delegates "fresh from the people," as Jackson was wont to say. In
2mo i, 1:fact, each convention was made up mainly of office holders and office
2mo i, 1:seekers, and the new institution was soon denounced as vigorously as
2mo i, 1:King Caucus had been, particularly by statesmen who failed to obtain a
2mo i, 1:nomination. Still it grew in strength and by 1840 was firmly
2mo i, 1:established.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The End of the Old Generation.=--In the election of 1824, the
2mo i, 1:representatives of the "aristocracy" made their last successful stand.
2mo i, 1:Until then the leadership by men of "wealth and talents" had been
2mo i, 1:undisputed. There had been five Presidents--Washington, John Adams,
2mo i, 1:Jefferson, Madison, and Monroe--all Eastern men brought up in prosperous
2mo i, 1:families with the advantages of culture which come from leisure and the
2mo i, 1:possession of life's refinements. None of them had ever been compelled
2mo i, 1:to work with his hands for a livelihood. Four of them had been
2mo i, 1:slaveholders. Jefferson was a philosopher, learned in natural science, a
2mo i, 1:master of foreign languages, a gentleman of dignity and grace of manner,
2mo i, 1:notwithstanding his studied simplicity. Madison, it was said, was armed
2mo i, 1:"with all the culture of his century." Monroe was a graduate of William
2mo i, 1:and Mary, a gentleman of the old school. Jefferson and his three
2mo i, 1:successors called themselves Republicans and professed a genuine faith
2mo i, 1:in the people but they were not "of the people" themselves; they were
2mo i, 1:not sons of the soil or the workshop. They were all men of "the grand
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:old order of society" who gave finish and style even to popular
2mo i, 1:government.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Monroe was the last of the Presidents belonging to the heroic epoch of
2mo i, 1:the Revolution. He had served in the war for independence, in the
2mo i, 1:Congress under the Articles of Confederation, and in official capacity
2mo i, 1:after the adoption of the Constitution. In short, he was of the age that
2mo i, 1:had wrought American independence and set the government afloat. With
2mo i, 1:his passing, leadership went to a new generation; but his successor,
2mo i, 1:John Quincy Adams, formed a bridge between the old and the new in that
2mo i, 1:he combined a high degree of culture with democratic sympathies.
2mo i, 1:Washington had died in 1799, preceded but a few months by Patrick Henry
2mo i, 1:and followed in four years by Samuel Adams. Hamilton had been killed in
2mo i, 1:a duel with Burr in 1804. Thomas Jefferson and John Adams were yet alive
2mo i, 1:in 1824 but they were soon to pass from the scene, reconciled at last,
2mo i, 1:full of years and honors. Madison was in dignified retirement, destined
2mo i, 1:to live long enough to protest against the doctrine of nullification
2mo i, 1:proclaimed by South Carolina before death carried him away at the ripe
2mo i, 1:old age of eighty-five.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Election of John Quincy Adams (1824).=--The campaign of 1824 marked
2mo i, 1:the end of the "era of good feeling" inaugurated by the collapse of the
2mo i, 1:Federalist party after the election of 1816. There were four leading
2mo i, 1:candidates, John Quincy Adams, Andrew Jackson, Henry Clay, and W.H.
2mo i, 1:Crawford. The result of the election was a division of the electoral
2mo i, 1:votes into four parts and no one received a majority. Under the
2mo i, 1:Constitution, therefore, the selection of President passed to the House
2mo i, 1:of Representatives. Clay, who stood at the bottom of the poll, threw his
2mo i, 1:weight to Adams and assured his triumph, much to the chagrin of
2mo i, 1:Jackson's friends. They thought, with a certain justification, that
2mo i, 1:inasmuch as the hero of New Orleans had received the largest electoral
2mo i, 1:vote, the House was morally bound to accept the popular judgment and
2mo i, 1:make him President. Jackson shook hands cordially with Adams on the day
2mo i, 1:of the inauguration, but never forgave him for being elected.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:While Adams called himself a Republican in politics and often spoke of
2mo i, 1:"the rule of the people," he was regarded by Jackson's followers as "an
2mo i, 1:aristocrat." He was not a son of the soil. Neither was he acquainted at
2mo i, 1:first hand with the labor of farmers and mechanics. He had been educated
2mo i, 1:at Harvard and in Europe. Like his illustrious father, John Adams, he
2mo i, 1:was a stern and reserved man, little given to seeking popularity.
2mo i, 1:Moreover, he was from the East and the frontiersmen of the West regarded
2mo i, 1:him as a man "born with a silver spoon in his mouth." Jackson's
2mo i, 1:supporters especially disliked him because they thought their hero
2mo i, 1:entitled to the presidency. Their anger was deepened when Adams
2mo i, 1:appointed Clay to the office of Secretary of State; and they set up a
2mo i, 1:cry that there had been a "deal" by which Clay had helped to elect Adams
2mo i, 1:to get office for himself.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Though Adams conducted his administration with great dignity and in a
2mo i, 1:fine spirit of public service, he was unable to overcome the opposition
2mo i, 1:which he encountered on his election to office or to win popularity in
2mo i, 1:the West and South. On the contrary, by advocating government assistance
2mo i, 1:in building roads and canals and public grants in aid of education,
2mo i, 1:arts, and sciences, he ran counter to the current which had set in
2mo i, 1:against appropriations of federal funds for internal improvements. By
2mo i, 1:signing the Tariff Bill of 1828, soon known as the "Tariff of
2mo i, 1:Abominations," he made new enemies without adding to his friends in New
2mo i, 1:York, Pennsylvania, and Ohio where he sorely needed them. Handicapped by
2mo i, 1:the false charge that he had been a party to a "corrupt bargain" with
2mo i, 1:Clay to secure his first election; attacked for his advocacy of a high
2mo i, 1:protective tariff; charged with favoring an "aristocracy of
2mo i, 1:office-holders" in Washington on account of his refusal to discharge
2mo i, 1:government clerks by the wholesale, Adams was retired from the White
2mo i, 1:House after he had served four years.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Triumph of Jackson in 1828.=--Probably no candidate for the
2mo i, 1:presidency ever had such passionate popular support as Andrew Jackson
2mo i, 1:had in 1828. He was truly a man of the people. Born of poor parents in
2mo i, 1:the upland region of South Carolina, schooled in poverty and adversity,
2mo i, 1:without the advantages of education or the refinements of cultivated
2mo i, 1:leisure, he seemed the embodiment of the spirit of the new American
2mo i, 1:democracy. Early in his youth he had gone into the frontier of Tennessee
2mo i, 1:where he soon won a name as a fearless and intrepid Indian fighter. On
2mo i, 1:the march and in camp, he endeared himself to his men by sharing their
2mo i, 1:hardships, sleeping on the ground with them, and eating parched corn
2mo i, 1:when nothing better could be found for the privates. From local
2mo i, 1:prominence he sprang into national fame by his exploit at the battle of
2mo i, 1:New Orleans. His reputation as a military hero was enhanced by the
2mo i, 1:feeling that he had been a martyr to political treachery in 1824. The
2mo i, 1:farmers of the West and South claimed him as their own. The mechanics of
2mo i, 1:the Eastern cities, newly enfranchised, also looked upon him as their
2mo i, 1:friend. Though his views on the tariff, internal improvements, and other
2mo i, 1:issues before the country were either vague or unknown, he was readily
2mo i, 1:elected President.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The returns of the electoral vote in 1828 revealed the sources of
2mo i, 1:Jackson's power. In New England, he received but one ballot, from
2mo i, 1:Maine; he had a majority of the electors in New York and all of them in
2mo i, 1:Pennsylvania; and he carried every state south of Maryland and beyond
2mo i, 1:the Appalachians. Adams did not get a single electoral vote in the South
2mo i, 1:and West. The prophecy of the Hartford convention had been fulfilled.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:[Illustration: ANDREW JACKSON]
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:When Jackson took the oath of office on March 4, 1829, the government of
2mo i, 1:the United States entered into a new era. Until this time the
2mo i, 1:inauguration of a President--even that of Jefferson, the apostle of
2mo i, 1:simplicity--had brought no rude shock to the course of affairs at the
2mo i, 1:capital. Hitherto the installation of a President meant that an
2mo i, 1:old-fashioned gentleman, accompanied by a few servants, had driven to
2mo i, 1:the White House in his own coach, taken the oath with quiet dignity,
2mo i, 1:appointed a few new men to the higher posts, continued in office the
2mo i, 1:long list of regular civil employees, and begun his administration with
2mo i, 1:respectable decorum. Jackson changed all this. When he was inaugurated,
2mo i, 1:men and women journeyed hundreds of miles to witness the ceremony. Great
2mo i, 1:throngs pressed into the White House, "upset the bowls of punch, broke
2mo i, 1:the glasses, and stood with their muddy boots on the satin-covered
2mo i, 1:chairs to see the people's President." If Jefferson's inauguration was,
2mo i, 1:as he called it, the "great revolution," Jackson's inauguration was a
2mo i, 1:cataclysm.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:THE NEW DEMOCRACY AT WASHINGTON
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Spoils System.=--The staid and respectable society of Washington
2mo i, 1:was disturbed by this influx of farmers and frontiersmen. To speak of
2mo i, 1:politics became "bad form" among fashionable women. The clerks and
2mo i, 1:civil servants of the government who had enjoyed long and secure tenure
2mo i, 1:of office became alarmed at the clamor of new men for their positions.
2mo i, 1:Doubtless the major portion of them had opposed the election of Jackson
2mo i, 1:and looked with feelings akin to contempt upon him and his followers.
2mo i, 1:With a hunter's instinct, Jackson scented his prey. Determined to have
2mo i, 1:none but his friends in office, he made a clean sweep, expelling old
2mo i, 1:employees to make room for men "fresh from the people." This was a new
2mo i, 1:custom. Other Presidents had discharged a few officers for engaging in
2mo i, 1:opposition politics. They had been careful in making appointments not to
2mo i, 1:choose inveterate enemies; but they discharged relatively few men on
2mo i, 1:account of their political views and partisan activities.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:By wholesale removals and the frank selection of officers on party
2mo i, 1:grounds--a practice already well intrenched in New York--Jackson
2mo i, 1:established the "spoils system" at Washington. The famous slogan, "to
2mo i, 1:the victor belong the spoils of victory," became the avowed principle of
2mo i, 1:the national government. Statesmen like Calhoun denounced it; poets like
2mo i, 1:James Russell Lowell ridiculed it; faithful servants of the government
2mo i, 1:suffered under it; but it held undisturbed sway for half a century
2mo i, 1:thereafter, each succeeding generation outdoing, if possible, its
2mo i, 1:predecessor in the use of public office for political purposes. If any
2mo i, 1:one remarked that training and experience were necessary qualifications
2mo i, 1:for important public positions, he met Jackson's own profession of
2mo i, 1:faith: "The duties of any public office are so simple or admit of being
2mo i, 1:made so simple that any man can in a short time become master of them."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Tariff and Nullification.=--Jackson had not been installed in power
2mo i, 1:very long before he was compelled to choose between states' rights and
2mo i, 1:nationalism. The immediate occasion of the trouble was the tariff--a
2mo i, 1:matter on which Jackson did not have any very decided views. His mind
2mo i, 1:did not run naturally to abstruse economic questions; and owing to the
2mo i, 1:divided opinion of the country it was "good politics" to be vague and
2mo i, 1:ambiguous in the controversy. Especially was this true, because the
2mo i, 1:tariff issue was threatening to split the country into parties again.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:_The Development of the Policy of "Protection."_--The war of 1812 and
2mo i, 1:the commercial policies of England which followed it had accentuated the
2mo i, 1:need for American economic independence. During that conflict, the
2mo i, 1:United States, cut off from English manufactures as during the
2mo i, 1:Revolution, built up home industries to meet the unusual call for iron,
2mo i, 1:steel, cloth, and other military and naval supplies as well as the
2mo i, 1:demands from ordinary markets. Iron foundries and textile mills sprang
2mo i, 1:up as in the night; hundreds of business men invested fortunes in
2mo i, 1:industrial enterprises so essential to the military needs of the
2mo i, 1:government; and the people at large fell into the habit of buying
2mo i, 1:American-made goods again. As the London _Times_ tersely observed of the
2mo i, 1:Americans, "their first war with England made them independent; their
2mo i, 1:second war made them formidable."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:In recognition of this state of affairs, the tariff of 1816 was
2mo i, 1:designed: _first_, to prevent England from ruining these "infant
2mo i, 1:industries" by dumping the accumulated stores of years suddenly upon
2mo i, 1:American markets; and, _secondly_, to enlarge in the manufacturing
2mo i, 1:centers the demand for American agricultural produce. It accomplished
2mo i, 1:the purposes of its framers. It kept in operation the mills and furnaces
2mo i, 1:so recently built. It multiplied the number of industrial workers and
2mo i, 1:enhanced the demand for the produce of the soil. It brought about
2mo i, 1:another very important result. It turned the capital and enterprise of
2mo i, 1:New England from shipping to manufacturing, and converted her statesmen,
2mo i, 1:once friends of low tariffs, into ardent advocates of protection.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:In the early years of the nineteenth century, the Yankees had bent their
2mo i, 1:energies toward building and operating ships to carry produce from
2mo i, 1:America to Europe and manufactures from Europe to America. For this
2mo i, 1:reason, they had opposed the tariff of 1816 calculated to increase
2mo i, 1:domestic production and cut down the carrying trade. Defeated in their
2mo i, 1:efforts, they accepted the inevitable and turned to manufacturing. Soon
2mo i, 1:they were powerful friends of protection for American enterprise. As the
2mo i, 1:money invested and the labor employed in the favored industries
2mo i, 1:increased, the demand for continued and heavier protection grew apace.
2mo i, 1:Even the farmers who furnished raw materials, like wool, flax, and hemp,
2mo i, 1:began to see eye to eye with the manufacturers. So the textile interests
2mo i, 1:of New England, the iron masters of Connecticut, New Jersey, and
2mo i, 1:Pennsylvania, the wool, hemp, and flax growers of Ohio, Kentucky, and
2mo i, 1:Tennessee, and the sugar planters of Louisiana developed into a
2mo i, 1:formidable combination in support of a high protective tariff.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:_The Planting States Oppose the Tariff._--In the meantime, the cotton
2mo i, 1:states on the seaboard had forgotten about the havoc wrought during the
2mo i, 1:Napoleonic wars when their produce rotted because there were no ships to
2mo i, 1:carry it to Europe. The seas were now open. The area devoted to cotton
2mo i, 1:had swiftly expanded as Alabama, Mississippi, and Louisiana were opened
2mo i, 1:up. Cotton had in fact become "king" and the planters depended for their
2mo i, 1:prosperity, as they thought, upon the sale of their staple to English
2mo i, 1:manufacturers whose spinning and weaving mills were the wonder of the
2mo i, 1:world. Manufacturing nothing and having to buy nearly everything except
2mo i, 1:farm produce and even much of that for slaves, the planters naturally
2mo i, 1:wanted to purchase manufactures in the cheapest market, England, where
2mo i, 1:they sold most of their cotton. The tariff, they contended, raised the
2mo i, 1:price of the goods they had to buy and was thus in fact a tribute laid
2mo i, 1:on them for the benefit of the Northern mill owners.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:_The Tariff of Abominations._--They were overborne, however, in 1824 and
2mo i, 1:again in 1828 when Northern manufacturers and Western farmers forced
2mo i, 1:Congress to make an upward revision of the tariff. The Act of 1828 known
2mo i, 1:as "the Tariff of Abominations," though slightly modified in 1832, was
2mo i, 1:"the straw which broke the camel's back." Southern leaders turned in
2mo i, 1:rage against the whole system. The legislatures of Virginia, North
2mo i, 1:Carolina, South Carolina, Georgia, and Alabama denounced it; a general
2mo i, 1:convention of delegates held at Augusta issued a protest of defiance
2mo i, 1:against it; and South Carolina, weary of verbal battles, decided to
2mo i, 1:prevent its enforcement.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:_South Carolina Nullifies the Tariff._--The legislature of that state,
2mo i, 1:on October 26, 1832, passed a bill calling for a state convention which
2mo i, 1:duly assembled in the following month. In no mood for compromise, it
2mo i, 1:adopted the famous Ordinance of Nullification after a few days' debate.
2mo i, 1:Every line of this document was clear and firm. The tariff, it opened,
2mo i, 1:gives "bounties to classes and individuals ... at the expense and to the
2mo i, 1:injury and oppression of other classes and individuals"; it is a
2mo i, 1:violation of the Constitution of the United States and therefore null
2mo i, 1:and void; its enforcement in South Carolina is unlawful; if the federal
2mo i, 1:government attempts to coerce the state into obeying the law, "the
2mo i, 1:people of this state will thenceforth hold themselves absolved from all
2mo i, 1:further obligations to maintain or preserve their political connection
2mo i, 1:with the people of the other states and will forthwith proceed to
2mo i, 1:organize a separate government and do all other acts and things which
2mo i, 1:sovereign and independent states may of right do."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:_Southern States Condemn Nullification._--The answer of the country to
2mo i, 1:this note of defiance, couched in the language used in the Kentucky
2mo i, 1:resolutions and by the New England Federalists during the war of 1812,
2mo i, 1:was quick and positive. The legislatures of the Southern states, while
2mo i, 1:condemning the tariff, repudiated the step which South Carolina had
2mo i, 1:taken. Georgia responded: "We abhor the doctrine of nullification as
2mo i, 1:neither a peaceful nor a constitutional remedy." Alabama found it
2mo i, 1:"unsound in theory and dangerous in practice." North Carolina replied
2mo i, 1:that it was "revolutionary in character, subversive of the Constitution
2mo i, 1:of the United States." Mississippi answered: "It is disunion by
2mo i, 1:force--it is civil war." Virginia spoke more softly, condemning the
2mo i, 1:tariff and sustaining the principle of the Virginia resolutions but
2mo i, 1:denying that South Carolina could find in them any sanction for her
2mo i, 1:proceedings.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:_Jackson Firmly Upholds the Union._--The eyes of the country were turned
2mo i, 1:upon Andrew Jackson. It was known that he looked with no friendly
2mo i, 1:feelings upon nullification, for, at a Jefferson dinner in the spring of
2mo i, 1:1830 while the subject was in the air, he had with laconic firmness
2mo i, 1:announced a toast: "Our federal union; it must be preserved." When two
2mo i, 1:years later the open challenge came from South Carolina, he replied that
2mo i, 1:he would enforce the law, saying with his frontier directness: "If a
2mo i, 1:single drop of blood shall be shed there in opposition to the laws of
2mo i, 1:the United States, I will hang the first man I can lay my hands on
2mo i, 1:engaged in such conduct upon the first tree that I can reach." He made
2mo i, 1:ready to keep his word by preparing for the use of military and naval
2mo i, 1:forces in sustaining the authority of the federal government. Then in a
2mo i, 1:long and impassioned proclamation to the people of South Carolina he
2mo i, 1:pointed out the national character of the union, and announced his
2mo i, 1:solemn resolve to preserve it by all constitutional means. Nullification
2mo i, 1:he branded as "incompatible with the existence of the union,
2mo i, 1:contradicted expressly by the letter of the Constitution, unauthorized
2mo i, 1:by its spirit, inconsistent with every principle on which it was
2mo i, 1:founded, and destructive of the great objects for which it was formed."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:_A Compromise._--In his messages to Congress, however, Jackson spoke the
2mo i, 1:language of conciliation. A few days before issuing his proclamation he
2mo i, 1:suggested that protection should be limited to the articles of domestic
2mo i, 1:manufacture indispensable to safety in war time, and shortly afterward
2mo i, 1:he asked for new legislation to aid him in enforcing the laws. With two
2mo i, 1:propositions before it, one to remove the chief grounds for South
2mo i, 1:Carolina's resistance and the other to apply force if it was continued,
2mo i, 1:Congress bent its efforts to avoid a crisis. On February 12, 1833,
2mo i, 1:Henry Clay laid before the Senate a compromise tariff bill providing for
2mo i, 1:the gradual reduction of the duties until by 1842 they would reach the
2mo i, 1:level of the law which Calhoun had supported in 1816. About the same
2mo i, 1:time the "force bill," designed to give the President ample authority in
2mo i, 1:executing the law in South Carolina, was taken up. After a short but
2mo i, 1:acrimonious debate, both measures were passed and signed by President
2mo i, 1:Jackson on the same day, March 2. Looking upon the reduction of the
2mo i, 1:tariff as a complete vindication of her policy and an undoubted victory,
2mo i, 1:South Carolina rescinded her ordinance and enacted another nullifying
2mo i, 1:the force bill.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:[Illustration: _From an old print._
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:DANIEL WEBSTER]
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:_The Webster-Hayne Debate._--Where the actual victory lay in this
2mo i, 1:quarrel, long the subject of high dispute, need not concern us to-day.
2mo i, 1:Perhaps the chief result of the whole affair was a clarification of the
2mo i, 1:issue between the North and the South--a definite statement of the
2mo i, 1:principles for which men on both sides were years afterward to lay down
2mo i, 1:their lives. On behalf of nationalism and a perpetual union, the stanch
2mo i, 1:old Democrat from Tennessee had, in his proclamation on nullification,
2mo i, 1:spoken a language that admitted of only one meaning. On behalf of
2mo i, 1:nullification, Senator Hayne, of South Carolina, a skilled lawyer and
2mo i, 1:courtly orator, had in a great speech delivered in the Senate in
2mo i, 1:January, 1830, set forth clearly and cogently the doctrine that the
2mo i, 1:union is a compact among sovereign states from which the parties may
2mo i, 1:lawfully withdraw. It was this address that called into the arena
2mo i, 1:Daniel Webster, Senator from Massachusetts, who, spreading the mantle
2mo i, 1:of oblivion over the Hartford convention, delivered a reply to Hayne
2mo i, 1:that has been reckoned among the powerful orations of all time--a plea
2mo i, 1:for the supremacy of the Constitution and the national character of the
2mo i, 1:union.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The War on the United States Bank.=--If events forced the issue of
2mo i, 1:nationalism and nullification upon Jackson, the same could not be said
2mo i, 1:of his attack on the bank. That institution, once denounced by every
2mo i, 1:true Jeffersonian, had been reestablished in 1816 under the
2mo i, 1:administration of Jefferson's disciple, James Madison. It had not been
2mo i, 1:in operation very long, however, before it aroused bitter opposition,
2mo i, 1:especially in the South and the West. Its notes drove out of circulation
2mo i, 1:the paper currency of unsound banks chartered by the states, to the
2mo i, 1:great anger of local financiers. It was accused of favoritism in making
2mo i, 1:loans, of conferring special privileges upon politicians in return for
2mo i, 1:their support at Washington. To all Jackson's followers it was "an
2mo i, 1:insidious money power." One of them openly denounced it as an
2mo i, 1:institution designed "to strengthen the arm of wealth and counterpoise
2mo i, 1:the influence of extended suffrage in the disposition of public
2mo i, 1:affairs."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:This sentiment President Jackson fully shared. In his first message to
2mo i, 1:Congress he assailed the bank in vigorous language. He declared that its
2mo i, 1:constitutionality was in doubt and alleged that it had failed to
2mo i, 1:establish a sound and uniform currency. If such an institution was
2mo i, 1:necessary, he continued, it should be a public bank, owned and managed
2mo i, 1:by the government, not a private concern endowed with special privileges
2mo i, 1:by it. In his second and third messages, Jackson came back to the
2mo i, 1:subject, leaving the decision, however, to "an enlightened people and
2mo i, 1:their representatives."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Moved by this frank hostility and anxious for the future, the bank
2mo i, 1:applied to Congress for a renewal of its charter in 1832, four years
2mo i, 1:before the expiration of its life. Clay, with his eye upon the
2mo i, 1:presidency and an issue for the campaign, warmly supported the
2mo i, 1:application. Congress, deeply impressed by his leadership, passed the
2mo i, 1:bill granting the new charter, and sent the open defiance to Jackson.
2mo i, 1:His response was an instant veto. The battle was on and it raged with
2mo i, 1:fury until the close of his second administration, ending in the
2mo i, 1:destruction of the bank, a disordered currency, and a national panic.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:In his veto message, Jackson attacked the bank as unconstitutional and
2mo i, 1:even hinted at corruption. He refused to assent to the proposition that
2mo i, 1:the Supreme Court had settled the question of constitutionality by the
2mo i, 1:decision in the McCulloch case. "Each public officer," he argued, "who
2mo i, 1:takes an oath to support the Constitution, swears that he will support
2mo i, 1:it as he understands it, not as it is understood by others."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Not satisfied with his veto and his declaration against the bank,
2mo i, 1:Jackson ordered the Secretary of the Treasury to withdraw the government
2mo i, 1:deposits which formed a large part of the institution's funds. This
2mo i, 1:action he followed up by an open charge that the bank had used money
2mo i, 1:shamefully to secure the return of its supporters to Congress. The
2mo i, 1:Senate, stung by this charge, solemnly resolved that Jackson had
2mo i, 1:"assumed upon himself authority and power not conferred by the
2mo i, 1:Constitution and laws, but in derogation of both."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The effects of the destruction of the bank were widespread. When its
2mo i, 1:charter expired in 1836, banking was once more committed to the control
2mo i, 1:of the states. The state legislatures, under a decision rendered by the
2mo i, 1:Supreme Court after the death of Marshall, began to charter banks under
2mo i, 1:state ownership and control, with full power to issue paper money--this
2mo i, 1:in spite of the provision in the Constitution that states shall not
2mo i, 1:issue bills of credit or make anything but gold and silver coin legal
2mo i, 1:tender in the payment of debts. Once more the country was flooded by
2mo i, 1:paper currency of uncertain value. To make matters worse, Jackson
2mo i, 1:adopted the practice of depositing huge amounts of government funds in
2mo i, 1:these banks, not forgetting to render favors to those institutions which
2mo i, 1:supported him in politics--"pet banks," as they were styled at the
2mo i, 1:time. In 1837, partially, though by no means entirely, as a result of
2mo i, 1:the abolition of the bank, the country was plunged into one of the most
2mo i, 1:disastrous panics which it ever experienced.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Internal Improvements Checked.=--The bank had presented to Jackson a
2mo i, 1:very clear problem--one of destruction. Other questions were not so
2mo i, 1:simple, particularly the subject of federal appropriations in aid of
2mo i, 1:roads and other internal improvements. Jefferson had strongly favored
2mo i, 1:government assistance in such matters, but his administration was
2mo i, 1:followed by a reaction. Both Madison and Monroe vetoed acts of Congress
2mo i, 1:appropriating public funds for public roads, advancing as their reason
2mo i, 1:the argument that the Constitution authorized no such laws. Jackson,
2mo i, 1:puzzled by the clamor on both sides, followed their example without
2mo i, 1:making the constitutional bar absolute. Congress, he thought, might
2mo i, 1:lawfully build highways of a national and military value, but he
2mo i, 1:strongly deprecated attacks by local interests on the federal treasury.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Triumph of the Executive Branch.=--Jackson's reelection in 1832
2mo i, 1:served to confirm his opinion that he was the chosen leader of the
2mo i, 1:people, freed and instructed to ride rough shod over Congress and even
2mo i, 1:the courts. No President before or since ever entertained in times of
2mo i, 1:peace such lofty notions of executive prerogative. The entire body of
2mo i, 1:federal employees he transformed into obedient servants of his wishes, a
2mo i, 1:sign or a nod from him making and undoing the fortunes of the humble and
2mo i, 1:the mighty. His lawful cabinet of advisers, filling all of the high
2mo i, 1:posts in the government, he treated with scant courtesy, preferring
2mo i, 1:rather to secure his counsel and advice from an unofficial body of
2mo i, 1:friends and dependents who, owing to their secret methods and back
2mo i, 1:stairs arrangements, became known as "the kitchen cabinet." Under the
2mo i, 1:leadership of a silent, astute, and resourceful politician, Amos
2mo i, 1:Kendall, this informal gathering of the faithful both gave and carried
2mo i, 1:out decrees and orders, communicating the President's lightest wish or
2mo i, 1:strictest command to the uttermost part of the country. Resolutely and
2mo i, 1:in the face of bitter opposition Jackson had removed the deposits from
2mo i, 1:the United States Bank. When the Senate protested against this arbitrary
2mo i, 1:conduct, he did not rest until it was forced to expunge the resolution
2mo i, 1:of condemnation; in time one of his lieutenants with his own hands was
2mo i, 1:able to tear the censure from the records. When Chief Justice Marshall
2mo i, 1:issued a decree against Georgia which did not suit him, Jackson,
2mo i, 1:according to tradition, blurted out that Marshall could go ahead and
2mo i, 1:enforce his own orders. To the end he pursued his willful way, finally
2mo i, 1:even choosing his own successor.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:THE RISE OF THE WHIGS
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Jackson's Measures Arouse Opposition.=--Measures so decided, policies
2mo i, 1:so radical, and conduct so high-handed could not fail to arouse against
2mo i, 1:Jackson a deep and exasperated opposition. The truth is the conduct of
2mo i, 1:his entire administration profoundly disturbed the business and finances
2mo i, 1:of the country. It was accompanied by conditions similar to those which
2mo i, 1:existed under the Articles of Confederation. A paper currency, almost as
2mo i, 1:unstable and irritating as the worthless notes of revolutionary days,
2mo i, 1:flooded the country, hindering the easy transaction of business. The use
2mo i, 1:of federal funds for internal improvements, so vital to the exchange of
2mo i, 1:commodities which is the very life of industry, was blocked by executive
2mo i, 1:vetoes. The Supreme Court, which, under Marshall, had held refractory
2mo i, 1:states to their obligations under the Constitution, was flouted; states'
2mo i, 1:rights judges, deliberately selected by Jackson for the bench, began to
2mo i, 1:sap and undermine the rulings of Marshall. The protective tariff, under
2mo i, 1:which the textile industry of New England, the iron mills of
2mo i, 1:Pennsylvania, and the wool, flax, and hemp farms of the West had
2mo i, 1:flourished, had received a severe blow in the compromise of 1833 which
2mo i, 1:promised a steady reduction of duties. To cap the climax, Jackson's
2mo i, 1:party, casting aside the old and reputable name of Republican, boldly
2mo i, 1:chose for its title the term "Democrat," throwing down the gauntlet to
2mo i, 1:every conservative who doubted the omniscience of the people. All these
2mo i, 1:things worked together to evoke an opposition that was sharp and
2mo i, 1:determined.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:[Illustration: AN OLD CARTOON RIDICULING CLAY'S TARIFF AND INTERNAL
2mo i, 1:IMPROVEMENT PROGRAM]
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Clay and the National Republicans.=--In this opposition movement,
2mo i, 1:leadership fell to Henry Clay, a son of Kentucky, rather than to Daniel
2mo i, 1:Webster of Massachusetts. Like Jackson, Clay was born in a home haunted
2mo i, 1:by poverty. Left fatherless early and thrown upon his own resources, he
2mo i, 1:went from Virginia into Kentucky where by sheer force of intellect he
2mo i, 1:rose to eminence in the profession of law. Without the martial gifts or
2mo i, 1:the martial spirit of Jackson, he slipped more easily into the social
2mo i, 1:habits of the East at the same time that he retained his hold on the
2mo i, 1:affections of the boisterous West. Farmers of Ohio, Indiana, and
2mo i, 1:Kentucky loved him; financiers of New York and Philadelphia trusted him.
2mo i, 1:He was thus a leader well fitted to gather the forces of opposition
2mo i, 1:into union against Jackson.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Around Clay's standard assembled a motley collection, representing every
2mo i, 1:species of political opinion, united by one tie only--hatred for "Old
2mo i, 1:Hickory." Nullifiers and less strenuous advocates of states' rights were
2mo i, 1:yoked with nationalists of Webster's school; ardent protectionists were
2mo i, 1:bound together with equally ardent free traders, all fraternizing in one
2mo i, 1:grand confusion of ideas under the title of "National Republicans." Thus
2mo i, 1:the ancient and honorable term selected by Jefferson and his party, now
2mo i, 1:abandoned by Jacksonian Democracy, was adroitly adopted to cover the
2mo i, 1:supporters of Clay. The platform of the party, however, embraced all the
2mo i, 1:old Federalist principles: protection for American industry; internal
2mo i, 1:improvements; respect for the Supreme Court; resistance to executive
2mo i, 1:tyranny; and denunciation of the spoils system. Though Jackson was
2mo i, 1:easily victorious in 1832, the popular vote cast for Clay should have
2mo i, 1:given him some doubts about the faith of "the whole people" in the
2mo i, 1:wisdom of his "reign."
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Van Buren and the Panic of 1837.=--Nothing could shake the General's
2mo i, 1:superb confidence. At the end of his second term he insisted on
2mo i, 1:selecting his own successor; at a national convention, chosen by party
2mo i, 1:voters, but packed with his office holders and friends, he nominated
2mo i, 1:Martin Van Buren of New York. Once more he proved his strength by
2mo i, 1:carrying the country for the Democrats. With a fine flourish, he
2mo i, 1:attended the inauguration of Van Buren and then retired, amid the
2mo i, 1:applause and tears of his devotees, to the Hermitage, his home in
2mo i, 1:Tennessee.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Fortunately for him, Jackson escaped the odium of a disastrous panic
2mo i, 1:which struck the country with terrible force in the following summer.
2mo i, 1:Among the contributory causes of this crisis, no doubt, were the
2mo i, 1:destruction of the bank and the issuance of the "specie circular" of
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:1836 which required the purchasers of public lands to pay for them in
2mo i, 1:coin, instead of the paper notes of state banks. Whatever the dominating
2mo i, 1:cause, the ruin was widespread. Bank after bank went under; boom towns
2mo i, 1:in the West collapsed; Eastern mills shut down; and working people in
2mo i, 1:the industrial centers, starving from unemployment, begged for relief.
2mo i, 1:Van Buren braved the storm, offering no measure of reform or assistance
2mo i, 1:to the distracted people. He did seek security for government funds by
2mo i, 1:suggesting the removal of deposits from private banks and the
2mo i, 1:establishment of an independent treasury system, with government
2mo i, 1:depositaries for public funds, in several leading cities. This plan was
2mo i, 1:finally accepted by Congress in 1840.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Had Van Buren been a captivating figure he might have lived down the
2mo i, 1:discredit of the panic unjustly laid at his door; but he was far from
2mo i, 1:being a favorite with the populace. Though a man of many talents, he
2mo i, 1:owed his position to the quiet and adept management of Jackson rather
2mo i, 1:than to his own personal qualities. The men of the frontier did not care
2mo i, 1:for him. They suspected that he ate from "gold plate" and they could not
2mo i, 1:forgive him for being an astute politician from New York. Still the
2mo i, 1:Democratic party, remembering Jackson's wishes, renominated him
2mo i, 1:unanimously in 1840 and saw him go down to utter defeat.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Whigs and General Harrison.=--By this time, the National
2mo i, 1:Republicans, now known as Whigs--a title taken from the party of
2mo i, 1:opposition to the Crown in England, had learned many lessons. Taking a
2mo i, 1:leaf out of the Democratic book, they nominated, not Clay of Kentucky,
2mo i, 1:well known for his views on the bank, the tariff, and internal
2mo i, 1:improvements, but a military hero, General William Henry Harrison, a man
2mo i, 1:of uncertain political opinions. Harrison, a son of a Virginia signer of
2mo i, 1:the Declaration of Independence, sprang into public view by winning a
2mo i, 1:battle more famous than important, "Tippecanoe"--a brush with the
2mo i, 1:Indians in Indiana. He added to his laurels by rendering praiseworthy
2mo i, 1:services during the war of 1812. When days of peace returned he was
2mo i, 1:rewarded by a grateful people with a seat in Congress. Then he retired
2mo i, 1:to quiet life in a little village near Cincinnati. Like Jackson he was
2mo i, 1:held to be a son of the South and the West. Like Jackson he was a
2mo i, 1:military hero, a lesser light, but still a light. Like Old Hickory he
2mo i, 1:rode into office on a tide of popular feeling against an Eastern man
2mo i, 1:accused of being something of an aristocrat. His personal popularity was
2mo i, 1:sufficient. The Whigs who nominated him shrewdly refused to adopt a
2mo i, 1:platform or declare their belief in anything. When some Democrat
2mo i, 1:asserted that Harrison was a backwoodsman whose sole wants were a jug of
2mo i, 1:hard cider and a log cabin, the Whigs treated the remark not as an
2mo i, 1:insult but as proof positive that Harrison deserved the votes of Jackson
2mo i, 1:men. The jug and the cabin they proudly transformed into symbols of the
2mo i, 1:campaign, and won for their chieftain 234 electoral votes, while Van
2mo i, 1:Buren got only sixty.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Harrison and Tyler.=--The Hero of Tippecanoe was not long to enjoy the
2mo i, 1:fruits of his victory. The hungry horde of Whig office seekers descended
2mo i, 1:upon him like wolves upon the fold. If he went out they waylaid him; if
2mo i, 1:he stayed indoors, he was besieged; not even his bed chamber was spared.
2mo i, 1:He was none too strong at best and he took a deep cold on the day of his
2mo i, 1:inauguration. Between driving out Democrats and appeasing Whigs, he fell
2mo i, 1:mortally ill. Before the end of a month he lay dead at the capitol.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Harrison's successor, John Tyler, the Vice President, whom the Whigs had
2mo i, 1:nominated to catch votes in Virginia, was more of a Democrat than
2mo i, 1:anything else, though he was not partisan enough to please anybody. The
2mo i, 1:Whigs railed at him because he would not approve the founding of another
2mo i, 1:United States Bank. The Democrats stormed at him for refusing, until
2mo i, 1:near the end of his term, to sanction the annexation of Texas, which had
2mo i, 1:declared its independence of Mexico in 1836. His entire administration,
2mo i, 1:marked by unseemly wrangling, produced only two measures of importance.
2mo i, 1:The Whigs, flushed by victory, with the aid of a few protectionist
2mo i, 1:Democrats, enacted, in 1842, a new tariff law destroying the compromise
2mo i, 1:which had brought about the truce between the North and the South, in
2mo i, 1:the days of nullification. The distinguished leader of the Whigs, Daniel
2mo i, 1:Webster, as Secretary of State, in negotiation with Lord Ashburton
2mo i, 1:representing Great Britain, settled the long-standing dispute between
2mo i, 1:the two countries over the Maine boundary. A year after closing this
2mo i, 1:chapter in American diplomacy, Webster withdrew to private life, leaving
2mo i, 1:the President to endure alone the buffets of political fortune.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:To the end, the Whigs regarded Tyler as a traitor to their cause; but
2mo i, 1:the judgment of history is that it was a case of the biter bitten. They
2mo i, 1:had nominated him for the vice presidency as a man of views acceptable
2mo i, 1:to Southern Democrats in order to catch their votes, little reckoning
2mo i, 1:with the chances of his becoming President. Tyler had not deceived them
2mo i, 1:and, thoroughly soured, he left the White House in 1845 not to appear in
2mo i, 1:public life again until the days of secession, when he espoused the
2mo i, 1:Southern confederacy. Jacksonian Democracy, with new leadership, serving
2mo i, 1:a new cause--slavery--was returned to power under James K. Polk, a
2mo i, 1:friend of the General from Tennessee. A few grains of sand were to run
2mo i, 1:through the hour glass before the Whig party was to be broken and
2mo i, 1:scattered as the Federalists had been more than a generation before.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:THE INTERACTION OF AMERICAN AND EUROPEAN OPINION
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Democracy in England and France.=--During the period of Jacksonian
2mo i, 1:Democracy, as in all epochs of ferment, there was a close relation
2mo i, 1:between the thought of the New World and the Old. In England, the
2mo i, 1:successes of the American experiment were used as arguments in favor of
2mo i, 1:overthrowing the aristocracy which George III had manipulated with such
2mo i, 1:effect against America half a century before. In the United States, on
2mo i, 1:the other hand, conservatives like Chancellor Kent, the stout opponent
2mo i, 1:of manhood suffrage in New York, cited the riots of the British working
2mo i, 1:classes as a warning against admitting the same classes to a share in
2mo i, 1:the government of the United States. Along with the agitation of opinion
2mo i, 1:went epoch-making events. In 1832, the year of Jackson's second
2mo i, 1:triumph, the British Parliament passed its first reform bill, which
2mo i, 1:conferred the ballot--not on workingmen as yet--but on mill owners and
2mo i, 1:shopkeepers whom the landlords regarded with genuine horror. The initial
2mo i, 1:step was thus taken in breaking down the privileges of the landed
2mo i, 1:aristocracy and the rich merchants of England.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:About the same time a popular revolution occurred in France. The Bourbon
2mo i, 1:family, restored to the throne of France by the allied powers after
2mo i, 1:their victory over Napoleon in 1815, had embarked upon a policy of
2mo i, 1:arbitrary government. To use the familiar phrase, they had learned
2mo i, 1:nothing and forgotten nothing. Charles X, who came to the throne in
2mo i, 1:1824, set to work with zeal to undo the results of the French
2mo i, 1:Revolution, to stifle the press, restrict the suffrage, and restore the
2mo i, 1:clergy and the nobility to their ancient rights. His policy encountered
2mo i, 1:equally zealous opposition and in 1830 he was overthrown. The popular
2mo i, 1:party, under the leadership of Lafayette, established, not a republic as
2mo i, 1:some of the radicals had hoped, but a "liberal" middle-class monarchy
2mo i, 1:under Louis Philippe. This second French Revolution made a profound
2mo i, 1:impression on Americans, convincing them that the whole world was moving
2mo i, 1:toward democracy. The mayor, aldermen, and citizens of New York City
2mo i, 1:joined in a great parade to celebrate the fall of the Bourbons. Mingled
2mo i, 1:with cheers for the new order in France were hurrahs for "the people's
2mo i, 1:own, Andrew Jackson, the Hero of New Orleans and President of the United
2mo i, 1:States!"
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=European Interest in America.=--To the older and more settled
2mo i, 1:Europeans, the democratic experiment in America was either a menace or
2mo i, 1:an inspiration. Conservatives viewed it with anxiety; liberals with
2mo i, 1:optimism. Far-sighted leaders could see that the tide of democracy was
2mo i, 1:rising all over the world and could not be stayed. Naturally the country
2mo i, 1:that had advanced furthest along the new course was the place in which
2mo i, 1:to find arguments for and against proposals that Europe should make
2mo i, 1:experiments of the same character.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=De Tocqueville's _Democracy in America_.=--In addition to the casual
2mo i, 1:traveler there began to visit the United States the thoughtful observer
2mo i, 1:bent on finding out what manner of nation this was springing up in the
2mo i, 1:wilderness. Those who looked with sympathy upon the growing popular
2mo i, 1:forces of England and France found in the United States, in spite of
2mo i, 1:many blemishes and defects, a guarantee for the future of the people's
2mo i, 1:rule in the Old World. One of these, Alexis de Tocqueville, a French
2mo i, 1:liberal of mildly democratic sympathies, made a journey to this country
2mo i, 1:in 1831; he described in a very remarkable volume, _Democracy in
2mo i, 1:America_, the grand experiment as he saw it. On the whole he was
2mo i, 1:convinced. After examining with a critical eye the life and labor of the
2mo i, 1:American people, as well as the constitutions of the states and the
2mo i, 1:nation, he came to the conclusion that democracy with all its faults was
2mo i, 1:both inevitable and successful. Slavery he thought was a painful
2mo i, 1:contrast to the other features of American life, and he foresaw what
2mo i, 1:proved to be the irrepressible conflict over it. He believed that
2mo i, 1:through blundering the people were destined to learn the highest of all
2mo i, 1:arts, self-government on a grand scale. The absence of a leisure class,
2mo i, 1:devoted to no calling or profession, merely enjoying the refinements of
2mo i, 1:life and adding to its graces--the flaw in American culture that gave
2mo i, 1:deep distress to many a European leader--de Tocqueville thought a
2mo i, 1:necessary virtue in the republic. "Amongst a democratic people where
2mo i, 1:there is no hereditary wealth, every man works to earn a living, or has
2mo i, 1:worked, or is born of parents who have worked. A notion of labor is
2mo i, 1:therefore presented to the mind on every side as the necessary, natural,
2mo i, 1:and honest condition of human existence." It was this notion of a
2mo i, 1:government in the hands of people who labored that struck the French
2mo i, 1:publicist as the most significant fact in the modern world.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Harriet Martineau's Visit to America.=--This phase of American life
2mo i, 1:also profoundly impressed the brilliant English writer, Harriet
2mo i, 1:Martineau. She saw all parts of the country, the homes of the rich and
2mo i, 1:the log cabins of the frontier; she traveled in stagecoaches, canal
2mo i, 1:boats, and on horseback; and visited sessions of Congress and auctions
2mo i, 1:at slave markets. She tried to view the country impartially and the
2mo i, 1:thing that left the deepest mark on her mind was the solidarity of the
2mo i, 1:people in one great political body. "However various may be the tribes
2mo i, 1:of inhabitants in those states, whatever part of the world may have been
2mo i, 1:their birthplace, or that of their fathers, however broken may be their
2mo i, 1:language, however servile or noble their employments, however exalted or
2mo i, 1:despised their state, all are declared to be bound together by equal
2mo i, 1:political obligations.... In that self-governing country all are held to
2mo i, 1:have an equal interest in the principles of its institutions and to be
2mo i, 1:bound in equal duty to watch their workings." Miss Martineau was also
2mo i, 1:impressed with the passion of Americans for land ownership and
2mo i, 1:contrasted the United States favorably with England where the tillers of
2mo i, 1:the soil were either tenants or laborers for wages.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Adverse Criticism.=--By no means all observers and writers were
2mo i, 1:convinced that America was a success. The fastidious traveler, Mrs.
2mo i, 1:Trollope, who thought the English system of church and state was ideal,
2mo i, 1:saw in the United States only roughness and ignorance. She lamented the
2mo i, 1:"total and universal want of manners both in males and females," adding
2mo i, 1:that while "they appear to have clear heads and active intellects,"
2mo i, 1:there was "no charm, no grace in their conversation." She found
2mo i, 1:everywhere a lack of reverence for kings, learning, and rank. Other
2mo i, 1:critics were even more savage. The editor of the _Foreign Quarterly_
2mo i, 1:petulantly exclaimed that the United States was "a brigand
2mo i, 1:confederation." Charles Dickens declared the country to be "so maimed
2mo i, 1:and lame, so full of sores and ulcers that her best friends turn from
2mo i, 1:the loathsome creature in disgust." Sydney Smith, editor of the
2mo i, 1:_Edinburgh Review_, was never tired of trying his caustic wit at the
2mo i, 1:expense of America. "Their Franklins and Washingtons and all the other
2mo i, 1:sages and heroes of their revolution were born and bred subjects of the
2mo i, 1:king of England," he observed in 1820. "During the thirty or forty
2mo i, 1:years of their independence they have done absolutely nothing for the
2mo i, 1:sciences, for the arts, for literature, or even for the statesmanlike
2mo i, 1:studies of politics or political economy.... In the four quarters of the
2mo i, 1:globe who reads an American book? Or goes to an American play? Or looks
2mo i, 1:at an American picture or statue?" To put a sharp sting into his taunt
2mo i, 1:he added, forgetting by whose authority slavery was introduced and
2mo i, 1:fostered: "Under which of the old tyrannical governments of Europe is
2mo i, 1:every sixth man a slave whom his fellow creatures may buy and sell?"
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Some Americans, while resenting the hasty and often superficial
2mo i, 1:judgments of European writers, winced under their satire and took
2mo i, 1:thought about certain particulars in the indictments brought against
2mo i, 1:them. The mass of the people, however, bent on the great experiment,
2mo i, 1:gave little heed to carping critics who saw the flaws and not the
2mo i, 1:achievements of our country--critics who were in fact less interested in
2mo i, 1:America than in preventing the rise and growth of democracy in Europe.
