2mo i, 1:THE MIDDLE BORDER AND THE GREAT WEST
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:"We shall not send an emigrant beyond the Mississippi in a hundred
2mo i, 1:years," exclaimed Livingston, the principal author of the Louisiana
2mo i, 1:purchase. When he made this astounding declaration, he doubtless had
2mo i, 1:before his mind's eye the great stretches of unoccupied lands between
2mo i, 1:the Appalachians and the Mississippi. He also had before him the history
2mo i, 1:of the English colonies, which told him of the two centuries required to
2mo i, 1:settle the seaboard region. To practical men, his prophecy did not seem
2mo i, 1:far wrong; but before the lapse of half that time there appeared beyond
2mo i, 1:the Mississippi a tier of new states, reaching from the Gulf of Mexico
2mo i, 1:to the southern boundary of Minnesota, and a new commonwealth on the
2mo i, 1:Pacific Ocean where American emigrants had raised the Bear flag of
2mo i, 1:California.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:THE ADVANCE OF THE MIDDLE BORDER
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Missouri.=--When the middle of the nineteenth century had been reached,
2mo i, 1:the Mississippi River, which Daniel Boone, the intrepid hunter, had
2mo i, 1:crossed during Washington's administration "to escape from civilization"
2mo i, 1:in Kentucky, had become the waterway for a vast empire. The center of
2mo i, 1:population of the United States had passed to the Ohio Valley. Missouri,
2mo i, 1:with its wide reaches of rich lands, low-lying, level, and fertile, well
2mo i, 1:adapted to hemp raising, had drawn to its borders thousands of planters
2mo i, 1:from the old Southern states--from Virginia and the Carolinas as well as
2mo i, 1:from Kentucky and Tennessee. When the great compromise of 1820-21
2mo i, 1:admitted her to the union, wearing "every jewel of sovereignty," as a
2mo i, 1:florid orator announced, migratory slave owners were assured that their
2mo i, 1:property would be safe in Missouri. Along the western shore of the
2mo i, 1:Mississippi and on both banks of the Missouri to the uttermost limits of
2mo i, 1:the state, plantations tilled by bondmen spread out in broad expanses.
2mo i, 1:In the neighborhood of Jefferson City the slaves numbered more than a
2mo i, 1:fourth of the population.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Into this stream of migration from the planting South flowed another
2mo i, 1:current of land-tilling farmers; some from Kentucky, Tennessee, and
2mo i, 1:Mississippi, driven out by the onrush of the planters buying and
2mo i, 1:consolidating small farms into vast estates; and still more from the
2mo i, 1:East and the Old World. To the northwest over against Iowa and to the
2mo i, 1:southwest against Arkansas, these yeomen laid out farms to be tilled by
2mo i, 1:their own labor. In those regions the number of slaves seldom rose above
2mo i, 1:five or six per cent of the population. The old French post, St. Louis,
2mo i, 1:enriched by the fur trade of the Far West and the steamboat traffic of
2mo i, 1:the river, grew into a thriving commercial city, including among its
2mo i, 1:seventy-five thousand inhabitants in 1850 nearly forty thousand
2mo i, 1:foreigners, German immigrants from Pennsylvania and Europe being the
2mo i, 1:largest single element.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Arkansas.=--Below Missouri lay the territory of Arkansas, which had
2mo i, 1:long been the paradise of the swarthy hunter and the restless
2mo i, 1:frontiersman fleeing from the advancing borders of farm and town. In
2mo i, 1:search of the life, wild and free, where the rifle supplied the game and
2mo i, 1:a few acres of ground the corn and potatoes, they had filtered into the
2mo i, 1:territory in an unending drift, "squatting" on the land. Without so much
2mo i, 1:as asking the leave of any government, territorial or national, they
2mo i, 1:claimed as their own the soil on which they first planted their feet.
2mo i, 1:Like the Cherokee Indians, whom they had as neighbors, whose very
2mo i, 1:customs and dress they sometimes adopted, the squatters spent their days
2mo i, 1:in the midst of rough plenty, beset by chills, fevers, and the ills of
2mo i, 1:the flesh, but for many years unvexed by political troubles or the
2mo i, 1:restrictions of civilized life.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Unfortunately for them, however, the fertile valleys of the Mississippi
2mo i, 1:and Arkansas were well adapted to the cultivation of cotton and tobacco
2mo i, 1:and their sylvan peace was soon broken by an invasion of planters. The
2mo i, 1:newcomers, with their servile workers, spread upward in the valley
2mo i, 1:toward Missouri and along the southern border westward to the Red River.
2mo i, 1:In time the slaves in the tier of counties against Louisiana ranged from
2mo i, 1:thirty to seventy per cent of the population. This marked the doom of
2mo i, 1:the small farmer, swept Arkansas into the main current of planting
2mo i, 1:politics, and led to a powerful lobby at Washington in favor of
2mo i, 1:admission to the union, a boon granted in 1836.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Michigan.=--In accordance with a well-established custom, a free state
2mo i, 1:was admitted to the union to balance a slave state. In 1833, the people
2mo i, 1:of Michigan, a territory ten times the size of Connecticut, announced
2mo i, 1:that the time had come for them to enjoy the privileges of a
2mo i, 1:commonwealth. All along the southern border the land had been occupied
2mo i, 1:largely by pioneers from New England, who built prim farmhouses and
2mo i, 1:adopted the town-meeting plan of self-government after the fashion of
2mo i, 1:the old home. The famous post of Detroit was growing into a flourishing
2mo i, 1:city as the boats plying on the Great Lakes carried travelers, settlers,
2mo i, 1:and freight through the narrows. In all, according to the census, there
2mo i, 1:were more than ninety thousand inhabitants in the territory; so it was
2mo i, 1:not without warrant that they clamored for statehood. Congress, busy as
2mo i, 1:ever with politics, delayed; and the inhabitants of Michigan, unable to
2mo i, 1:restrain their impatience, called a convention, drew up a constitution,
2mo i, 1:and started a lively quarrel with Ohio over the southern boundary. The
2mo i, 1:hand of Congress was now forced. Objections were made to the new
2mo i, 1:constitution on the ground that it gave the ballot to all free white
2mo i, 1:males, including aliens not yet naturalized; but the protests were
2mo i, 1:overborne in a long debate. The boundary was fixed, and Michigan, though
2mo i, 1:shorn of some of the land she claimed, came into the union in 1837.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Wisconsin.=--Across Lake Michigan to the west lay the territory of
2mo i, 1:Wisconsin, which shared with Michigan the interesting history of the
2mo i, 1:Northwest, running back into the heroic days when French hunters and
2mo i, 1:missionaries were planning a French empire for the great monarch, Louis
2mo i, 1:XIV. It will not be forgotten that the French rangers of the woods, the
2mo i, 1:black-robed priests, prepared for sacrifice, even to death, the trappers
2mo i, 1:of the French agencies, and the French explorers--Marquette, Joliet, and
2mo i, 1:Menard--were the first white men to paddle their frail barks through the
2mo i, 1:northern waters. They first blazed their trails into the black forests
2mo i, 1:and left traces of their work in the names of portages and little
2mo i, 1:villages. It was from these forests that Red Men in full war paint
2mo i, 1:journeyed far to fight under the _fleur-de-lis_ of France when the
2mo i, 1:soldiers of King Louis made their last stand at Quebec and Montreal
2mo i, 1:against the imperial arms of Britain. It was here that the British flag
2mo i, 1:was planted in 1761 and that the great Pontiac conspiracy was formed two
2mo i, 1:years later to overthrow British dominion.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:When, a generation afterward, the Stars and Stripes supplanted the Union
2mo i, 1:Jack, the French were still almost the only white men in the region.
2mo i, 1:They were soon joined by hustling Yankee fur traders who did battle
2mo i, 1:royal against British interlopers. The traders cut their way through
2mo i, 1:forest trails and laid out the routes through lake and stream and over
2mo i, 1:portages for the settlers and their families from the states "back
2mo i, 1:East." It was the forest ranger who discovered the water power later
2mo i, 1:used to turn the busy mills grinding the grain from the spreading farm
2mo i, 1:lands. In the wake of the fur hunters, forest men, and farmers came
2mo i, 1:miners from Kentucky, Tennessee, and Missouri crowding in to exploit the
2mo i, 1:lead ores of the northwest, some of them bringing slaves to work their
2mo i, 1:claims. Had it not been for the gold fever of 1849 that drew the
2mo i, 1:wielders of pick and shovel to the Far West, Wisconsin would early have
2mo i, 1:taken high rank among the mining regions of the country.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:From a favorable point of vantage on Lake Michigan, the village of
2mo i, 1:Milwaukee, a center for lumber and grain transport and a place of entry
2mo i, 1:for Eastern goods, grew into a thriving city. It claimed twenty thousand
2mo i, 1:inhabitants, when in 1848 Congress admitted Wisconsin to the union.
2mo i, 1:Already the Germans, Irish, and Scandinavians had found their way into
2mo i, 1:the territory. They joined Americans from the older states in clearing
2mo i, 1:forests, building roads, transforming trails into highways, erecting
2mo i, 1:mills, and connecting streams with canals to make a network of routes
2mo i, 1:for the traffic that poured to and from the Great Lakes.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Iowa and Minnesota.=--To the southwest of Wisconsin beyond the
2mo i, 1:Mississippi, where the tall grass of the prairies waved like the sea,
2mo i, 1:farmers from New England, New York, and Ohio had prepared Iowa for
2mo i, 1:statehood. A tide of immigration that might have flowed into Missouri
2mo i, 1:went northward; for freemen, unaccustomed to slavery and slave markets,
2mo i, 1:preferred the open country above the compromise line. With incredible
2mo i, 1:swiftness, they spread farms westward from the Mississippi. With Yankee
2mo i, 1:ingenuity they turned to trading on the river, building before 1836
2mo i, 1:three prosperous centers of traffic: Dubuque, Davenport, and Burlington.
2mo i, 1:True to their old traditions, they founded colleges and academies that
2mo i, 1:religion and learning might be cherished on the frontier as in the
2mo i, 1:states from which they came. Prepared for self-government, the Iowans
2mo i, 1:laid siege to the door of Congress and were admitted to the union in
2mo i, 1:1846.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Above Iowa, on the Mississippi, lay the territory of Minnesota--the home
2mo i, 1:of the Dakotas, the Ojibways, and the Sioux. Like Michigan and
2mo i, 1:Wisconsin, it had been explored early by the French scouts, and the
2mo i, 1:first white settlement was the little French village of Mendota. To the
2mo i, 1:people of the United States, the resources of the country were first
2mo i, 1:revealed by the historic journey of Zebulon Pike in 1805 and by American
2mo i, 1:fur traders who were quick to take advantage of the opportunity to ply
2mo i, 1:their arts of hunting and bartering in fresh fields. In 1839 an
2mo i, 1:American settlement was planted at Marina on the St. Croix, the outpost
2mo i, 1:of advancing civilization. Within twenty years, the territory, boasting
2mo i, 1:a population of 150,000, asked for admission to the union. In 1858 the
2mo i, 1:plea was granted and Minnesota showed her gratitude three years later by
2mo i, 1:being first among the states to offer troops to Lincoln in the hour of
2mo i, 1:peril.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:ON TO THE PACIFIC--TEXAS AND THE MEXICAN WAR
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Uniformity of the Middle West.=--There was a certain monotony about
2mo i, 1:pioneering in the Northwest and on the middle border. As the long
2mo i, 1:stretches of land were cleared or prepared for the plow, they were laid
2mo i, 1:out like checkerboards into squares of forty, eighty, one hundred sixty,
2mo i, 1:or more acres, each the seat of a homestead. There was a striking
2mo i, 1:uniformity also about the endless succession of fertile fields spreading
2mo i, 1:far and wide under the hot summer sun. No majestic mountains relieved
2mo i, 1:the sweep of the prairie. Few monuments of other races and antiquity
2mo i, 1:were there to awaken curiosity about the region. No sonorous bells in
2mo i, 1:old missions rang out the time of day. The chaffering Red Man bartering
2mo i, 1:blankets and furs for powder and whisky had passed farther on. The
2mo i, 1:population was made up of plain farmers and their families engaged in
2mo i, 1:severe and unbroken labor, chopping down trees, draining fever-breeding
2mo i, 1:swamps, breaking new ground, and planting from year to year the same
2mo i, 1:rotation of crops. Nearly all the settlers were of native American stock
2mo i, 1:into whose frugal and industrious lives the later Irish and German
2mo i, 1:immigrants fitted, on the whole, with little friction. Even the Dutch
2mo i, 1:oven fell before the cast-iron cooking stove. Happiness and sorrow,
2mo i, 1:despair and hope were there, but all encompassed by the heavy tedium of
2mo i, 1:prosaic sameness.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:[Illustration: SANTA BARBARA MISSION]
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=A Contrast in the Far West and Southwest.=--As George Rogers Clark and
2mo i, 1:Daniel Boone had stirred the snug Americans of the seaboard to seek
2mo i, 1:their fortunes beyond the Appalachians, so now Kit Carson, James Bowie,
2mo i, 1:Sam Houston, Davy Crockett, and John C. Fremont were to lead the way
2mo i, 1:into a new land, only a part of which was under the American flag. The
2mo i, 1:setting for this new scene in the westward movement was thrown out in a
2mo i, 1:wide sweep from the headwaters of the Mississippi to the banks of the
2mo i, 1:Rio Grande; from the valleys of the Sabine and Red rivers to Montana and
2mo i, 1:the Pacific slope. In comparison with the middle border, this region
2mo i, 1:presented such startling diversities that only the eye of faith could
2mo i, 1:foresee the unifying power of nationalism binding its communities with
2mo i, 1:the older sections of the country. What contrasts indeed! The blue grass
2mo i, 1:region of Kentucky or the rich, black soil of Illinois--the painted
2mo i, 1:desert, the home of the sage brush and the coyote! The level prairies of
2mo i, 1:Iowa--the mighty Rockies shouldering themselves high against the
2mo i, 1:horizon! The long bleak winters of Wisconsin--California of endless
2mo i, 1:summer! The log churches of Indiana or Illinois--the quaint missions of
2mo i, 1:San Antonio, Tucson, and Santa Barbara! The little state of
2mo i, 1:Delaware--the empire of Texas, one hundred and twenty times its area!
2mo i, 1:And scattered about through the Southwest were signs of an ancient
2mo i, 1:civilization--fragments of four-and five-story dwellings, ruined dams,
2mo i, 1:aqueducts, and broken canals, which told of once prosperous peoples
2mo i, 1:who, by art and science, had conquered the aridity of the desert and
2mo i, 1:lifted themselves in the scale of culture above the savages of the
2mo i, 1:plain.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The settlers of this vast empire were to be as diverse in their origins
2mo i, 1:and habits as those of the colonies on the coast had been. Americans of
2mo i, 1:English, Irish, and Scotch-Irish descent came as usual from the Eastern
2mo i, 1:states. To them were added the migratory Germans as well. Now for the
2mo i, 1:first time came throngs of Scandinavians. Some were to make their homes
2mo i, 1:on quiet farms as the border advanced against the setting sun. Others
2mo i, 1:were to be Indian scouts, trappers, fur hunters, miners, cowboys, Texas
2mo i, 1:planters, keepers of lonely posts on the plain and the desert, stage
2mo i, 1:drivers, pilots of wagon trains, pony riders, fruit growers, "lumber
2mo i, 1:jacks," and smelter workers. One common bond united them--a passion for
2mo i, 1:the self-government accorded to states. As soon as a few thousand
2mo i, 1:settlers came together in a single territory, there arose a mighty shout
2mo i, 1:for a position beside the staid commonwealths of the East and the South.
2mo i, 1:Statehood meant to the pioneers self-government, dignity, and the right
2mo i, 1:to dispose of land, minerals, and timber in their own way. In the quest
2mo i, 1:for this local autonomy there arose many a wordy contest in Congress,
2mo i, 1:each of the political parties lending a helping hand in the admission of
2mo i, 1:a state when it gave promise of adding new congressmen of the "right
2mo i, 1:political persuasion," to use the current phrase.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Southern Planters and Texas.=--While the farmers of the North found the
2mo i, 1:broad acres of the Western prairies stretching on before them apparently
2mo i, 1:in endless expanse, it was far different with the Southern planters.
2mo i, 1:Ever active in their search for new fields as they exhausted the virgin
2mo i, 1:soil of the older states, the restless subjects of King Cotton quickly
2mo i, 1:reached the frontier of Louisiana. There they paused; but only for a
2mo i, 1:moment. The fertile land of Texas just across the boundary lured them on
2mo i, 1:and the Mexican republic to which it belonged extended to them a more
2mo i, 1:than generous welcome. Little realizing the perils lurking in a
2mo i, 1:"peaceful penetration," the authorities at Mexico City opened wide the
2mo i, 1:doors and made large grants of land to American contractors, who agreed
2mo i, 1:to bring a number of families into Texas. The omnipresent Yankee, in the
2mo i, 1:person of Moses Austin of Connecticut, hearing of this good news in the
2mo i, 1:Southwest, obtained a grant in 1820 to settle three hundred Americans
2mo i, 1:near Bexar--a commission finally carried out to the letter by his son
2mo i, 1:and celebrated in the name given to the present capital of the state of
2mo i, 1:Texas. Within a decade some twenty thousand Americans had crossed the
2mo i, 1:border.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Mexico Closes the Door.=--The government of Mexico, unaccustomed to
2mo i, 1:such enterprise and thoroughly frightened by its extent, drew back in
2mo i, 1:dismay. Its fears were increased as quarrels broke out between the
2mo i, 1:Americans and the natives in Texas. Fear grew into consternation when
2mo i, 1:efforts were made by President Jackson to buy the territory for the
2mo i, 1:United States. Mexico then sought to close the flood gates. It stopped
2mo i, 1:all American colonization schemes, canceled many of the land grants, put
2mo i, 1:a tariff on farming implements, and abolished slavery. These barriers
2mo i, 1:were raised too late. A call for help ran through the western border of
2mo i, 1:the United States. The sentinels of the frontier answered. Davy
2mo i, 1:Crockett, the noted frontiersman, bear hunter, and backwoods politician;
2mo i, 1:James Bowie, the dexterous wielder of the knife that to this day bears
2mo i, 1:his name; and Sam Houston, warrior and pioneer, rushed to the aid of
2mo i, 1:their countrymen in Texas. Unacquainted with the niceties of diplomacy,
2mo i, 1:impatient at the formalities of international law, they soon made it
2mo i, 1:known that in spite of Mexican sovereignty they would be their own
2mo i, 1:masters.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Independence of Texas Declared.=--Numbering only about one-fourth
2mo i, 1:of the population in Texas, they raised the standard of revolt in 1836
2mo i, 1:and summoned a convention. Following in the footsteps of their
2mo i, 1:ancestors, they issued a declaration of independence signed mainly by
2mo i, 1:Americans from the slave states. Anticipating that the government of
2mo i, 1:Mexico would not quietly accept their word of defiance as final, they
2mo i, 1:dispatched a force to repel "the invading army," as General Houston
2mo i, 1:called the troops advancing under the command of Santa Ana, the Mexican
2mo i, 1:president. A portion of the Texan soldiers took their stand in the
2mo i, 1:Alamo, an old Spanish mission in the cottonwood trees in the town of San
2mo i, 1:Antonio. Instead of obeying the order to blow up the mission and retire,
2mo i, 1:they held their ground until they were completely surrounded and cut off
2mo i, 1:from all help. Refusing to surrender, they fought to the bitter end, the
2mo i, 1:last man falling a victim to the sword. Vengeance was swift. Within
2mo i, 1:three months General Houston overwhelmed Santa Ana at the San Jacinto,
2mo i, 1:taking him prisoner of war and putting an end to all hopes for the
2mo i, 1:restoration of Mexican sovereignty over Texas.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:The Lone Star Republic, with Houston at the head, then sought admission
2mo i, 1:to the United States. This seemed at first an easy matter. All that was
2mo i, 1:required to bring it about appeared to be a treaty annexing Texas to the
2mo i, 1:union. Moreover, President Jackson, at the height of his popularity, had
2mo i, 1:a warm regard for General Houston and, with his usual sympathy for rough
2mo i, 1:and ready ways of doing things, approved the transaction. Through an
2mo i, 1:American representative in Mexico, Jackson had long and anxiously
2mo i, 1:labored, by means none too nice, to wring from the Mexican republic the
2mo i, 1:cession of the coveted territory. When the Texans took matters into
2mo i, 1:their own hands, he was more than pleased; but he could not marshal the
2mo i, 1:approval of two-thirds of the Senators required for a treaty of
2mo i, 1:annexation. Cautious as well as impetuous, Jackson did not press the
2mo i, 1:issue; he went out of office in 1837 with Texas uncertain as to her
2mo i, 1:future.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Northern Opposition to Annexation.=--All through the North the
2mo i, 1:opposition to annexation was clear and strong. Anti-slavery agitators
2mo i, 1:could hardly find words savage enough to express their feelings.
2mo i, 1:"Texas," exclaimed Channing in a letter to Clay, "is but the first step
2mo i, 1:of aggression. I trust indeed that Providence will beat back and humble
2mo i, 1:our cupidity and ambition. I now ask whether as a people we are
2mo i, 1:prepared to seize on a neighboring territory for the end of extending
2mo i, 1:slavery? I ask whether as a people we can stand forth in the sight of
2mo i, 1:God, in the sight of nations, and adopt this atrocious policy? Sooner
2mo i, 1:perish! Sooner be our name blotted out from the record of nations!"
2mo i, 1:William Lloyd Garrison called for the secession of the Northern states
2mo i, 1:if Texas was brought into the union with slavery. John Quincy Adams
2mo i, 1:warned his countrymen that they were treading in the path of the
2mo i, 1:imperialism that had brought the nations of antiquity to judgment and
2mo i, 1:destruction. Henry Clay, the Whig candidate for President, taking into
2mo i, 1:account changing public sentiment, blew hot and cold, losing the state
2mo i, 1:of New York and the election of 1844 by giving a qualified approval of
2mo i, 1:annexation. In the same campaign, the Democrats boldly demanded the
2mo i, 1:"Reannexation of Texas," based on claims which the United States once
2mo i, 1:had to Spanish territory beyond the Sabine River.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Annexation.=--The politicians were disposed to walk very warily. Van
2mo i, 1:Buren, at heart opposed to slavery extension, refused to press the issue
2mo i, 1:of annexation. Tyler, a pro-slavery Democrat from Virginia, by a strange
2mo i, 1:fling of fortune carried into office as a nominal Whig, kept his mind
2mo i, 1:firmly fixed on the idea of reelection and let the troublesome matter
2mo i, 1:rest until the end of his administration was in sight. He then listened
2mo i, 1:with favor to the voice of the South. Calhoun stated what seemed to be a
2mo i, 1:convincing argument: All good Americans have their hearts set on the
2mo i, 1:Constitution; the admission of Texas is absolutely essential to the
2mo i, 1:preservation of the union; it will give a balance of power to the South
2mo i, 1:as against the North growing with incredible swiftness in wealth and
2mo i, 1:population. Tyler, impressed by the plea, appointed Calhoun to the
2mo i, 1:office of Secretary of State in 1844, authorizing him to negotiate the
2mo i, 1:treaty of annexation--a commission at once executed. This scheme was
2mo i, 1:blocked in the Senate where the necessary two-thirds vote could not be
2mo i, 1:secured. Balked but not defeated, the advocates of annexation drew up a
2mo i, 1:joint resolution which required only a majority vote in both houses,
2mo i, 1:and in February of the next year, just before Tyler gave way to Polk,
2mo i, 1:they pushed it through Congress. So Texas, amid the groans of Boston and
2mo i, 1:the hurrahs of Charleston, folded up her flag and came into the union.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:[Illustration: TEXAS AND THE TERRITORY IN DISPUTE]
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Mexican War.=--The inevitable war with Mexico, foretold by the
2mo i, 1:abolitionists and feared by Henry Clay, ensued, the ostensible cause
2mo i, 1:being a dispute over the boundaries of the new state. The Texans claimed
2mo i, 1:all the lands down to the Rio Grande. The Mexicans placed the border of
2mo i, 1:Texas at the Nueces River and a line drawn thence in a northerly
2mo i, 1:direction. President Polk, accepting the Texan view of the controversy,
2mo i, 1:ordered General Zachary Taylor to move beyond the Nueces in defense of
2mo i, 1:American sovereignty. This act of power, deemed by the Mexicans an
2mo i, 1:invasion of their territory, was followed by an attack on our troops.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:President Polk, not displeased with the turn of events, announced that
2mo i, 1:American blood had been "spilled on American soil" and that war existed
2mo i, 1:"by the act of Mexico." Congress, in a burst of patriotic fervor,
2mo i, 1:brushed aside the protests of those who deplored the conduct of the
2mo i, 1:government as wanton aggression on a weaker nation and granted money and
2mo i, 1:supplies to prosecute the war. The few Whigs in the House of
2mo i, 1:Representatives, who refused to vote in favor of taking up arms,
2mo i, 1:accepted the inevitable with such good grace as they could command. All
2mo i, 1:through the South and the West the war was popular. New England
2mo i, 1:grumbled, but gave loyal, if not enthusiastic, support to a conflict
2mo i, 1:precipitated by policies not of its own choosing. Only a handful of firm
2mo i, 1:objectors held out. James Russell Lowell, in his _Biglow Papers_, flung
2mo i, 1:scorn and sarcasm to the bitter end.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=The Outcome of the War.=--The foregone conclusion was soon reached.
2mo i, 1:General Taylor might have delivered the fatal thrust from northern
2mo i, 1:Mexico if politics had not intervened. Polk, anxious to avoid raising up
2mo i, 1:another military hero for the Whigs to nominate for President, decided
2mo i, 1:to divide the honors by sending General Scott to strike a blow at the
2mo i, 1:capital, Mexico City. The deed was done with speed and pomp and two
2mo i, 1:heroes were lifted into presidential possibilities. In the Far West a
2mo i, 1:third candidate was made, John C. Fremont, who, in cooperation with
2mo i, 1:Commodores Sloat and Stockton and General Kearney, planted the Stars and
2mo i, 1:Stripes on the Pacific slope.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:In February, 1848, the Mexicans came to terms, ceding to the victor
2mo i, 1:California, Arizona, New Mexico, and more--a domain greater in extent
2mo i, 1:than the combined areas of France and Germany. As a salve to the wound,
2mo i, 1:the vanquished received fifteen million dollars in cash and the
2mo i, 1:cancellation of many claims held by American citizens. Five years later,
2mo i, 1:through the negotiations of James Gadsden, a further cession of lands
2mo i, 1:along the southern border of Arizona and New Mexico was secured on
2mo i, 1:payment of ten million dollars.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=General Taylor Elected President.=--The ink was hardly dry upon the
2mo i, 1:treaty that closed the war before "rough and ready" General Taylor, a
2mo i, 1:slave owner from Louisiana, "a Whig," as he said, "but not an ultra
2mo i, 1:Whig," was put forward as the Whig candidate for President. He himself
2mo i, 1:had not voted for years and he was fairly innocent in matters political.
2mo i, 1:The tariff, the currency, and internal improvements, with a magnificent
2mo i, 1:gesture he referred to the people's representatives in Congress,
2mo i, 1:offering to enforce the laws as made, if elected. Clay's followers
2mo i, 1:mourned. Polk stormed but could not win even a renomination at the hands
2mo i, 1:of the Democrats. So it came about that the hero of Buena Vista,
2mo i, 1:celebrated for his laconic order, "Give 'em a little more grape, Captain
2mo i, 1:Bragg," became President of the United States.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:THE PACIFIC COAST AND UTAH
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=Oregon.=--Closely associated in the popular mind with the contest about
2mo i, 1:the affairs of Texas was a dispute with Great Britain over the
2mo i, 1:possession of territory in Oregon. In their presidential campaign of
2mo i, 1:1844, the Democrats had coupled with the slogan, "The Reannexation of
2mo i, 1:Texas," two other cries, "The Reoccupation of Oregon," and "Fifty-four
2mo i, 1:Forty or Fight." The last two slogans were founded on American
2mo i, 1:discoveries and explorations in the Far Northwest. Their appearance in
2mo i, 1:politics showed that the distant Oregon country, larger in area than New
2mo i, 1:England, New York, and Pennsylvania combined, was at last receiving from
2mo i, 1:the nation the attention which its importance warranted.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:_Joint Occupation and Settlement._--Both England and the United States
2mo i, 1:had long laid claim to Oregon and in 1818 they had agreed to occupy the
2mo i, 1:territory jointly--a contract which was renewed ten years later for an
2mo i, 1:indefinite period. Under this plan, citizens of both countries were free
2mo i, 1:to hunt and settle anywhere in the region. The vanguard of British fur
2mo i, 1:traders and Canadian priests was enlarged by many new recruits, with
2mo i, 1:Americans not far behind them. John Jacob Astor, the resourceful New
2mo i, 1:York merchant, sent out trappers and hunters who established a trading
2mo i, 1:post at Astoria in 1811. Some twenty years later, American
2mo i, 1:missionaries--among them two very remarkable men, Jason Lee and Marcus
2mo i, 1:Whitman--were preaching the gospel to the Indians.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Through news from the fur traders and missionaries, Eastern farmers
2mo i, 1:heard of the fertile lands awaiting their plows on the Pacific slope;
2mo i, 1:those with the pioneering spirit made ready to take possession of the
2mo i, 1:new country. In 1839 a band went around by Cape Horn. Four years later a
2mo i, 1:great expedition went overland. The way once broken, others followed
2mo i, 1:rapidly. As soon as a few settlements were well established, the
2mo i, 1:pioneers held a mass meeting and agreed upon a plan of government. "We,
2mo i, 1:the people of Oregon territory," runs the preamble to their compact,
2mo i, 1:"for the purposes of mutual protection and to secure peace and
2mo i, 1:prosperity among ourselves, agree to adopt the following laws and
2mo i, 1:regulations until such time as the United States of America extend their
2mo i, 1:jurisdiction over us." Thus self-government made its way across the
2mo i, 1:Rocky Mountains.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:[Illustration: THE OREGON COUNTRY AND THE DISPUTED BOUNDARY]
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:_The Boundary Dispute with England Adjusted._--By this time it was
2mo i, 1:evident that the boundaries of Oregon must be fixed. Having made the
2mo i, 1:question an issue in his campaign, Polk, after his election in 1844,
2mo i, 1:pressed it upon the attention of the country. In his inaugural address
2mo i, 1:and his first message to Congress he reiterated the claim of the
2mo i, 1:Democratic platform that "our title to the whole territory of Oregon is
2mo i, 1:clear and unquestionable." This pretension Great Britain firmly
2mo i, 1:rejected, leaving the President a choice between war and compromise.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:Polk, already having the contest with Mexico on his hands, sought and
2mo i, 1:obtained a compromise. The British government, moved by a hint from the
2mo i, 1:American minister, offered a settlement which would fix the boundary at
2mo i, 1:the forty-ninth parallel instead of "fifty-four forty," and give it
2mo i, 1:Vancouver Island. Polk speedily chose this way out of the dilemma.
2mo i, 1:Instead of making the decision himself, however, and drawing up a
2mo i, 1:treaty, he turned to the Senate for "counsel." As prearranged with party
2mo i, 1:leaders, the advice was favorable to the plan. The treaty, duly drawn in
2mo i, 1:1846, was ratified by the Senate after an acrimonious debate. "Oh!
2mo i, 1:mountain that was delivered of a mouse," exclaimed Senator Benton, "thy
2mo i, 1:name shall be fifty-four forty!" Thirteen years later, the southern part
2mo i, 1:of the territory was admitted to the union as the state of Oregon,
2mo i, 1:leaving the northern and eastern sections in the status of a territory.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:=California.=--With the growth of the northwestern empire, dedicated by
2mo i, 1:nature to freedom, the planting interests might have been content, had
2mo i, 1:fortune not wrested from them the fair country of California. Upon this
2mo i, 1:huge territory they had set their hearts. The mild climate and fertile
2mo i, 1:soil seemed well suited to slavery and the planters expected to extend
2mo i, 1:their sway to the entire domain. California was a state of more than
2mo i, 1:155,000 square miles--about seventy times the size of the state of
2mo i, 1:Delaware. It could readily be divided into five or six large states, if
2mo i, 1:that became necessary to preserve the Southern balance of power.
2mo i, 1:
2mo i, 1:_Early American Relations with California._--Time and tide, it seems,
2mo i, 1:were not on the side of the planters. Already Americans of a far
2mo i, 1:different type were invading the Pacific slope. Long before Polk ever
2mo i, 1:dreamed of California, the Yankee with his cargo of notions had been
2mo i, 1:around the Horn. Daring skippers had sailed out of New England harbors
2mo i, 1:with a variety of goods, bent their course around South America to
2mo i, 1:California, on to China and around the world, trading as they went and
2mo i, 1:leaving pots, pans, woolen cloth, guns, boots, shoes, salt fish, naval
2mo i, 1:stores, and rum in their wake. "Home from Californy!" rang the cry in
2mo i, 1:many a New England port as a good captain let go his anchor on his
2mo i, 1:return from the long trading voyage in the Pacific.
